read about state politics, search a directory of businesses, or find information about
college, high school and professional athletics."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   28.  NATIONAL ARCHIVES &amp; RECORDS ADMINISTRATION (NARA) -- new links
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.nara.gov/">(1)  NARA HOME PAGE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nara.gov/
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.nara.gov/nara/nail.html">(2)  NARA NAIL</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nara.gov/nara/nail.html
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.nara.gov/gils/gils.html">(3)  NARA GILS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nara.gov/gils/gils.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The NARA has made three new resources available via the
Web.  The highlight of the NARA homepage is its Online Exhibit Hall, which contains
an exhibit on poster art from World War II, as well as facsimiles and information about
the Declaration of Independence, Constitution, Bill of Rights, and Emancipation
Proclamation.  The National Audiovisual Information Locator (NAIL) is a searchable
database holding thousands of descriptions of items in the Still Picture, and Motion
Picture, and Video Branches of NARA.  The NARA Government Information Locator
Service (GILS) is a searchable database of National Archives information resources."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.pbs.org/citizens96/">29.  PBS CITIZENS  96 PAGE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.pbs.org/citizens96/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "PBS Citizens  96 Page is a web page  from an election year
five-part television series.  It focuses on  citizen involvement and dialog', and provides a
citizen's level view of the issues of the 1996 campaign."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.spyder.net/politics/">30.  POLITICS BY THE NUMBERS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.spyder.net/politics/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Computer Projects, Inc. Offers access through the WWW to 
Politics by the Numbers,' weekly tallies and statistical analysis of votes cast by members
of Congress on specific bills.  The site also includes links to other political web pages."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.rtis.com/nat/pol/">31.  REALCOM NATIONAL POLITICS &amp; PERSONALITIES</a>
   <br>
   http://www.rtis.com/nat/pol/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The RealCom National Politics &amp; Personalities page offers
links to almost every political party imaginable, including: Communist, Democratic,
Green, Republican, Patriot, and Ross Perot's United We Stand.  It also points to
political organizations such as the Federal News Service, the NRA, and Anarchy
Online, among others."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   32.  ROBERT CROWN LAW LIBRARY AT STANFORD LAW SCHOOL -- new link
   <br>
   <a href="http://www-leland.stanford.edu/group/law/library/how/unpublish.htm">(1)  UNPUBLISHED DECISIONS</a>
   <br>
   http://www-leland.stanford.edu/group/law/library/how/unpublish.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Robert Crown Law Library at Stanford Law School is
pleased to announce an exciting addition to our web page.  We now have the complete
text of the unpublished decision, Tamara Hood v. National Enquirer, as well as a
hypertext embedded table of contents for the opinion.  The Law Library plans to add
more unpublished and depublished materials to our web site in the future, and we'll keep
you posted of any significant additions."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.state.ia.us">33.  STATE OF IOWA</a>
   <br>
   http://www.state.ia.us/
</dt>
