<h1>Internet Update #8</h1>

<center>
<h3>THE GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY LAW SCHOOL</h3>
<h3>JACOB BURNS LAW LIBRARY</h3>
<h3>INTERNET UPDATE #8</h3>
<h3>APRIL 1996</h3>
</center>

Welcome to the eighth issue of the <i>Internet Update</i>, a listing of new and noteworthy websites,
gopher sites, and listserv &amp; newsgroup information.
<p>

<h3>This issue contains the following websites:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>Black Film Center Archive (BFC/A) of Indiana University</li>
  <li>Budget '97 -- available sites</li>
  <li>Census Bureau -- update</li>
  <li>Center for History and New Media#</li>
  <li>EPA Region 3</li>
  <li>Federal Domestic Assistance Catalog</li>
  <li>FindLaw#</li>
  <li>Global Information Locator#</li>
  <li>Infonautics Corporation</li>     
  <li>Innovative Law Users Group (ILUG)</li>
  <li>Kiplinger Washington Editors</li>
  <li>Law Journal Extra! Natural Language Searching of Circuit Court Opinions search engine</li>
  <li>Louisiana Supreme Court</li>
  <li>Mayo Health O@sis</li>
  <li>National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Laws</li>
  <li>National Park Service#</li>
  <li>North Carolina Supreme Court & Court of Appeals Opinions</li>
  <li>Peace Corps</li> 
  <li>Southern Illinois University School of Law Library -- new site</li>
  <li>Texas Administrative Code -- change of address</li>
  <li>University of Colorado-Boulder Government Publications Library: (1) Main Site and (2) International Site</li>
  <li>University of Wisconisn -- Women's Studies Bibliographies#</li>
  <li>Washburn University School of Law -- new CHAT service</li>
  <li>Women's History Month#</li>
</ol>

<h3>This issue contains the following listservs:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>Assessing Environmental Impacts of Agriculture discussion group</li>
  <li>Court-Web-L</li>
  <li>Cyberspace-Law</li>
  <li>International Relations List</li>
  <li>LAW-TAG Mailing List</li>
  <li>Lexis Counsel Connect's Newsletter ÎThe Squib' mailing list</li>
</ol>

<center>
<h2> ~ W E B S I T E S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.indiana.edu/~bfca/index.html>1.  BLACK FILM CENTER ARCHIVE (BFC/A) OF INDIANA UNIVERSITY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.indiana.edu/~bfca/index.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The BFC/A 'is a repository of films and related materials by and about African Americans.'  Its holdings list over 700 films and video cassettes, as well as archival photographs, is available.  It also provides its 'Black Camera' newsletter, as well as contact information, a collections use policy, and pointers to other film sites of interest."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>2.  BUDGET '97 -- available sites<br>
   <a href=http://www.doc.gov/BudgetFY97/index.html>http://www.doc.gov/BudgetFY97/index.html</a>
   <br>
   <a href=http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/aces/aaces002.html>http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/aces/aaces002.html</a>
   <br>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i></i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.census.gov/ftp/pub/population/www/>3.  CENSUS BUREAU -- update</a>
   <br>
   http://www.census.gov/ftp/pub/population/www/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The U.S. Census Bureau has recently updated national, state, and county population estimates through 1995."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://web.gmu.edu/chnm/>4.  CENTER FOR HISTORY AND NEW MEDIA</a>
   <br>
   http://web.gmu.edu/chnm/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Center for History and New Media, a collaboration between George Mason University, the American Social History Project, and the Center for Media and Learning at the City College of New York, is an attempt to respond to the way new media are changing the teaching and studying of history.  The Center aspires 'to produce innovative historical works in the new media' such as CD-ROM disks on U.S. history, and present seminars and conferences on history and new media."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.epa.gov/region03/>5.  EPA REGION 3</a>
   <br>
   http://www.epa.gov/region03/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement, "The EPA's Region 3 now has a homepage on the Agency's web server.  Located in Philadelphia, Region 3 serves the states of Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, West Virginia, and DC.  Information about Region 3's programs, including the Chesapeake Bay Program, is provided, including a special feature allowing users to send inquiries directly to EPA for a response."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.gsa.gov/regions/wk/wku/>6.  FEDERAL DOMESTIC ASSISTANCE CATALOG</a>
   <br>
   http://www.gsa.gov/regions/wk/wku/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement, "The Federal Domestic Assistance Catalog, produced by the GSA, is available in a searchable format via the web.  The Catalog Îis a government-wide compendium of Federal programs, projects, services, and activities which provide assistance or benefits to the American public' and it includes both financial and non-financial sources of assistance."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.findlaw.com/>7.  FINDLAW</a>
   <br>
   http://www.findlaw.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "'FindLaw,' a resource for legal scholarship, is available on the WWW.  Students, scholars, and those involved in the legal profession can gain access to law-related academic journals and reviews, a directory of law schools, a subject index, and a listing of legal resources on the Internet."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.usgs.gov/gils/locator.html>8.  GLOBAL INFORMATION LOCATOR</a>
   <br>
   http://www.usgs.gov/gils/locator.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The idea behind the Global Information Locator initiative is that our Global Information Infrastructure should be designed to make it easy for people to find information of all kinds, in all media, in all languages, for all time. The emerging Global Information Infrastructure will increase the volume of mass media communications, but its greatest potential is to help individual people communicate particular information. Here we open a window on some of the dazzling technologies becoming available to help people connect in the knowledge space that is our global heritage and legacy. We also raise a sublime challenge--Can we build an infrastructure that enhances in fundamental and equitable ways the free flow of ideas worldwide?"</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.elibrary.com/>9.  INFONAUTICS CORPORATION</a>
   <br>
   http://www.elibrary.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Infonautics Corporation offers access through the WWW to 'The Electric Library,' an archive of more than 1000 magazines, newspapers, and journals.  The archive contains access to the full text of more than 150 newspapers and more than 900 magazines.  Students and other users can search the complete texts of more than 2000 works of literature and view images from a collection of more than 18000 photographs."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://ftplaw.wuacc.edu/ilug/ilug.htm>10.  INNOVATIVE LAW USERS GROUP (ILUG) WEBSITE</a>
   <br>
   http://ftplaw.wuacc.edu/ilug/ilug.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The ILUG is pleased to announce the availability of its WWW site.  In addition to information about ILUG, the website provides links to Innovative, Innovative's INNTouch newsletter, the archives for this listserv, the ILUG enhancements request page (password needed), etc.  One feature currently under development at the website is a section titled Member Created Documentation.  The purpose of this section is to provide access to copies of documentation that libraries have created for users of local Innovative systems."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://kiplinger.com/>11.  KIPLINGER WASHINGTON EDITORS</a>
   <br>
   http://kiplinger.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Kiplinger Washington Editors offers access through the WWW to Kiplinger Online.  Users can select from a variety of advice, news, and feature articles on business and personal finance.  Several newsletters are available from the website, including Kiplinger's Retirement Report, Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine, and The Kiplinger Washington Letter."
</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://search.ljx.com>12.  LAW JOURNAL EXTRA! NATURAL LANGUAGE SEARCHING OF CIRCUIT COURT OPINIONS</a>
   <br>
   http://search.ljx.com
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Law Journal Extra! and Compassware Development Inc. have introduced a new state-of-the-art search engine that will allow lawyers to perform powerful and concise searches for U.S. Circuit Courts of Appeal decisions on the WWW.  New York-based Law Journal Extra! is the award-winning website for legal news, case law and related resources on the Internet and the online home of The National Law Journal, New York Law Journal, and Law Technology Product News.  Compassware's MagnetSearch technology will allow lawyers to search Circuit Court of Appeals decisions from October 1994 to the present using natural language and conceptual language queries."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.gnofn.org/~lasc>13.  LOUISIANA SUPREME COURT</a>
   <br>
   http://www.gnofn.org/~lasc
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Louisiana Supreme Court Clerk's office and the Law Library of Louisiana announce the Supreme Court of Louisiana Homepage.  The Supreme Court page has the court's actions available from news releases, with opinions beginning with those released 2/28/96.  The releases are not searchable.  There are also portions of the court rules, information from the clerk's office, and information about the Judicial Administrator, Judiciary Commission, Judicial Council and Judicial College."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.mayo.ivi.com/ivi/mayo/common/htm/index.htm>14.  MAYO HEALTH O@SIS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.mayo.ivi.com/ivi/mayo/common/htm/index.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Online Health Network has a new name and new home.  We're now the Mayo Health O@sis and we've moved to a new location.  You'll find the same reliable health information at Mayo Health O@sis that you've found on Online Health Network.  Plus you'll have access to new resources, features and services as we develop them."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.law.upenn.edu/library/ulc/ulc.htm>15.  NATIONAL CONFERENCE OF COMMISSIONERS ON UNIFORM STATE LAWS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.upenn.edu/library/ulc/ulc.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement, "The Law School of the University of Pennsylvania announces that its website is now the official site for the current drafts produced by the National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Laws' in-progress drafting projects."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.nps.gov>16.  NATIONAL PARK SERVICE (NPS)</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nps.gov
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "NPS offers an electronic visitor center, a directory of info on a variety of activities and services at the nation's parks.  Users can retrieve info on park entrance fees, phone numbers of park facilities, and agency publications."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>17.  NORTH CAROLINA SUPREME COURT & COURT OF APPEALS OPINIONS<br>
