<h1>Internet Update #9</h1>

<center>
<h3>THE GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY LAW SCHOOL</h3>
<h3>JACOB BURNS LAW LIBRARY</h3>
<h3>INTERNET UPDATE #9</h3>
<h3>MAY 1996</h3>
</center>

Welcome to the ninth issue of the <i>Internet Update</i>, a listing of new and noteworthy websites,
gopher sites, and listserv &amp; newsgroup information.
<p>

<h3>This issue contains the following websites:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>Achoo, the Internet Health Care Directory#</li>
  <li>American Verse Project</li>
  <li>Anti-Terrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act of 1996</li>
  <li>Car Talk (Click and Clack)#</li>
  <li>Department of Defense Index of Specifications and Standards</li>
  <li>European Union's Information Society Project Office (ISPO)#</li>
  <li>Federal Agriculture Improvement & Reform Act of 1996, PL 104-127#</li>
  <li>Federal Bulletin Board</li>
  <li>Heritage Foundation#</li>
  <li>Internet Daily Stock Report#</li>
  <li>Legal Information Institute (LII) -- new links</li>
  <li>Line Item Veto Act, PL 104-130</li>
  <li>NASDAQ Stock Market#</li>
  <li>National Center for Agricultural Law Research and Information</li>
  <li>National Endowment for the Arts#</li>
  <li>Paul Ehrlich and the Population Bomb#</li>
  <li>President Clinton's 1996 Trade Policy Agenda and 1995 Annual Report on Trade Agreements Program#</li>
  <li>Supreme Court of Florida Opinions</li>
  <li>UCC Article 2B Draft (2/2/96)</li>
  <li>University of Virginia Social Science Data Center#</li>
</ol>

<h3>This issue contains the following listservs:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>Legaltech Discussion Group</li>
  <li>UCCLAW-L Discussion Group</li>
</ol>

<center>
<h2> ~ W E B S I T E S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.achoo.com>1.  ACHOO, THE INTERNET HEALTH CARE DIRECTORY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.achoo.com
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Achoo, the Internet Health Care Directory, provided by MNI Systems Corp., aims to be a comprehensive catalog for health care sites.  It is organized by subject hierarchy beginning with human life, practice of medicine, and business of health, and continues with many sub-hierarchies.  Each site contains a brief annotation.  The directory is searchable.  At present, Achoo contains over 5000 sites."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.hti.umich.edu/english/amverse/>2.  AMERICAN VERSE PROJECT</a>
   <br>
   http://http://www.hti.umich.edu/english/amverse/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The American Verse Project, a part of the University of Michigan Humanities Text Initiative, is assembling an electronic archive of volumes of American poetry prior to 1920.  Full texts are being made available in both HTML and SGML (Standard Generalized Markup Language).  At present, over 25 verse volumes are available.  Authors include William Cullen Bryant, Emily Dickinson, Paul Laurence Dunbar, Ralph Waldo Emerson, Edna St. Vincent Millay, and George Sylvester Viereck, among others."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://thomas.loc.gov:80/home/c104query.html>3.  ANTI-TERRORISM AND EFFECTIVE DEATH PENALTY ACT OF 1996</a>
   <br>
   http://thomas.loc.gov:80/home/c104query.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>Search for "S 735" and choose the enrolled version.</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://cartalk.com>4.  CAR TALK (CLICK & CLACK)</a>
   <br>
   http://cartalk.com
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Car Talk (Click & Clack), the NPR show and syndicated column by Tom & Ray Magliozzi, is now available via the Web.  Included are selected excerpts from the radio show (via RealAudio); a weekly car problem puzzler; a searchable archive of four years of 'Click and Clack' newspaper columns; a searchable directory of both radio stations and newspapers that carry 'Car Talk' and 'Click and Clack'; classified ads; a 'Virtually Useful Data' section, with an interactive survey, detailed reports including National Highway Transportation Safety Administration report citations on recalls, complaints, and crash tests on hundreds of models, and test drive notes; an electronic 'post card' rack that allows you to send a personalized email postcard to a friend.  (Of course, as Tom and Ray say, 'No stamp is required.  Please do not try to lick the screen.'."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.dtic.mil/dps-phila/dodiss>5.  DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE INDEX OF SPECIFICATIONS & STANDARDS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.dtic.mil/dps-phila/dodiss
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Defense Printing Service Detachment Office (DPSDO) homepage now offers the Department of Defense Index of Specifications & Standards (DoDISS), a keyword searchable list of unclassified Federal and Military specifications, standards, and related standardization documents, as well as those nongovernment standards adopted for DoD use."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.ispo.cec.be/>6.  EUROPEAN UNION'S INFORMATION SOCIETY PROJECT OFFICE (ISPO)</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ispo.cec.be/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The objectives of the ISPO include: 'to create awareness of the potential impact of the information society; to address information society issues by providing a forum for the pooling of relevant solutions; and to facilitate the launching of relevant international cooperation actions.'  Its bimonthly newsletter, 'Information Society Trends' contains information on information technology-related services, products, markets, companies, legislation, policies and technology issues."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://thomas.loc.gov/home/hot-titl.html>7.  FEDERAL AGRICULTURAL IMPROVEMENT & REFORM ACT OF 1996</a>
   <br>
   http://thomas.loc.gov/home/hot-titl.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>Select "F," then select "Farm Bill" then select "H.R. 1976."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://fedbbs.access.gpo.gov>8.  FEDERAL BULLETIN BOARD</a>
   <br>
   http://fedbbs.access.gpo.gov
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The FBB is an electronic bulletin board service that enables Federal agencies to provide immediate, self-service access to Federal information in electronic form.  It now is also a web server that provides easier access to more than 7,500 files in a variety of formats and subject areas from over 25 Government agencies representing all three branches of the Federal Government.  The FBB includes information from the White House and Executive Branch agencies, such as the Departments of State and Treasury (Office of Foreign Assets Control), the Merits Systems Protection Board and the Federal Labor Relations Authority."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.heritage.org/>9.  HERITAGE FOUNDATION</a>
   <br>
   http://www.heritage.org/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Heritage Foundation is one of the best known conservative think tanks in the U.S., and its website offers voluminous information on various topics.  Its publications library offers full text in 12 subject categories from its 'FYI,' 'Heritage Lecture,' 'Backgrounder,' and 'Executive Memorandum' series.  Selected stories from 'Policy Review:  The Journal of American Citizenship,' are available, as well as articles from 'The Insider Newsletter.'  Its 'Congressional District Ranking Book' gives rankings based on census figures for vital statistics, education, housing, and employment.  It also provides an 'Index for Economic Freedom' for over 100 countries."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://netday.iworld.com/stocks/>10.  INTERNET DAILY STOCK REPORT</a>
   <br>
   http://netday.iworld.com/stocks/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Internet Daily Stock Report contains a daily market recap and morning report on how Internet related stocks are faring.  Provided by Internet World, it also contains an Internet stock index of over twenty companies, with names, stock symbols, and business type.  Hypertext links to the homepages of those companies are provided."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>11.  LEGAL INFORMATION INSTITUTE (LII) -- new link <br>
   <a href=http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/cases/historic.htm>(1)  LANDMARK SUPREME COURT DECISIONS</a>
   <br>
   http://http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/cases/historic.htm   
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Under a license, recently concluded with InfoSynthesis, publishers of the USSC+ CDROM, the LII will be placing a steadily growing number of historic decisions on the WWW server, including <u> Brown v. Board of Education (I and II)</u>, <u>New York Times v. Sullivan</u>, <u>Bakke</u>, the 'Pentagon Papers' case, and more."</i>
</dd>
<br>
<dt>
   <a href=http://www.law.cornell.edu/focus/liieye.htm>(2)  LII'S EYE ON THE COURTS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.cornell.edu/focus/liieye.htm
</dt>
<dd>
    <i>From the announcement:  "Joining the current awareness services already offered by Cornell's LII -- BigEar, liibulletin, and liibulletin-ny -- is a new WWW page providing links to newsworthy decisions handed by any of the many appellate courts now covered on the Net, along with relevant background when available."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://thomas.loc.gov/home/hot-titl.html>12.  LINE ITEM VETO ACT (PL 104-130)</a>
   <br>
   http://thomas.loc.gov/home/hot-titl.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Los Angeles Times website includes daily news and features, coverage of movies & entertainment, a computers & technology section, a special section devoted to Southern California sights and events, classified advertising, and chat boards.  The site will be free.  A fee based site will also be available, with access to Times' archives, as well as educational and research services."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.nasdaq.com/>13.  NASDAQ STOCK MARKET</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nasdaq.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The NASDAQ Stock Market is available via the Web.  The no-nonsense page offers 15 minute delayed stock quotes and includes options for a full quote:  best bid, best asked, today's high, low, last sale, previous day's close, net change and share volume.  Also available are multi-quotes for up to five companies at once, index activity, which lets you choose companies based on subject type, the NASDAQ 100 Index, and a most active list--dollar volume, share volume, 10 most advanced and declined.  You can look up companies by name or symbol and company stock information is accompanied by a hypertext connection to that company's page, as well as a connection to the SEC EDGAR database."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://law.uark.edu/arklaw/aglaw/>14.  NATIONAL CENTER FOR AGRICULTURAL LAW RESEARCH AND INFORMATION WEBSITE</a>
   <br>
   http://law.uark.edu/arklaw/aglaw/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "With the passage of the new farm bill by the House and Senate, this is a good time to invite you to visit the National Center for Agricultural Law Research and Information website.  A link is set up to the final farm bill text that was recently approved by Congress and sent to the President.  The Center web page also offers information about the Center and its publications, additional farm bill versions and information, and links to other agriculture, government agency, general law, international law, and full-text law sites, and an annotated environmental law bibliography."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://arts.endow.gov/>15.  NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR THE ARTS</a>
   <br>
   http://arts.endow.gov/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The National Endowment for the Arts (NEA) has recently opened a website.  It consists of three parts:  a guide to the NEA, with an overview of the NEA grant-making program that includes applicant guidelines and staff information, as well as a hyperlinked list of state and regional arts organizations; an arts resource center, with a listing of NEA publications, information about international funding opportunities, and a large listing of arts service organizations in over 20 subject categories; and 'artscommunity,' an online NEA publication that contains features such as a focus on a particular community, a featured artist, a writers' corner, and endowment news, as well as links to other arts-related sites."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.pbs.org/population_bomb/>16.  PAUL EHRLICH AND THE POPULATION BOMB</a>
   <br>
   http://www.pbs.org/population_bomb/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The human population is likely to double by the middle of the 21st century, soaring past an estimated 10 billion people on the planet.  The new PBS television documentary and companion website, Paul Ehrlich and the Population Bomb, looks at the ideas of one scientist whose theories link overpopulation to a broad range of global problems."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.ustr.gov/reports/tpa/1996/contents.html>17.  PRESIDENT CLINTON'S 1996 TRADE POLICY AGENDA AND 1995 ANNUAL REPORT ON THE TRADE AGREEMENTS PROGRAM</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ustr.gov/reports/tpa/1996/contents.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Full-text of President Clinton's recently released 1996 Trade Policy Agenda and 1995 Annual Report on the Trade Agreements Program, is available at the U.S. Trade Representative's web page.  The Trade Policy Agenda contains Clinton's agenda for implementation of U.S. trade agreements such as the Uruguay Round Agreements and NAFTA, as well as bilateral agenda highlights, regional trade and investment, and multilateral negotiations.  The 1995 Annual Report contains a complete rundown of U.S. bilateral, multilateral, and regional trade activities for the year.  Also included, are selected sections of the U.S. trade law membership and structure of the WTO, and a list of 'substantive trade agreements entered into by the U.S. since 1984."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://nersp.nerdc.ufl.edu/~lawinfo/>18.  SUPREME COURT OF FLORIDA OPINIONS</a>
   <br>
   http://nersp.nerdc.ufl.edu/~lawinfo/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The opinions of the Supreme Court of Florida since September 1995 are brought to you by the University of Florida College of Law, in cooperation with the Supreme Court of Florida.  All cases are in full-text on the web, and can be downloaded in RTF format.  The files to download are located at the end of each case."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href=http://www.kentlaw.edu/ulc/uniform/uccart2/ucc2b296.html>19.  UCC ARTICLE 2B DRAFT (2/2/96)</a>
   <br>
   http://www.kentlaw.edu/ulc/uniform/uccart2/ucc2b296.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i></i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>20.  UNIVERSITY OF VIRGINIA SOCIAL SCIENCE DATA CENTER<br>
   <a href=http://www.lib.virginia.edu/socsci/ccdb>(1)  UNIVERSITY AND CITY DATA BOOKS FOR 1988 AND 1994</a>
   <br>
   http://www.lib.virginia.edu/socsci/ccdb
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The University of Virginia Social Science Data Center has made 'County & City Data Books' for 1988 and 1994 available to be searched via the web.  'County & City Data Book' is a Census Bureau publication which is distributed every four to six years.  It contains over 200 demographic, economic, and governmental variables from both federal government and private agency sources, presented for the purpose of multi-area comparisons or single area profiles.  It is designed to present a 'snapshot' of county, city and state data for the years it covers.  There is usually a two year lag between the year of the book and the year of the data."</i>
</dd>
<br>
<dt>
   <a href=http://www.lib.virginia.edu/socsci/interactives.html>(2)  OTHER RESOURCES</a>

   <br>
   http://www.lib.virginia.edu/socsci/interactives.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Also included are the 'Regional Economic Information System' (REIS) 1969-1993, with national, regional, state and county employment, income, and earnings data; 'County Business Patterns' 1977-1993, with two digit SIC (Standard Industrial Classification) business data on establishments, employment, and payroll; 'World Tables' (World Bank) 1950-1992, with 244 economic and social variables for 189 countries, and the '1987 SIC Manual,' among others.  Also included are pointers to other interactive statistical data resources."</i>
</dd>

</dl> 

<center>
<h2>~ L I S T S E R V S ~</h2>
</center>

<dl>
<dt>
   <b>1.  LEGALTECH DISCUSSION GROUP</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Participants in the Legaltech list will discuss legal-related technology used in law practices and courts.  Some of the topics may include legal-related software, experiences with technology in law practice, use of the Internet, and hardware.  The Legal Technology Resource Center (LRTC) of the ABA will periodically post information regarding LTRC programs and services to the list."  To subscribe:  </i>
   <p>
   <i>Send email to: </i>listserver@abanet.org<br>
   <i>With this message: </i>subscribe legaltech <your email address>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <b>2.  UCCLAW-L DISCUSSION GROUP</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "This is a moderated discussion group conducted through electronic mail.  We welcome all members of the legal community to participate in the discussion, specifically including attorneys, judges, law professors, law students, law librarians and legal editors.  The scope of the discussion is any and all aspects of the UCC, including but not limited to secured transactions, sales of goods, leases of goods, negotiable instruments, bank deposits & electronic fund transfers, and letters of credit."</i>
   <p>
   <i>Send email to: </i>listproc@assocdir.wuacc.edu<br>
   <i>With this message: </i>subscribe UCCLAW-L <your name>
</dd>

</dl>

