<h1>Internet Update #10</h1>

<center>
<h3>THE GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY LAW SCHOOL</h3>
<h3>JACOB BURNS LAW LIBRARY</h3>
<h3>INTERNET UPDATE #10</h3>
<h3>JUNE 1996</h3>
</center>

Welcome to the tenth issue of the <i>Internet Update</i>, a listing of new and noteworthy websites,
gopher sites, and listserv &amp; newsgroup information.
<p>

<h3>This issue includes the following websites:</h3>


<ol>
  <li>ALI-ABA</li>
  <li>American Bankruptcy Institute</li>
  <li>American Law Sources Online</li>
  <li>Atlanta Legal Aid Society (ALAS)</li>
  <li>Atlanta Volunteer Lawyers Foundation (AVLF)</li>
  <li>Catherwood Electronic Archive</li>
  <li>Cato Institute#</li>
  <li>Central Notice</li>
  <li>Congressional Quarterly -- addition to site#</li>
  <li>Department of Education's AskERIC</li>
  <li>Electronic Banking Resource Center#</li>
  <li>Environmental Organization WebDirectory</li>
  <li>InterNet Bankruptcy Library's Directory of Bankruptcy Clerks</li>
  <li>"Last Writes?  Re-assessing the Law Review in the Age of Cyberspace" by Bernard Hibbitts,
Associate Professor of Law, University of Pittsburgh School of Law</li>
  <li>Lender Liability</li>
  <li>New York State Unified Court System (NYS UCS)</li>
  <li>Office of the State Comptroller for New York State</li>
  <li>Richmond Journal of Law &amp; Technology</li>
  <li>Russian Information Services#</li>
  <li>Thomson &amp; Thomson Trademark and Copyright</li>
  <li>United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit</li>
  <li>USDA -- new publications: (1) Agricultural Fact Book 1996 and (2) Agricultural Statistics
1995-96#</li>
  <li>Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition#</li>
  <li>Wasserman, Schneider &amp; Babb International Trade</li>
  <li>White House (1) Economic Statistics Briefing Room and (2) Social Statistics Briefing Room#</li>
  <li>World Reports</li>
</ol>


<center>
<h2> ~ W E B S I T E S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.ali-aba.org">1.  ALI-ABA</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ali-aba.org
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "ALI-ABA is the American Law Institute-American Bar
Association Commission on Continuing Professional Education.  Its site lists schedules
of CLE courses and broadcasts and has information about its periodicals and
publications, including The Practical Lawyer, The Practical Litigator, The Practical Real Estate Lawyer, and The Practical Tax Lawyer.  Publications can be ordered online."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.abiworld.org">2.  AMERICAN BANKRUPTCY INSTITUTE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.abiworld.org
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "American Bankruptcy Institute delivers daily bankruptcy-related news and an archive of weekly reviews of important bankruptcy events.  The site also offers legislative news and a newsletter about insolvency issues, 'Cracking the Code.'  ABI members can use this site as a gateway to ABI Online, a restricted online service with a variety of bankruptcy databases and private chat areas."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.lawsource.com/also/alsohome.htm">3.  AMERICAN LAW SOURCES ONLINE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.lawsource.com/also/alsohome.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "American Law Sources Online endeavors to be a one-stop
site for legal research, providing a compilation of links to sources of American law that are available without charge.  The site is organized by jurisdiction, i.e., federal, state and territory.  For each jurisdiction there are links to sources (cases, statutes, etc.), commentary (law reviews, etc.), and practice aids (e.g., court information, official forms, other resources)."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/PI/ALAS/">4.  ATLANTA LEGAL AID SOCIETY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.emory.edu/PI/ALAS/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Atlanta Legal Aid Society (ALAS) has represented
Atlanta's poor in civil legal cases since 1924.  The ALAS site includes complete
information about their organization, services, and volunteer opportunities, including
their AIDS Legal Project, Home Defense Program, Senior Citizens Project, and Mental
Health Law Project, among others.  The ALAS site also includes its two newsletters,
information about summer internships for law students, unique forms to facilitate
community involvement and volunteerism, and its complete inventory of Community
Education brochures."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/PI/AVLF/">5.  ATLANTA VOLUNTEER LAWYERS FOUNDATION (AVLF)</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.emory.edu/PI/AVLF/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Atlanta Volunteer Lawyers Foundation (AVLF) is a
non-profit foundation dedicated to providing access to justice in civil matters, through the use of volunteer attorneys for persons of low income in Fulton County, Georgia.  The AVLF site provides complete information about the foundation and its services, lists specific volunteer opportunities available to attorneys, law firms, and law students, and also includes a page with links to other pro bono and volunteer attorney service organizations on the Web and to major non-profit sites."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.ilr.cornell.edu/library/e_archive">6.  CATHERWOOD ELECTRONIC ARCHIVE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ilr.cornell.edu/library/e_archive
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Martin P. Catherwood Library of the School of
Industrial and Labor Relations, Cornell University, has been chosen as a site for
collecting, transmitting, and archiving selected federal labor reports on the Internet.  The move is designed to make U.S. government reports accessible to a wider population, including scholars and businesses overseas.  The library has established the Catherwood Electronic Archive, in collaboration with several offices within the U.S. Department of Labor, for the dissemination of national reports via the Internet."
</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.cato.org">7.  CATO INSTITUTE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.cato.org
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Cato Institute is a think tank based on 'limited
government, free markets, individual liberty, and peace.'  Its website is highlighted by the full text of many of its Briefing Papers, all of its Foreign Policy Briefing Series, over 100 of its Policy Analysis Series, all of its Social Security Privatization Series, and articles from its semi-monthly Cato Policy Reports (under Publications and Broadcasts).   In addition, the site offers information about the Institute, its staff, its events, and its other publications."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.notice.com">8.  CENTRAL NOTICE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.notice.com
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Central Notice is intended as a central site for posting
important announcements, notably notices of class-action lawsuits, product recalls, and missing children.  There is no charge to lawyers for posting class-action notices.  Product information comes mostly from government sources, such as the Consumer Product Safety Commission and the National Transportation Safety Board.  An electronic
mailing list notifies you of new postings.  You can subscribe by sending an email to:</i>
legal@notice.com, <i>with the word </i>"subscribe" <i>(without quotes) as the subject."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://voter96.cqalert.com/cq_job.htm">9.  CONGRESSIONAL QUARTERLY'S AMERICAN VOTER '96 ON THE JOB</a>
   <br>
   http://voter96.cqalert.com/cq_job.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Congressional Quarterly has recently added an enhancement to its website, CQ's American Voter '96 On the Job.  Here you can search your House or Senate member by name, zip code, or state, and find a detailed profile, and available recent floor speeches, bills filed, and committee roll call votes."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://ericir.syr.edu/">10.  DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION'S ASKERIC</a>
   <br>
   http://ericir.syr.edu/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Department of Education offers access to a newly designed homepage for AskERIC, which directs users to an Internet-based education-information service.  In addition to the ERIC database, the site comprises three major services, a question-and-answer service, a virtual library, a research-and-development section."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www2.cob.ohio-state.edu/~richards/banking.htm">11.  ELECTRONIC BANKING RESOURCE CENTER</a>
   <br>
   http://www2.cob.ohio-state.edu/~richards/banking.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Electronic Banking Resource Center, provided by an
MBA graduate student at Ohio State University, is a one stop resource for information
about banking on the Internet.  It contains pointers to explanations of various open
payment standards; a FAQ on electronic money/Internet payment systems that
discusses such issues as challenges of Internet payment systems, electronic cash, credit cards, and checks and the Web, and advice for merchants on the Internet, among others; a page of pointers to examples of Internet financial transactions; and a large page of pointers to banks on the Internet.  The Resource Center also contains points to other banking related sites."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.webdirectory.com/">12.  ENVIRONMENTAL ORGANIZATION WEBDIRECTORY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.webdirectory.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "This highly useful directory links a wide range of
environmental information into one central place.  The highest level of the index is divided by general topic.  Subsequent levels of the index break these general topics down into small topics, and so on, in a hierarchial manner.  The individual links often have a brief one or two line annotation."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://bankrupt.com/clerks.html">13.  INTERNET BANKRUPTCY LIBRARY'S DIRECTORY OF BANKRUPTCY CLERKS</a>
   <br>
   http://bankrupt.com/clerks.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>Listings appear alphabetically, by state and district.  Also provides hypertext links to circuit court opinions.</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.law.pitt.edu/hibbitts/last.htm">14.  "LAST WRITES?  RE-ASSESSING THE LAW REVIEW IN THE AGE OF CYBERSPACE," BY BERNARD HIBBITTS, ASSOCIATE PROFESSOR OF LAW, UNIVERSITY OF PITTSBURGH, SCHOOL OF LAW</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.pitt.edu/hibbitts/last.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Law librarians and legal information professionals interested in the impact that the Internet may have on the law review as an institution might like to check out a Web-posted, hypertext and multimedia-based article on the subject.  A print version of the piece is scheduled to appear in the June issue of the NYU Law Review, and the Akron Law Review will shortly be producing a special symposium issue comprised of academics' comments."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.america.net/~jerryb/index.html">15.  LENDER LIABILITY LAW</a>
   <br>
   http://www.america.net/~jerryb/index.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Lender Liability Law Home Page features the 'Lender
Liability Primer,' offering an overview of the field, information on hot topics and trends, and links to related sites.  The site is maintained by Gerald Blanchard, author of the treatise, <u></i>Lender Liability, Law, Practice and Prevention<i></u>, published by Clark Boardman Callaghan."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://nyslgti.gen.ny.us/oca">17.  NEW YORK STATE UNIFIED COURT SYSTEM (NYS UCS)</a>
   <br>
   http://nyslgti.gen.ny.us/oca
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "We have expanded the information and the links on the NYS UCS home page.  The latest addition includes 800 and 888 numbers for information
about the courts, job openings, and civil service test schedules.  We have the Craco
committee report to the Chief Judge about the profession and the courts and will shortly add the report of the Chief Administrative Judge for 1995 about electronic recording in Surrogates' and Court of Claims.  You will also find the addresses of all the public access law libraries, the Law Library Handbook, micrographics, guidelines, some of the indices to our Appellate Records &amp; Briefs Collection, and information about applying for the New York Bar exam."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.osc.state.ny.us/">17.  OFFICE OF THE STATE COMPTROLLER FOR NEW YORK STATE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.osc.state.ny.us/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The web page of the Office of the State Comptroller of New York State opened to the public on Friday, May 3, 1996.  The site includes audits of NY state agencies, legal opinions of the State Comptroller and NYS local government
services and audits.  There is also information regarding unclaimed funds, the New York State and Local Retirement System and press releases."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt">18.  RICHMOND JOURNAL OF LAW &amp TECHNOLOGY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.urich.edu/~jolt
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Richmond Journal of Law &amp; Technology is the first student-edited law journal to publish exclusively online. The latest issue (Vol. II, Issue 1 (January 29, 1996)) includes articles on self-incrimination and cryptographic keys, online provider liability, and the federal broadband law."  Volume I, Issue I (April 10, 1995) is available in the site's archive."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.friends-partners.org/rispubs/rl-top.html">19.  RUSSIAN INFORMATION SERVICES</a>
   <br>
   http://www.friends-partners.org/rispubs/rl-top.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Russian Information Services, the publisher of 'Russian Life' magazine, has established a website for the 40-year old magazine of Russian culture, history, travel, and business.  The site resides on the Friends &amp; Partners server at the University of Tennessee, a site for persons with an interest in travel to or business in Russia."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.thomson-thomson.com">20.  THOMSON &amp; THOMSON TRADEMARK AND COPYRIGHT</a>
   <br>
   http://www.thomson-thomson.com
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "'Trademark and Copyright Resources,' includes the full text of a variety of U.S. and international laws, documents and agreements related to
intellectual property.  It also includes recent news, downloadable trademark, patent and copyright forms, and information on other online products, such as Trademarkscan, a fee-based service that searches 14 trademark databases."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.fedcir.gov/">21.  UNITED STATES COURT OF APPEALS FOR THE FEDERAL CIRCUIT</a>
   <br>
   http://www.fedcir.gov/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit now has its own web page.  The web page includes the following features: pointers to the
searchable collection of the Federal Circuit opinions at the Emory University Law School and Georgetown University Law School websites; court precedential opinions on the same day as their release (precedential opinions are posted for 90 days following release); court rules and court information; pending argument calendars; and information on Court activities and events, including the upcoming Federal Circuit Judicial Conference."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   22.  USDA -- new publications<br>
   <a href="http://www.usda.gov/factbook/contents.htm">(1)  AGRICULTURAL FACT BOOK 1996</a>
   <br>
   http://www.usda.gov/factbook/contents.htm
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.usda.gov/nass/pubs/agr95_96/acro9596.htm">(2)  AGRICULTURAL STATISTICS 1995-96</a>
   <br>
   http://www.usda.gov/nass/pubs/agr95_96/acro9596.htm
</dt>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.wsj.com">23.  WALL STREET JOURNAL INTERACTIVE EDITION</a>
   <br>
   http://www.wsj.com
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Wall Street Journal has launched its Interactive Edition on the Web.  It includes the content of the print version, as well as weather and sports sections.  The content can be accessed by section or by a general index that can be found under Table of Contents on the home page.  Stories that mention companies contain hypertext links that allow the reader to obtain more information about a company, including latest news stories, a 20 minute delayed company stock report, and a 'briefing book' on the company which includes background information, a financial overview, stock performance measures, previous WSJ articles about the company, and company press releases."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.customs.com/">24.  WASSERMAN, SCHNEIDER &amp; BABB INTERNATIONAL TRADE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.customs.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "'International Trade,' the just-refurbished site of the New York City law firm Wasserman, Schneider &amp; Babb, is a comprehensive source of
information about customs and international trade law.  It includes links to other
international trade sites as well as news and decisions related to the field."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   25.  WHITE HOUSE ECONOMIC AND SOCIAL STATISTICS BRIEFING ROOMS<br>
   <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/fsbr/esbr.html">(1) Economics Statistics Briefing Room</a>
   <br>
   http://www.whitehouse.gov/fsbr/esbr.html
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/fsbr/ssbr.html">(2) Social Statistics Briefing Room</a>
   <br>
   http://www.whitehouse.gov/fsbr/ssbr.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The White House Website has made access to current U.S.
economic and social data much easier by establishing the Economic &amp; Social Statistics Briefing Rooms.  The power of these sites is that they not only offer brief statistics and charts, but that they also link to the agency that is responsible for the data, allowing interested users to obtain much more detailed data when available.  The Economic Briefing Room contains current data on income, output, employment, unemployment and earnings, product and business activity, prices, money, credit and securities markets, transportation, and international statistics.  The Social Briefing Room contains data on crime, demographics, education, and health.  These two sites make the distinction between agencies that produce particular types of data invisible to the user."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.hg.org/currwr.html">26.  WORLD REPORTS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.hg.org/currwr.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "World Reports, a joint publication of Lex Mundi, an
international affiliation of law firms, and Kluwer Law Publishers International, intended to be a forum for the discussion of legal developments throughout the world.  The current issue (Vol. VIII, No. 1 (March 1996)) has articles on alternative dispute resolution, health-care law and corporate law."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



