<h1>Internet Update #11</h1>

<center>
<h3>THE GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY LAW SCHOOL</h3>
<h3>JACOB BURNS LAW LIBRARY</h3>
<h3>INTERNET UPDATE #11</h3>
<h3>JULY 1996</h3>
</center>

Welcome to the eleventh issue of the <i>Internet Update</i>, a listing of new and noteworthy websites,
gopher sites, and listserv &amp; newsgroup information.
<p>

<h3>This issue includes the following websites:</h3>


<ol>
  <li>Edward Bennett Williams Law Library's Legal Explorer</li>
  <li>EPA National Library Network Program</li>
  <li>Financial Data Finder#</li>
  <li>High Technology Law Review</li>
  <li>Humanities Online#</li>
  <li>Media and Communications Studies#</li>
  <li>"Preserving Digital Information: Report of the Task Force on Archiving of Digital
Information"#</li>
  <li>Quotations -- updated and revised#</li>
  <li>Race, Ethnicity and Politics</li>
  <li>Rettig on Reference -- reviews and reference works#</li>
  <li>State Parks Online#</li>
  <li>U.S. Census Bureau International Programs Center (IPC)</li>
  <li>U.S. Senate's Budget Bulletin</li>
  <li>Washington Post Online#</li>
  <li>World Resources 1996-97: Guide to the Global Environment source book#</li>
</ol>


<center>
<h2> ~ W E B S I T E S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.ll.georgetown.edu">1.  EDWARD BENNETT WILLIAMS LAW LIBRARY'S LEGAL EXPLORER</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ll.georgetown.edu
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The staff of the Edward Bennett Williams Law Library invite you to take a look at their recently updated Legal Explorer website.  The Georgetown University Legal Explorer contains links to many sources of law and law-related information.  Some of these links are accessed by clicking on buttons for the following areas: Federal, State and Territorial, and Foreign and International.  State and Territorial coverage is provided through a clickable map of the United States whose links lead to separate pages for each of the states and territories.  These pages cover the law and government of each state or territory.  Additional links are provided to sites relating to state and local government.  The links for Federal and Foreign and International coverage are not quite as comprehensive yet, but new links are being added on a daily basis."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.epa.gov/natlibra/index.html">2.  EPA NATIONAL LIBRARY NETWORK PROGRAM</a>
   <br>
   http://www.epa.gov/natlibra/index.html<p>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The EPA Library Network works to improve access to
information for EPA decision making and environmental awareness.  Their new website
offers access to the EPA national catalog (via telnet); Library Network Policy and
Procedures; and a sorted list of EPA libraries.  Under construction are a list of journals held by EPA libraries and a core list for an environmental reference collection."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.cob.ohio-state.edu/dept/fin/osudata.htm">3.  FINANCIAL DATA FINDER</a>
   <br>
   http://www.cob.ohio-state.edu/dept/fin/osudata.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Ohio State University Department of Finance has made
a Financial Data Finder available on the Web.  There are pointer pages to data
providers, including Canadian, Australian, United Kingdom, and Spanish, as well as
U.S. providers; historical data; free and for-fee current quotations; market news and
analysis; and business libraries.  'Couch potato' investing tips are also provided.  Most links have brief annotations.  There are also links to other Internet finance resources."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://server.berkeley.edu/BTLJ/">4.  HIGH TECHNOLOGY LAW JOURNAL</a>
   <br>
   http://server.berkeley.edu/BTLJ/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "University of California at Berkeley's Boalt Hall School of Law offers access through the WWW to High Technology Law Journal, a semi-annual
electronic publication focusing on any topic of law that is affected by technology.  Topics include artificial intelligence, network security, business and international trade, or defense systems."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://h-net.msu.edu/">5.  HUMANITIES ONLINE</a>
   <br>
   http://h-net.msu.edu/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The highlight of the Humanities Online website at Michigan State University is the H-Net List of Lists, a page containing over 75 scholarly discussion lists from H-Africa to H-World, as well as several humanities lists not affiliated with H-Net.  Each listing contains subscription information, and may also contain discussion logs, reviews of scholarly works, calls for papers, conference announcements, grant, scholarship and fellowship information, and links to related sites when available."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.aber.ac.uk/~dgc/medmenu.html">6.  MEDIA AND COMMUNICATIONS STUDIES</a>
   <br>
   http://www.aber.ac.uk/~dgc/medmenu.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Media and Communications Studies is a British-based
gateway to Web resources useful in the academic study of media and communication. 
The pages use frames to provide a panel of navigational icons along the side of the
browser window.  As the server is located in Wales, the initial loading of the home page may require some patience for those users located in other areas, but once the icons are loaded navigation is straightforward.  The site is organized into sixteen areas, including film studies, media influence, textual analysis, and gender, class &amp; ethnicity."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.rlg.org/ArchTF/">7.  "PRESERVING DIGITAL INFORMATION: REPORT OF THE TASK FORCE ON ARCHIVING OF DIGITAL INFORMATION"</a>
   <br>
   http://www.rlg.org/ArchTF/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "'Preserving Digital Information,' produced by a task force commissioned by The Commission on Preservation and Access (CPA) and The
Research Libraries Group (RLG) is available on the Internet.  The purpose of this 64-page study 'was to investigate the means of ensuring  continued access indefinitely into the future of records stored in digital electronic form.'  The authors consisted of individuals from industry, museums, archives and libraries, scholarly societies, and government, among others."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.starlingtech.com/quotes/">8.  QUOTATIONS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.starlingtech.com/quotes/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Sporting a new look and user interface, as well as five
hundred new quotations (and a new URL), the Quotations Page allows the user to
search ten Internet quotation archives for keywords.  A new advanced search page offers the choice to search by the text of quotations, author or subject, or all fields; users may search in more than one collection at a time on the advanced search page.  The site also provides links to other quotation resources on the Internet, organized by topic."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.providence.edu/polisci/rep/">9.  RACE, ETHNICITY AND POLITICS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.providence.edu/polisci/rep/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "American Political Science Association has created a homepage on the WWW on 'Race, Ethnicity and Politics.'  The site is designed to serve
political science professors and graduate students interested in research related to
African-American, Asian-American, Latino and Native-American people.  It includes
information on meetings, a link to subscribe to the 'Race-Pol' mailing list, and related information."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.hwwilson.com/retintro.html">10.  RETTIG ON REFERENCE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.hwwilson.com/retintro.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Rettig on Reference is a service of H.W. Wilson.  Each
month it provides reviews of approximately twenty new adult reference books and several Internet-based reference sources.  Items reviewed are selected for their relevance to the North American library community.  Online publication began in October 1995."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.crl.com/~ddickson/parks.html">11.  STATE PARKS ONLINE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.crl.com/~ddickson/parks.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "State Parks Online contains links to information on state parks in 44 states.  Most of the links are to state departments of tourism, but there are some to personal pages.  Also included are a park of the week, miscellaneous individual state park sites, and a link to L.L. Bean's ParkSearch service.  This site provides one-stop shopping for prospective vacationers."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.census.gov/ftp/pub/ipc/www/">12.  U.S. CENSUS BUREAU INTERNATIONAL PROGRAMS CENTER (IPC)</a>
   <br>
   http://www.census.gov/ftp/pub/ipc/www/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The IPC is the area within the U.S. Census Bureau that
conducts international research, international technical assistance and training, and
makes software products available to countries around the world.  The site includes a
world population clock, information resources, and several searchable databases of
information."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.senate.gov/comm/budget/releases/bulletin.htm">13.  U.S. SENATE'S BUDGET BULLETIN</a>
   <br>
   http://www.senate.gov/comm/budget/releases/bulletin.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "U.S. Senate offers access through the WWW to 'Budget
Bulletin' a weekly newsletter on the federal budget.  It features information on current budgetary debates, pending legislation, and Presidential proposals, and it includes links to the Senate Budget Committee's home page."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com">14.  WASHINGTON POST ONLINE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.washingtonpost.com
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Washington Post has recently opened an online version on the Web.  The site includes the full text of the daily edition, plus news from the 50 states, a daily congressional calendar, and over 1000 pages of links to news, reference and websites for over 200 countries around the world."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.wri.org/wri/wr-96-97/index.html">15.  WORLD RESOURCES 1996-97:  A GUIDE TO THE GLOBAL ENVIRONMENT</a>
   <br>
   http://www.wri.org/wri/wr-96-97/index.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Full text of the 'World Resources 1996-97: A Guide to the Global Environment' produced by the World Resources Institute, United Nations
Environment Programme, United Nations Development Programme, and World Bank,
is available via the Web.  It is the official source book for the United Nations Habitat II Conference being held in Istanbul, Turkey June 3-14, 1996.  The tenth edition of 'World Resources' contains two major sections: (1) Global Conditions and Trends and Data Tables, and (2) The Urban Environment, a special section concentrating on how urban population growth is affecting the global environment."</i>
</dd>

</dl>

<hr>

<i>Internet Update</i> is compiled by Leslie A. Lee, Reference Librarian at the Jacob Burns Law
Library, and is issued monthly as a service to the George Washington University Law School
community.

