<h1>Internet Update #13</h1>

<center>
<h3>THE GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY LAW SCHOOL</h3>
<h3>JACOB BURNS LAW LIBRARY</h3>
<h3>INTERNET UPDATE #13</h3>
<h3>SEPTEMBER 1996</h3>
</center>

Welcome to the thirteenth issue of the <i>Internet Update</i>, a listing of new and noteworthy websites,
gopher sites, and listserv &amp; newsgroup information.
<p>

<h3>This issue includes the following websites:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>Air &amp; Waste Management Association</li>
  <li>Center for Democracy and Technology#</li>
  <li>Complete Guide to Palestine's Websites#</li>
  <li>FCC's Telecommunications Act of 1996</li>
  <li>FDA Regulations on Nicotine, Cigarettes, and Smokeless Tobacco#</li>
  <li>GOP Platform -- full-text sources: (1) Republican National Platform and (2) Politics Now#</li>
  <li>GPO Pathway Services#</li>
  <li>Graduate School Guide</li>
  <li>GWU Career Development Office Job Postings</li>
  <li>HUD User</li>
  <li>Initial Public Offerings ("IPO") Central#</li>
  <li>Kentucky Attorney General Opinions (1994-current)</li>
  <li>Library of Virginia Digital Library Project</li>
  <li>Mapquest -- Worldwide Coverage#</li>
  <li>Meta-Index for U.S. Legal Research#</li>
  <li>New York Times: Business Connections#</li>
  <li>New York University Law Library: (1) Homepage and (2) WebJulius</li>
  <li>OAQPS Technology Transfer Network (TTN 2000)</li>
  <li>Pace Global Environmental Law Network</li>
  <li>Resource Renewal Institute (RRI)</li>
  <li>SmartCILP</li>
  <li>Trade Point USA</li>
  <li>University of Alabama School of Law</li>
  <li>University of California GPO Gate#</li>
  <li>University of Memphis Migrating Government Publications -- search by (1) SuDoc Number
or (2) Title#</li>
  <li>U.S. Dept. of Education's National Center for Education Statistics report, "The Condition of
Education 1996"</li>
  <li>U.S. Dept. Of Labor: The Minimum Wage#</li>
  <li>"Where the Wild Things Are: Librarian's Guide to the Best Information on the Net"</li>
  <li>World Law Resource List: Non-U.S. Law-Related Resources for Internet Users</li>
</ol>


<h3>This issue contains the following listservs:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>Computer Law Observer#</li>
  <li>Constitutional Law Abstracts Electronic Newsletter</li>
  <li>CORELINK Discussion List#</li>
  <li>Corporate/Securities/Finance Law Abstracts Electronic Newsletter</li>
  <li>FCC Daily Digest Electronic Newsletter</li>
  <li>HISLAW-L Discussion List</li>
  <li>INTL-DOC, International Documents Discussion List#</li>
  <li>Law &amp; Economics Abstracts Electronic Newsletter</li>
  <li>Law &amp; Politics Book Review Electronic Newsletter</li>
  <li>Lifton's Labor Law Letter#</li>
  <li>Supreme Court Decisions Electronic Newsletter</li>
</ol>


<center>
<h2> ~ W E B S I T E S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.awma.org/">1.  AIR &amp; WASTE MANAGEMENT ASSOCIATION</a>
   <br>
   http://www.awma.org/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The purpose of the Air &amp; Waste Management Association is
to enhance environmental knowledge and provide quality information on which to base
environmental decisions.  They also seek to assist in the professional development and
critical environmental decision making of their members to benefit society.  A&amp;WMA
produces a series of one-page fact sheets on specific environmental topics.  They also
produce information books that provide a more in-depth study of general topics such as
air pollution, and pollution prevention for our land, water, and air."</i>
</dd>
</dl>

<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.cdt.org/">2.  CENTER FOR DEMOCRACY AND TECHNOLOGY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.cdt.org/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Center For Democracy and Technology, a non-profit
public interest organization, offers this website with information about the state of free
speech and civil liberties on the Internet.  Visitors to the site will find current headlines,
updated every few days, as well as coverage of issues related to privacy, terrorism,
cryptography, infrastructure, and digital telephony, among others.  Back issues of CDT
policy publications are also available, organized chronologically and annotated with a
subject line.  Coverage of the issues reflects the mission of CDT, which develops and
advocates public policies that advance constitutional civil liberties and democratic values
in new computer and communications technologies."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.birzeit.edu/palarc/iplinks.html">3.  COMPLETE GUIDE TO PALESTINE'S WEBSITES</a>
   <br>
   http://www.birzeit.edu/palarc/iplinks.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "This site, provided by Birzeit University, organizes 29
Palestinian websites into categories: academic and research, educational institutions,
government and services, human rights, Internet service providers, media, personal
homepages, and travel.  Each entry is annotated, providing the user with a clear idea of
the kind of quality of information found on each site.  The site also presents a 'Golden
Olive Award' to Palestinian sites that provide 'a well-thought-out, well-implemented,
information-rich contribution to the wider community of the World Wide Web.'  There
are also links to the 'Palestine Archive' and to Birzeit University's homepage, which,
though little more than a month old, are amassing significant amounts of information
useful to the study of Palestine."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.fcc.gov/telecom.html">4.  FCC'S TELECOMMUNICATIONS ACT OF 1996</a>
   <br>
   http://www.fcc.gov/telecom.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Given the continuing interest, if not controversy, in the
Telecommunications Act of 1996, the FCC has developed a website with more than
adequate data for the most ardent researcher.  Included are schedules of FCC
proceedings, copies of news releases, announcements of meetings, and charts depicting
FCC research.  You also find links to resources beyond the FCC."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   5.  FDA REGULATIONS ON NICOTINE, CIGARETTES, AND SMOKELESS TOBACCO
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/fda">http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/fda</a>
   <br>
   <a href="http://fedbbs.access.gpo.gov/libs/fda_fr.htm">http://fedbbs.access.gpo.gov/libs/fda_fr.htm</a>
   <br>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Recent U.S. Food and Drug Administration nicotine
regulation documents have been aggregated at one site within the GPO website.  The
documents are available in both text and .pdf format.  They are "Regulations Restricting
the Sale and Distribution of Cigarettes and Smokeless Tobacco to Protect Children and
Adolescents" (final rule, released 8/28/96) and "Regulations Restricting the Sale and
Distribution of Cigarettes and Smokeless Tobacco to Protect Children and Adolescents"
(proposed rule, released 8/11/96).  In addition, a searchable "Analysis Regarding the
Food and Drug Administration's Jurisdiction Over Nicotine-Containing Cigarettes and
Smokeless Tobacco Products (8/11/96) is available."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
6.  GOP PLATFORM -- FULL TEXT
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.rnc.org/hq/platform96/">(1)  REPUBLICAN NATIONAL PLATFORM</a>
   <br>
   http://www.rnc.org/hq/platform96/
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.politicsnow.com/campaign/conventions/gop/platform/">(2)  POLITICS NOW</a>
   <br>
   http://www.politicsnow.com/campaign/conventions/gop/platform/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Republican presidential nominee Bob Dole claims he hasn't
read the party platform, but now you can, and judge for yourself the prospective policies
of that party.  The Republican National Committee has made the full-text of the platform
available at its website.  In addition, PoliticsNow, a collaborative effort of ABC News,
the Washington Post, and the National Journal, has made the platform available.  Also
available at this site are a listing of Platform Committee, platform news from various
sources (provided by Lexis/Nexis), and full-text of the 1992 party platform."</i>
</dd>
</dl>




<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/aces/aces760.html">7.  GPO PATHWAY SERVICES</a>
   <br>
   http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/aces/aces760.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Pathway Services, a product of the U.S. Government
Printing Office, is an attempt by that agency to make finding U.S. government
information easier for both librarians and interested end users.  It does this by
connecting the user to many sources of government information from one site.  Users
can browse the information by topic (though the topic listing is a work in progress at this
time) or by title, arranged alphabetically by agency.  This title page contains a 'New
Additions' hypertext link to help interested users keep up with new releases across
agencies.  Government Information Locator Services (GILS) records can also be
browsed.  These records contain information about government agencies, along with
relevant hypertext links.  Pathway Services also provides keyword searching of
government information sites, as well as MoCat.  This site shows great promise in
helping information seekers use one location as a gateway to all their government
information needs."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.schoolguides.com/">8.  GRADUATE SCHOOL GUIDE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.schoolguides.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Graduate School Guide offers access through the World Wide
Web to a directory of addresses of graduate schools in the United States.  Students can
use a mouse to click on a map of the United States to select a school by state, or can
click on an icon to search according to academic discipline."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.law.gwu.edu/cdo/">9.  GWU CAREER DEVELOPMENT OFFICE JOB POSTINGS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.gwu.edu/cdo/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Career Development Office now has a home page which
includes our job postings.  Job notices are posted and updated daily.  Students and Law
School alumni will have access through the Internet 24 hours a day.  We are pleased to
be able to offer on-line job postings and thank Mike Briggs and Scott Pagel for their
assistance.  Access to the job postings is through the law school home page.  For
students and alumni accessing the postings outside of the GW system, a password,
which may be obtained by calling the CDO, will be necessary to view the job postings. 
The job binders will still be maintained in the CDO Resource Library and the paper
version of the Graduate Career Opportunities Newsletter will still be compiled and mailed
twice monthly."</i>
</dd>
</dl>




<dl>
<dt>
   10.  HUD USER
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.huduser.org/">http://www.huduser.org/</a>
   <br>
   <a href="gopher://huduser.org:73/">gopher://huduser.org:73/</a>
   <br>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "For the statistically-minded, the HUD User site has a
wealth of data on housing and housing industry trends and is the major source for
Federal Government reports and information on housing policy and programs, building
technology, economic development, and urban planning.  The handsome opening page is
just one step from the HUD User Database -- a forms-rich array, wonderful for
researcher."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.ipocentral.com/">11.  INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS ("INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS ("IPO")
CENTRAL"</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ipocentral.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS ("IPO") Central, provided by The Reference Press, 
contains a wealth of information on IPOs.  It features a complete list of companies that 'filed for an 
initial public offering of common stock on or after May 6, 1996, the first day that all US companies 
were required to file electronically,' along with EDGAR Online SEC filings.  This directory can be
accessed alphabetically or by date, and the latest filings are available under a separate menu item. 
INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS ("IPO") Central also highlights one featured INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS ("IPO") per week, with a free link to a Hoover Online profile on that company.  'The Insider' offers short analytical columns on IPOs,
and the 'Beginner's Guide' has links to basic INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS ("IPO") information to help the novice.  The site also offers links to other INITIAL
PUBLIC OFFERINGS ("IPO")-related sites.  INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS ("IPO") Central does not at this time offer a searchable interface to its directory, but the
providers promise improved search features soon.  Note that listings are removed from the directory after six months and that EDGAR Online is in no way related to
EDGAR." </i>
</dd>
</dl>


<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://162.114.63.168/">12.  KENTUCKY ATTORNEY GENERAL OPINIONS</a>
   <br>
   http://162.114.63.168/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The University of Louisville School of Law Library has begun
posting Kentucky Attorney General Opinions.  Currently coverage begins in 1994 and
is complete to present. All documents are in Rich Text Format (.RTF).  In order to view
them, you may need to configure your web browser to recognize this format.  The
documents can be viewed by most word processors, such as WordPerfect or Word for
Windows."</i>
</dd>
</dl>


<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://leo.vsla.edu/lva/lva.html">13.  LIBRARY OF VIRGINIA DIGITAL LIBRARY PROJECT</a>
   <br>
   http://leo.vsla.edu/lva/lva.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "A sign of the future for library collections, the Library of
Virginia recently announced completion of Phase I of its Digital Library Project. 
Started in 1995, this project preserves both archival and library collections and permits
Internet access.  Over 600,000 images were scanned and 40 electronic finding aids
were developed to help users navigate the collections.  Here you find the Virginia Colonial
Records Project, the U.S. Army Signal Corps Photograph Collection, the collection of
family Bible records, and the Electronic Card Indexes Project.  The photograph collection
contains 3,500 black and white photographs taken during World War II at the
Hampton Roads Port of Embarkation." </i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.mapquest.com/">14.  MAPQUEST -- WORLDWIDE COVERAGE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.mapquest.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "To its detailed coverage of the United States, Mapquest has
added maps for cities and regions around the world.  The interactive atlas can now
display international locations on six continents; maps are detailed to the highway and
boulevard level.  For U.S. addresses, users may search for locations by street address
and view a map of the neighborhood.  Registration, free of charge, allows the user to
return to the Mapquest site with settings intact; settings include which points of interest
will be highlighted, how the maps should be displayed, and even which maps will be
labeled and stored for future reference.  The U.S.-only services on the site include
Tripquest, a route planner that covers the U.S., Canada, and Mexico."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://gsulaw.gsu.edu/metaindex/">15.  META-INDEX FOR U.S. LEGAL RESEARCH</a>
   <br>
   http://gsulaw.gsu.edu/metaindex/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "This page, provided by the Georgia State University College
of Law search forms for many U.S. Federal Government law sources; each form
contains sample search criteria.  The judicial opinions section provides search forms for
the Supreme Court as well as all Federal Circuit courts.  The legislation section allows
searching of the <u>U.S. Code</u>, as well as searching of bills (104th Congress, both full-text
and by bill number) and the full text of the <u>Congressional Record</u>.  There are also search
forms for federal regulation, people in law, and other legal sources.  Users may enter
search criteria directly into the forms on this meta-index page, or can follow the link to
the source page for direct searching.  The searches of standard sources (opinions and
legislation) are presented without instructions, while the 'Other Sources' section provides
descriptions of the source and tips for searching.  Users may register to be notified by e-mail when the page is modified."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/library/cyber/reference/busconn.html">16.  NEW YORK TIMES: BUSINESS CONNECTIONS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nytimes.com/library/cyber/reference/busconn.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The New York Times On the Web has recently added a new
section, Business Connections, to its highly selective collection of Web links.  The new
section provides one-stop shopping for the most authoritative business-related network
resources available.  For example, the Markets listings include links to all U.S.
exchanges, foreign exchanges, and selected market information sites.  The Investing
section offers a dozen links to general information and a half-dozen more to the top
investment companies and trading services such as Merrill Lynch, Paine Webber, and
Charles Schwab.  Company Information provides traditional sources such as Dun &amp;
Bradstreet along with the Web 100 -- the top U.S. and international companies on the
Web.  A good selection of business directories is included, in addition to separate listings
for business and financial news, banking &amp; finance, and government &amp; public
organizations.  Note that free registration to The New York Times On the Web is
required before entry into any of their pages."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   17.  NEW YORK UNIVERSITY LAW LIBRARY HOMEPAGE
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.nyu.edu/law/library">(1) HOMEPAGE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nyu.edu/law/library
   <br>
   <a href="http://julius.law.nyu.edu">(2)  WEBJULIUS</a>
   <br>
   http://julius.law.nyu.edu/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "New York University Law Library is pleased to announce our homepage
and web-based OPAC (WebJulius). The homepage is maintained by Leslie Rich, and WebJulius is
maintained by Terry Ballard."</i>
</dd>
</dl>


<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://ttnwww.rtpnc.epa.gov/">18.  OAQPS TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER NETWORK (TTN 2000)</a>
   <br>
   http://ttnwww.rtpnc.epa.gov/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Born from the OAQPS Technology Transfer Network
Bulletin Board System (TTN BBS), TTN 2000 offers all the information of the
original TTN BBS, but with WWW pages, an FTP site and traditional BBS access. 
With TTN 2000, all the information is available from any connectivity option.  The
TTN is sponsored by the Information Transfer and Program Integration Division of the
U.S. EPA's Office of Air Quality Planning and Standards, located in Research
Triangle Park, NC.  Features include the AP-42 (Compilation of Air Pollutant
Emission Factors), Clean Air Act Recently Signed Rules, and air quality modeling
information."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://joshua.law.pace.edu/env/environ.html">19.  PACE GLOBAL ENVIRONMENTAL LAW NETWORK</a>
   <br>
   http://joshua.law.pace.edu/env/environ.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Pace University has created the 'Pace Global Environmental
Law Network on the World Wide Web.  The site includes a virtual library on
environmental law complete with catalogues and the full text of legal sources on the
Internet The site also includes the <u>Pace Interactive Earth Law Journal</u> and a section
called 'Pace Professional Dialogue,' where professionals, educators, and students can
discuss environmental law and related issues."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.rri.org/">20.  RESOURCE RENEWAL INSTITUTE (RRI)</a>
   <br>
   http://www.rri.org/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Resource Renewal Institute (RRI) promotes Green Plans
as the path to a sustainable environment and economy.  Green Plans are dynamic
programs by which all elements of society agree on long-term environmental goals and
take responsibility for achieving them.  This site has been developed to educate and
inform those interested in Green Plans and provides information and avenues for further
investigation."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.law.washington.edu/~cilp">21.  SMARTCILP</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.washington.edu/~cilp
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Gallagher Law Library is pleased to announce
SmartCILP, a personalized periodical awareness tool for legal researchers created from
the Current Index to Legal Periodicals (CILP).  CILP and SmartCILP are products
created by the Marian Gould Gallagher Law Library of the University of Washington
School of Law."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.tpusa.com/">22.  TRADE POINT USA</a>
   <br>
   http://www.tpusa.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "One business arrangement encouraged by the Internet is
partnering, evident from this page sponsored by the United Nations and featuring
international trade information from the Economist Intelligence Unit, Dun &amp; Bradstreet
Information Services, and Price Waterhouse.  A range of services is offered, from free
and subscription to listing and special.  The free services include the I-TRADE Export
Guide, I-TRADE Exhibition Center for catalogues and listings, and I-TRADE Forum
for experts."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.law.ua.edu">23.  UNIVERSITY OF ALABAMA SCHOOL OF LAW</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.ua.edu
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>University of Alabama School of Law has just made its website available on the Web.</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.gpo.ucop.edu">24.  UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA GPO GATE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.gpo.ucop.edu
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The GPO Federal Depository Library at the University of
California is a GPO gateway that makes selected databases browsable as well as
searchable.  For those not savvy to the intricacies of searching techniques, a quick look
at such databases as <u>Economic Indicators</u>, <u>US Government Manual</u>, and Public Laws
immediately shows how much more access this new resource provides users.  UC
gateway provides access to databases by subject as well as title."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   25.  UNIVERSITY OF MEMPHIS MIGRATING GOVERNMENT PUBLICATIONS
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.people.memphis.edu/~mapepin/migrate3.htm">(1)  BY SUDOC NUMBER</a>
   <br>
   http://www.people.memphis.edu/~mapepin/migrate3.htm
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.people.memphis.edu/~mapepin/titlmig.htm">(2) BY TITLE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.people.memphis.edu/~mapepin/titlmig.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The University of Memphis Government Publications
Department, recognizing that many government documents will soon be available in
electronic format only, has set up two sites (arranged by title and by Superintendent of
Documents classification) that connect users directly to the documents, without regard
for where the document was created.  Although the Memphis sites are not
comprehensive, they serve as an example of how libraries can take a leading role in
helping users navigate the increasingly crowded waters of electronic government
information."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.ed.gov/NCES/pubs/ce/index.html">26.  U.S. DEPT. OF EDUCATION'S NATIONAL CENTER FOR EDUCATION
STATISTICS REPORT, "THE CONDITION OF EDUCATION 1996"</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ed.gov/NCES/pubs/ce/index.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "At the heart of 'The Condition of Education 1996' recently
released on the web by the U.S. Department of Education's National Center for
Education Statistics, are '60 indicators, representing a consensus of professional
judgment on the most significant national measures of the condition and progress of
education.'  Indicators are arranged in six categories: Access, Participation, and
Progress; Achievement, Attainment, and Curriculum; Economic and Other Outcomes of
Education; Size, Growth, and output of Institutions; and Human and Financial
Resources of Educational Institutions.  The complete 1992 and 1994 reports are also
available, along with selections from the 1995 report."</i>
</dd>
</dl>




<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.dol.gov/">27.  U.S. DEPT. OF LABOR: MINIMUM WAGE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.dol.gov/ (then click on "Minimum Wage")
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The U.S. Department of Labor has produced a set of web
pages to help employers and employees understand the implementation of the new
minimum wage law, signed by President Clinton on 8/20/96.  The main page has links
to information for employers, a summary of employees' rights, coverage of minimum
wage laws in each state, and 1996 amendments to the Fair Labor Standards Act.
Users may also follow a link to the DoL's Wage and Hour Division for more complete
information about workplace regulations.  A new minimum wage poster, for posting in
the workplace, is available in Adobe Acrobat (.pdf) format."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.sau.edu/gateway.html">28.  "WHERE THE WILD THINGS ARE: LIBRARIAN'S GUIDE TO THE BEST
INFORMATION ON THE NET"</a>
   <br>
   http://www.sau.edu/gateway.html (and click on "Where the Wild Things Are")
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "St. Ambrose University offers access through the World Wide
Web to 'Where the Wild Things Are: Librarian's Guide to the Best Information on the
Net.'  The site links users to reference sources available on the Internet, including
sections on current news, electronic texts, job guides, and important sites sorted by
academic discipline."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="http://www.law.osaka-u.ac.jp/legal-info/worldlist/worldlst.htm">29.  WORLD LAW RESOURCE LIST: NON-U.S. LAW-RELATED RESOURCES
FOR INTERNET USERS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.osaka-u.ac.jp/legal-info/worldlst.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "This 176KB page, edited and copyrighted by Makoto
Ibusuki, offers legal references for 57 countries with links to each country's government
documents.  The contents page includes internal links to a description of the list, the
Country and Area Index, the Resource Index of each Country and Area, and Reference
Books and Articles for Legal Research on the Internet."</i>
</dd>
</dl>



<center>
<h2>~ L I S T S E R V S ~</h2>
</center>

<dl>
<dt>
   <b>1.  COMPUTER LAW OBSERVER</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Computer Law Observer is distributed each month via e-mail by
Challenge Communications, a legal content provider located in Baltimore, MD.  It is currently written
by William S. Galkin, a lawyer and adjunct professor of computer law at the University of Maryland
School of Law.  Each issue of the Observer contains an article discussing an important legal
development relating to the Internet and computer technology in general.  The articles are written for
both lawyers and non-lawyers." To subscribe:</i>

<p>

   <i>Send e-mail to: </i>ChallComm@aol.com<br>
   <i>And request to be added to the list</i>

</dd>
</dl>


<dl>
<dt>
   <b>2.  CONSTITUTIONAL LAW ABSTRACTS ELECTRONIC NEWSLETTER</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>The Constitutional Law Abstracts newsletter contains summaries of forthcoming articles regarding
constitutional law issues.  To subscribe:</i>

<p>

   <i>Send e-mail to: </i>sandy_barnes@journal.com<br>
   <i>With a message identifying yourself and indicating your interest in subscribing to the Constitutional
Law Abstracts newsletter.</i>

</dd>
</dl>


<dl>
<dt>
   <b>3.  CORELINK DISCUSSION LIST</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Previously a list dedicated to the national standards movement in education
and core curriculum, CORELINK has been re-focused to cover the following subject areas: leading
issues in national educational policy, applications of telecommunications and the Internet to education,
partnerships between business and education involving technology, philosophical and theoretical matters
pertaining to learning and online culture." To subscribe:</i>

<p>

   <i>Send e-mail to: </i>listproc@mercury.cair.du.edu<br>
   <i>With message: subscribe CORELINK &lt;your first name, your last name&gt;</i>

</dd>
</dl>


