<h1>Internet Update #14</h1>

<center>
<h3>THE GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY LAW SCHOOL</h3>
<h3>JACOB BURNS LAW LIBRARY</h3>
<h3>INTERNET UPDATE #14</h3>
<h3>OCTOBER 1996</h3>
</center>

Welcome to the fourteenth issue of the <i>Internet Update</i>, a listing of new and noteworthy websites,
gopher sites, and listserv &amp; newsgroup information.
<p>

<h3>This issue includes the following websites:</h3>


<ol>
  <li>Accounting sites:  (1) Accounting Resources on the Internet--Rutgers University and (2)
Information on International Accounting Network#</li>
  <li>Australian Governments' Entry Point#</li>
  <li>Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) Selective Access Data</li>
  <li>Canadian Information By Subject#</li>
  <li>CataLaw--Index to Legal and Government Resources on the Net</li>
  <li>Census Data for the United States, 1790-1860#</li>
  <li>Darby &amp; Darby, P.C.</li>
  <li>Department of Environmental Health Library</li>
  <li>The Electronic Green Journal</li>
  <li>Emerging Law on the Electronic Frontier</li>
  <li>EPA Environmental Appeals Board</li>
  <li>Far Eastern Economic Review</li>
  <li>GSA's Government Information Xchange#</li>
  <li>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies</li>
  <li>Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy#</li>
  <li>Issues  96 -- New York Times &amp; NPR#</li>
  <li>MEDIAPOLIS#</li>
  <li>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</li>
  <li>National Archives and Records Administration</li>
  <li>National Center For Education Statistics (NCES) -- two new sites:  (1) Youth Indicators 1996
and (2) Historically Black Colleges and Universities 1976-1994#</li>
  <li>NETLiNkS Afrocentric Guide -- addition to site:  (1) The Written Word -- African-American
and Canadian Literature#</li>
  <li>Nixon-Presley Meeting -- George Washington University National Security Archive#</li>
  <li>Perot v. FEC -- full text of Ross Perot's complaint</li>
  <li>PlanetOut &amp; Yahoo PlanetOut Headlines#</li>
  <li>University of Nebraska College of Law &amp; Schmid Law Library</li>
  <li>United Nations Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty Conference on Disarmament
Information and other related documents#</li>
  <li>U.S. Historical Maps -- two sites:  (1) Rare Map Collection at the Hargrett Library, University
of Georgia and (2) "Exploring the West from Monticello: A Perspective in Maps from
Columbus to Lewis and Clark"#</li>
  <li>U.S. Supreme Court Decisions: 1937-1975#</li>
  <li>Verner &amp; Brumley, P.C.</li>
  <li>WWWebster Dictionary#</li>
</ol>


<h3>This issue contains the following listservs:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>AFRI-PHIL, African Culture Discussion List#</li>
  <li>Decluttr--Recovery From Cluttery List#</li>
  <li>EDEM-ELECT, Electronic Democracy &amp; Elections Discussion List#</li>
  <li>E-TEACH, Electronic Teaching in Law School List</li>
  <li>H-SAfrica, South African History Discussion List#</li>
  <li>SourceLaw digital newsletter</li>
  <li>TRIBAL LAW Discussion List</li>
</ol>

<center>
<h2> ~ W E B S I T E S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>
<dt>
   1.  ACCOUNTING SITES<br>
   <a href="http://www.rutgers.edu/accounting/raw/internet/internet.htm">(1)  ACCOUNTING RESOURCES ON THE INTERNET--RUTGERS UNIVERSITY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.rutgers.edu/accounting/raw/internet/internet.htm
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.rutgers.edu/accounting/raw.htm">(2)  INFORMATION ON INTERNATIONAL ACCOUNTING NETWORK</a>
   <br>
   http://www.rutgers.edu/accounting/raw.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Accounting Resources on the Internet, provided by
Rutgers University, provides one-stop shopping for accounting resources.  Here,
interested Internauts can find information on the 'Big Six' accounting firms, links
to over 200 accounting firms in the U.S., U.K., and Canada, 30 different
accounting associations, information on accounting-related publications,
educational, finance, and audit resources, and more.  Accounting Resources is part
of the Rutgers Accounting Web, which in turn, is part of the International
Accounting Network (IAN), at present, includes providers from the U.K., Australia,
Finland, and the University of Hawaii."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.nla.gov.au/oz/gov/">2.  AUSTRALIAN GOVERNMENTS' ENTRY POINT</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nla.gov.au/oz/gov/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Australian Governments' Entry Point has
connections to commonwealth, state, and local government information, as well as
judicial information."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.bls.gov/sahome.html">3.  BUREAU OF LABOR STATISTICS (BLS) SELECTIVE ACCESS DATA</a>
   <br>
   http://www.bls.gov/sahome.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "BLS Selective Access allows users to specify exactly what data they
would like from a large selection of its databases, including local area unemployment statistics,
consumer price indexes, and producer price indexes, among others.  By interacting with the
system four or five times, a user can retrieve a customized table of historical data."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.nlc-bnc.ca/caninfo/ecaninfo.htm">4.  CANADIAN INFORMATION BY SUBJECT</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nlc-bnc.ca/caninfo/ecaninfo.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The National Library of Canada has expanded on
previous websites devoted to information about Canada by building a subject tree
and populating the tree with links to Canadian-specific information on each
subject.  The subject tree is based on the Dewey Decimal Classification and makes
the site easy and interesting to browse--and you don't have to be a librarian.  You
can also browse the subject tree in alphabetical order, and keyword searching will
be available soon."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.CataLaw.com">5.  CATALAW--INDEX TO LEGAL AND GOVERNMENT RESOURCES ON THE
INTERNET</a>
   <br>
   http://www.CataLaw.com
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "CataLaw is the great new searchable metaindex of legal
and government resources on the Internet.  It is the catalog of catalogs of law on
the Internet.  CataLaw speeds research by arranging hundreds of legal and
government indexes into a single, simple, intuitive metaindex.  By using CataLaw,
you can examine the most information in a minimum of time.  CataLaw is a
commercial venture that is accepting advertising sponsorship in an extremely
flexible way.  A very large opening discount is now being offered.  Details are
available at the website."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://icg.harvard.edu/census/">6.  CENSUS DATA FOR THE UNITED STATES, 1790-1860</a>
   <br>
   http://icg.harvard.edu/census/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Instructional Computing Group of Harvard
University, in cooperation with Inter-university Consortium for Political and Social
Research at the University of Michigan, has made a subset of historical data from
U.S. decennial censuses from 1790 to 1860 available for forms-based querying on
the web.  Data availability varies by year and state.  From 1790 to 1830, most data
concerns population breakouts by age, sex, and free or slave.  From 1840 to 1860
much more data is available, including occupation, education, churches, mortality,
and property and wealth, among others.  After year selection, users query the
database for state(s) and variable(s).  Data returned can then be sorted by
variable.  Data are available at the state and county level, although county
querying is not possible.  There is no facility at this time for downloading data to
statistical programs; however, this is a small price to pay for a virtual treasure
house of U.S. historical information."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.darbylaw.com/">7.  DARBY &amp; DARBY, P.C.</a>
   <br>
   http://www.darbylaw.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Darby &amp; Darby, an intellectual property law firm with
offices in Manhattan and Los Angeles, is pleased to announce the availability of its
WWW page.  In addition to information about the firm, you can also learn about
significant developments in IP law at this site."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://weber.u.washington.edu/~dehlib/">8.  DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH LIBRARY</a>
   <br>
   http://weber.u.washington.edu/~dehlib/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The University of Washington has created a home page
on the WWW that offers an extensive guide to the resources of its Department of
Environmental Health Library, along with links to related resources on the
Internet.  The Environmental Health Library Current Contents Bulletin is available
at the site, along with journal and thesis listings and information on legislation
relevant to environmental health."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://drseuss.lib.uidaho.edu:70/docs/egj.html">9.  THE ELECTRONIC GREEN JOURNAL</a>
   <br>
   http://drseuss.lib.uidaho.edu:70/docs/egj.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Electronic Green Journal, published on an
irregular basis by the University of Idaho Library, is a professional publication
devoted to disseminating information concerning sources on international
environmental topics including: assessment, conservation, development, disposal,
education, hazards, pollution, resources, technology, and treatment.  Academically
sponsored, the focus is to publish articles, bibliographies, reviews, and
announcements for the educated generalist as well as the specialist."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.usc.edu/dept/annenberg/journal.html">10.  EMERGING LAW ON THE ELECTRONIC FRONTIER</a>
   <br>
   http://www.usc.edu/dept/annenberg/journal.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The well known Journal of Computer-Mediated
Communication (JCMC), a joint project of the Annenberg School for
Communication at the University of Southern California and the Information
Systems Division of the School of Business Administration, Hebrew University of
Jerusalem, is a net-only journal focusing on  issues that present special challenges
in computer-mediated communication in a globally interconnected 'NetWorld.'"</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.epa.gov/eab/">11.  EPA ENVIRONMENTAL APPEALS BOARD</a>
   <br>
   http://www.epa.gov/eab/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Environmental Appeals Board (EAB) of the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency is the final Agency decision maker on
administrative appeals under all major environmental statutes that EPA
administers.  It is an impartial, three-member body which is independent of all
Agency components outside the Office of the Administrator.  It was created in 1992
in recognition of the growing importance of EPA adjudicatory proceedings as a
mechanism for implementing and enforcing the environmental laws.  The site
includes information on the EAB and how it works as well as '1994 Selected
Highlights' and 'EAB Formal Opinions Issued Since 1992.'"</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.feer.com/">12.  FAR EASTERN ECONOMIC REVIEW</a>
   <br>
   http://www.feer.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "A weekly publication from Review Publishing Company,
the Far Eastern Economic Review, a world authority on Asian current affairs,
business, economies and investment, is now available in an interactive edition on
the web.  This frames-based, free (after registration) site contains the contents of
each week's issue, as well as a searchable archive of articles previously published
on the site.  In addition, articles from recent issues can be browsed by country and
topic (under 'Business News').  The site also provides up-to-the-minute Asian
business news, and pointers to Asian websites.  Note that the registration process is
lengthy, but the content behind it is well worth the wait."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.info.gov/">13.  GSA'S GOVERNMENT INFORMATION XCHANGE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.info.gov/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The GSA has established the Government Information
Xchange in order to facilitate the assimilation, sharing and dissemination of
information resources among federal, state and local governments, and to provide
a convenient forum for all levels of government to share and exchange information
with businesses and the American public.  The Xchange is a page of links to
federal, state, and local government information providers, as well as selected
foreign government sources.  It is searchable as well as browsable."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/glsj.html">14.  INDIANA JOURNAL OF GLOBAL LEGAL STUDIES</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/glsj.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Indiana University School of Law publishes an
electronic edition of Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies on the WWW.  The
peer-reviewed, interdisciplinary journal examines the relationship between
domestic and international law, and culture, economics, and politics.  Topics
include environmental law, immigration policy, and international trade and
investment."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   15.  INSTITUTE FOR AGRICULTURE AND TRADE POLICY
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.iatp.org/iatp/">http://www.iatp.org/iatp/</a>
   <br>
   <a href="gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:70/11/trade/iatp">gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:70/11/trade/iatp</a>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy, an
organization whose  mission is to create environmentally and economically
sustainable communities and regions through sound agriculture and trade policy,
has recently upgraded its website to include information on the Institute's projects
and publications in the fields of trade, agriculture, and the environment.  One of
the highlights of the site is its Global Food Security Resources section, which
provides a Food Security Resources Guide, a selected bibliography of 55 resources
in the subject, and 10 full-text IATP documents on it.  The website is an
enhancement of the IATP's gopher site."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/issues/">16.  ISSUES  96--NEW YORK TIMES &amp; NPR</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nytimes.com/issues/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Issues  96 is  a six week online collaboration by The
New York Times on the Web and National Public Radio focussing on the issues in
this fall's U.S. election campaign.'  In the areas of community, money, rights,
safety, and world, the site offers synopses of several sub-issues, a collection of NPR
and New York Times stories about the issues, a primer on the issues (produced by
'the nonpartisan research group Public Agenda'), forums hosted by NPR
correspondents or other experts, and 'Where They Stand,' which points to the party
platforms on the issues.  There are also links to Project Vote Smart and the Library
of Congress' Thomas service.  In addition, the site contains transcripts and audio
clips on issues from local voters (part of NPR's Election Project).  The highlight of
the site is the availability of over 120 articles, transcripts, and audio files from the
two sponsors."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.partal.com/mediapolis/ANG/index.html">17.  MEDIAPOLIS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.partal.com/mediapolis/ANG/index.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "MEDIAPOLIS, provided by Lavinia TV and BiB Media,
is meant to be  a whole resources index about mass media about the Net.  To that
end, this frames-based site has compiled a large number of international
(predominantly European and American) links to press, radio, TV, news agencies,
university media, and advertising.  While the site is a work in progress and the
strength of each section varies, the press section is particularly strong.  The fact
that MEDIAPOLIS is organized on international lines also is a plus.  At present the
site is available in English, Spanish, and French."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.ksc.nasa.gov/legal/newsletter/environment/">18.  NATIONAL AERONAUTICS AND SPACE ADMINISTRATION</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ksc.nasa.gov/legal/newsletter/environment/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The National Aeronautics and Space Administration
offers access to  'Environmental Newsletter.'  Developed by the Kennedy Space
Center's Office of the Chief Counsel, the monthly publication provides users with
information on proposed or recently issued federal and state regulations and
rulings, and legislation on environmental issues.  Topics include air, waste, and
water regulations, health &amp; safety, and new technology."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.nara.gov/nara/electronic/">19.  NATIONAL ARCHIVES AND RECORDS ADMINISTRATION</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nara.gov/nara/electronic/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "National Archives and Records Administration has
added information about the Center for Electronic Records to its site to the WWW. 
The site provides information on how to gain access to the Center's holdings,
which include records created by Congress, the courts, the White House,
Presidential commissions, and executive-branch departments and agencies."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   20.  NATIONAL CENTER FOR EDUCATION STATISTICS (NCES)
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.ed.gov/NCES/pubs/yi/">(1)  YOUTH INDICATORS 1996</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ed.gov/NCES/pubs/yi/
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.ed.gov/NCES/pubs/96902.html">(2)  HISTORICALLY BLACK COLLEGES AND UNIVERSITIES</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ed.gov/NCES/pubs/96902.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The U.S. Department of Education's National Center
for Education Statistics (NCES) has recently made two publications (in .pdf
format) available at its website.  Youth Indicators 1996: Trends in the Well-Being
of American Youth is 'a statistical compilation of data on family structure, jobs,
education, and other elements that comprise the world of young people.'  It
contains 69 tables and charts covering such subjects as demographics, family
income, health, employment, and educational outcomes, among others.  The tables
and charts, which generally present data from the early 1970s to the early 1990s,
are intended to give quick, concise information.  Historically Black Colleges and
Universities 1976-1994 is a 112-page statistical review of all aspects of its topic,
highlighted by 9 charts and 54 tables covering enrollment, degrees conferred, staff
and salaries, finance, revenue, and expenditures.  The Executive Summary and
Introduction, which appear on the website, encapsulate the findings."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   21.  NETLINKS AFROCENTRIC GUIDE
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.netlinks.net/Netlinks/AFRO/words.html">(1)  THE WRITTEN WORD--AFRICAN-AMERICAN AND CANADIAN LITERATURE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.netlinks.net/Netlinks/AFRO/words.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "NETLiNkS Afrocentric Guide to the WWW has recently
added 'The Written Word' to its compilation of African-American and Canadian
resources.  This annotated pointers page includes an eclectic collection of
information and full-text sites.  Included are individual works, collections of works,
historic speeches, and connections to such sites as H-AFRARTS, The Quarterly
Black Review of Books, and other meta-collections of African-American literature,
among others.  Also included in the Afrocentric Guide are Afro Web Directory,
Events Calendar, Black History Archive, and Flavour of the Week.  It is one of the
better Afrocentric meta-indexes on the web."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.seas.gwu.edu/nsarchive/nsa/elvis/elnix.html">22.  NIXON-PRESLEY MEETING--GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY
NATIONAL SECURITY ARCHIVE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.seas.gwu.edu/nsarchive/nsa/elvis/elnix.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "One of the highlights of the recently opened National
Security Archive website is the Richard Nixon-Elvis Presley meeting section.  After
writing a six-page letter in which he suggested being made a ' Federal
Agent-at-Large in the Bureau of Narcotics and Dangerous Drugs,' Elvis Presley
visited President Nixon on 12/21/70.  This site contains an image of the actual
letter along with a transcription, and several presidential staff memoranda
regarding the meeting (in .gif format).  In addition, there is background on the
meeting and photographs from it.  The Nixon-Presley meeting is but one example
of declassified documents that the Archive has acquired through FOIA and made
available at the site.  In addition, the Archive contains material on the Cuban
Missile Crisis, selected White House e-mail, and a searchable catalog of
bibliographic records in its Nuclear Non-Proliferation Database (1945-1990)."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.ljx.com/topstories/perot.html">23.  PEROT V FEC--FULL TEXT OF ROSS PEROT'S COMPLAINT</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ljx.com/topstories/perot.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The full text of Ross Perot's complaint against the
Federal Election Commission and the Commission on Presidential Debates is
available.  A Washington, D.C. federal judge is to hear arguments on why the
presidential debates should not be permitted to go forward without him.  The first
debate is set for Oct. 6."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   24.  PLANETOUT &amp; YAHOO PLANETOUT HEADLINES
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.planetout.com/">(1)  PLANETOUT</a>, http://www.planetout.com/
   <br>
   <a href="http://headlines.yahoo.com/planetout">(2)  YAHOO PLANETOUT HEADLINES</a>, http://headlines.yahoo.com/planetout
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Available since mid-1995 on the Microsoft Network
(MSN), PlanetOut moves to the Web (as well as onto America Online, a major
sponsor of the site).  Calling itself a  'worldwide community of gay, lesbian, bi, and
transpeople,' the site offers a new home for the longstanding Queer Resources
Directory (QRD), which since 1991 has been the Internet starting point for
researchers and others interested in issues of marginal sexualities.  In addition,
there is a  'netQueery,' as well as arts and entertainment features, political and
community pages, and chat and message areas.  The news section is updated daily,
and is also available in the PlanetOut section of the Yahoo Headlines service. 
Though the site is new to the Web, it shows considerable polish that is the result of
a year's presence on MSN.  Registration is free and optional."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   25.  UNIVERSITY OF NEBRASKA COLLEGE OF LAW &amp; SCHMID LAW LIBRARY
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.unl.edu/lawcoll/">(1)  LAW COLLEGE</a>, http://www.unl.edu/lawcoll/
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.unl.edu/lawcoll/library">(2)  SCHMID LAW LIBRARY</a>, http://www.unl.edu/lawcoll/library
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The University of Nebraska College of Law and the
Schmid Law Library invite you to visit our home page.  We are still under
construction and would welcome your ideas and comments.  Please send them to
Sally Wise, sallyw@unllib.unl.edu."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.unog.ch/frames/disarm/disset.htm">26.  UNITED NATIONS COMPREHENSIVE NUCLEAR TEST BAN TREATY
CONFERENCE ON DISARMAMENT INFORMATION</a>
   <br>
   http://www.unog.ch/frames/disarm/disset.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Full text of the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban
Treaty, adopted by the UN General Assembly on September 10, 1996, is available
(in .pdf format) from the UN Office (Geneva) website.  In addition, the site
contains information on the Conference on Disarmament, as well as selected full
texts of major international documents on disarmanent and related issues,
including  Prohibition of the Use in War of Asphyxiating, Poisonous or Other
Gases' (1925), Geneva Convention documents (1949), 'Partial Test Ban Treaty'
(1963), and  Convention on the Prohibition of the Development, Production,
Stockpiling and Use of Chemical Weapons' (1993), among many others.  Some of
these documents are in .pdf format, others are ASCII text. Connections to the free
Adobe Acrobat reader can be obtained from the Conference on Disarmament
Information home page."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   27.  U.S. HISTORICAL MAPS
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.libs.uga.edu/darchive/hargrett/maps/maps.html">(1)  RARE MAP COLLECTION OF THE HARGRETT LIBRARY, UNIVERSITY OF
GEORGIA</a>
   <br>
   http://www.libs.uga.edu/darchive/hargrett/maps/maps.html
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.lib.virginia.edu/exhibits/lewis_clark/home.html">(2)  "EXPLORING THE WEST FROM MONTICELLO: A PERSPECTIVE IN  MAPS
FROM COLUMBUS TO LEWIS AND CLARK"</a>
   <br>
   http://www.lib.virginia.edu/exhibits/lewis_clark/home.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Two of the more impressive historical map sites on the
Internet are: the Rare Map Collection at the Hargrett Library, University of
Georgia; and 'Exploring the West from Monticello: A Perspective in Maps from
Columbus to Lewis and Clark,' a collection of maps and navigational instruments
taken from an exhibition at the University of Virginia's Alderman Library. 
Hargrett's collection contains hundreds of image, and, as might be expected,
specializes in Georgia historical maps.  However, it also contains many national
and international maps from the early new world, colonial, US Revolutionary and
post-Revolutionary eras.  The actual size of each map is indicated and author is
given when available.   'Exploring the West...' contains 33 items, topically
arranged, from 'Novus Orbis: Images of the New World, 1507-1669,' to 'To the
Western Ocean: Planning the Lewis and Clark Expedition.'  The power of this site
is not so much in the maps themselves, but in the lavish annotations that
accompany them.  A bibliography and pointers to related sites are included."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.fedworld.gov/supcourt/index.htm">28.  U.S. SUPREME COURT DECISIONS: 1937-1975</a>
   <br>
   http://www.fedworld.gov/supcourt/index.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Full text of U.S. Supreme Court Decisions from 1937 to
1975 (7,407 decisions from volumes 300 through 422 of U.S. Reports) has been
made available via the U.S. Air Force FLITE (Federal Legal Information Through
Electronics) system.  Users may access the decisions through a search interface
that presently allows querying by keyword or case name.  Decisions are available
in ASCII format."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://vernbrum.wld.com">29.  VERNER &amp; BRUMLEY, P.C.</a>
   <br>
   http://vernbrum.wld.com
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Verner &amp; Brumley, P.C., announces its website.  Verner
&amp; Brumley, based in Dallas, TX, restricts its practice to family law.  The firm's
four attorneys prosecute and defend family law cases throughout the state."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www-lj.eb.com/mw/">30.  WWWEBSTER DICTIONARY</a>
   <br>
   http://www-lj.eb.com/mw/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Britannica Online has made Merriam-Webster's
WWWebster Dictionary available for searching on the web.  Each retrieved word is
accompanied by pronunciation, usage, grammatical function, a brief etymology,
and of course, definition.  A thesaurus can be queried for similar words, hypertext
cross references are available, misspellings return suggested spellings, and there
are hypertext links to illustrations. The search system supports internal wildcards
(single and multiple letter) and right hand truncation searching.  There is also an
extensive pronunciation guide.  In addition to the dictionary, the site also contains
selected transcripts of the syndicated radio show, 'Word for the Wise.'"</i>
</dd>
</dl>

<center>
<h2>~ L I S T S E R V S ~</h2>
</center>


<dl>
<dt>
   <b>1.  AFRI-PHIL, AFRICAN CULTURE DISCUSSION LIST</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "The primary purpose of AFRI-PHIL is to provide a forum for the
exchange of views, experiences, techniques, and philosophical information pertaining to the
teaching and study of African and African-diaspora cultures.  The principal emphasis of the list
will be upon the philosophical examination of African thought and culture, though this emphasis
should not be taken restrictively or in a manner excluding the consideration of other approaches
(e.g., literary, historical, anthropological, etc.)."  To subscribe:</i>

<p>

<i>Send e-mail to:</i>  LISTSERV@BUCKNELL.EDU<br>
<i>With the message:</i> SUB AFRI-PHIL &lt;your name&gt;.

</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <b>2.  DECLUTTR--RECOVERY FROM CLUTTERING MAILING LIST</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Decluttr is for discussion of recovery from cluttering (aka messiness,
hoarding).  It is primarily for clutterers; but family members and professional are welcome. 
Appropriate topics include personal experiences, helpful organizations, and useful books."</i>

<p>

<i>Send e-mail to: </i> LISTSERV@SJUVM.STJOHNS.EDU<br>
<i>With the message:</i>  SUB Decluttr &lt;your name&gt;

</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <b>3.  EDEM-ELECT, ELECTRONIC DEMOCRACY &amp; ELECTIONS DISCUSSION LIST</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "EDEM-ELECT has been established to promote citizen exchange
efforts during the election season.  EDEM-ELECT intends to bring together those working to
facilitate online public discussion and participation in elections held in 1996 or 1997. 
Depending upon the usefulness of this forum its charter may be expanded or reduced.  For now,
EDEM-ELECT is focused on the exchange of ideas, plans, and experiences among individuals
and groups working across the world to develop local, regional, or national efforts. 
EDEM-ELECT will concentrate on the  how to's' of organizing local, non-partisan efforts; such
as how to recruit volunteers, how to work with campaigns, the media and political organizations,
and how to coordinate the technical and social/political aspects of online open forums.  It must
be noted, however, this list is not for abstract discourse on the virtues and/or vices of
representative and/or direct democracy."  To subscribe,</i>

<p>

<i>Send e-mail to: </i> listproc@mtn.org<br>
<i>With the message:</i> subscribe edem-elect &lt;your name&gt;

</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <b>4.  E-TEACH, ELECTRONIC TEACHING IN LAW SCHOOLS LIST</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "E-TEACH is an Internet Listserv residing on the Chicago-Kent
College of Law SUN Ultra-l.  The list is for general discussion of electronic teaching and
learning issues in law schools.  The group is a private one, limited to law professors,
administrators, and technical staff interested in these issues."  To subscribe:</i>

<p>

<i>Send e-mail to: </i> listserv@chicagokent.kentlaw.edu<br>
<i>With the message:</i>  Subscribe E-TEACH &lt;your name, position, and institution&gt;

</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <b>5.  H-SAFRICA, SOUTH AFRICAN HISTORY DISCUSSION LIST</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "H-SAfrica is a new electronic discussion group dedicated to the
promotion of all aspects of South African history.  H-SAfrica can be described as a cross
between an academic journal and a friendly academic newspaper that is delivered to your
electronic mailbox on an almost daily basis.  It will provide all sorts of useful information, like
international job adverts, book reviews, conference announcements and calls for papers. 
Subscribers will be notified at times of new computer software, websites, films and videos."  To
subscribe:</i>

<p>

<i>Send e-mail to:</i>  listserv@h-net.msu.edu<br>
<i>With the message:</i>  SUB H-SAfrica &lt;your name, institution&gt;

</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <b>6.  SOURCELAW DIGITAL NEWSLETTER</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "SourceLaw is a digital newsletter that covers international online
legal and government resources, including the Internet, America Online, CompuServe, Prodigy,
Microsoft Network and other commercial services, and U.S. federal and state court electronic
bulletin board systems.  SourceLaw offers news and updates geared to the needs of law
librarians, legal researchers, paralegals, legal educators, lawyers and legal services consumers. 
SourceLaw costs $59 for an annual subscription."  To request an introductory free subscription
(three issues) or to subscribe:</i>

<p>

<i>Send e-mail to: </i> jimevans@sourcelaw.com  <i>-or-</i>  sourcelaw@aol.com

</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <b>7.  TRIBAL LAW DISCUSSION LIST</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement: "Tribal Law is an open forum that will enable interaction by  native
people and others interested in the laws and policy that effect Native Americans on the North
American continent.  Students, teachers, and professionals, as well as anyone else interested in
the subject matter, may post and discuss legal and policy issues regarding recent tribal, state,
and federal court decisions, Indian public policy, social services and the legal history of Native
Americans within the United States and Canada.  It is our hope that through this forum people
may become better informed and will also be able to use the list for research and discussion as
well as for posting their tribe's recent tribal court decisions for discussion and analysis."  To
subscribe:</i>

<p>

<i>Send e-mail to:</i>  listserv@thecity.sfsu.edu<br>
<i>With the message:</i>  subscribe triballaw &lt;your name&gt;

</dd>
</dl>

