<body>

<h1>Internet Update #3</h1>
<center>
<h3>THE GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY LAW SCHOOL</h3>
<h3>JACOB BURNS LAW LIBRARY</h3>
<h3>INTERNET UPDATE #3</h3>
<h3>NOVEMBER 1995</h3>
</center>

Welcome to the third issue of the <i>Internet Update</i>, a listing of new and noteworthy websites,
gopher sites, and listserv &amp; newsgroup information.
<p>

<h3>This issue includes the following websites:</h3>


<ol>
  <li>American Arbitration Association</li>
  <li>Court TV Law Center</li>
  <li>Elderlaw Resources</li>
  <li>Emory Law School Web -- new links: (1)  Federal Circuit Court of Appeals Online, (2) 
Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals Online, and (3)  Tenth Circuit Court of Appeals Online</li>
  <li>EPA Region 2</li>
  <li>European Law Journal</li>
  <li>InterCat</li>
  <li>MSU-CIBER (International Business Resources on the WWW)</li>
  <li>National Conference of State Legislatures WWW</li>
  <li>TaxSites:  Income Tax Information on the Internet</li>
  <li>United States Senate</li>
  <li>University of Michigan Law School</li>
 </ol>


<h3>This issue includes the following gopher sites:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>People of Color Environmental Groups Directory</li>
</ol>


<h3>This issue includes the following listservs:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>EPA INTERNET NEWSBRIEF</li>
  <li>IMMPROF (Immigration Law Discussion Group)</li>
  <li>LWSCHOLAR (Legal Scholarship Discussion Group)</li>
  <li>TEACHLAWRES-L (LR&amp;W Discussion Group)</li>
</ol>

<center>
<h2> ~ W E B S I T E S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.adr.org">1.  AMERICAN ARBITRATION ASSOCIATION</a>
   <br>
   http://www.adr.org/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>This website contains materials concerning alternative dispute resolution methods, statutes, rules,
scholarly articles, etc.</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.courttv.com">2.  COURT TV LAW CENTER</a>
   <br>
   http://www.courttv.com
</dt>
<dd>
<i>This website contains many full-text documents ready for downloading or reading, including transcripts of the Menendez retrial, Nixon's and Elvis's wills, etc.</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.panix.com/~goldfarb/elderlaw.html">3.  ELDERLAW RESOURCES</a>
   <br>
   http://www.panix.com/~goldfarb/elderlaw.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>The New York law firm of Goldfarb and Abrandt has created a website that contains links to various resources about the law and how it effects senior citizens, as well as articles about the
rights of the elderly and disabled, guardianships, and trusts and estates.</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   4.  EMORY LAW SCHOOL--NEW LINKS
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/fedcircuit/">(1)  FEDERAL CIRCUIT COURT OF APPEALS ONLINE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.emory.edu/fedcircuit/
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/7circuit/">(2)  SEVENTH CIRCUIT COURT OF APPEALS ONLINE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.emory.edu/7circuit/
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/10circuit/">(3)  TENTH CIRCUIT COURT OF APPEALS ONLINE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.emory.edu/10circuit/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i></i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.epa.gov/Region2/">5.  EPA REGION 2</a>
   <br>
   http://www.epa.gov/Region2/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The EPA's Region 2, which encompasses New York, New Jersey, Puerto Rico, and the United States Virgin Islands, has just established a homepage.  Although the website is still under construction, it presently provides background on Jeanne Fox, the Regional Administrator; access to 'Highlights,' the region's external newsletter; Region 2 public notices; and an overview of the Region 2 library.  Information on special projects, regional initiatives, and programs are also provided, including the Environmental Justice GIS Mapping Project, Region 2 pollution prevention activities, and 3-dimensional views of contaminated sediments in the New
York/New Jersey harbor. Links to related government and environmental sites throughout the region as well as links to resources on the Agency's homepage are also available."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.iue.it/LAW/ELJ/Welcome.html">6.  EUROPEAN LAW JOURNAL</a>
   <br>
   http://www.iue.it/LAW/ELJ/Welcome.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>The European Law Journal is designed to fill a major gap in the current literature in law and other social sciences on issues of European Law.  Based at the European University Institute in
Florence and published in English, it brings together contributions across disciplines and national academic traditions.  The main focus is on the law of the European Union.  Tables of contents and abstracts for Volume 1, Issues 1 &amp; 2 are currently available.</i>
</dd>
<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.oclc.org:6990/">7.  INTERCAT</a>
   <br>
   http://www.oclc.org:6990/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>This website is an experimental database, created by OCLC, that includes bibliographic records for over 1000 Internet resources, searchable by author or keyword.</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://ciber.bus.msu.edu/busres.htm">8.  MSU-CIBER (INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS RESOURCES ON THE WWW)</a>
   <br>
   http://ciber.bus.msu.edu/busres.htm<p>
</dt>
<dd>
<i>From the website's introductory statement:  "Michigan State University's Center for International Business Education and Research (MSU-CIBER) has been designated as a national resource
center in international business education by the U.S. Department of Education.  MSU-CIBER draws on the vast international expertise and resources of Michigan State University to enhance
management education and research and to assist businesses as they address the challenge of competing in the global marketplace.  Under the guidance of its Business Advisory Council, MSU-CIBER designs and implements activities for local, regional, and national impact."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.ncsl.org/">9.  NATIONAL CONFERENCE OF STATE LEGISLATURES WWW</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ncsl.org/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>This website includes links to the National Conference of State Legislature's (NCSL) publications and databases which provide information about upcoming NCSL events and conferences,
information about NCSL itself, and links to other public policy websites.</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.best.com/~ftmexpat/html/taxsites.html">10.  TAXSITES:  INCOME TAX INFORMATION ON THE INTERNET</a>
   <br>
   http://www.best.com/~ftmexpat/html/taxsites.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "This website, prepared and maintained by Frank McNeil, lists and describes Internet sites that have information useful to income tax preparers.  The site includes links to foreign, federal and state tax forms and instructions, articles about taxes, relevant laws and regulations, newsgroups and listservs, software, vendor products, proposed changes to U.S. tax laws, and much more.  A very carefully thought-out site with much to offer.  Updated often."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.senate.gov/">11.  UNITED STATES SENATE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.senate.gov/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The United States Senate's World Wide Web server provides information from and about the members of the Senate, Senate Committees, and Senate leadership and support offices.  This evolving service also provides general background information about U.S. Senate legislative procedures, Senate facilities in the Capitol Building, and the history of the Senate.  Welcome!"</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.law.umich.edu/">12.  UNIVERSITY OF MICHIGAN LAW SCHOOL</a>
   <br>
   http://www.law.umich.edu/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From their announcement:  "The University of Michigan Law School is proud to announce the unveiling of its Internet site on the World Wide Web.  The site is designed to provide a forum to
meet the information needs of alumni, faculty, staff, current and prospective students, and the global legal community on the Internet.  Serving a role as the central repository for information about the University of Michigan Law School, the site includes many helpful features.  The entire site can be searched by key word using a search form or the search box on the main page.  Databases of all kinds can be searched as well, including a faculty/staff directory, course schedules, course descriptions and an event calendar.  Among the many online publications
include our alumni magazine, Law Quad Notes, as well as numerous student legal journals.  Web conferences are also being implemented on the site.  These threaded message groups allow users to create discussions on a wide variety of topics and reply to the messages authored by others."</i>
</dd>

</dl>

<center>
<h2> ~G O P H E R  S I T E S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>
<dt>
   <a href="gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org/11/pubs/envcolor94">1.  PEOPLE OF COLOR ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS DIRECTORY</a>
   <br>
   gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org/11/pubs/envcolor94
</dt>
<dd>
<i>From the announcement:  "Compiled by Dr. Robert D. Bullard of the University of California, Riverside, the 1992 People of Color Environmental Groups Directory was intended to serve as a
networking tool for environmental justice activists at the grass-roots level by providing these organizations with an awareness of like-minded groups and thereby facilitating the sharing of
information and activities.  The 1994-95 update provides not only updated data for organizations in the United States, but also includes entries for Canada and Mexico, and a  list of legal resource groups.  In addition to the basic information such as name, address, and phone number, each entry in the directory provides a brief mission statement, issues addressed by the organization, type of activities, constituency served, geographic focus, and membership base, among other data."</i>
</dd>

</dl>

<center>
<h2> ~ L I S T S E R V S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>
<dt>
   <b>1.  EPA INTERNET NEWSBRIEF</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Internet Newsbrief is a weekly service from the EPA Headquarters Library that provides a sampling of new and/or useful Internet resources for EPA staff and other environmental professionals."  To subscribe</i>:

<p>

<i>send to:  </i>listserver@unixmail.rtpnc.epa.gov<br>
<i>with the message:  </i>subscribe INTERNETNB-L &lt;first name, last name&gt;
</dd>
<p>


<dt>
   <b>2.  IMMPROF (IMMIGRATION LAW LIST)</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "A new Internet discussion list has been created for Immigration Law professors.  `IMMPROF' is open to those who teach Immigration Law (whether full or part time) and to professors who have significant research interests in this area.  The list is intended to create a forum for Immigration Law professors to discuss current topics and share ideas."  To subscribe:</i>

<p>

<i>send to:  </i>listproc@lists.colorado.edu<br>
<i>with the message:  </i>subscribe immprof &lt;your name, position, &amp;institution&gt;

</dd>
<p>

<dt>
   <b>3.  LWSCHOLAR (LEGAL SCHOLARSHIP DISCUSSION GROUP)</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Announcing LWSCHOLAR, a new Internet discussion list of the Association of American Law Schools(AALS) Provisional Section of Scholarship and Law Reviews.  It is directed at full-time faculty members of AALS member and fee-paid law schools.  The list services in lieu of a newsletter, with its purpose being to disseminate information about the section.  LWSCHOLAR members discuss issues of legal scholarship and law reviews among law professors."  To subscribe:</i>

<p>

<i>send to:  </i>majordomo@cwsl.edu<br>
<i>with the message:  </i>subscribe lwscholar &lt;your name&gt;

</dd>
<p>


<dt>
   <b>4.  TEACHLAWRES-L (LR&amp;W DISCUSSION GROUP)</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "This discussion list is devoted to the topic of teaching legal research in all kinds of settings, using all types of instruction.  Topics raised may include:  Efforts to coordinate legal research instruction among law school, law firm and court libraries; Innovative teaching techniques; and preferred research strategies."  To subscribe:</i>

<p>
<i>send to:  </i>listproc@lawlib.wuacc.edu<br>
<i>with the message:  </i>subscribe teachlawres-l &lt;first name, last name&gt;

</dd>
</dl>


<hr>

<i>Internet Update</i> is compiled by Leslie A. Lee, Reference Librarian at the Jacob Burns Law
Library, and is issued monthly as a service to the George Washington University Law School
community.

