<html>
<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Natural Science, Mathematics and Physical Education Courses
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alinf=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3>
Natural Science, Mathematics and Physical Education</font><br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions<p><hr size=8>
Biology</font><hr>
BIO 101 General Biology</b><br>
A course designed for the non-science major. Topics discussed are principles of biology; structure-function-environmental interactions of organisms and current social/economic issues which have a biological base. (Offered every spring semester)			(4)
<hr>
BIO 105 Environmental Science</b><br>
An exploration of interrelationships of environmental factors and how they influence and are influenced by national and global environmental problems. Also listed as ENV 105. (Offered every fall semester)							(4)
<hr>
BIO 125 Cell Structure and Function</b><br>
An investigation of life at the cellular level which emphasizes: the structure and function of cell organelles; the interaction of cells in the structure and function of multicellular organisms; and developmental processes in various eukaryotic organisms. Conceptual frameworks for doing science are also explored. (Offered every spring semester)								(4)
<hr>
BIO 202 Human Biology</b><br>
Prerequisite: sophomore standing or consent of instructor. Fundamentals of cell biology, developmental biology and genetics provide a basis for survey of normal structure, function and interaction of human organ systems. A variety of modern health issues such as nutrition, cancer, alcoholism, heart disease and aging are explored. This course is not intended for natural science and nursing majors. (Offered every spring semester)														(4)
<hr>
BIO 203 Anatomy and Physiology I</b><br>
Development, structure and function of cells and tissues; structure and function of the nervous and endocrine systems. (Offered every fall semester)													(4)
<hr>
BIO 204 Anatomy and Physiology II</b><br>
Prerequisite: BIO 203. Structure, function and interrelationships of vertebrate organ systems. (Offered every spring semester)	(4)
<hr>
BIO 205 Zoology</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 105, BIO 125. Basic concepts of animal physiology, ecology and evolutionary biology followed by a phylogenetic survey of the invertebrate animals (including the unicellular protistans) and the vertebrae animals. The concept of natural selection as a determinate of animal structure and function serves as the focal point for this foundation course. (Offered every fall semester)		(4)
<hr>
BIO 206 Ornithology</b><br>
Avian biology emphasizing identification, behavioral patterns and adaptations for survival. (Offered as needed)		(4)
<hr>
BIO 207 Microbiology</b><br>
Prerequisite: BIO 203 or BIO 125. Bacteria and other microorganisms and their importance; aseptic techniques, methods of staining and isolation of bacteria, and various aspects of microbial physiology and control; lecture and laboratory. (Offered every spring semester)	(4)
<hr>
BIO 295 Introductory Topics in Biology</b><br>
Prerequisite: to be determined by the Division of Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education. An introductory study of a specific topic in biology. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in biology. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)										(1-3)
<hr>
BIO 309 Medical Microbiology</b><br>
Prerequisite: BIO 207. Characterization, isolation, identification, and the relationships of bacteria, fungi, and viruses to disease; lecture and laboratory. (Offered as needed)										(4)
<hr>
BIO 310 Immunology</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 207, CHM 206. An introductory course in immunology in which the basic principles and concepts are stressed. Topics to be studied include the nature of antigens, haptens, immunoglobulins, complement and their interactions; the structure, behavior, and interactions of the cell types involved in the immune response; natural resistance and acquired immunity; immune tolerance; allergies; autoimmunity; immune deficiencies; and the histocompatibility complex. (Offered as needed)							(3)
<hr>
BIO 318 Genetics</b><br>
Prerequisite: BIO 125. Animals, plants and microorganisms are used to illustrate the principles of heredity including a consideration of classical Mendelian transmission genetics, molecular genetics and population genetics. Students conduct a limited research project and a seminar on a specific topic. Problem-solving approach is emphasized. (Offered alternate years)					(4)
<hr>
BIO 324 Invertebrate Zoology</b><br>
Prerequisite: BIO 205. An organ systems approach to a study of the adaptations of various invertebrate species to the marine, freshwater and terrestrial environments. Each student completes a self-designed and executed research project. (Offered as needed)			(4)
<hr>
BIO 326 Vertebrate Zoology</b><br>
Prerequisite: BIO 203 or BIO 205. The evolutionary relationships of vertebrate groups, their organ systems and the homeostatic functions of those systems in their physiological and behavioral adaptations. (Offered alternate years)							(4)
<hr>
BIO 327 Botany</b><br>
Interrelationships of structure, function and reproduction as they apply to flowering plants. (Offered every spring semester)	(4)
<hr>
BIO 328 Advanced Plant Biology</b><br>
Prerequisite: BIO 327. Development, anatomy-morphology; life-history patterns and evolution of the major plant groups of vascular plants. (Offered as needed)			(4)
<hr>
BIO 330 Developmental Biology</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 125, BIO 205. Common principles of development at the organism, tissue, cellular and molecular level are illustrated with selected invertebrate and vertebrate animals, plants and microorganisms. In addition to the classical concepts of gametogenesis, embryology and regeneration, this course covers such developmental phenomena as growth, pattern formation, cell and tissue movements, tissue interactions and cytodifferentiation. (Offered as needed)				(4)
<hr>
BIO 337 Ecology and Evolution</b><br>
Prerequisite: BIO 125. Qualitative and quantitative study of the interrelationships of the organism and the environment. (Offered alternate years)				(4)
<hr>
BIO 341 Kinesiology</b><br>
Prerequisite: BIO 204. Application of biomechanical principles to the movement of the human body. Emphasis on the muscles of the extremities, head, neck and trunk including interventions, actions, group actions and palpations. Laboratory includes activity analysis with practice sessions. (Offered every fall semester)		(3) 
<hr>
BIO 343 Neuroanatomy and Physiology</b><br>
Prerequisite: BIO 204. Detailed study of the development, morphology, internal configuration, function and pathological defects of the central nervous system. (Offered every fall semester)						(4)
<hr>
BIO 351 Comparative Animal Physiology</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 125, CHM 206. This course examines the physiological functions of animal systems in regard to internal and external homeostasis and regulation. (Offered as needed)(4)
<hr>
BIO 353 Cell and Molecular Biology</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 125, BIO 318. Detailed treatment of ultrastructure and function of eukaryotic cells is balanced with the study of cellular function at the molecular level which includes bioenergetics, metabolism, metabolic regulation and membrane phenomena. Students also develop an appreciation for appropriate techniques and current literature. (Offered alternate years)			(4)
<hr>
BIO 399 Independent Study</b><br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(2-4)
<hr>
BIO 440 Natural Science Seminar</b><br>
Prerequisite: junior or senior standing. Presentation, analysis, discussion and integration of current topics in the natural sciences as developed in the literature. (Offered every odd fall semester)						(1)
<hr>
BIO 495 Advanced Topics in Biology</b><br>
Prerequisite: to be determined by the Division of Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education. An advanced study of a specific topic within biology. Intended for juniors and seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in biology. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)	(1-3)
<hr>
BIO 499 Senior Research</b><br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(2-4)
<hr size=8>

<font size=+2>Chemistry</font>
<hr>
CHM 107 Elements of Physiological Chemistry</b><br>
This is an introductory course designed to develop an understanding of the human body's basic biochemicals and their activities. It is intended for students in health-related fields. Emphasis is on genetics, control of proteins, synthesis, food digestion and intermediate metabolism. (Offered every fall semester)				(3)
<hr>
CHM 111 General Chemistry </b><br>
Introduction to fundamental chemical principles and concepts. Emphasis on atomic and molecular structure, basic bonding theory and reactions in an aqueous environment. Oriented toward medical and biochemistry applications. Strong laboratory component. Lecture and Laboratory. (Offered every fall semester)	 	(4)
<hr>
CHM 206 Organic Chemistry I</b><br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in CHM 111 or instructor's permission. Principles of covalent bonding as they apply to aliphatic and aromatic systems, including Lewis structures, molecular geometry and bond polarity. Analytical techniques such as ultraviolet and infrared spectroscopy are used to investigate structure. High emphasis is placed on the knowledge of nomenclature and functional group chemistry. An introduction to reaction mechanisms and stereochemistry is provided. Laboratory work stresses functional groups separation techniques and qualitative analysis. Lecture and Laboratory. (Offered every spring semester) 	(4)
<hr>
CHM 207 Organic Chemistry II</b><br>
Prerequisite: CHM 206. Synthesis and analysis of organic compounds. Nuclear magnetic resonance and infrared spectroscopic analysis as a tool in the identification of unknowns. Insights into electrophilic and nucleophilic reaction mechanisms. Laboratory emphasizes synthetic schemes and qualitative organic analysis. (Offered every fall semester)			(4)
<hr>
CHM 212 Advanced Chemical Principles</b><br> 
Prerequisite: CHM 207 or consent of instructor. Advanced bonding concepts, chemical kinetics and thermodynamics. Solution equilibria, solubility and complexion ion equilibria, and electrochemistry. Laboratory work stresses quantitative analysis using traditional gravimetric and volumetric techniques as well as instrumental methods. (Offered every spring semester)						(4)
<hr>
CHM 295 Introductory Topics in Chemistry</b><br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education. An introductory study of a specific topic within chemistry. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in chemistry. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)						(1-3)
<hr>
CHM 318 Biochemistry I</b><br>
Prerequisite: CHM 206. The role of water in biochemistry; protein structure and function; enzyme kinetics, mechanisms and regulation; metabolism or carbohydrates; lipids, and nitrogen compounds; oxidative phosphorylation; laboratory exercises. (Offered every odd fall semester)						(4)
<hr>
CHM 319 Biochemistry II</b><br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in CHM 318. Integration of metabolism; hormones; photosynthesis; membranes, DNA structure, replication, and transcription, gene regulation, protein biosynthesis; laboratory exercises. (Offered every even spring semester)			(4)
<hr>
CHM 328 Introduction to Physical Chemistry</b><br>
Prerequisites: CHM 212, MAT 106. Theory and application of the laws of thermodynamics: heat, work, energy, enthalpy, entropy, free energy. Properties of solutions, chemical equilibrium kinetics. (Offered alternate years) 	(4)
<hr>
CHM 399 Independent Study</b><br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(2-4)
<hr>
CHM 440 Natural Science Seminar</b><br>
Prerequisite: junior or senior standing. Presentation, analysis, discussion and integration of current topics in the natural sciences as developed in the literature. (Offered every fall semester)						(1)
<hr>
CHM 495 Advanced Topics in Chemistry</b><br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education. An advanced study of a specific topic within chemistry. Intended for juniors and seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in chemistry. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)						(1-3)
<hr>
CHM 499 Senior Research</b><br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(2-4)
<hr size=8>
<font size=+2>Mathematics</font>
<hr>
MAT 102 College Algebra</b><br>
Sets; real numbers; logic; algebraic expressions; factoring; fractions; exponents; solving algebraic equations; inequalities; linear systems; and applications. (Offered every fall semester)  						(3)
<hr>
MAT 104 Mathematics for Liberal Arts </b><br>
This course is designed to provide the student a basic understanding of the structure of mathematics. It covers such topics as set notation; symbolic logic; numeration systems; relations; operations, identity and inverse elements; mathematical systems (finite and infinite); metric and non-metric geometry. (Offered every semester)				(3)
<hr>
MAT 105 Elementary Functions</b><br>
The real number system, real valued functions, graphing of functions; algebraic functions; polynomial functions; graphing linear and quadratic functions; rational functions; exponential functions; logarithmic functions; circular functions; and applications. (Offered every fall semester)			(3)
<hr>
MAT 106 Calculus I</b><br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in MAT 105. Limits; continuous functions; derivatives; antiderivatives; definite integrals; Fundamental Theorem of Calculus; applications. (Offered every spring semester)				(3)
<hr>
MAT 201 Finite Mathematics</b><br>
Functions and lines; systems of linear equations; systems of linear inequalities; linear programming (including an introduction to the Simplex Method); sets and counting; probability; game theory. (Offered every spring semester)						(3)
<hr>
MAT 207 Calculus II</b><br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in MAT 106. Applications of integral calculus; techniques of integration including (1) change of variables, (2) trigonometric substitution, (3) integration by parts and (4) partial fractions; improper integrals; sequences; series; tests for convergence; Taylor's formula; Taylor series expansion of a function; and applications. (Offered every fall semester)						(3)
<hr>
MAT 210 Calculus III</b><br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in MAT 207. Parametric equations and polar coordinates; vectors and surfaces; vector-valued functions; differential calculus of functions of several variables; multiple integrals; vector calculus. (Offered every spring semester)			(3)
<hr>
MAT 295 Introductory Topics in Mathematics</b><br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education. An introductory study of a specific topic within mathematics. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in mathematics. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)				(1-3)
<hr>
MAT 309 Probability and Statistics</b><br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in MAT 106. Finite sample spaces; counting techniques; random variables; distributions; testing of hypotheses; applications. (Offered every odd fall semester)						(3)
<hr>
MAT 311 Abstract Algebra</b><br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in MAT 106. Algebraic structures, groups, rings, fields, polynomial domains. (Offered every even fall semester)						(3)
<hr>
MAT 312 Linear Algebra</b><br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in MAT 106. Matrix algebra; vector spaces; subspaces; bases for vector spaces; determinants; solving linear systems; linear transformations; change of basis; eigenvalues and eigenvectors; applications. (Offered every spring semester)	(3)
<hr>
MAT 317 Foundations of Geometry</b><br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in MAT 106. Axiomatic systems; finite geometries; advanced Euclidean concepts; plane hyperbolic geometry. (Offered every odd fall semester)		(3)
<hr>
MAT 321 Differential Equations</b><br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in MAT 210. Classification of differential equations; general solutions; particular solutions; techniques; separation of variables; exact equations; homogeneous equations; integrating factors; firstÐorder linear equations; linear equations of higher order; method of undetermined coefficients; variation of parameters; applications; systems of equations; LaPlace transforms; power series methods. (Offered every even spring semester)(3)
<hr>
MAT 399 Independent Study</b><br>
Prerequisites: junior or senior standing and consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)						(1-3)
<hr>
MAT 416 Complex Analysis</b><br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in MAT 210. Complex number system; analytic functions; elementary functions; mappings; integrals; power series; residues; poles; conformal mappings. (Offered alternate years)			(3)
<hr>
MAT 417 Numerical Analysis</b><br>
Prerequisites: C- or better in MAT 210 and a computer programming language. Taylor polynomials; computer representation of numbers; error analysis; roots of equations; interpolation; approximation of functions; numerical integration and differentiation; solution of systems of linear equations; solution of ordinary differential equations. (Offered every even spring semester)		(3)
<hr>
MAT 495 Advanced Topics in Mathematics</b><br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education. An advanced study of a specific topic within mathematics. Intended for juniors and seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in mathematics. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)				(1-3
<hr size=8>
<font size=+2>Physical Education</font> 
<hr>
PE 103 Badminton</b><br>
Beginning strokes and strategies, rules and play for both singles and doubles. (Offered every odd fall semester)			(1)
<hr>
PE 111 Golf I</b><br>
Rules and beginning techniques for strokes, swing and play. (Offered every spring semester)						(1)
<hr>
PE 112 Golf II</b><br>
Prerequisite: PE 111. Advanced play. (Offered as needed)				(1)
<hr>
PE 115 Shape-Up</b><br>
Stretching exercises, work on the Universal and other weights and building endurance in an aerobic exercise. (Offered every spring semester)						(1)
<hr>
PE 116 Advanced Lifesaving</b><br>
American Red Cross course. Covers rescues, releases, disrobing and artificial resuscitation. (Offered as needed)			(1)
<hr>
PE 119 Basic Swimming</b><br>
Beginning through intermediate. This course covers all nine strokes, basic survival and other water-related skills. Certification in Red Cross course based on individual's ability. (Offered as needed)				(1)
<hr>
PE 120 Synchronized Swimming I</b><br>
Course designed for deep water swimmers. Sculling, figures and strokes incorporated in routines with music. (Offered as needed);.c1.				(1)
<hr>
PE 122 Tennis I</b><br>
Beginning forehand ground stroke, backhand ground stroke and serve. Rules and play for both singles and doubles. (Offered every fall semester)						(1)
<hr>
PE 123 Tennis II</b><br>
Prerequisite: PE 122. Advanced tennis. (Offered as needed)			(1)
<hr>
PE 125 Canoeing</b><br>
Prerequisites: basic skills for survival in water. Types of canoes, strokes and paddles. Methods of handling canoes in all weather conditions. (Offered as needed)			(1)
<hr>
PE 126 Outdoor Living</b><br>
Basic practical course to learn skills to better utilize and enjoy the outdoors through camping, hiking and biking. (Offered every even fall semester)				(1)
<hr>
PE 128 Sailing I</b><br>
Prerequisites: basic skills for survival in water. Terms, types of boats, gear and fittings as well as points of sailing. Practical testing on solo sailing and rigging. (Offered as needed)	(1)
<hr>
PE 140 Design for Active Living</b><br>
The framework of the course includes both theory and activity components. In the theory focus, students are presented with an integrative and holistic approach to health issues and concerns. In the activity focus, students study a variety of aspects of fitness and exercise and participate in a fitness/exercise program of their choice and design. In addition, such techniques as yoga and self-defense are presented as augmenting activities. Furthermore, topics such as weight control and nutrition, stress management and others leading to development of a positive self-image are included. This course provides instruction in the knowledge and skills necessary to develop a healthy, integrated lifestyle. (Offered every semester)			(3)
<hr>
PE 220 Prevention, Care, and Rehabilitation of Sport Injuries</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 203, BIO 204. Acquire knowledge and develop skills necessary in the understanding of how to prevent, care for and rehabilitate common sports-related injuries to the body. As part of the class, each student works in an athletic training practical setting while receiving the necessary theoretical background. (Offered as needed)			(3)
<hr>
PE 295 Introductory Topics in Physical Education</b><br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education. An introductory study of a specific topic within physical education. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in physical education. The students may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)			(1-3)
<hr>
PE 399 Independent Study</b><br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(1-3)
<hr>
PE 495 Advanced Topics in Physical Education</b><br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education. An advanced study of a specific topic within physical education. Intended for juniors and seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in physical education. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)			(1-3)
<hr size=8>
<font size=+2>Physics</font>
<hr>
PHY 201 General Physics I</b><br>
Prerequisite: MAT 106. Principles of vectors, mechanics, dynamics, work energy, momentum. Rotational kinematics and dynamics, statics, oscillatory motion, waves, sound fluids. (Offered every odd fall semester)		(4)
<hr>
PHY 202 General Physics II</b><br>
Prerequisites: MAT 106 and PHY 201. Principles and laws of electricity and magnetism, current, resistance, emf and DC circuits, electromagnetic oscillations and AC circuits, electromagnetic waves, light, geometric and wave optics. (Offered every even spring semester)		(4)
<hr>
PHY 295 Introductory Topics in Physics</b><br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education. An introductory study of a specific topic within physics. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in physics. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)						(1-4)
<hr>
PHY 399 Independent Study</b><br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(1-3)
<hr>
PHY 495 Advanced Topics in Physics</b><br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education. An advanced study of a specific topic within physics. Intended for juniors and seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in physics. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)	(1-4)

