<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Occupational Therapy Division Briefs
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff Link=0000ff alink=ff0000 Vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+2>
Occupational Therapy<br></font>
<font size=+3>
Division Briefs</font>
<p>
Occupational therapy is a human service profession that uses everyday activities (occupations) associated with work, self-care and play to help people whose lives have been disrupted by illness, deficits in development, the aging process and social or emotional problems to lead independent, productive and satisfying lives.  A few examples of the range of services an occupational therapist may perform include evaluating children with developmental disabilities and planning treatment activities to help them grow mentally and physically; designing and constructing splints for people with physical disabilities; helping people with physical disabilities learn how to carry out daily tasks at home, on the job and in the community; conducting group or individual treatment to help patients in a mental health center learn to cope with daily activities and prepare for return to their communities; helping the elderly adjust to the special problems of aging and remain physically and mentally active; and suggesting changes in the layout of design of home, school and place of work to give greater independence to people with disabilities and to prevent such disabilities. 
<p>
The Daisy Marquis Jones Program in Occupational Therapy offers a comprehensive course of classroom, laboratory and clinical study.  After four years of academic study with an emphasis on liberal arts and professional courses, the student is eligible to participate in the professional internships required for certification to practice.  These internships include two required three months, full-time field work experiences with the option of a third experience in an area of special interest.  Upon successful completion of the internships, the student receives a bachelor of science degree.
<p>
The Occupational Therapy Program is accredited by the Accreditation Council for Occupational Therapy Education (ACOTE) of the American Occupational Therapy Association (AOTA).  Graduates of the program are able to sit for the national certification examination for the occupational therapist administered by the National Board for Certification in Occupational Therapy (NBCOT).  After successful completion of this exam, the individual is an occupational therapist, registered  (OTR).  Most states require licensure in order to practice; however, state licenses are usually based on the results of the AOTCB Certification Examination.

<hr></font><font size=+2>
