<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Experiential Learning Opportunities
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff Link=0000ff alink=ff0000 Vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+2>
Occupational Therapy<br></font>
<font size=+3>
Experiential Learning Opportunities</font>
<p><font size=+2><hr><center>
Lorenzetti's Field Period Earns a Gold Medal</font></center><p>

Occupational therapy major John Lorenzetti helped train a potential gold medalist for the 1995 State Special Olympics. Lorenzetti spent his Field Period assisting the Newark Developmental Center and its olympic hopefuls as a recreational therapist aide. 
<p>
"I assisted the members of several different units with perfecting their bowling, swimming and skiing techniques," Lorenzetti said.
<p>
Lorenzetti assisted a senior occupational therapist with 65-75 patients throughout Wayne County. He not only worked with the patients on their sports, he also helped them through the tasks of daily life. 
<p>
"We spent one half of the day working on sports and the other half talking to patients, eating with them and assisting them with their program," Lorenzetti said. 
<p>
Lorenzetti learned many things about his field working with special olympians including how to become a better therapist. 
<p>
"This Field Period helped me learn how to open up to each individual. As I watched the patients go through their daily struggles, I also learned that all goals are achievable," Lorenzetti said. 
<p>
Lorenzetti, a senior at Keuka, found his Field Period both challenging and satisfying. The challenge was not knowing what was going to happen next. His satisfaction was knowing that he helped people achieve. 
<p>
"Watching clients' faces and seeing their expressions of excitement when they reach a goal gives me great satisfaction," Lorenzetti said. 
 <p>
The education of an occupational therapist requires classroom and clinical forms of instruction. The clinical aspect does not begin within an occupational therapy clinic until January of the senior year. It is at this time that the student has the knowledge base to benefit from a clinical practice experience without producing an adverse effect on patient care. The senior year January experience is solidified with two full-time subsequent clinical experiences in specified practice arenas. Occupational therapy clinics are used throughout the United States. 
<p>
Prior to the above clinical experiences, students spend each January within a faculty-guided work experience:  Field Period. As stated above, these experiences for the freshman through the junior years are considered essential for the development of an occupational therapy student. It is recommended that students complete one Field Period experience in an organization that provides occupational therapy services. Students are not assigned to occupational therapy, but can rotate through several departments to help confirm their career decision to become an occupational therapist. 
<p>
The junior year Field Period experience is completed within a human service organization. This experience is a practical application of the concepts and principles that students learned in the fall occupational therapy courses. 
<p>
All experiential learning is designed by the student with guidance and evaluation by their academic advisor.




