<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Occupational Therapy Courses
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alinf=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3>Occupational Therapy</font><br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions</font><hr>
OT 315 Foundations of Human Performance</b><br>
Prerequisite: Acceptance into the occupational therapy major. Examines the practice of occupational therapy from a person-environment-performance framework and addresses the many determinants of occupational performance, ranging from physiological factors to sociocultural and political influences. Laboratory experiences provide opportunities to explore occupation as a therapeutic medium. (Offered every fall semester)						 								(4)
<hr>
OT 322 Group and Interpersonal Communication</b><br>
Prerequisite: OT 315. This course studies basic group dynamics and individual interaction strategies. These communication skills are linked to occupational therapy models of practice which are used in a variety of practice settings with varying performance deficits. The course emphasizes personal growth while developing these essential tools for therapeutic interventions. These communication skills also form the base for collaborative relationships with peers, colleagues and supervisors at varying professional levels and environments. Lecture and laboratory format. (Offered every spring semester)						 						(4);
<hr>
OT 334 Occupational Performance I: Infants through Adolescence</b><br>
Prerequisites: OT 346 (will be taken concurrently), BIO 341, BIO 343, OT 315, OT 390. This course identifies the development of various occupational roles and tasks at specific ages and stages from conception through adolescence (age 19). It utilizes the person-environment-performance framework to enable students to make informed decisions based on the assessment process. The range of occupational performance is emphasized thus providing parameters for recognizing dysfunction. Lecture, readings and laboratory will comprise the learning experiences. (Offered every spring semester)					 					(4);
<hr>
OT 358 Medical Conditions in Occupational Therapy</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 203, BIO 204, BIO 341, BIO 343. A lecture course that presents the etiology, epidemiology, signs, symptoms, prognosis and related complications of the medical conditions most commonly seen in occupational therapy practice. Medical terminology is taught in conjunction with each condition. (Offered every spring semester)				 				(3);
<hr>
OT 390 Occupational Therapy (Level I) Field Period</b><br>
Prerequisite: OT 315. This is an experiential field period designed by the student in collaboration with their OT advisor to build on the concepts and principles learned in Foundations of Human Performance. It emphasizes identification, valuing and application of the contextual factors influencing the person-environment-performance model introduced in Foundations. The student s junior level experiences and learning will serv as foundational knowledge for more indepth coursework in the spring courses related to occupational performance, conditions adversely affecting performance and basic skills for clinical reasoning. (Offered every January)								(3);
<hr>
OT 399 Independent Study</b><br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				 			(1-3);
<hr>
OT 415 Developmental-Cognitive Dimensions of Performance</b><br>
Prerequisites: OT 344, OT 346, OT 358. This course will utilize lectures, demonstrations and lab experiences to facilitate the student s understanding of assessment and intervention for commonly identified deficits in an individual s developmental and cognitive dimensions of performance. Class activities will focus on the major components of and the critical relationship between the neuromotor, sensorimotor and cognitive systems; the factors with which they influence the quality and quantity of performance across the life span will be emphasized. (Offered every fall semester)										 				(4);
<hr>
OT 425 Psychological Dimensions of Performance</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 341, OT 315, BIO 343, OT 358, OT 334, OT 346, PSY 123, PSY 328, PSY 336. This course focuses on the impact selected disorders have on identity, self-protection, motivation and disruption of subsystems. Includes pharmacological agents and their effect on performance. Methods of assessing psychological performance factors and intervention strategies are taught through lecture and laboratory experiences. (Offered every spring semester)	 								(4);
<hr>
OT 435 Physiological Dimensions of Performance</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 203, BIO 204, BIO 341, OT 315, BIO 343, OT 358. This course focuses on the assessment and intervention of conditions that result in deficits in physiological performance including cardiorespiratory function, muscle strength, muscle endurance, flexibility and body composition. (Offered every spring semester)					 				(4);
<hr>
OT 445 Sensory-Motor Dimensions of Performance</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 341, BIO 343, OT 334, OT 346, OT 322, OT 358. Lecture and discussion of selected neurological conditions that result in impairments of the sensory-motor system which in turn impacts on human performance. (Offered every fall semester)		(4);
<hr>
OT 346 Occupational Performance II: Adults through Death</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 341, BIO 343, OT 315, OT 390, (OT 334 will be taken concurrently). This course identifies the development of various occupational roles and tasks at specific ages and stages from adulthood (age 20) until the end of life. It utilizes the person- environment-performance framework to enable students to make informed decisions based on the assessment process. The range of occupational performance is emphasized thus providing parameters for recognizing dysfunction. Lecture will be combined with experiential activities. (Offered every fall semester)									 						(3);
<hr>
OT 470 Professional Service Management</b><br>
Prerequisites: OT 210, OT 350 or OT 430 or OT 440. Enhancement of student s ability to function effectively within a system delivering professional occupational therapy services. Includes external and internal influences on administrative functions of planning, organizing, directing and controlling. Lecture. (Offered every spring semester)					 			(3);
<hr>
OT 484 Evaluating Change in Human Performance</b><br>
Prerequisite: SS 231. Examines basic research strategies and protocols which are designed to assess human performance in a practice environment. Emphasizes not only the production of research but also the integration of empirical findings and methods into practice. (Offered every spring semester)										 			(3);
<hr>
OT 490 Occupational Therapy (Level I) Field Period</b><br>
Prerequisite: OT 415, OT 425, OT 445, OT 435. This is an experiential field period designed for the student to practice evaluation, treatment planning and intervention skills learned the previous semester in the above Occupational Therapy practice courses. The field sites are clinical settings supervised by an occupational therapy practitioner. The time frame is adequate enough to initiate and follow a client to evaluate for changes in the person-environment-performance configuration. The student learning contract is similar for all sites. The student is also expected to identify experiences for new learning: multiple, coexisting performance deficits and conditions in one person. These new experiences will be addressed in the Contextual Approaches course in the following semester. (Offered every January)					(3);
<hr>
OT 496 A Contextual Approach to Performance Intervention</b><br>
Prerequisites: BIO 341, BIO 343, OT 315, OT 322, OT 334, OT 346, OT 358, OT 390, OT 415, OT 425, OT 435, OT 445, OT 490. This is the Occupational Therapy capstone course taught through the use of experiential learning in the form of small work groups, lecture and large group synthesis of the information. The focus of this class is on the examination of the context of performance intervention used in Occupational therapy. Extensive case study analysis of individuals with multiple needs will develop the student s clinical reasoning skills. In addition, this class includes information on team interactions, developing the professional self and the psychodynamics and ethical considerations of therapist/client interactions. Lecture and lab. (Offered every spring semester)								 	(4);
<hr>
OT 501 Level II Fieldwork (Required)</b><br>
Prerequisites: All academic coursework must be completed. The student must complete 470 hours of clinical experience under the direct supervision of a registered occupational therapist.  The type of clinical setting or environment is a collaborative effort between the Fieldwork Co-ordinator, the student and the clinical site supervisor. The student learning objectives are developed by the fieldwork sites with review by the Occupational Therapy Division. The primary emphasis for this fieldwork is the student s  transition from academic learner to entry level practitioner. The  student must translate the academic knowledge base to actual clinical practice in a professional manner. Registration in this course constitutes full-time attendance. (July-September) (Offered every year)							 											 							(6);
<hr>
OT 502 Level II Fieldwork (Required)</b><br>
Prerequisite: OT 501. The student must complete 470 hours of clinical experience under the direct supervision of a registered occupational therapist. The type of clinical setting or environment is a collaborative effort between the Fieldwork Co-ordinator, the student and the clinical site supervisor. The student learning objectives are developed by the fieldwork sites with review by the Occupational Therapy Division. The primary emphasis for this fieldwork is the student s transition from academic learner to entry level practitioner. The student must translate the academic knowledge base to actual clinical practice in a professional manner. Registration in this course constitutes full-time attendance. (July-September) (October-December) (Offered every year)											(6);
<hr>
OT 503 Level II Fieldwork (Optional)</b><br>
Prerequisites: OT 501, OT 502. The student must complete 470 hours of clinical experience under the direct supervision of a registered occupational therapist. The clinical setting or environment is a special interest area for the student but the site needs approval between the student and Fieldwork Co-ordinator. The student learning objectives are developed by the fieldwork sites with review by the Occupational Therapy Division. The primary emphasis  for this fieldwork is the student's transition from academic learner to entry level practitioner. The student must translate the academic knowledge base to actual clinical practice in a professional manner. Registration in this course constitutes full-time attendance. (July-September) (Offered every year from January to March)									(6);

<hr>
