<font size=+3>
Faculty Profiles</font>
<p>
<font size=+2>Professors</font><p>

<b>Thomas X. Carroll</b><br>
Professor of Chemistry (1982); B.S., Hobart College; M.S., Ph.D., Yale University. Dr. Carroll conducts research at Oregon State during the summers and Field Periods. Background:  physical chemist, electron spectroscopist 
<p>
<b>Joan E. Magnusen</b><br>
Professor of Biology (1982); B.A., St. Andrews Presbyterian College; M.S., Ph.D., University of Maryland. Dr. Magnusen and Ms. Schleiermacher (listed below)direct a Field Period which explores the Everglades every third year. Background:  developmental biologist, invertebrate zoologist
<p>
<b>Mary P. Schleiermacher</b><br>
Professor of Physical Education (1970); B.S., M.S., SUNY College at Cortland
<p>
<b>Roy E. Shortt</b><br>
Professor of Mathematics (1965); B.S., Syracuse University; M.A., University of Washington. Keuka's 1996 Professor of the Year, Professor Shortt has been with the College since 1965.
<p>
<b>Edgar E. Webber</b><br>
Professor of Biology (1967); B.S., University of Massachusetts; M.S., Cornell University; Ph.D., University of Massachusetts. Dr. Webber was recently published in the Journal of New England Botanical Society for his research in marine algae Background:  marine phycologist.  
<p>
<b>James E. White</b><br>
Professor of Biology (1962); A.B., Dartmouth College; Ph.D., Rutgers University. Background:  vertebrate zoologist, ecologist
<p>
<font size=+2>Associate Professors</font>
<p>
<b>Gary L. Hickernell</b><br>
Associate Professor of Chemistry (1990); B.S., Allegheny College, Ph.D., University of Washington. Dr. Hickernell is working hand-in-hand with Keuka students and a consortium of colleges to develop discovery based chemistry. The consortium believes the best way to learn science is to do science!Background:  natural products organic chemist 
<p>
<b>Marianne R. Jahnke</b><br>
Associate Professor of Biology (1990); B.S., Western Illinois University; Ph.D., SUNY Stony Brook. Dr. Jahnke is a member of the College's academic computing committee and is working to integrate computer assisted instruction into the classroom. Background:  glycoprotein biochemist, monoclonal antibodies
<p>
<font size=+2>Assistant Professors</font>
<p>
<b>Thomas K. Dickinson</b><br>
Assistant Professor of Biology and Occupational Therapy (1995); B.S., Syracuse University; M.S., Barry University; Ph.D., Pennsylvania State University. Background:  neuroanatomy and physiology 
