<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Experiential Learning Opportunities
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff Link=0000ff alink=ff0000 Vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="dolphin1.gif">
<font size=+2>
Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education <br></font>
<font size=+3>
Experiential Learning Opportunities</font>
<p><font size=+1>
Students majoring in natural sciences transformed classroom theories into practical experiences during Field Period 1996! Keukonians worked and learned at: 
<ul>
<li>medical centers (biomedical research)
<li>veterninary clinics
<li>high schools
<li>hospitals
<li>zoos
<li>wildlife teaching hospitals
<li>Center for Disease Control
<li>SUNY Health Center
<li>Roswell Park Cancer Hospital
<li>New York State Agricultural Experimental Station
<li>Monroe County Medical Examiners Office
<li>Mystic Marinelife Aquarium (see profile below)
</ul><center><hr>
<b>Rochester Resident Catches the "One That Got Away" During Field Period</b>
</font><p></center>
Gliding gracefully through the water, Aurora watches for signs of her caretaker for the day. Sneaking silently up behind her, Aurora greets her with a mouthful of water and smiles, and waits expectantly for Megan Cope, a Keuka College senior majoring in biology, to rub her tongue. Aurora is a 1,365 pound, 10'6" Beluga whale. She calls the Mystic Marinelife Aquarium in Mystic, Ct., home. Cope calls the organization her Field Period sponsor and affectionately refers to Aurora as a "pill." <br>
"Each animal has its own personality," Cope said.<br>
And Cope can prove this statement from hands-on experience. With three Keuka College Field Periods each devoted to marine mammals' care and research jumping from her College transcript, Cope knows the direction her life will go.<br> 
"I have found my passion," Cope, daughter of Rochester, N.Y., residents James and Ellie Cope, said.<br>
As a Keuka freshman, Cope completed her first Field Period as a volunteer for a dolphin research center, working with trainers and in a dolphin child therapy program. For her junior year Field Period, she completed a behavioral study on a stranded, rare dolphin in Clearwater, Fl. Cope's senior year found her gaining experience in the research and veterinary services department of the Connecticut aquarium.<br>
<img align=right src="dolphin.gif">"Each one has been a sequential learning experience. I am learning my field step-by-step, progressively assuming more responsibilities," Cope said.<br>
In addition to taking care of creatures of the deep, Cope assisted a graduate student complete a section of her doctorate research project. This is a perfect fit with Cope's ultimate professional objectives:  behavioral and ecological research.<br>
"Through Field Periods, I have found a flood of research and projects to explore," Cope said, adding that she aslo has developed a list of professional contacts and mentors. <br>
"My supervisor is Dr. David St. Aubin. He is well-known and respected in the scientific community and has devoted a lot of attention to helping me succeed," Cope said.<br>
Cope earned three academic credits for each of these Field Periods. Following the philosophy of the Keuka College program, she researched, applied for and developed learning objectives for each of the annually-required placements.<br>
Field Period was created in 1942 and was Keuka's response to the war effort. Keukonians volunteered their time and talent for the good of the community, while applying classroom theories to real world situations.
<hr></font><font size=+2>
<img src="greendot.gif"><a href="./dvnsm.html">Return to the Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Physical Education Division page</a><br>
<img src="greendot.gif"><a href="./index.html">Return to the Keuka College home page</a></font>
</body>
</html>

