<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Education Courses
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alink=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3><b>Education </b></font> <br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions</font><p>
<hr>
EDU 105 Diverse Learners:<br>
A study of diverse learners in American schools: description, prevalence, characteristics, causes, variations of severity, accommodations, adaptations, legal issues, effects of conditions on the life of children, parents and the community. (Offered every semester)		(3)
<hr>
EDU 150 Early Childhood:<br>
The learning environment in the early years (2-5); learning centers; current topics in early childhood discussed on a seminar basis. (Offered as needed)														(3)
<hr>
EDU 202 Elementary Science Methods:<br>
Prerequisites: EDU 101, BIO 101 or BIO 105 or BIO 204 or CHM 111 or BIO 202. Teaching methods peculiar to science instruction emphasizing the inquiry process and recent teaching materials. (Offered every semester)						(2)
<hr>
EDU 210 Perspectives on Disabilities I:<br>
Prerequisites: EDU 105 (may be taken concurrently). Course focuses on the developmental, learning, behavioral and social characteristics and needs of students with mild and moderate disabilities, and on the continuum of service delivery models available in schools and communities. The unique skills, competencies and strategies required to provide an appropriate education in the least restrictive environment are explored from both theoretical and practical perspectives. Etiological factors are discussed. An emphasis is placed on understanding parental and family relationships, and on the life long living skills needed for people with these types of disabilities. An individualized education program (IEP) for a student is developed. (Offered every semester)											(3)
<hr>
EDU 211 Perspectives on Disabilities II:<br>
Prerequisites: EDU 105 (may be taken concurrently). Course focuses on the developmental, learning, behavioral and social characteristics and needs of students with severe, profound and/or multiple 
disabilties, and on the continuum of service delivery models available in schools and communities. The unique skills, competencies and strategies required to provide an appropriate education in the least restrictive environment are explored from both theoretical and practical perspectives. Etiological factors are discussed, An emphasis is placed on understanding parental and family relationships, and on the life long living skills needed for people with these types of disabilities. An individualized education program (IEP) for a student is developed. (Offered every semester)									(3)
<hr>
EDU 290 Exploratory Education field Period:<br>
An off-campus experience in a public or private school as an exploration of teaching as an appropriate career choice. Exposure to the demands of the teaching profession and the nature of school-aged children. This field period should be evaluated by the student's advisor or some other non-education faculty member. (Offered every January and summer semester)							(3)
<hr>
EDU 291 Elementary Education Field Period:<br>
Prerequisite: consent of education department faculty member. An off-campus K-6 education classroom laboratory experience with exposure to curriculum, materials, classroom management, instructional planning and methodology, and children.				(3)
<hr>
EDU 292 Secondary Education Field Period:<br>
Prerequisite: consent of education department faculty member. An off-campus 7-12 education classroom laboratory experience with exposure to curriculum, materials, classroom management, instructional planning and methodology, and children.				(3)
<hr>
EDU 293 Special Education Field Period:<br>
Prerequisite: consent of education department faculty member. An off-campus special education classroom laboratory experience with exposure to curriculum, materials, classroom management, instructional planning and methodology, and children.			(3)
<hr>
EDU 294 Elementary/Special Education field Period:<br>
Prerequisite: Consent of education department faculty member. An off- campus elementary/special education field period in an included classroom with exposure to curriculum, materials, classroom management, instructional planning and methodology, and children with and without disabilities or cultural differences. (Offered every January and summer semester)						(3)
<hr>
EDU 295 Secondary/Special Education Field Period:<br>
Prerequisite: Consent of education department faculty member. An off- campus secondary/special education field period in included classrooms with exposure to curriculum, materials, classroom management, instructional planning and methodology,  and children with and without disabilities or cultural differences. (Offered every January and summer semester)						(3)
<hr>
EDU 301 Elementary Social Studies Methods:<br>
Prerequisite: EDU 101. Social studies teaching and methods appropriate to the elementary teacher; concepts, generalizations, value clarification, inquiry, simulations, learning centers, cooperative learning, expository teaching and the use of classroom technology. (Offered every semester)															(2)
<hr>
EDU 302 Substance Use and Abuse:<br>
Effects of various medications on the educational, cognitive, physical, social and emotional behavior or individuals; signs of substance use and abuse; procedures for addressing the needs of a student using or abusing substances; how to work with human service organizations; curriculum and strategies for instructing students about substance use and abuse. (Offered every fall semester).					(2)
<hr>
EDU 303 History and Philosophy of American Educational Thought:<br>
Prerequisite: junior standing. Philosophical foundations, aims and methods of American education; European sources and theories of education affecting the structure and formation of American educational thought; historical and contemporary educational theories and practices; development of a personal philosophy of education. Also listed as PHL 303. (Offered every spring semester)				(3)
<hr>
EDU 304 Elementary Mathematics Methods:<br>
Prerequisites: EDU 101 and completion of mathematics core course. Teaching methods peculiar to school mathematics; arithmetic skills; mathematical concepts and generalizations, problem solving; and evaluative techniques. (Offered every semester)			(2)
<hr>
EDU 305 Measurement and Evaluation:<br>
Basic concepts of testing, test construction, teacher-made tests, item analysis, standardized tests, evaluation and descriptive statistics. (Offered every spring semester)												(3)
<hr>
EDU 306 Assessment in Inclusive Schools:<br>
Basic concepts of assessment including testing and test construction; consideration of descriptive statistics; methods of assessment as it relates to new issues involving student progress and performance; consideration of natural/authentic assessment and portfolios; and relating assessment to student goals and objectives as required in IEPs. (Offered every spring semester)						(3)
<hr>
EDU 307 Foundations of Education:<br>
Prerequisite: Junior standing. Historical, social and philosophical foundations of American schools including public, private and special schools; European sources and theories of education affecting the structure of American educational thought; historical and educational practices with considered emphasis on the development of special education; development of a personal philosophy of education. (Offered every spring semester)															(3)
<hr>
EDU 308 Teaching in Inclusive Schools:<br>
Prerequisite: EDU 105. The role of teacher as a decision-maker, and the need for the teacher to understand and collaborate with parents, other educational personnel and related service providers in the school and community. The course draws heavily on the principles of the effective schools movement, and provides intensive emersion of the student in the four principles of effective instruction which are planning, managing, delivering and evaluating instruction. A unique focus of the course is on the special relationship between regular and special teachers and the collaboration that must occur to enhance the learning of all students. Broad methodological and curriculum issues are included as is a focus on the application of technology in the teaching-learning process. (Offered every fall semester)						(2)
<hr>
EDU 310 Literacy in the Inclusive Classroom:<br>
Prerequisite: EDU 101. An introduction to the methods and materials for instruction in reading, writing and the language arts in the inclusive elementary classroom. The emphasis will be on thematic units and literature based unit planning; basal reading programs will be included. The integration of skill instruction into an authentic whole language program is fundamental to this course. (Offered every semester)		(3)
<hr>
EDU 311 Methods of Teaching Secondary Science:<br>
Prerequisites: BIO 205, CHM 206. Emphasis is placed on the development of instructional techniques used in secondary science lecture, laboratory and discussions; the development and use of those techniques; and the development of skills in course, curriculum and laboratory planning for the sciences. (Offered as needed)											(3)
<hr>
EDU 315 Methods of Teaching Secondary English:<br>
Prerequisites: ENG 102, EDU 101. Aims and techniques for teaching secondary school English. (Offered every even fall semester)	(3)
<hr>
EDU 316 Literacy and the Diverse Learner:<br>
Prerequisite: EDU 310. A continued investigation of the methods and materials for instruction in reading, writing and other language arts for the elementary aged child. The emphasis will be on the individualization of instruction for children who are gifted, and those who exhibit difficulty in  learning literacy skills in the self-contained classroom, in pull-out programs and with specialists working within the self-contained classroom. Interaction with consultant teachers, other specialists and parents will be addressed. (Offered every semester)				(3)
<hr>
EDU 319 Methods of Teaching Secondary Mathematics:<br>
Prerequisite: C- or better in MAT 106. Methods of teaching secondary school mathematics. (Offered as needed)			(3)
<hr>
EDU 320 Integrated Methods I:<br>
Prerequisite: EDU 105 (may be taken concurrently). Study of how to teach using the constructivist model of instruction with child-centered and child-active techniques; use of manipulatives; discrepant events; "hands-on" science activities; interdisciplinary thinking. Learning contracts, text book based units and independent free time activities will be included in this course. (Offered every semester)			(3)
<hr>
EDU 321 Integrated Methods II:<br>
Prerequisite: EDU 105 (may be taken concurrently). Study of how to teach with learning centers, contractual learning inquiry learning, teaching concepts and generalizations, simulation, values clarification, expository teaching; learning with computers; modification of lesson planning for special needs students. A non-text book based unit will be included. (Offered every semester)					(2)
<hr>
EDU 330 Teaching Students with Mild and Moderate Disabilities:<br>
Prerequisites: EDU 101, EDU 235. The course emphasizes the planning and development of alternate methods and materials to teach students with mild and moderate disabilities in regular classrooms, resource rooms or special classes. (Offered every spring semester)		(3)
<hr>
EDU 331 Teaching Students with Severe and Multiple Disabilities:<br>
Prerequisites: EDU 101, PSY 250, EDU 130 or PSY 130. The planning and development of appropriate teaching methods and materials for the student with severe and multiple disabilities in all instructional settings and from early childhood through vocational levels. (Offered every fall semester)														(3)
<hr>
EDU 341 The Psychology and Education of Students with Learning Disabilities:<br>
Prerequisite: EDU 130. Characteristics and psychological theories of learning disabilities; evaluation of diagnostic and remediation measures, with a special focus on affective instruction based on the principles of individualization. Also listed as PSY 341. (Offered every spring semester)															(3)
<hr>
EDU 352 Day Care Administration:<br>
Familiarization with the day care director's administrative role and responsibilities. Learn what is involved in creating and managing a day care center. (Offered as needed)											(3)
<hr>
EDU 355 Educational psychology:<br>
Prerequisite: PSY 101 or PSY 123. The understanding and application of psychological findings and principles relating to education. Examine the broad array of learning and behavior characteristics found in the diverse population of today's schools, including he similarities and differences between "normal" and "exceptional". Understanding the tenets of the primary theories of learning (behavioral, information processing, cognitive, humanistic) and the application of those tenets to teaching school aged children. The  psychological aspects of learning environments and instructional organizational approaches are explored. Also listed as PSY 355. (Offered every spring semester)				(3)
<hr>
EDU 358 Reading in the Content Areas:<br>
Prerequisite: EDU 101. Acquisition of skills necessary for the adequate study of reading materials in the subject areas; preparation of prospective teachers enabling them to learn a variety of methods in order to assist their students in increasing reading proficiency and understanding of content of materials. (Offered every fall semester)									(3)
<hr>
EDU 366 Methods of Teaching Social Studies:<br>
Prerequisite: EDU 101. Social studies teaching theory and methods appropriate for the secondary social studies teacher; emphasis is placed on developing thinking skills and problem solving, course content selection and organization, expository methods, inquiry, learning, constructs, learning centers and affective, confluent and cooperative learning and the use of classroom technology. (Offered every even fall semester)		(3)
<hr>
EDU 399 Independent Study:<br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)								(1-3)
<hr>
EDU 401 Diagnostic Reading:<br>
Prerequisite: approval of education faculty. Diagnostic teaching procedures for classrooms; adaptation of reading materials for diagnostic instruction, special procedures for slow learning children. (Offered every semester)						(3)
<hr>
EDU 410 Professional Teaching Techniques:<br>
Prerequisite: approval of education faculty. Integration of knowledge for effective classroom instruction; techniques for classroom management; application of teaching methodologies; individualization of instruction for special needs students; working with parents and the community; the effect of one's own cultural biases and differences that affect one's teaching; the practice of education in a professional, non-discriminatory and ethical manner; child abuse training. (Offered every semester)								(2)
<hr>
EDU 411 Student Teaching Seminar :<br>
Prerequisites: EDU 410 and approval of education faculty. This seminar is the natural conclusion to EDU 410 Professional Teaching Techniques. In this seminar, students evaluate the effectiveness of the methodology taught in EDU 410, discuss mutual problems, and generally deal with aspects of student teaching strengths and weaknesses. In addition, there is opportunity for access to certification procedures and job interview techniques, especially relevant to teaching 
positions. (Offered every semester) 							(1)
<hr>
EDU 451 Student Teaching Elementary Education:<br>
Prerequisites: approval of education faculty and all completed course competencies. Fourteen-week sequence of supervised student teaching in area K-3 and 4-6 classrooms. (Offered every semester)									(11)
<hr>
EDU 452 Student Teaching Secondary Education:<br>
Prerequisites: All completed course competencies and approval of faculty. Fourteen-week sequence of supervised student teaching in area 7-9 and 10-12 classrooms. (Offered every semester)										(11)
<hr>
EDU 453 Student Teaching Special Education:<br>
Prerequisites: All completed course competencies and permission from course instructor. Fourteen-week sequence of supervised student teaching in area K-12 special education settings. (Offered every semester)							(11)
<hr>
EDU 454 Student Teaching in Elementary and Special Education:<br>
Prerequisites: approval of education faculty and all completed course competencies. Fourteen-week sequence of supervised student teaching in elementary and special education. (Offered every semester)									(11)
<hr>
EDU 455 Student Teaching in Secondary/Special Education:<br>
Prerequisites: Approval of education faculty and all complete course competencies. Fourteen-week sequence of supervised student teaching in secondary and special education. (Offered every semester)									(11)
<hr>
EDU 495 Advanced Topics in Education:<br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Education. An advanced study of a specific topic in education. Intended for juniors and seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in education. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)															(1-3)
<hr><font size=+2>
