<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Sociology
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alink=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3><b>Sociology</b></font> <br>
<font size=+2>at Keuka College</font><p>
<font size=+1>
<b>Major Briefs</b><br>
The sociology program stresses both traditional liberal arts and career education through emphases on applied sociology/sociological practice and criminal justice. The program provides an understanding of the nature and process of stability and change in human social life and an understanding of the workings of social groups, from the macro-level of the society as a whole, through the intermediate institutional and organizational levels, to the micro-level of the small, informal group. Designed to develop independence of thought, clarity of understanding and an ability to apply knowledge to analysis of real-life situations, the program offers students substantive knowledge of social life, as well as theoretical and methodological orientations in sociology. Field Period placements in applied settings of interest to the student are an important part of the sociology program.
       <p>
The sociology major may be completed with either a concentration in applied sociology/sociological practice or criminal justice. A sociology minor is also available.
<p>
<p>

<b>
Career Options</b><br>
Career opportunities are available in virtually any vocation that involves working with people. Representative examples include the areas of juvenile services, social planning and policy-making, personnel management, public and industrial relations, probation, law enforcement, community action and social research. The program also prepares students for graduate study in sociology and such related fields as counseling, administration, law, applied social research and program development. 

<p>
<b>
<a href="./socicrdr.html">Course Descriptions</a></b><p>

<b><a href="./admifi.html">Admissions Information</a></b></font>
