<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Food, Hotel, and Resort Management Courses
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alinf=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3>
Food, Hotel, and Resort Management</font><br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions</font><p><hr>

FHR 110 Introduction to Food, Hotel and Resort Management<br>
This course examines and analyzes the organization, operation and management of food service facilities, hotels, resorts and other segments of the hospitality industry as well as clubs, hospital/nursing homes, life-care centers, schools and contract feeding companies. Social and economic forces influencing industry development are explored as well as career opportunities and requirements for success in each field. (Offered every fall semester)			(3)
<hr>
FHR 210 Food Production and Service Management<br>
Prerequisite: FHR 110. Prerequisite: FHR 211. This course examines menu planning and quantity recipe standardization interjected with techniques, methods, principles and standards of food production and services. Supporting areas such as purchasing, receiving, storage, equipment, safety and sanitation are included. (Offered every spring semester)				(2)
<hr>
FHR 211 Food Production and Service Management Lab<br>
Prerequisite: FHR 210. Students assume responsibility for planning, preparing, serving and managing each preparation. Each student is responsible for purchasing a professional knife kit and chefÕs uniform. (Offered every spring semester)				(2)
<hr>
FHR 220 Hotel Operations<br>
Prerequisite: FHR 110. This course examines the operation of hotels and their various departments; rooms, food and beverage, marketing and sales, and human resources. Emphasis on the techniques and tools of management. (Offered every fall semester)				(3)
<hr>
FHR 230 Distinguished Lecture Series<br>
This course is designed to introduce students to leading hospitality industry executives who have made significant professional contributions. The speakers address topics in management history, leadership, finance, development, marketing, operations, and current and future challenges facing the industry. Lectures are followed by discussion with students and faculty. This course may be repeated each year for a maximum of two credits. (Offered as needed)	(1)
<hr>
FHR 301 Field Period in Food, Hotel and Resort Management<br>
Prerequisite: consent of food, hotel and resort management faculty member. An educational experience with exposure to the various functional areas in the food, hotel and resort industry. (Offered annually)			(3)
<hr>
FHR 320 Food, Beverage and Labor Cost Control<br>
Prerequisite: MIS 120. This course examines current methods and principles of food, beverage and labor cost controls for hotels, restaurants and institutions. A managerial accounting approach providing internal management with data which serves as the basis for operational decision making. (Offered every fall semester)	(3)
<hr>
FHR 330 Meeting and Convention Planning<br>
Prerequisite: FHR 220. This course examines the organizing, arranging, marketing, costing and operating of convention and group business meetings, large and small. Students explore meeting planning as an independent business activity or as a meeting planning coordinator within a hotel or resort complex. (Offered every fall semester)			(3)
<hr>
FHR 340 Convention Sales and Services<br>
Prerequisites: FHR 220, FHR 330, MKT 220. This course examines the marketing functions and delivery systems for hospitality services from a managerial point of view. Topics to be analyzed include the human factors of the market, product and market analysis, competitive pricing and methods of approaching the market, and the tools used in the industry for dealing with distributors, national accounts, commercial and noncommercial operators, and vendors. (Offered every spring semester)				(3)
<hr>
FHR 345 Property and Risk Management<br>
Prerequisites: FHR 220, BUS 202. This course examines issues of risk management as applied to life safety, security and disaster preparedness. (Offered every fall semester)	(3)
<hr>
FHR 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered as needed)				(1-3)
<hr>
FHR 420 Function and Fine Dining Management<br>
Prerequisite: FHR 320. The systematic presentation of catering for special functions. Students develop, organize, prepare, serve and manage food functions typically offered in hotel, resort and contract food service settings. (Offered every spring semester)			(2)
<hr>
FHR 432 Special Topics in Food Service Management<br>
Prerequisites: junior or senior standing and approval of instructor. The content of this course changes from semester to semester. Its purpose is to provide the student with information and/or an experiential component dealing with topics of special interest. Each "topic" is selected on the basis of its significance to the hospitality industry. The student may repeat the course but not the topic. (Offered as needed)		(1-3)
<hr>
FHR 434 Special Topics in Hotel/Resort Management<br>
Prerequisites: junior or senior standing and approval of instructor. The content of this course changes from semester to semester. Its purpose is to provide the student with information and/or an experiential component dealing with topics of special interest. Each "topic" is selected on the basis of its significance to the hospitality industry. The student may repeat the course but not the topic. (Offered as needed)		(1-3)
<hr>
FHR 436 Special Topics in Travel and Tourism<br>
Prerequisites: junior or senior standing and approval of instructor. The content of this course changes from semester to semester. Its purpose is to provide the student with information and/or an experiential component dealing with topics of special interest. Each "topic" is selected on the basis of its significance to the hospitality industry. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)		(1-3)
<hr>
FHR 438 Special Topics in Senior Living Communities<br>
Prerequisites: junior or senior standing and approval of instructor. The content of this course changes from semester to semester. Its purpose is to provide the student with information and/or experiential component dealing with topics of special interest. Each "topic" is selected on the basis of its significance to the hospitality industry. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)		(1-3)
<hr>
FHR 440 Leadership and Organizational Behavior<br>
Prerequisites: FHR 210, FHR 211, HRM 208. This course examines theories of motivation, behavior and leadership. Students learn the elements of leadership and analyze their leadership abilities. Leadership is explored in self-management, leading individuals and groups. How the leader behaves, leads, communicates, manages and achieves in today's hospitality business environment. (Offered every spring semester)				(3)
<hr>
FHR 450 Tourism Planning and Development<br>
Prerequisites: FHR 110, MKT 220. This course examines consumer demand for tourism-related products and services; the development and financing of superstructure and infrastructure elements; analysis of the effects of tourism in social, economic and environmental terms. Topics range from market analysis and conceptual planning to site development, transportation, accommodations and support industries. (Offered every fall semester)			(3)
<hr>
FHR 460 Managerial Decision Making<br>
Prerequisite: senior standing in food, hotel and resort management major. This course examines the impact of numerous managerial disciplines on each other and how these disciplines must be addressed in making managerial decisions in food and hotel/resort management. Discipline studies include human resources management, labor relations, information systems, production systems, marketing and financial management. This course serves as a capstone course in this major. (Offered every spring semester)	(3)
<hr>
