<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Fine Arts Courses
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alinf=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3>
Fine Arts</font><br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions</font><p><hr size=8>


<font size=+2>Art</font><hr>
ART 101 Art, Meaning and Media<br>
A broad introduction to concepts, vocabulary, media and history of art which reveals universal qualities in human aesthetic responses, as well as the special differences that define societies and cultures, through examples from the past and the present and from diverse cultures. Opportunities for experiential learning in workshops in various media are an integral part of the course. (Offered every semester)			(3)
<hr>
ART 102 History of Western Art<br>
A survey of fine art in the Western world from the cave painting to the art of mid-19th century. (Offered as needed)			(3)
<hr>
ART 105 Visual Design<br>
A dynamic approach to surface rendering through color manipulation and creative problem solving, including color systems, basic principles of design, composition and visual expression. (Offered every even spring semester)	(3)
<hr>
ART 110 Drawing I<br>
Studio course in creating illusions of form, light and space on a two-dimensional surface through manipulation of tone. (Offered every even fall semester)				(3)
<hr>
ART 117 Art Education Workshop<br>
Art skills, techniques, methods, and basic philosophy for the elementary classroom teacher. (Offered as needed)			(3)
<hr>
ART 120 Painting I<br>
Foundation study of painting, including color theory. Emphasis on direct observation and practice. Exposure to paintings and artists of the past. (Offered every odd spring semester)		 				(3)
<hr>
ART 130 Ceramics I<br>
Clay work involving hand-building and basic glazing techniques for functional and nonfunctional objects. (Offered every fall semester)						(3)
<hr>
ART 140 Printmaking I<br>
The techniques of creating printed images from blocks of wood, linoleum, plexiglass and other techniques explored for their expressive and aesthetic potential. (Offered every odd fall semester)				(3)
<hr>
ART 150 Sculpture I<br>
A studio course in the study of form and space relationships as applied to sculpture, presenting basic techniques. Process to involve work in wood, clay and plaster. (Offered every spring semester)				(3)
<hr>
ART 210 Drawing II<br>
Prerequisite: ART 110. Advanced study of visual perception and creativity through the process of drawing. (Offered every even fall semester)						(3)
<hr>
ART 220 Painting II<br>
Prerequisite: ART 120. Painting exercises geared to individual needs and creative development. (Offered every odd spring semester)	(3)
<hr>
ART 230 Ceramics II<br>
Prerequisite: ART 130. Basic wheel-throwing techniques; problems in functional and nonfunctional construction; combining techniques; glaze chemistry and kiln firing. (Offered every fall semester)				(3)
<hr>
ART 240 Printmaking II<br>
Prerequisite: ART 140. The various methods of printmaking, including stencil printing, relief printing, screen printing and other techniques explored for their expressive and aesthetic potential. (Offered every odd fall semester)						(3)
<hr>
ART 250 Sculpture II<br>
Prerequisite: ART 150. Problem solving using the materials and techniques dealt with in ART 150. Issues in contemporary sculpture are emphasized. (Offered every spring semester)	(3)
<hr>
ART 295 Introductory Topics in Art<br>
Prerequisite: to be determined by the Division of Humanities and Fine Arts. An introductory study of a specific topic within art. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in art. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)				(1-3)
<hr>
ART 321 Advanced Studio Problems<br>
A theme oriented studio course related to the individual interests of advanced students. (Offered as needed)			(3)
<hr>
ART 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(1-3)
<hr size=8>
<font size=+2>Dance</font><hr>
DAN 101 Introduction to Dance<br>
An overview of the study of dance as an art form through discussion of dance and its relation to the other arts. Technique sessions introduce students to classical forms and exploration of modern and jazz modes. Emphasis is on the fundamentals of movement, rhythm, composition and style. This course provides students with an opportunity to experience and develop an appreciation for dance. Offered as a fine arts core option. (Offered annually)				(3)
<hr>
DAN 102 Concert Workshop<br>
Study of the methods used by choreographers, involving patterns, dynamics, and symbolism, through improvisation and structured formats. Public performance by audition only. May be repeated for up to six credit hours. (Offered annually)				(1)
<hr>
DAN 130 Basics of Modern Dance<br>
Fundamentals of modern dance technique creating the development of strength, flexibility, balance, control and endurance. Study of styles evolved by Denishawn, Wigman, Limon, Humphrey, Graham and others. (Offered as needed)	(1)
<hr>
DAN 140 Basics of Jazz Dance <br>
Elementary jazz techniques and their foundation in various ethnic cultures. Application to contemporary dance forms and exercise programs. (Offered as needed)		(1)
<hr>
DAN 211 Advanced Techniques<br>
By audition only, for selected individuals who have completed intermediate training in ballet or modern dance techniques. Required for a minor in dance. A student should seriously consider her/his ability to participate in this course when choosing a minor. Primarily a studio course focusing on the proper execution of technical skills. (Offered as needed)			 	(3)
<hr>
DAN 295 Introductory Topics in Dance<br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Humanities and Fine Arts. An introductory study of a specific topic within dance. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in dance. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)				(1-3)
<hr>
DAN 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered as needed)				(1-3) 
<hr size=8>
<font size=+2>Music</font><hr>
MUS 101 Music Appreciation<br>
Development of listening techniques and a historical perspective of music styles through exposure to music by great composers. (Offered every semester)			(3);
<hr>
MUS 120 Chorale<br>
Ensemble singing using advanced choral material; preparation and presentation of concerts on and off campus, including an annual tour. Open to students on the basis of auditions. Participation for the entire academic year is encouraged. May be repeated for credit. A maximum of six semester credit hours may be applied toward graduation. (Offered every semester)		 		(1);
<hr>
MUS 130 Private Piano<br>
An individual program of practice is developed that teaches basic hand position and fingering, knowledge of music notation and terms for the piano, and pedaling techniques. Goal of number of pieces learned varies from student to student. Only two credits may be counted toward graduation. (Offered every semester)	(1);
<hr>
MUS 131 Private Voice<br>
Private instruction to improve the fundamentals of singing including posture, diction, placement, resonance, intonation and breath control. May be repeated for credit. A maximum of six credits may be applied toward graduation. A fee is charged, payment of which should be arranged through the Business office by full-time students; for part-time students fee arrangement should be made through the instructor. (Offered every semester)				(1);
<hr>
MUS 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(1-3);
<hr size=8>
<font size=+2>Theatre</font><hr>
THR 101 Introduction to Theatre & Drama<br>
Overview of dramatic literature, theatre history and the many aspects of theatre arts: acting, directing, design, technical theatre. Read plays, prepare scenes, view live and filmed performances. (Offered annually)	(3);
<hr>
THR 104 Theatre Laboratory<br>
Participation in a major stage production from rehearsal through performance as actor, designer, stage manager, carpenter, electrician, costumer, publicist. May be repeated for credit. A maximum of six credit hours may be applied toward graduation. (Offered every semester) 	(1);
<hr>
THR 105 Reader's Theatre<br>
A study of the theories and principles of oral communication through the medium of interpretive reading and an understanding of professional reader s theatre. (Offered as needed)						(3);
<hr>
THR 201 Elements of Acting<br>
Theory and practice of acting techniques, theatre games, improvisations, vocal and physical exercises, script analysis, character analysis, blocking and prepared scenes. (Offered as needed)				(3);
<hr>
THR 295 Introductory Topics in Theatre<br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Humanities and Fine Arts. An introductory study of a specific topic within theatre. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in theatre. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)			(1-3);
<hr>
THR 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(1-3);
<hr>
THR 401 Directing Theatrical Productions<br>
Prerequisite: THR 201. Theory and practice of play directing. (Offered as needed)	(4);
<hr>
<font size=+2><img src=greendot.gif><a href="./finearts.html">Return to the Fine Arts major page</a><br>
<img src=greendot.gif><a href="./dvhumfa.html">Return to the Humanities and Fine Arts page</a><br>
<img src=greendot.gif><a href="./index.html">Return to the Keuka College home page</a><br>
</font></body>
</html>
