<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Organizational Com. Courses
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alinf=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3>
Organizational Communication</font><br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions</font><p><hr>
COM 122 Introduction to Communication<br>
Prerequisite: ENG 101. Study of the various mass media and their place in our society. Attention to communication theory and mass communication processes. (Offered every spring semester)										(3)
<hr>
COM 123 Public Speaking<br>
Theory and practice of speaking before a variety of audiences. Research for and preparation of original speeches. (Offered every even fall semester)														(3)
<hr>
COM 201 Interpersonal and Group Communication Skills<br>
Provides an introduction to the theory and practice of interpersonal and group communication. The course emphasizes experiential learning, as students apply theoretical concepts to a variety of interpersonal and group discussion exercises. As they become familiar with principles of communication, students will put those principles into practice, learning specific applications of communication techniques to work group settings. Oral communication formats covered in the course include the panel discussion, symposium and leadership of meetings. (Offered every odd fall semester)															(3)
<hr>
COM 221 Media Writing<br>
Prerequisite: ENG 101. Techniques of journalism applied to a series of news and feature writing assignments. Attention to writing for electronic as well as print media. Includes supervised practical experience with on  or off-campus organizations. (Offered every even fall semester)															(3)
<hr>
COM 295  Introductory Topics in Communication<br>
Prerequisite: To be determined by the Division of Humanities and Fine Arts. An introductory study of a specific topic with communication. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in communication. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)												(1-3)
<hr>
COM 301 Organizational Communication<br>
Students will become familiar with the role of communication in organizational cultures, the structure of organizational communication systems and strategies for managing organizational communication. Through observation and case studies, students will apply theory to practical situations. (Offered every even fall semester)										(3)
<hr>
COM 320 Writing for Professionals<br>
Prerequisite: ENG 102. The study and practice of the formal writing used by professionals in the fields of business, social service, health care and science. Includes business letters and resumes, formal reports and a variety of other forms of writing used in the professional fields mentioned above. (Offered every odd fall semester)										(3)
<hr>
COM 350  Desktop Publishing<br>
Prerequisite: ENG 101. (Working knowledge of word processing recommended.)  Course is designed to acquaint students with skills necessary to compose and produce journals, newsletters, brochures, advertising and public relations materials, using most current word processing software and formatting packages. Students will be expected to master journalistic editing skills as well as creative methods of layout and design. (Offered every even spring semester)											(3)
<hr>
COM 399  Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite:  Consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)								(1-3)
<hr>
COM 401 Senior Practicum in Communication<br>
Students will be placed in on- or off-campus communication internships. They will meet with the faculty evaluator on a bi-weekly basis to report on their progress. Outside readings will be assigned as needed. Evaluation will be based on a report from the student s internship supervisor, a portfolio of the student s work during the internship and a final, written report by the student, integrating relevant theory with the semester s practical experience. May be repeated. (Offered as needed)										(3)
<hr>
