<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Management Courses
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alinf=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3>
Management</font><br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions</font><p><hr>
<font size=+2>Business:</font><hr>
BUS 101 Introduction to Business and Society<br>
An examination of contemporary business institutions and their relationship to society. Topics include historical antecedents, basis of the American enterprise system, functional areas of business and principles of management. (Offered every fall semester)			(3)
<hr>
BUS 135 Business Ethics<br>
Foundations and development of business institutions in America; goals, values and ethics in a business world; ethical dilemmas, ambiguities, conflicts and uncertainties in business; scope and responsibilities to society, the firm and ethical principles.  (Offered as needed)	(3)
<hr>
BUS 202 Legal Environment of Business<br>
An introduction to legal principles and their relationships to business organizations. Representative topics include the constitutional authority to regulate business, consumer law, employment and labor relations law, torts and crimes related to business and intellectual property. A substantial part of the course covers contract law and commercial paper. Cases from New York Law are used extensively to assist the students in understanding the everyday applications of the law. (Offered every fall semester)		
(3)
<hr>
BUS 295 Introductory Topics in Business<br>
Prerequisite: to be determined by the Division of Business and Management. An introductory study of a specific topic within business. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in business. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)			(3)
<hr>
BUS 302 Advanced Business Law<br>
Prerequisite: BUS 202. This course explores, among other things, bankruptcy, agency, real and personal property, partnerships, corporations, sales, secured transactions, legal liability of accountants, and the Securities Acts of 1933 and 1934. Cases from New York Law are used extensively to assist the student in understanding everyday applications of the law. This course is required for, but not restricted to, accounting majors, and provides preparation, in part, for the Uniform Certified Public Accounting Examination (Law Part). (Offered as needed)(3)
<hr>
BUS 330 Operations & Production Management<br>
Prerequisites: MAT 201, SS 231, BUS 101. A study of current production theories and practices. Topics to be studied include: capacity planning, transportation modeling, inventory control, facility location, product design, time and motion studies, and scheduling. Emphasis is placed on problem solving, solution techniques, and terminology. (Offered every spring semester)						(3)
<hr>
BUS 350 International Business<br>
Prerequisites: BUS 101, ECO 211, ECO 210, MKT 220, ACC 101. This course offers an introduction to the vital issues of international business including economics, political, cultural and operational differences with emphasis on multinational corporate policy and strategy. (Offered every odd spring semester)	(3)
<hr>
BUS 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisites: junior or senior standing and consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)						(1-3)
<hr>
BUS 444 Strategic Management<br>
Prerequisites: BUS 330, MAT 201,  and senior standing. Analysis of complex management issues and problems; utilizing teams, case studies, experiential management 
exercises, individual research and formal oral presentation and defense. (Offered every fall semester)		(3)
<hr>
BUS 495 Advanced Topics in Business<br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Business and Management. An advanced study of a specific topic within business. Intended for juniors and seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in business. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)			(1-3)
<hr>
<font size=+2>Human Resource Management</font><hr>

HRM 208 Human Resources Management<br>
Prerequisite: BUS 101. Aspects of the human resource function operable in business organizations; analysis of employment personnel testing, job classification, wage and salary administration, and performance evaluation; overview of labor relations in American business. (Offered every spring semester)										(3)
<hr>
HRM 310 Industrial Labor Relations<br>
Prerequisite: HRM 208. A study of current problems faced in the area of labor relations. The course examines management and union philosophies, strategies and tactics used in the collective bargaining process through the use of interviewing techniques and case studies. (Offered every even fall semester)											(3)
<hr>
HRM 320 Human Resources Training and Development<br>
Prerequisite: HRM 208. This course is concerned with the theory and research of the systematic development and evaluation of training programs in a variety of organizational settings. The course provides a theoretical as well as practical orientation to the field. (Offered every odd fall semester)						(3)
<hr>
HRM 330 Wage and Salary Scale Development<br>
Prerequisite: HRM 208. This course studies and analyzes the basic concepts of compensation administration in organizations. Topics such as the foundation for wage and salary programs, methods of job evaluation, building wage and salary structures, and the legal constraints placed upon compensation programs are studied. (Offered every odd fall semester)(3)
<hr>
HRM 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)			(3)
<hr>
HRM 440 Senior Seminar in Human Resource Management<br>
Prerequisite: HRM 208. The case method technique is used to familiarize future managers with issues involving designing and administering a system for hiring, advancing and rewarding workers. The issues covered reflect the issues of current concern to human resource management professionals (e.g. affirmative action, comparable worth, the aging work force, termination and early retirement). The class functions as a seminar with students leading discussion of topics and cases. (Offered every odd fall semester)									(3)
<hr>
<font size=+2>Management</font><hr>

MGT 295 Introductory Topics in Management<br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Business and Management. An introductory study of a specific topic within management. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in management. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)										(1-3)
<hr>
MGT 345 Organizational Behavior<br>
Prerequisites: HRM 208, BUS 101. Logical and rational design of organizations; emergent behavior in the individual and the group including interaction and effect on the organization. (Offered every even spring semester)								(3)
<hr>
MGT 350 Small Business Seminar<br>
Prerequisites: 2.5 GPA and permission of instructor. Analysis of issues related to small business including accounting, data processing, marketing, management, legal matters and funding. (Offered as needed)												(1)
<hr>
MGT 351 Small Business Management<br>
Prerequisite: BUS 101. An analysis of the management concerns associated with small business. This course examines the means of ownership and characteristics of small business, as well as the benefits derived from and problems associated with managing small retail stores, service-oriented organizations, franchises and manufacturing firms. Problems in marketing, finance, production, accounting, personnel and insurance associated with the management of a small business are studied and analyzed. Development of a business plan. (Offered every odd spring semester)	(3)
<hr>
MGT 353 Business and Government Relations<br>
Prerequisites: ECO 210, ECO 211, BUS 101; POL 120 or POL 130. Analysis of government impact on business decisions; statutory requirements, regulation, and promotion of domestic and foreign business activities. Analysis of corporate political activity and current issues in business-government relations. (Offered every odd fall semester)							(3)
<hr>
MGT 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(1-3)
<hr>
MGT 430 Management Seminar<br>
Prerequisite: senior standing or consent of instructor. Analytical, ethical and conceptual role of the manager in an organizational structure emphasizing the interrelationships of various managerial styles. (Offered as needed)									(3)
<hr>
MGT 450 Management Internship<br>
Prerequisites: junior or senior standing and consent of instructor. One-semester internship with a public or private organization provides opportunities for practical experience in management and observation of the concepts and the actual practice of managerial procedure. (Offered every semester)											(1-12)
<hr>
MGT 495 Advanced Topics in Management<br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Business and Management. An advanced study of a specific topic within management. Intended for juniors and seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in management. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)											(1-3)
<hr>
<font size=+2>Management Information Systems</font><hr>

MIS 101 Computer Orientation<br>
An introduction to the nature and function of computer hardware and software including a description of how computers work; their advantages and limitations; the types of computers and hardware elements of computer systems; languages, programming and commercial software packages. Also listed as CSC 101. (Offered every semester) 						(1)
<hr>
MIS 120 Introduction to Computer Systems<br>
An introduction to computer systems and microcomputers. Elements of the larger computer systems such as the CPU, mass storage devices, printers and terminals; basic knowledge of how computers operate. Use of microcomputers by individual owners, operators and managers of business enterprises. Efficient utilization of commercially available software packages to aid business operations. Also listed as CSC 120. (Offered every spring semester)				(3)
<hr>
MIS 220 Decision Support Systems<br>
Prerequisite: MIS 120 or CSC 120. An analysis of the microcomputer information support systems that aid management of all levels in problem solving and decision making. A hands-on approach is used to help students understand and apply individual strategies and to integrate the strategies into a comprehensive whole. Also listed as CSC 220. (Offered every odd spring semester)														(3)
<hr>
MIS 224 Computer Programming: FORTRAN<br>
The programming language FORTRAN technique used in data processing; scientific and general computing. Also listed as CSC 224. (Offered every even spring semester)		(3)
<hr>
MIS 225 Computer Programming: COBOL<br>
Structured programming, syntax and format of COBOL; input/output; report editing; program design; control breaks; and record processing. Also listed as CSC 225. (Offered every even fall semester)													(3)
<hr>
MIS 226 Pascal Programming I<br>
Structured programming; syntax and format of Pascal; input/output; procedures and functions; data types; files; and program development. Also listed as CSC 226. (Offered every even spring semester)													(3)
<hr>
MIS 250 Systems Analysis and Design I<br>
Prerequisite: CSC 120 or MIS 120. System development, emphasis on current system documentation through the use of both classical and structured tools and techniques for describing process flows, data structures, file designs, input and output designs, and program specifications. Discussion of the information gathering and reporting activities as well as the transition from analysis to design. (Offered every odd fall semester)								(3)
<hr>
MIS 295 Introductory Topics in Management Information Systems<br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Business and Management. An introductory study of a specific topic within management information systems. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in management information systems. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)				(1-3)
<hr>
MIS 325 Advanced Computer Programming:COBOL<br>
Prerequisite: MIS 225 or CSC 225. An introduction to computer programming in a business environment. Emphasis on the fundamentals of structured program design, development, testing, implementation and documentation of common business-oriented applications. Discussion and application of top-down design strategies and structured programming techniques for designing and developing problem solutions. Coverage of language syntax, data and file structures, input and output devices, and operating systems facilities for implementing batch programs for report generation, input editing, table processing, and sequential file creation and access. Also listed as CSC 325. (Offered as needed)											(3)
<hr>
MIS 326 Pascal Programming II<br>
Prerequisite: MIS 226 or CSC 226.  Advanced study of Pascal; additional data structures including pointers, linked lists, sets, records; recursion; emphasis is on structured design of large programming projects.  Also listed as CSC 326. (Offered every spring semester)			(3)
<hr>
MIS 327 Computer Programming C<br>
Prerequisite:  MIS 226 or CSC 226.  Structured programming; syntax and format of computer; input/output; functions; data types; text files.  Also listed as CSC 327. (Offered every odd spring semester)												(3)
<hr>
MIS 350 Systems Analysis and Design II<br>
Prerequisite: MIS 250. Advanced study of structured systems development. Emphasis on strategies and techniques of structured analysis and structured design for producing logical methodologies for dealing with complexity in the development of information systems. Also listed as CSC 350. (Offered every even spring semester)								(3)
<hr>
MIS 360 Database Program Development<br>
Prerequisite: MIS 120 or CSC 120. Introduction to application program development in a database environment with an emphasis on loading, modifying and querying the database; applications of data structures; indexed and direct file organizations; models of data including hierarchical, network and relational. Topics also include storage devices, data administration, and data analysis  design and implementation. Also listed as CSC 360. (Offered every even fall semester)	(3)
<hr>
