<html>
<head>
<title>
Keuka College: English Courses
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alinf=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3>
English</font><br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions</font><p><hr>
ENG 101 College English I<br> 
Prerequisite: a grade of C  or better in GED 022 or by placement exam. An introductory course in reading and writing, with emphasis on the writing process. Primary attention is given to providing students with practice in writing for a variety of purposes and in accordance with the principles of standard written English. Complementary work in developing speaking skills. (Offered every semester)			(3)
<hr>
ENG 102 College English II<br> 
Prerequisite: a grade of C  or better in ENG 101 or by placement exam. Continued development of the writing, reading and speaking skills introduced in College English I with special emphasis on advanced argument and research techniques. (Offered every semester)		(3)
<hr>
ENG 118 Poems, Plays and Prose<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. An introduction to the study of literature through the examination of representative works from a variety of genres, historical periods and cultural traditions, with an emphasis on the nature of the various literary kinds: prose fiction, nonfiction prose, drama and poetry. The approach may be topical or thematic and vary from semester to semester. (Offered annually)				(3)
<hr>
ENG 208 Form in Literature<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. An introduction to the study of literature through the examination of representative works from a single literary genre: poetry, drama, the short story, the novel, nonfiction prose, etc. The approach may be topical or thematic and may vary from semester to semester. Course may be repeated with the consent of the instructor. (Offered annually)	 						(3)
<hr>
ENG 209 Topics in World Literature<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. A thematic or topical approach to significant literary works from cultural traditions other than American or British. Focus and reading list may change and is announced in advance. (Offered annually)						(3)
<hr>
ENG 210 Traditions of Literature<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. An introduction to the study of literature through a thematic or topical approach to significant literary works written in English within a given cultural tradition: American, British, Commonwealth, etc. Focus and reading list may change and is announced in advance. May be repeated with the consent of the instructor. (Offered annually)		 					(3)
<hr>
ENG 213 Children s Literature<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. A survey of quality literature past and present for children and young adults. (Offered every odd spring semester)
<hr>
ENG 218 Creative Writing<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. Writing and reviewing the writing of peers with the aim of improving skills and better understanding the elements that make for effective creative writing. Focus may be on fiction, poetry, or drama. May be repeated once with the consent of the instructor. (Offered every even spring semester)									 			(3)
<hr>
ENG 230 Tutoring in Reading and Writing<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 102. Weekly seminars include the theory and practice of collaborative learning background in approaches to teaching writing, listening and questioning skills. Practical supervised work in tutoring. Course also helps students improve their own writing, revising and reading skills. (Offered every fall semester)							 			(1)
<hr>
ENG 295 Introductory Topics in English<br> 
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Humanities and Fine Arts. An introductory study of a specific topic within English. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little background in English. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)											 			(1-3)
<hr>
ENG 301 Creative Writing Workshop<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 218. Advanced study of and practice in the writing of poetry or fiction, with emphasis on personal style, technical polish and marketing manuscripts. (Offered every even spring semester)								(3)
<hr>
ENG 306 Structure and History of English<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. Study of the structure and historical development of the English language. (Offered every odd fall semester)	(3)
<hr>
ENG 312 Topics in Genre<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. A study of one genre selected from the four genres of poetry, drama, prose fiction and nonfiction. Focus changes and is announced in advance. May be repeated with the consent of instructor. (Offered annually) 						(3)
<hr>
ENG 314 Selected Authors<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. Intensive study of a single author or a group of authors. (Offered as needed)				(3)
<hr>
ENG 315 Shakespeare<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. A representative study of selected comedies, tragedies, history plays and problem plays. May be repeated once with consent of instructor. (Offered every even spring semester)									(3) 
<hr>
ENG 316 Alternative Voices<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. A course which focuses on writers whose voices are sometimes excluded or under represented in the traditional canon: female writers, writers of color, or other  alternative voices  who must struggle to be heard in cultural settings either indifferent, uncomprehending, or even openly hostile. Issues of gender, cultural, racial, political or philosophical difference may be explored. (Offered Spring 1995 and every even fall semester thereafter) 											(3)
<hr>
ENG 319 Writing Expository Prose<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. The study and practice of writing nonfiction prose, including essay, newspaper and magazine writing, use of humor, with emphasis on improving expository writing skills. (Offered every odd spring semester)					(3)
<hr>
ENG 320 Selected Studies in Literature<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. Advanced study of selected issues and topics; for example, third world literatures, science fiction, myth. Focus changes and is announced in advance. (Offered as needed)									(3) 
<hr>
ENG 323 American Literature I: Beginnings to 1865<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. An examination of American authors from the colonial beginnings to 1865. Attention is paid to the evolution of the language. Focus may change and is announced in advance. May be repeated once with the consent of instructor. (Offered every odd fall semester)										 					(3)
<hr>
ENG 324 American Literature II: Since 1865<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. A continuation of the study of American literature by surveying American writers of the Modern and Post-modern era, beginning with 1865 and continuing to the present day. (Offered every even spring semester)					(3)
<hr>
ENG 331 British Literature I: Beginnings to 17th Century<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. An examination of British authors from the beginnings to the 17th century. Attention is paid to the evolution of the language. Focus may change and is announced in advance. May be repeated once with consent of the instructor. (Offered every even fall semester)										 					(3)
<hr>
ENG 332 British Literature II: 17th-19th Century<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. An examination of British authors from the seventeenth century through the nineteenth century. Attention is paid to the evolution of the language. Focus may change and is announced in advance. May be repeated once with consent of instructor. (Offered every odd spring semester)										 			(3)
<hr>
ENG 333 British Literature III: 19th-20th Century<br> 
Prerequisite: ENG 101. An examination of British authors of the Victorian and Modern eras. Attention is paid to the evolution of the language. (Offered every odd fall semester)	 										(3)
<hr>
ENG 399 Independent Study<br> 
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				 				(1-3)
<hr>
ENG 450 Senior Seminar<br> 
Prerequisites: senior standing and permission of the instructor. A grade of C- or higher is required to pass this course. The study of various approaches to the interpretation of literature through the study of selected texts. In addition, students are required to develop and carry out a major written project under the supervision of the instructor. (Offered every spring semester)		 				(3)
<hr>
ENG 451 Senior Project in Creative Writing<br> 
Prerequisites: must be an English major with a concentration in creative writing and in the final semester of classes of his/her Keuka College career. Preparation of a 20 30 page manuscript of creative writing. Student works independently though in consultation with a faculty member. (Offered every semester)									 			(3)
<hr>
ENG 495 Advanced Topics in English<br> 
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Humanities and Fine Arts. An advanced study of a specific topic within English. Intended for juniors and seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in English. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)											 			(3)
<hr>
