<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Basic and Applied Social Sciences Division Briefs
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff Link=0000ff alink=ff0000 Vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+2>
Basic and Applied Social Sciences<br></font>
<font size=+3>
Division Briefs</font>
<p>
Basic and Applied Social Sciences is an interdisciplinary division consisting of criminal justice, history, political science, psychology, social work and sociology. Each discipline retains autonomy, although interdisciplinary interaction both inside and outside the division is encouraged. Courses within each discipline are intended to provide a basic foundation in each major and to complement offerings in the various disciplines.
<p>
New tools and techniques are propelling the Division of Basic and Applied Social Science into the twenty-first century.
<p>
Keuka students can study behaviors, attitudes and reactions in the new observation room that has full-color video taping capabilities. 
<p>
The newly created socialization area allows social work students to identify with their profession. In addition to the abnormal psychology courses taught at Keuka, psychology majors now study clinical psychology. 
<p>
New interactive study guides provide students with immediate feedback. These guides accompany textbooks and direct students to the textbook chapter detailing the concept for further study. Students are trained for research professions with the statistical software package which allows them to analyze data and test hypothesis. 
<ul>
<li>Political science and history majors can speak directly with the White House while utilizing the Internet.

<li>The recent approval of the criminal justice major by the State Department of Education will train Keuka students to disarm the growing rate of teen crime.

<li>1,036 graduates shape Keuka's future as professors, lawyers, researchers, psychologists and social workers.
</ul>
<hr></font><font size=+2>
