<html>
<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Nursing Courses
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alinf=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3>Nursing</font><br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions</font><hr>
NUR 120 Human Nutrition<br>
This course involves a holistic approach to human nutrition and the study of nutritional needs across the life span within the context of the individual, the family and the society. The focus is on normal nutrition, and the identification of physiological responses to selected examples of excess or deficient nutritional states. (Offered every fall semester)					 			(2);
<hr>
NUR 201 Transition to Professional Nursing<br>
This course serves as a transition into baccalaureate nursing for the registered nurse. The major focus is an introduction to concepts and processes that serve as a foundation for professional nursing practice. The nursing process is emphasized, applying Roy s Adaptation Model to culturally diverse individuals, families and groups. Content also includes epidemiology, legal/ethical issues in professional nursing, teaching/learning principles and practices, leadership/management theories, and concepts of growth and development. (Offered every semester)		(4);
<hr>
NUR 210 Introduction to Adaptation Nursing<br>
The major focus of this course is an introduction to the structure (systems) and process (adaptation) of Roy s Adaptation Model, factors that affect client adaptation and the role of the nurse in promoting adaptation. Historical, ethical and legal dimensions; the nursing process; communication skills; and client teaching are included in the discussion of the professional nurse s role. Lecture and laboratory clinical experiences. (Offered every fall semester)		 										(3);
<hr>
NUR 220 Implementation of Adaptation Nursing<br>
Prerequisite: NUR 210. Introduction to the nursing process using Roy s Adaptation Model of Nursing applied to clients with a loss of system integrity.  Roy s four modes provide the framework for the course which will be expanded upon in NUR 305. Lecture, laboratory and clinical practicum. (Offered every spring semester)						 			(4);
<hr>
NUR 230 Adaptation to Pharmacological Agents<br>
Prerequisite: NUR 210. This course focuses on the nursing process with clients who are using pharmacological agents to facilitate effective adaptation. It includes content on the classification and use of drugs, as well as on drug and medication administration. Lecture, laboratory. (Offered every spring semester)									 		(2);
<hr>
NUR 240 Health Assessment Across Life Span<br>
Prerequisites: NUR 120, NUR 210. Study of the various components of physical assessment and health history across the life span, using  Roy s Adaptation Model Nursing Process as the framework. (Offered every spring semester)					(3);
<hr>
NUR 250 Adaptation to Change: Birth through Aging<br>
Prerequisite: NUR 301. This course focuses on concepts of growth and development from birth through aging, as well as adaptation of the individual to change and loss of system integrity. It serves as the foundation for NUR 305 and NUR 306. Adaptation needs of the client are considered across all four of Roy s modes. Lecture. (Offered every fall semester)		 			(2);
<hr>
NUR 301 Professional Practice I <br>
Prerequisites: all sophomore level nursing courses. This course focuses on concepts and processes which serve as a foundation for all junior level nursing courses. The course addresses the holistic nursing process with culturally diverse individuals, families, groups and communities with loss of system integrity. The psychological and sociological aspects of Roy s Adaptation Model are emphasized. Crisis intervention, the concepts and principles of epidemiology and current issues in health care are introduced. Lecture. (Offered every fall semester)		(3);
<hr>
NUR 305 Promotion of Physiologic Adaptation<br>
Prerequisites: NUR 250, NUR 301. This course focuses on the study of adaptation of the client with a significant loss of system integrity whose primary needs are in the physiologic mode. Emphasis is on application of the nursing process and integration of nursing theory into clinical practice. Lecture and clinical practicum. (Offered every fall semester)			 				(4);
<hr>
NUR 306 Promotion of Psycho social Adaptation<br>
Pre- or Co-requisites: NUR 301, NUR 304. The focus of this course is on the study of adaptation of clients with loss of system integrity, whose primary needs are in the psycho social modes. Emphasis is on application of the nursing process and integration of nursing theory into clinical practice. Lecture and clinical practicum. (Offered every fall semester)		 					(3);
<hr>
NUR 324 Family Adaptation to Change<br>
Prerequisite: NUR 301. Growth and development from birth through adolescence, as well as family theory, provide the framework for this course, which serves as a foundation for NUR 325 and NUR 326. The major focus is on the family s adaptation to change. Lecture only. (Offered every spring semester)									 			(2);
<hr>
NUR 325 Family Adaptation to the Reproductive Cycle<br>
Prerequisite: NUR 301. Co-requisite: NUR 324. This course focuses on the adaptation of low-risk and high-risk clients and their families throughout all phases of the reproductive cycle. The nursing process and selected conceptual frameworks are used to explore the physiological and psychosocial changes of neonatal, child bearing and gynecological clients and their families. The impact of cultural, political, economic, ethical and legal factors are explored. Lecture and clinical practicum. (Offered every spring semester)						(3);
<hr>
NUR 326 Adaptation: Children with Loss of System Integrity<br>
Prerequisite: NUR 301. Co-requisite: NUR 324. This course focuses on adaptive responses of families with children experiencing loss of system integrity. The pathophysiological and psychosocial effects of selected acute, terminal and selected chronic illnesses in children are explored. Emphasis is n application of the nursing process and integration of nursing content with clinical practice.  Lecture and clinical practicum. (Offered every spring semester) 		 								(3);
<hr>
NUR 328 Nursing Research<br>
Prerequisite: SS 231 and all sophomore level nursing courses. This course examines each step of the research process, with emphasis upon the ability to develop researchable problems related to nursing practice and patient care and the ability to critique research proposals and reports. The relevance and importance of clinical scholarship in nursing is explored. Course content includes the ethics of research, quantitative vs. qualitative research methods, theory development and utilization of research findings in practice. Lecture. (Offered every spring semester) 	(2);
<hr>
NUR 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				 			(1-3);
<hr>
NUR 401 Professional Practice II<br>
Prerequisites: All sophomore and junior level nursing courses. This course focuses on concepts and processes which serve as a foundation for all senior level nursing courses. The content builds on sophomore and junior level nursing courses and draws upon the liberal arts core and prerequisites for nursing. The primary emphasis is on critical thinking in nursing, development of nursing as a science and current issues in nursing and health care delivery. Personal growth and socialization for professional practice are supported by course activities. (Offered every fall semester)										 					(3);
<hr>
NUR 405 Adaptive Needs of Systems Attaining Stability<br>
Pre- or Co-requisite: NUR 401. This course serves as a foundation for NUR 406 and NUR 407. Concepts and principles underlying chronic illnesses and rehabilitation nursing are presented.  The course addresses obstacles and challenges to adaptation for clients with long-term health care needs throughout the lifespan.  The nurse's role as a member of the health care team caring for individuals, families and groups with chronic illness is explored  The course also examines the function of support groups, the role of the community and public policy as it relates to chronic illness.  (Offered every fall semester)								 					(2);
<hr>
NUR 406 Community/Home Care<br>
Prerequisites: NUR 401, NUR 405.  This course focuses on the nursing process with individual and family systems attaining stability in the home environment. Emphasis is on the role(s) of the professional nurse working with family members and community agency personnel to provide nursing care for clients with adaptive needs in all four of Roy s modes in the home setting. Assessment is made of the home and of a selected agency that supports delivery of home care services. Selected issues are researched and discussed. Lecture and clinical practicum. (Offered every spring semester)								 					(3);
<hr>
NUR 407 Nursing Care of Systems Attaining  Stability<br>
Pre- or Co-requisites: NUR 401, NUR 405. This course focuses on the rehabilitation of clients of any age who have acute or chronic health care problems in any of Roy s Adaptive Modes. Maintenance or promotion of optimal adaptation is stressed. A variety of health care settings is used. Lecture and clinical practicum. (Offered every fall semester)				 			(4);
<hr>
NUR 421 Nursing Management/Leadership<br>
Prerequisite: NUR 401. This course focuses on the synthesis of leadership, communication, adaptation, organization, behavioral group and change theories and applies them to clinical nursing management and the health care system.  Opportunity is provided in the clinical area to apply theories presented in class. (Offered every spring semester)				 				(3);
<hr>
NUR 422 Adaptation for Health Promotion<br>
This course focuses on the nursing process with selected individual, family, group and community systems in actual or potential need of adaptive assistance. Content focuses on analysis, decision-making, application of selected health promoting strategies and evaluation. Nursing actions are directed toward promoting or developing processes or resources to maintain integrity or broaden the adaptive level of the system. Lecture and clinical practicum. (Offered every fall semester)									(3);
<hr>
NUR 491 Field Period in Nursing<br>
Prerequisite: NUR 401. Provides an opportunity for the student to further develop personal and professional role behaviors in a relatively long-term and increasingly independent framework. The emphasis is on the integration of previously learned knowledge into the more realistic practice setting. Students focus on care of clients with loss of system integrity and/or in crisis, which they have already studied and applied in the more structured clinical practicum. Preparatory classes and campus laboratories are included in this experience. (Offered every January)	  	 (3);
<hr>
NUR 495 Advanced Topics in Nursing<br>
Prerequisites: To be determined by the Division of Nursing. An advanced study of a specific topic in nursing. Intended for juniors and seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in nursing. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)	(1-3);
<hr>
<font size=+2><img src=greendot.gif><a href="./dvnurse.html">Return to the Nursing Division page</a><br>
<img src=greendot.gif><a href="./index.html">Return to the Keuka College home page</a><br>
</font></body>
