<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Psychology 
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alinf=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3>
Psychology </font><br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions</font><p><hr>
SWK 101 Introduction to Social Work<br>
A foundation course which provides introductory overview of the social work profession examined through the scope of:  the profession's historical development and relationship to current social welfare service; diverse practice settings; and special issues and/or groups within social work practice settings (including racism, aging, women, sexuality, disabled and others) (Offered every fall semester 			(3)
<hr>
SWK 211 Generalist Social Work Practice I<br>
Prerequisite: PSY 123, SOC 101, SWK 101 and approval from the instructor. Introduction to social work profession; values, ethics, theories, concepts and generalist practice methods.  Foundational skills to include: counselor/client relationships, interviewing and assessment techniques, skills in communication and confidentiality, professional writing, social work documentation and use of clinical supervision. (Offered every semester)			 					(3)
<hr>
SWK 212 Generalist Social Work Practice II<br>
Prerequisites: SWK 211, SS 231. Focus on the professional use of self through client and systems work. Skills emphasis will be in nonverbal behavior, use of various clinical assessment tools, awareness of and sensitivity to cultural diversity and self awareness. Students will integrate qualitative and quantitative research to generalist social work practice and further develop skills of critical thinking. (Offered every semester)				(3)
<hr>
SWK 250 Substance Abuse and Families<br>
Prerequisites: SOC 101 or PSY 101 or SWK 101. Substance abuse within family systems and society-at-large is a prevalent issue in social work practice. This course will provide an overview of the progression of substance abuse and how it  impacts individuals, families, social institutions and communities. Identification of substance abuse and dependency, basic counselor-client practice skills and levels of social work intervention will be incorporated into the curriculum. The format will be interactive and experiential. (Offered every even spring semester)		 			(3)
<hr>
SWK 295 Introductory Topics in Social Work<br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Basic and Applied Social Sciences. An introductory study of a specific topic within social work. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in social work. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)				(1-3)
<hr>
SWK 301 Social Welfare Policy and Service I<br>
Prerequisites: SWK 212, SOC 101, PSY 123, POL 130. Policy development process including: framework for analysis; examination of  history  of social welfare in the United States; the ideology, values, and policies that have influenced social programs and current programs, organizations, provisions and issues; participation in lobbying on the National Association of Social Workers Legislative Day is required; grant writing lab. (Offered every spring semester)
				(3)
<hr>
SWK 311 Generalist Social Work Practice III<br>
Prerequisites: SWK 211, SWK 212, SWK 321, SOC 101, SOC 301, PSY 123,  BIO 202. Multi-client system approach, beginning with the context of family and moving from micro-mezzo-macro systems. Integrate theoretical frameworks and bio-psycho-social variables in understanding and intervening in systems. Skills of ethics, values, confidentiality, advocacy, organizational change and counseling techniques emphasized as they relate to a multi-client system. Work with groups, special needs populations and cultural diversity addressed from this perspective. Beginning look at macro structures of organizations, agencies, government and funding impact on client services. Quantitative and qualitative field research project to practically apply above issues to social work problems and solutions. (Offered every spring semester)						(3)
<hr>
SWK 321 Human Behavior and Social Environment I<br>
Prerequisites: PSY 123, BIO 202, SOC 101, SOC 221. Content about human bio-psycho-social development through the life stages, including knowledge about social systems in which individuals live (families, groups, organizations, instructions, communities). The application of systems to a social work perspective of human development; emphasis on life situations encountered by generalist social workers and impact of factors such as oppression, discrimination, poverty and sexism. (Offered every semester)			(3)
<hr>
SWK 330 Populations-At-Risk<br>
Prerequisites: SOC 101, PSY 123, SWK 211, SWK 212, SWK 321 AND SOC 221. Social justice and social responsibility are important components of the social work curriculum. Social justice refers to understanding of diversity. Social responsibility refers to student commitment in enhancing the quality of life for their community, family and client systems. This course is designed to integrate previous theory and practice content on human oppression, discrimination and economic deprivation. Content will focus on how these realities impact the following people:  people of color, women, gay and lesbian persons, older Americans, poor persons, disabled persons, various ethnic groups and rural areas. Students will learn strategies for social change which improve the quality of life for client systems, their families and community, as well as, eradicate the effects of oppression. (Offered every spring semester)			(3)
<hr>
SWK 331 Child Welfare Interventions<br>
Child welfare services and the juvenile justice system; impact on children of such problems as abuse, juvenile delinquency, emotional disturbance; the child as a human being. (Offered Spring '97 and as needed thereafter)	(3)
<hr>
SWK 332 Group Processes<br>
Prerequisites: SOC 101 or SWK 211. Formation, definition and process of a group; group interactions using group exercises and experiences. Also listed as SOC 332. (Offered every odd spring semester)		(3)
<hr>
SWK 333 Interventions with Older Persons<br>
Aging as an individual's lifespan issue, as well as an area of societal concern and policy development; health, economic, political, ecological, social, and familial issues and the role of the social worker. (Offered as needed)						(3)
<hr>
SWK 390 Junior Social Work Field Period<br>
Prerequisite: admittance into major and written consent of a social work faculty member. Off-campus experiential education in varied community agency settings with exposure to direct practice, service roles and diverse populations. (Offered every summer and January)	 					(3)
<hr>
SWK 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(1-3)
<hr>
SWK 401 Social Welfare Policies and Services II<br>
Prerequisite: SWK 301, SWK 311, SWK 321, SOC 301, SS 231. An examination of selected laws, programs, benefits and services that form the basis of social welfare policy in the United States. Social welfare policy analysis and its application. The structure of service delivery systems, organizations and social inequities in service delivery and to organizational change strategies that promote social and economic justice. An introduction to program development. (Offered every fall semester)		(3)
<hr>
SWK 411 General Social Work Practice and Research IV<br>
Prerequisites: SWK 311, SWK 321, SOC 301 and SS 231. Addresses the intervention, termination and evaluation stages in the generalist mode as related to various size client systems; emphasis on social work roles of advocate, broker and community planner in selected fields of social service practice. Systematic evaluation of practice for addressing organization and community issues, and measurement of practice interventions. (Offered every fall semester)						(3)
<hr>
SWK 421 Human Behavior and Social Environment II<br>
Prerequisites: SWK 311, SWK 321, SWK 301. Examination of macro-level phenomena relevant to the profession of social work and generalist practice, building on content from various academic disciplines such as sociology, psychology, human biology and political science. Examination of social systems theory and utilization of ecosystemic approach; emphasis on human diversity and the social environment continues. (Offered every fall semester)		 					(3)
<hr>
SWK 450 Senior Practicum and Seminar<br>
Prerequisite:  only those students who are candidates for the baccalaureate degree in social work may be admitted into the practicum and seminar. Block placement in social service agencies including generalist work at an approved setting for a minimum of 32 hours a week and a semester research project. Students evaluate their own practice interventions utilizing quantitative and qualitative methodologies. Students develop greater awareness of professional use of self in practice settings. (Offered every spring semester)						(15)
<hr>
SWK 490 Senior Social Work Field Period<br>
Prerequisite: SWK 390 and written consent of a social work faculty member. Off-campus experiential education in varied community agency settings with exposure to direct practice, service roles and diverse populations. (Offered every summer and January)			 					(3)
<hr>
SWK 495 Advanced Topics in Social Work<br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Basic and Applied Social Sciences. An advanced study of a special topic within social work. Intended for juniors or seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in social work. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)		(3)


<hr>
<font size=+2><img src=greendot.gif><a href="./social.html">Return to the Social Work major page</a><br>
<img src=greendot.gif><a href="./dvbass.html">Return to the Basic and Applied Social Sciences Division page</a><br>
<img src=greendot.gif><a href="./index.html">Return to the Keuka College home page</a><br>
</font>
</body>
</html>
