<head>
<title>
Keuka College: English
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alink=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3><b>English</b></font> <br>
<font size=+2>at Keuka College</font><p>
<font size=+1>
<b>Major Briefs</b><br>
Students majoring or minoring in English explore the power of language. They develop a greater sensitivity to the relationship between language and the world in which they live. By studying literature and sharpening their writing skills, students enhance their verbal and written abilities. 
<p>
Students in the English program develop their ability to read critically and write clearly and persuasively. Through the study of prose, poetry and drama, students develop techniques to respond to life experiences with the written word. And, they gain an historical perspective through the study of British and American literature. 
<p>
Studying English offers the student practical and personal benefits. Understanding English raises students' awareness levels of the range of the human experience and at the same time helps them to express their own perceptions of that experience with greater creativity.
<p>
Keuka offers majors in English, English 7-12, English with a concentration in writing/communication and English with a concentration in creative writing. Minors are offered in English and creative writing.   
<p>



<b>
Career Options</b><br>
Students of English can offer perspective employers a range of skills that are much in demand in today's work force:  the ability to communicate effectively, to think rigorously and creatively and to adapt themselves readily to new circumstances in a rapidly changing world. Graduates in English may go on to careers in communication, teaching, business, government and numerous other fields. They also may pursue graduate work in the humanities, journalism, business, law, medicine, education, library science, social services or other areas. 

<p>
<b>
<a href="engcrdr.html">Course Descriptions</a></b><p>

