<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Nursing Division Briefs
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff Link=0000ff alink=ff0000 Vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+2>
Nursing<br></font>
<font size=+3>
Division Briefs</font><p>
The Keuka College nursing program is designed for students who are preparing for RN licensure and for registered nurses returning to school to obtain a bachelor of science in nursing (B.S.N.). The purpose of baccalaureate nursing education is to provide knowledge of the theory and practice of professional nursing. In addition to focusing on the care of individual clients in acute care settings, baccalaureate programs expand this preparation to include the care of the family, groups and community. Students practice in a variety of health care settings, initiate and coordinate health care and learn to think critically. Comprehensive health care is emphasized, which includes prevention, maintenance, health promotion, rehabilitation, counseling and education for clients and families across the life span. 
<p>
Clinical practice becomes increasingly self-directed as the student progresses through the program. Clinical affiliations are numerous and take place in a variety of urban and rural health care settings. Graduates of the Keuka College baccalaureate nursing program are able to assume a wide range of care roles in institutional and community settings.
<p>
A special characteristic of the program is the senior level Field Period in nursing when the student has an opportunity to practice in a variety of health care environments. During this Field Period, the student must integrate previous course work, receiving intensive preparation for postgraduate employment. 
<p>
1,355 graduates shape our future as registered nurses, home health care providers, wellness and nurse educators. 
<p>
Keuka's Step II program puts registered nurses boasting a two-year degree or nursing diploma on track to a bachelor of science degree. The flexible program, tailored to each student's needs and schedule, prepares graduates for supervisory and upper level administration positions in traditional health care systems and emerging community health care environments. 
<p>
The program is accredited by the Council of Baccalaureate and Higher Degree Programs of the National League for Nursing. Following completion of the program and the awarding of the baccalaureate degree, the graduate is eligible to apply for the National Council Licensure Examination (NCLEX) for professional nursing and to apply for a license to practice as a registered nurse (RN). 

<hr></font><font size=+2>
<img src="greendot.gif"><a href="./dvnurse.html">Return to the Nursing Division page</a><br>
<img src="greendot.gif"><a href="./index.html">Return to the Keuka College home page</a></font>
</body>
