<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Experiential Learning Opportunities
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff Link=0000ff alink=ff0000 Vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+2>
Humanities and Fine Arts<br></font>
<font size=+3>
Experiential Learning Opportunities</font>
<p>
A Keuka Field Period is the height of career exploration. It can, also, provide insight into entirely new lifestyles, immersing you in cultures miles away from your own, in philosophy and distance. 
<p>
11 students traveled to Mexico this year, thanks to the leadership of Michaela Cosgrove, assistant professor of Spanish. 
<p>
"Career exploration allows students to 'try on' a profession; a cultural immersion experience teaches students to observe a totally new environment with appropriate cultural perspective," Cosgrove said. 
<p>
Cosgrove led the Keuka students through present day Mexico City and the Yucatan after spending months preparing students with Mexico's past and insights regarding its social history. The student-travelers had two common learning objectives, understanding the important aspects of Mexico's social and cultural history from European and indigenous perspectives and how this history is reflected in contemporary Mexican society. In addition, each student selected a third, personal learning objective. 
<p>
Jane McMillan, a junior from Lowville, N.Y., studied myths surrounding the Quetzalcoatl and how they affected the people of Mexico. 
<p>
Although it is easy to become consumed by personal routines and daily life, there is a world full of experiences, adventures and memories. Traveling expands a person's horizons and enhances Keuka's liberal arts education!

<hr></font><font size=+2>
