<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Criminal Justice/Criminology Courses
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alinf=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3>
Criminal Justice/Criminology</font><br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions</font><p><hr>
CRM 101 Introduction to Criminal Justice<br>
Study of criminal justice system, including law enforcement, the courts and correctional methods; origins, ideologies and consequences of various systems, both historically and cross-culturally, with emphasis on contemporary American criminal justice. (Offered every spring semester, beginning Spring 1998)			(3)
<hr>
CRM 201 Criminology Theory and Methods<br>
Prerequisite:  CRM 101. Critical examination of theories and research findings in criminology; methods of control and treatment of crime; evaluation of theories and methods as they apply to selected types of crimes, with emphasis on needs and directions for future efforts. (Offered every fall semester, beginning Fall 1997)						(3)
<hr>
CRM 211 Relations of Law Enforcement<br>
Prerequisite: CRM 101. Issues of law enforcement agencies at local, state and federal levels; interrelations with other criminal justice agencies and community groups, such as media and neighborhood watch groups; problem area, such as perceived police intrusion, corruption and excessive force. (Offered every odd fall semester, beginning Fall 1997)		(3)
<hr>
CRM 221 Criminal Investigation<br>
Prerequisite: CRM 101. Methods of step-by-step inquiry in search for evidence to establish facts connected with crimes, their commission, and the perpetrators; methods of criminalistics to examine and evaluate physical crime evidence; role of law in these processes. (Offered every even spring semester, beginning Spring 1998) 	(3)
<hr>
CRM 231 Courts, Prosecution and Defense<br>
Prerequisite: CRM 101. Study of the structures, functions and processes of criminal courts and courtroom work groups; lower criminal courts, trial courts and appellate courts; judges, prosecutors and defense counsel; prosecution, adjudication and sentencing. (Offered every odd spring semester, beginning Spring 1999)	(3)
<hr>
CRM 232 Punishment, Treatment and Corrections<br>
Prerequisite: CRM 101. Philosophies, theories and practices in the post-conviction stage of criminal justice; institutionalization and its alternatives, such as parole, community service and probation. (Offered every even spring semester, beginning Spring 1998)	(3)
<hr>
CRM 301 Criminal Law<br>
Prerequisites: CRM 101; CRM 201. Comparative study of criminal law with emphasis on United States constitution, highlighting first, fourth, fifth and sixth amendments; prosecution and defense in crimes against persons, property and public order; application of New York State penal law and definitions. (Offered every fall semester, beginning Fall 1997)		(3)
<hr>
CRM 311 Organized Crime<br>
Prerequisites: CRM 101; CRM 201. Local, regional, national and international crime groups and organizations as part of a criminal system that includes government officials, business leaders and police; provision of unlawful services in strong public demand and protection through corruption and intimidation. (Offered every odd fall semester, beginning Fall 1999)	(3)
<hr>
CRM 312 Predatory Crime and Violence<br>
Prerequisites: CRM 101; CRM 201. Analysis of such offenses as robbery, vandalism, arson, stalking, assaults, domestic violence, sex crimes and homicides as committed by both occasional and career criminals. In-depth exploration of the range of theoretical explanations for such offenses. (Offered every even spring semester, beginning Spring 1998)		(3)
<hr>
CRM 321 Juvenile Delinquency<br>
Prerequisites: CRM 101; CRM 201. Course approaches juvenile delinquency as a unique kind of crime, different from ordinary adult crime in etiology, motive, prevention, justice system and treatment. Emphasis on research findings and synthesis of theoretical perspectives in analysis and explanation of delinquency. (Offered every even fall semester)			(3)
<hr>
CRM 322 White Collar and Corporate Crime<br>
Prerequisites: CRM 101; CRM 201. Offenses committed by the more privileged members of society in the course of their occupation, including crimes such as embezzlement committed by individuals for personal gain, and crimes for corporate gain that violate business law committed as part of regular business practice. (Offered every odd fall semester, beginning Fall 1997)	 			(3)
<hr>
CRM 390 Junior Criminology/Criminal Justice Field Period<br>
Prerequisite: Junior status in the major. First experiential education experience in criminology/criminal justice agency setting to learn basic operations and participate in agency activities. Involves final group discussion and written analytical report. (Offered every January and summer, beginning January 1997)	(3)
<hr>
CRM 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite: Consent of instructor. (Offered every semester, beginning Fall 1997)	(1-3)
<hr>
CRM 401 Internship in Criminology/Criminal<br>
Prerequisites: Senior status and at least 24 credits in major. Supervised field work in a criminology/criminal justice setting for at least 35 hours a week for a minimum of 14 weeks. Completion of a formal project or paper under the guidance of a faculty member in the program is required and will be presented in the CRM 402 Seminar. (Offered every fall semester, beginning Fall 1997)					(12)
<hr>
CRM 402 Seminar: Case Studies in Criminology/Criminal Justice<br>
Prerequisites: CRM 101; CRM 201; CRM 301; CRM 401; Senior status in major. Utilization of criminological theories and methods in analysis of case studies, including students' experiences from their own internships (CRM 401); application of research skills to prepare, present and defend relevant findings to a critical audience. (Offered every spring semester, beginning Spring 1998)				(3)
<hr>
CRM 490 Senior Criminology/Criminal Justice Field Period<br>
Prerequisite: Senior status in major. Second experiential education experience in criminology/criminal justice agency setting to learn basic operations and participate in agency activities. Involves final group discussion and written analytical report. (Offered every January and summer semester, beginning with January 1997)					 	(3)

<hr>
