<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Sociology
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff link=0000ff alinf=ff0000 vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+3>
Sociology </font><br>
<font size=+2>Course Descriptions</font><p><hr>
SOC 101 Introduction to Sociology<br>
The sociological perspective as applied to the contemporary world; concepts and principles used to analyze social relationships and institutions. (Offered every semester)	(3)
<hr>
SOC 213 Medical Sociology<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. Study of health care as a social institution; social and cultural implications of sickness and health; community organization for health; impact of medical ideology and division of labor on treatment of physical and mental illnesses. (Offered every fall semester)						(3)
<hr>
SOC 221 Minority Group Relations<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. Interrelations of various American minority groups to dominant or other minority groups including tensions, conflicts and accommodations; consequences of the subordinate-dominant group situation to groups and individuals. (Offered every spring semester)						(3)
<hr>
SOC 223 Crime, Deviance and Social Control<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. Criminal and deviant behavior; interaction between society, delinquents, criminals and deviants; social controls inside and outside correctional systems; relevant theories in contemporary criminological research. (Offered every fall semester)	(3)
<hr>
SOC 241 Sociology of Work and Leisure<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. Sociological study of people at work and play; impact and relevance of industrialization and the Protestant work ethic on production and consumption by human beings in the industrial and post-industrial world. (Offered every even spring semester)		(3)
<hr>
SOC 295 Introductory Topics in Sociology<br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Basic and Applied Social Sciences. An introductory study of a specific topic within sociology. Intended for freshmen and sophomores, or for students with little or no background in sociology. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)						(3)
<hr>
SOC 301 Methods of Social Research<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. Basic qualitative and quantitative methods of empirical social research; techniques of design, hypothesis testing, collection, analysis and interpretation of data. (Offered every spring semester)	(3) 
<hr>
SOC 303 Cultural Sociology<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. Cultural analysis of social phenomena; diverse conceptualizations of culture, influence of culture on group cohesion and conflict, clarification of predominant American values and goals, dynamics of culture, and origins and effects of various subcultures and contracultures. (Offered every odd fall semester)
				(3)
<hr>
SOC 321 Sociology of Women and Work<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. The historical and contemporary basis of the sexual division of labor; the nature of women's work in the labor market and the home; strategies for improving women's social and economic position. (Offered as needed)			(3)
<hr>
SOC 322 Power and Society<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. The power process in various kinds of human interaction (political, familial, organizational); theoretical perspectives explaining this process. (Offered every even fall semester)				(3)
<hr>
SOC 331 Collective Behavior<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. Sociological study of comparatively unstructured social situations and their products, such as crowds, riots, mobs, rumor, contagion, mass hysteria, panics, crazes, fads, fashions, revivals, public opinion, propaganda, mass behavior, social movements, reforms and revolutions. (Offered every odd fall semester)				(3)
<hr>
SOC 332 Group Processes<br>
Prerequisites: SOC 101 or SWK 211. Formation, definition and process of a group; group interactions using group exercises and experiences. Also listed as SWK 332. (Offered every odd spring semester)		(3)
<hr>
SOC 333 Mind, Self and Society<br>
Prerequisites: SOC 101 or PSY 227. Emergence and development of the self as a social product; effects of social interaction on individual thought and action. (Offered every even fall semester)						(3)
<hr>
SOC 341 Social Stratification<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. Hierarchical organization of societies; principle theories and concepts of stratification; correlates of inequality including life chances, life styles, stratacultures and power relationships. (Offered every odd spring semester) 
				(3)
<hr>
SOC 343 Communities<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. The structure and processes of communities in post-industrial America and their effects on the lives of individuals and social groups. (Offered every odd fall semester)			(3)
<hr>
SOC 344 Sociology of the Family<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. Basic concepts relating to family systems in a cross-cultural perspective; emphasis on historical development and change. (Offered every odd spring semester)	(3)
<hr>
SOC 351 Sociological Theory<br>
Prerequisite: SOC 101. Conceptually distinct schools in the sociological tradition; major theoretical orientations and models in the study of social phenomena. (Offered every spring semester)				(3)
<hr>
SOC 399 Independent Study<br>
Prerequisite: consent of instructor. (Offered every semester)				(1-3)
<hr>
SOC 402 Social Intervention<br>
Prerequisites: SOC 101 and junior or senior standing. Case studies of directed social change in response to social problems; utilization of social science through sociological practice; theories and methods of applied social research and social policy research. (Offered every odd spring semester)				(3)
<hr>
SOC 410 Internship in Sociological Practice<br>
Prerequisites: senior status and at least 30 hours in the major, including sociology major core and applied sociology core. Supervised field work in a practice setting for at least 35 hours a week for a minimum of 14 weeks. Completion of a formal project or paper under the guidance of a faculty member in sociology is required. (Offered every fall semester)			(12)
<hr>
SOC 442 Associations<br>
Prerequisites: SOC 101 and junior or senior standing. Study of such organizational forms as administrative and voluntary associations; control structures, theories, interdependence and change; intergroup relations and effects on individuals and associations. (Offered every even spring semester)				(3)
<hr>
SOC 443 Criminal Justice Systems<br>
Prerequisites: SOC 101 and junior or senior standing. Comparative study of criminal justice systems both historically and cross-culturally, including formal and informal law enforcement and trial and correctional methods;  origins, ideologies and consequences of various systems, with emphasis on contemporary American criminal justice system. (Offered every even spring semester)			(3)
<hr>
SOC 495 Advanced Topics in Sociology<br>
Prerequisites: to be determined by the Division of Basic and Applied Social Sciences. An advanced study of a specific topic within sociology. Intended for juniors and seniors, or for students with an appropriate background in sociology. The student may repeat the course, but not the topic. (Offered as needed)			(3)

<hr>
