<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Experiential Learning Opportunities
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff Link=0000ff alink=ff0000 Vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+2>
Nursing<br></font>
<font size=+3>
Experiential Learning Opportunities</font>
<p>
The Spring 1996 semester at Keuka College marked the first semester of a three-year service learning project funded by the Foundation for Long Term Care, in Albany, NY. Through this project Keuka College students volunteer in the gerontology field, gaining hands-on experience. In  the course, Perspectives on the Aging, students spend much of the semester learning in nursing homes, community-based agencies and long term care facilities. 
<p>
The course enhances the student's knowledge of the aging population related to service learning. Students volunteer their time and talents as they gain practical experience in the field. A dozen Keuka students are working and learning in area organizations. 
<p>
"This generation of students is the most effected by the rising costs associated with a growing aging population, smaller families and growth of the female work force. Participation in service learning courses focusing on the issues and policies governing practices can only help raise awareness levels, interest and civic responsibility for meeting the needs fo the elderly. This course serves as a backdrop for anticipated future contributions students will make as concerned members of their communities," Keuka College Associate Professor Nursing Kay Viggiani said.   


