<head>
<title>
Keuka College: Humanities and Fine Arts Faculty
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=ffffff Link=0000ff alink=ff0000 Vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+2>
Humanities and Fine Arts<br></font>
<font size=+3>
Faculty Profiles</font>
<p><font size=+2>
Associate Professors</font><p>
<b>Dexter Benedict<br></b>
Associate Professor of Art (1992) B.A., Ottawa University; M.F.A., University of North Carolina at Greensboro. Dexter has organized more than 10 art exhibits in the College's Lightner Library, representing different art media (drawings, paintings, sculptures) and different artists (student, local and regional).
<p>
<b>Robert Darling<br></b>
Associate Professor of English (1988); B.A., Elmira College; M.A., Syracuse University; Ph.D., University of Rhode Island. Bob has been published in more than 50 magazines in the U.S., Canada, England and Australia. He has won several poetry awards. 
<p>
<b>Joanne Desotelle<br></b>
Associate Professor of English and Chairperson of the Humanities and Fine Arts Division (1990); B.A., M.A., Moorhead State University; Ph.D., University of North Dakota. Joanne is an active member of the College's computer planning and computer pedagogy committees and recently attended a workshop on "Technology and the Design of Courses of Study." 
<p>
<b>Norman R. Muir<br></b>
Associate Professor of English and Assistant Academic Dean (1994); B.A., Keene State College; M.A., Northeastern University; Ph.D., SUNY Stony Brook
<p>
<b>Douglas W. Richards<br></b>
Associate Professor of English (1987); A.B., Hamilton College; M.A.T., Colgate University; A.M., Ph.D., University of Rochester. Doug presented "Helping Students Learn about College:  A Thematic Focus for Freshman Writing Courses" at the 1995 College Conference on Composition and Communication. 
<p>
<font size=+2>Assistant Professors</font><p>
<b>Anita Chirco<br></b>
Assistant Professor of English (1991); B.A., St. John Fisher College; M.P.S., Cornell University; Ph.D., Syracuse University. Anita published an article entitled "Pedagogy and Workload:  How Can I Know What My Problem Is (or How To Solve It) Until I Hear Myself Say That I Have a Problem?" in the College Consortium of the <i>Finger Lakes Journal</i>. 
<p>
<b>Michaela A. Cosgrove<br></b>
Assistant Professor of Spanish (1980); B.A., M.A., SUNY Albany. Michaela has been selected to lead an annual workshop at the National Society for Experiential Education in New Orleans.
<p>
<b>Mark Wenderlich<br></b>
Assistant Professor of Theatre (1990); B.A., SUNY College at Potsdam; M.A., University of Iowa; M.F.A., Syracuse University. Directed "Love Letters" for the Geneva Theatre Guild. He has appeared in several commercial shoots, one published by the New York Times.

<hr></font><font size=+2>
