<html>
<head>
<title>
Latest News
</title>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" text=000000 link=0000ff vlink=006000>
<img align=right src="coltop2.gif">
<font size=+1> Keuka College </font>
<br>
<b><font size=+3> Latest News</font></b><br><p>
<br>
<p><hr>
<font size=+2>


Strong Appointed Interim President; Others Assume New Responsibilities
</font><p>
The Keuka College Board of Trustees has appointed Frank P. Strong, Jr., Board of Trustees chair, as the College's interim president, effective January 1, 1997. Keuka President Arthur F. Kirk Jr. announced his resignation from the College last month, to assume the presidency of St. Leo College outside of Tampa, Fla.  Strong served as Keuka's acting president from February to August 1995 while Kirk completed a six-month sabbatical.  
<p>
Marilyn Baader, Keuka College Board of Trustees vice chair and a member of the College's Class of 1963, steps up to acting chair of the College's governing board. Baader is a resident of Cayuga, N.Y.  A Board-appointed committee, chaired by Richard Rosett, of Rochester, N.Y., will conduct a national search for Keuka's 18th president.  
<p>
"Frank Strong is an experienced executive," Baader said. "His professional and volunteer experience, coupled with his years of service as a Trustee and former experience in our president's office, offer Keuka a knowledgeable, seasoned and strong leader. "
<p>
Strong, who retired from Eastman Kodak in 1991 after a 34-year career, is a resident of Fairport, N.Y. He is a veteran engineer, senior executive and group vice president. His current business pursuits concentrate on corporate governance. He has been a member of Keuka's Board of Trustees since 1987 and has worked closely with Kirk to realize Keuka College's goals and plan for its future. In July 1994, Strong assumed board chairmanship after serving for three years as vice chair. 
<p>
"It is with enthusiasm that I begin my tenure as interim president of Keuka College, knowing first-hand, what a tremendous experience it is to steer the course of an institution that has made such remarkable strides in the last decade," Strong, who holds a master's degree in engineering and business administration from Dartmouth College, said. "My priority will be to see that Keuka's strategic and operating plans remain on track, ensuring continued growth and quality."
<p>
In addition to his involvement with Keuka, Strong is a member of Governor Pataki's Privatization Commission and serves Dartmouth's Thayer School of Engineering, the Otetiana Council, Boy Scouts of America and the Rochester-Monroe County Visiting Nurse Service. 
<p>
Reporters:  Strong will be available for personal interviews at your convenience. Please call Stephanie  at (315) 536-4411 ext. 5241 to schedule an appointment. 
<hr>
<br>
