<A HREF="http://www.tut.fi/cgi-bin/cgiwrap/~kvweb/aglimpse"><IMG WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=35 SRC="images/BtnSearch.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="Search"></A><BR>

</TD>
<!-- toinen sarake, johon tulee varsinainen leipateksti, leveytta ei ole asetettu -->
<TD VALIGN=TOP>
<!-- sisennysta varten tarvitaan DefinitionList -->
<DL>
<!-- uusi kappale aloitetaan P-DT yhdistelmalla -->
<P><DT>
<!-- Otsikoiden fontiksi arial/helvetica, koska se nayttaa paremmalta -->
<!-- Huomaa myos englanninkielelle tyypillinen otsikoiden capitalisointi -->

<FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><H1>Costs and Financial Support</H1></FONT>
<!-- sisennys tapahtuu DD-tagilla -->

<P><DT>
<FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><H2>Cost of Studies</H2></FONT>
<DD>
Higher education in Finland is free, i.e. there are no tuition fees to be paid to the institutions
of higher education (International University Courses in English are an exception).
However, the membership fee for the Student Union is compulsory for all undergraduate
students; postgraduate students may join the Union if they wish. The membership fee,
which also entitles students to use the services of the student health center, is about FIM 500
per year. In addition to this, a foreign student must be able to pay for his food, lodgings, clothes,
study material, social life, etc. The average living expenses of a single student are at least
FIM 3000 per month.
<p>
According to the Aliens Act every foreign student (except Scandinavians) is required to present
a financial statement which is FIM 30 000 for one academic year. The financial statement must
be in order when applying for a student visa from Finnish Embassies.

<P><DT>
<FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><H2>Financial Support</H2></FONT>
<DD>
<b>Please notice that Tampere University of Technology cannot offer any financial support to
foreign students.</b> You must be able to finance your studies yourself or have a scholarship
from your home country or from other sources. And please notice that at the present situation
it is very difficult to find part-time work in Finland.
<p>
The Finnish Center for International Mobility and Exchange Programs (CIMO) under the Ministry
of Education offers scholarships to foreign students both under reciprocal scholarship programs
based on bilateral cultural agreements and under specialist research programs. These
scholarships should be applied through the educational authorities of your own country.
The scholarships are announced anually to the governments of the recipient countries,
who will propose the candidates to CIMO for final approval. For more information please
contact the educational authorities in your country.
<p>

</DL>
<!-- sopivaan valiin voi iskea sinisen viivan erottamaan asioita toisistaan -->
