<!-- toinen sarake, johon tulee varsinainen leipateksti, leveytta ei ole asetettu -->
<TD VALIGN=TOP>
<!-- sisennysta varten tarvitaan DefinitionList -->
<DL>
<!-- uusi kappale aloitetaan P-DT yhdistelmalla -->
<P><DT>
<!-- Otsikoiden fontiksi arial/helvetica, koska se nayttaa paremmalta -->
<!-- Huomaa myos englanninkielelle tyypillinen otsikoiden capitalisointi -->

<FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><H1>Student Union and Free Time Activities</H1></FONT>
<!-- sisennys tapahtuu DD-tagilla -->
<DD>
All students at the University belong to the Student Union after paying its membership fee. The
membership provides various discounts e.g. in bookstores, theatres and from buss and trains
tickets.<p>

The Student Union organizes a lot of leisure activities such as concerts, film screenings,
excursions, parties etc. The biggest event is on May Day when the academic year of Technology
students culminates and freshmen become fully-fledged students. The most important insignia for
them is the tasselled cap, which unites the students of technology. Also the foreign
students are able to order the tasseled cap from the Student Union. The cap costs
a couple of hundreds of marks depending on the time when it is ordered.<p>

Each department has a student guild which looks after their student's interest at department level
and provides cultural and other free-time activities. Every autumn the guilds organize a project of
getting overalls. Students wear overalls for most of the informal university excursions, "overall
parties", etc.<p>

Into the Student Union belong some 60 associations which offer students a lot of activities, from
fishing and sailing to profession-specific clubs. These include tennis, ice-hockey, football, "s&auml;hly"
and many others. There is also an athletic club room in the Main Building for students and
university staff.<p>

International tutors and their friends organize lots of fun, get-togethers once a week in different
pubs, caf&eacute;s or bars in Tampere to have a drink and to discuss current topics.<p>

When being in a foreign country people usually want to see more than just the place where they
are living, so travelling within and outside Finland will propably be one leisure activity for the
foreign students. Travelling in Finland is easy, the bus and the train networks are good, and
students will get tickets at a reduced rate (usually 50% of the normal price). Helsinki and Turku
are only two hours away from Tampere. If you want to see Lapland you can easily travel by plane
or train to the north.<p>

The capital of Sweden, Stockholm is across the Baltic sea from Turku. You can go there by a
huge luxury ferry at a reduced student price. The voyage takes about 10 hours. St. Petersburg in
Russia and Tallinn in Estonia are also within easy reach from Finland. Coach and train excursions
are organized by several travel agents to St. Petersburg and they have frequent boat connections
to Tallinn from Helsinki.<p>

<DT>
<FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><H2>See also:</H2></FONT>
<DD>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://butler.cc.tut.fi/~yokunta">Student Union</a> <i>(sorry, only in Finnish)</i>
<li><a href="http://proffa.cc.tut.fi/~itnet/">Student Union Information Pages for International Students</a>
</ul>
</DL>

