<!-- uusi kappale aloitetaan P-DT yhdistelmalla -->
<P><DT>
<!-- Otsikoiden fontiksi arial/helvetica, koska se nayttaa paremmalta -->
<!-- Huomaa myos englanninkielelle tyypillinen otsikoiden capitalisointi -->
<FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><h1>Department of Mechanical Engineering</h1></FONT>
<!-- sisennys tapahtuu DD-tagilla -->
<DD>
<UL type=disk>
<li><A HREF="#etcs">The ECTS Departmental Coordinators</a>
<li><A HREF="#institutes">Description of the Institutes and Laboratories and Their Activities in the Department of Electrical Engineering</a>
<li><A HREF="#study">Study Options available in the Department of Mechanical Engineering</a>
<ul>
<li><A HREF="#mecha">Engineering Mechanics</a>
<li><A HREF="#desi">Machine Design</a>
<li><A HREF="#produ">Production Engineering</a>
</ul>
</ul>
</dl>
<p>
<a name="etcs">
<h3>THE ECTS COORDINATORS</h3>
<p>
Professor Reijo Karvinen, <br>
Tampere University of Technology,<br>
The Department of Mechanical Engineering, <br>
Korkeakoulunkatu 2,<br>
P.O.Box 589, SF-33101 Tampere, Finland<br>
Tel: 358-31-365 2021, fax: 358-31-365 2034<p>

<p>
<a name="#institutes">
<h2>Description of the Institutes and Laboratories and Their
Activities in the Department of Mechanical Engineering</h2>

<p>

<b>Machine Design</b><p>

<p>

The institute possesses the research staff and laboratory equipment of
suitable versaitility for important model and prototype experiments in
the field of product development. It is at the peak of international
competence in vibration measurements, those supporting product
development at W&auml;rtsil&auml; Diesel a case in point.<p>

<p>

Vibration analyses are fundamental in the development of condition
monitoring systems. For measurements connected with power
transmission, the Institute has test stands of which particular use
has been made by gear manufacturers in their product
development. Product development addresses the total life-cycle of a
product, starting with customer needs and ending with recycling.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>Engineering Mechanics</b><p>

<p>

The Institute of Engineering Mechanics teaches and researches the
behavior of structures and machines from the strength of materials
point of view. Another focus of intrest is machine vibrations.<p>

<p>

Teaching aims to develop ability in calculation methods and
measurement techniques for design and research related to product
development.<p>

<p>

The research areas currently receiving emphasis are optimization,
application of the finite-element method, and the analysis of
vibrations in structures. An example of the last mentioned is
vibration research on big diesel engine, carried out in cooperation
with W&auml;rtsil&auml; Diesel Oy.<p>

<p>

<b>Production Engineering</b><p>

<p>

Within the field of manufacturing industry the Institute gives
education in the areas of manufacturing methods and their
automatization and quality-assurance techniques, including
measurements and calibrations. Many of the skills imparted are
applicable also in more widely in the discrete manufacturing
industry.<p>

<p>

On the foundation of these basic techniques, productivity design for
production systems is developed in order to support product-design
activities.<p>

<p>

Education is supported by research, part of which consists of
industrial applications. The other part is carried out within the
Institute. Research is used to deepen the level of knowledge and to
develop new design and planning tools, e.g. software. The Institute is
participating in 1994-95 in the international project EUREKA
MAINE-EU744 (FMSMAINT SYSTEM).<p>

<p>
<a name="study">
<h2>Study Options Available in These Departments</h2>


<b>Engineering Mechanics</b><p>

- Analysis and optimization of strength, rigidity, and vibration in supporting <p>

  structures<p>

<p>

<b>Machine Design</b><p>

<p>

- Design of machines and machine systems<p>

- Tribology<p>

- Noise and vibration problems<p>

- CAD<p>

- Maintenance engineering<p>

<p>

<b>Production Engineering</b><p>

<p>

- Production engineering and production systems for production engineering industry<p>

<p>

<p>

<a name="mecha">
<h2>Engineering Mechanics</h2>

<p>

<p>

<b>23100 Introduction to Statics of Rigid Bodies 		3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Associate prof. Pertti Holopainen<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Fundamental concepts and principles of Mechanics. Equivalent system of forces
acting on fixed and movable rigid bodies. Equilibrium of particles and rigid bodies. Applications
to structures in plane and space. Beams, cables and trusses. Work principles. Stability.<p>

REQUIREMENTS:  Approved exercises and individual work. Two intermediate exams or a
written examination.<p>

LITERATURE: Pertti Holopainen: Statiikan perusteet.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>23110 Advanced Statics of Rigid Bodies       		3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Associate prof. Pertti Holopainen<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Funicular polygon. Statically determinate structures such as Beam; frames, space
trusses. Three-hinged Arches. Influence lines. Maximum stress graphs. Complementary work and
the principle of virtual forces. Potential energy, equilibrium and stability. Application to simple
linear and non-linear structures.<p>

REQUIREMENTS:  Approved exercises. Two intermediate exams or a written examination.<p>

LITERATURE: Pertti Holopainen: Statiikan jatkokurssi. P. Loikkanen:<p>

Rakenteiden statiikka 1 (1972). T.M. Charlton: Energy Principles in Theory of Structures.<p>

<p>

<b>23120 Introduction to Dynamics of Rigid Bodies 	4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Associate prof. Pertti Holopainen<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Kinematics and Kinetics of particles and rigid bodies, mainly in plane. Harmonic
vibration of single degree of freedom systems.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and individual work. Intermediate<p>

exams or a written examination.<p>

LITERATURE: Pertti Holopainen: Dynamiikan perusteet. Beer &amp; Johnston: Vector Mechanics
for Engineers, Dynamics or L.J. Meriam: Dynamics.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>23130 Advanced Dynamics of Rigid Bodies      		3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Associate prof. Pertti Holopainen<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Kinematics: Finite rotations. Euler's angles. Kinetics: Euler's equations, gyroscopic
motion. Lagrange's equations. Periodic and non-periodic vibrations of single degree of freedom
systems. Multi-degree of freedom systems and normal mode method.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises. Two intermediate examinations or a written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Pertti Holopainen: Dynamiikan jatkokurssi. L.J. Meriam: Dynamics. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>23140 Dynamics of Structures	         		6.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Associate prof. Pertti Holopainen<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 42 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Dealing structures as different discrete systems. The normal mode method. Discrete
approximation in time using single-step algorithms. Dealing structures, beams, frames and plates,
as continuous systems.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises, two individual works and a written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture material. Clough &amp; Penzien: Dynamics of Structures, McGraw-Hill,
1975. Paz: Structural Dynamics, Van Nostrand Reinhold, 1985. Craig: Structural Dynamics,
Wiley &amp; Sons, 1981.<p>

<p>

<b>23150 Mechanics of Robots 			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Associate prof. Pertti Holopainen<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Kinematics, inverse kinematics and kinetics of robots. Trajectory generation.
Strength examinations.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved two individual works and a written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Pertti Holopainen:Robottimekaniikka (handout). J.J.Craig: Introduction to
robotics, mechanics and control.<p>

REMARKS: Lectures in every second years. No lectures in 1996-97.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>23200  Special Course in Mechanics    		6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Associate prof. Pertti Holopainen<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Variational principles of mechanics, nonlinear mechanics and tensocalculus pointing
out in different ways in different years.<p>

