REMARKS: Lectures in every second year. Lectures in 1996-1997.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>23510 Strength of Materials I                		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

 <p>

Lecturer Simo Virtanen<p>

Lectures 42 h. Excercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

 <p>

CONTENTS: Introduction to stress and strain. Tension, compression, shear, torsion and bending.
Stresses and deflections of beams. Buckling of columns. Strain energy. Limit load in plasticity.
Strength hypothesis and fatigue.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises, individual work and a written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Outinen &amp; Vulli: Lujuusopin perusteet.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>23520 Strength of Materials II               		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

 <p>

Lecturer Simo Virtanen<p>

Lectures 42 h. Excercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

 <p>

CONTENTS: Stress and strain state. Basic equations of linear elasticity theory. Constitutive
relations. Introduction to sinite element method. Introduction to plates and shells. Yield conditions for beams. Energy principles. Viscoelasticity. Ceramic &amp; composite structures.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and team work. Written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>23530 Continuum Mechanics                    		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

 <p>

Prof. Juhani Koski <p>

Lectures 42 h. Excercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

CONTENTS: Introduction to tensor algebra with indicial notation. Stress and strain tensor.
Nonlinear kinematics. Differential equations of solid mechanics. Constitutive laws of elastic
systems.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and team work. Written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced. <p>

<p>

<p><b>
23541 Theory of Bars and Beams               		6.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

 <p>

Prof. Juhani Koski  <p>

Lectures 28 h. Excercises 42 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

 <p>

CONTENTS: Bending theory of straigth and curved beams. Use of singular functions. Buckling
and lateral buckling. Energy methods. Saint-Venant and warping torsion. Collapse load in frames.
Matrix methods of trusses and frames.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and team work. Written examination. <p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

REMARKS: No lectures in 1996-1997.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>23555 Theory of Plates and Shells            		6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Juhani Koski  <p>

Lectures 42 h. Excercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Plane stress and plane strain. Analysis of plates. Theory of surfaces. Analysis of
rotation symmetric and general shells. Membrane and bending stresses in shells.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and team work, written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture material.<p>

REMARKS: No lecture in 1995-96.<p>

<p>

  <p>

<b>23571 Experimental Structural Mechanics      		6.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

 <p>

Lecturer Simo Virtanen<p>

Lectures 28 h. Excercises 56 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

 <p>

CONTENTS: Generalized measurement systems. Experiment planning. Electrical-resistance strain
gauges. Residual stresses. Basic concepts in dynamic measurements. Experimental modal analysis.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Reports on lab work and a written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture material. Dally &amp; Riley: Experimental Stress Analysis. 3. p. McGraw-Hill, New York 1991, 639 s. Ewins: Modal Testing: Theory and Practice. Research Studies
Press, Letchworth 1986. 269 s.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>23580 Thermomechanics and Creep              		6.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

 <p>

Prof. Juhani Koski<p>

Lectures 28 h. Excercises 42 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

 <p>

CONTENTS: Thermoelasticity and its basic cases. Heat conduction. Thermal stresses of different
structures. Stability, creep and relaxation.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises, team work and a written examination.<p>

LITERATURE: Boley, B.A. &amp; Weiner, J.H.: Theory of thermal stresses. Wiley, 1966. 586 s.<p>

REMARKS: No lectures in 1996-1997.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>23591 Finite Element Method			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Ass. Esa Murtola<p>

Lectures 28 h. Excercises 42 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

 <p>

CONTENTS: Concept of spatial discretization of physical domain. Shape functions. Coordinate
transformation. Isoparametric elements. Applications to different linear structural problems.
Computer program packages. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises, team work, written exam.<p>

LITERATURE:  Outinen &amp; Pramila: Lujuusopin elementtimenetelm&auml;n k&auml;ytt&ouml;, copies of lecture
material 110 A &amp; B.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>23610 General Finite Element Method          		6.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

 <p>

Senior ass. Jarmo Niemi<p>

Lectures 28 h. Excercises 42 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

 <p>

CONTENTS: Finite element method in general field problems. Applications to acoustics, fluid
mechanics and heat conduction.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises, individual work and a written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Huebner, K.H. and Thornton, E.A., The Finite Element Method for Engineers. 2.
painos. Wiley Interscience, New York, 1982. Zienkiewicz, O.: The Finite Element Method,
McGraw-Hill, 1989 vol, 1991 vol 2.<p>

<p>

<b>23615 Design Optimization and Decision Making	4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Juhani Koski<p>

Lectures 42 h. Excercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The course consists of the most popular approaches of optimization, operations
research and decision making emphasizing their applications to engineering design. Formulation of
optimization problem and the most important solution methods. Numerical solution by using
existing computer programs. Optimal control and simulation. Transportation problem.
Applications of game and queueing theory. Fuzzy formulation. Multicriteria optimization and
decision making. Applications in different fields of engineering design.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and team work. Written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Arora, J.S., Introduction to Optimum Design McGraw-Hill, New York 1989.
Taha, H.A., Operations Research, An introducting. Macmillan, New York, 1992. Eschenauer, H.,
Koski, J. and Osyczka, A. (Eds.), Multicriteria Design Optimization, Procedures and
Applications. Springer-Verlag, Berlin, 1990. Sakawa, M., Fuzzy Sets and Interactive Multiobjective Optimization. Plenum Press, New York, 1993.<p>

REMARKS: Lectures in every second year. Will be lectured in 1996. This course is a part of
Mechanical Engineering Graduate School and is applicable to the licentiate examination in several
fields of engineering.<p>

<p>

 <p>

<b>23621 Structural Optimization                		6.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

 <p>

Prof. Juhani Koski<p>

Lectures 42 h. Excercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

 <p>

CONTENTS: Linear programming in plastic analysis and design of load supporting structures.
Optimality criteria methods. Dynamic and geometric programming. Nonlinear programming<p>

applied to different structures. Shape optimization of components. Computer packages for
structural optimization. Multicriterion optimization.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises, team work and a written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Haftka R.T. and Gurdal Z.: Elements of structural Optimization, Kluver, Dordrecht, 481s. Kirsch, U., Optimum Structural Design. McGraw-Hill, New York, 1993. 441 s. <p>

 <p>

<p>

<b>23630 Fracture Mechanics and Fatigue         		6.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

 <p>

Senior ass. Jarmo Niemi.<p>

Lectures 42 h. Excercises 42 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

 <p>

CONTENTS: Linear fracture mechanics. Introduction to nonlinear fracture mechanics. Derivation
and application of different fracture parameters. Basic approaches for calculating fatigue life of
stressed component.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises, team work and a written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Ikonen &amp; Kantola: Murtumismekaniikka, Otakustantamo, 1986.<p>

