LITERATURE: Selected at the beginning of the seminar.<p>

<p>

<b>24777 Project Work in Concurrent Engineering		9,0 ETCS credits

	</b><p>

Prof. Asko Riitahuhta, prof. Veli Siekkinen ,  assoc. prof. Erno Keskinen<p>

Excercises 84 h.<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The student becomes acquainted with industrial product development and performs
a group project on an actual design task from industry. Together with this course , also courses
23777, 25777 or 27777 can be taken depending on the nature of the individual project.<p>

COURSE REQUIREMENTS: Accepted exercise project.<p>

NOTE: Preliminary requirement: passed course 24310 Machine Elements and accepted exercises
from course 24600 Product Development Theory. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>24850 Maintenance of Industrial Plants		3,0 ETCS credits</b><p>

	<p>

Prof. Veli Siekkinen<p>

Lectures 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Importance of maintenance for the company. Concepts and terminology of
maintenance. Information systems in maintenance. Materials administration and cost accounting in
maintenance.<p>

COURSE REQUIREMENTS: Accepted written examination based on the lectures.<p>

LITERATURE: Kunnossapito ja k&auml;ytt&ouml;varmuus. Gummerus Oy, Jyv&auml;skyl&auml; 1985.<p>

NOTE: Periodic course on fall term.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>24860 Condition Monitoring Methods		3,0 ETCS credits	

</b><p>

Prof. Veli Siekkinen<p>

Lectures 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Introduction to condition monitoring. Various measurement and examination
methods. Manual and automatic condition monitoring systems. Laboratory exercises with
condition monitoring methods.<p>

COURSE REQUIREMENTS: Accepted laboratory exercises, and subsequent written examination based on the lectures.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes.<p>

NOTE: Periodic course on spring term.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>
<a name="produ">
<h2>Production Engineering</h2>

<p>

<p>

<b>27114 Production Process Engineering     		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Paul H. Andersson<p>

Lectures 56 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To give the students knowledge of processes in various fields of production. <p>

CONTENTS: Introduction to the production engineering. Presentation of various industrial
production processes. The course gives an overall view of the technologies, equipment and other
parameters applied in the processes.<p>

REQUIREMENT: A passed examination on the contents of lectures and literature.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27121 Production Systems 			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Ilkka Lapinleimu<p>

Lectures 56 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To give the student an understanding on the operation and development
possibilities of production systems.<p>

CONTENTS: Production processes within mechanical engineering. The design of a production
system for metal, machine and electrotechnic industry on the basis of business requirements and
the product. The design of controllability and speed. The core and supportive systems.<p>

REQUIREMENT: A passed examination on the contents of lectures and literature stated at the
beginning of the course.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

REMARKS: The acquired knowledge can be deepened with the project course 27123.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27122 Producibility				4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Ilkka Lapinleimu<p>

Lectures 56 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Project work takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To give the student an understanding on the manufacture of machine parts and on
taking manufacturability into account in the design phase. The principles of Concurrent Engineering. The calculation of the product's production costs.<p>

CONTENTS: <p>

REQUIREMENT: A passed exercise work. <p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27123 Design of Manufacturing Systems		4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Ilkka Lapinleimu, assoc. prof. Paul H. Andersson<p>

assoc. prof. Heikki Tikka and assoc. prof. Seppo Torvinen<p>

Project work takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: After a passed course the student is able to design a production system and to pay
attention to the product manufacturability.<p>

CONTENTS: The course includes an exercise work in which the product is analysed from the
manufacturability point of view. According to the obtained results the product structure is
improved and finally a production system is designed in order to effectively manufacture the
product. The project work is carried out in teams and the principles of Concurrent Engineering
are applied.<p>

REQUIREMENT: A passed project work.<p>

REMARKS: The course is based on theory courses 27121, 27122 and 27145. The course
replaces the earlier course 27113. If the amount of attending students has to be limited, this will
be done according to the amount of studies carried out so far.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27210 Introduction to Production Automation		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Seppo Torvinen<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To give the student an understanding on the basics of production automation, its
systems and sub-systems.<p>

CONTENTS: The automation of stand-alone machine tools. The basics of the design of automated production systems. Workpiece handling in flexible manufacturing. Numerical control of
machine tools. The basics of Flexible Manufacturing and Assembly techniques. The course
includes demonstrations and company visits.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed exercises and examination on the contents of lectures, exercises and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27220 Production Information Systems     		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Seppo Torvinen<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 42 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The student gets acquainted with the information systems in the field of production
engineering.<p>

CONTENTS: The improvement of production activities with the help of information technology
and production automation (CIM). Computer Aided Design and Production Planning (CAD and
CAPP). Production Planning Systems (PPS). Control systems for Flexible Manufacturing
Systems. Tool management in flexible manufacturing environments (TMS). Automatic Data
Collection (ADC) and Maintenance information systems. Computer aided quality assurance
(CAQ).<p>

REQUIREMENT: Passed exercises and examination on the contents of lectures, exercises and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27230 Off-line Programming        			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Heikki Tikka<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h. <p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The course gives an overview of programming machine tools, robots and co-ordinate measuring machines with CAD/CAM systems.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed exercises and a written examination on the contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

REMARKS: Recommended supporting courses 27415 Manufacturing Methods and 24230
Advanced CAD.<p>

LITERATURE: Pikkarainen: Tietokoneavusteinen NC-ohjelmointi, Valtion painatuskeskus,
Helsinki 1990, APT-kielen ohjelmointiopas, TTKK 1980, MET:n Tekninen tiedotus 5/92 and
additional reading stated at the lectures.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27250 Laboratory Course in Production Automation</b>  <b>	4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

			<p>

Assoc. prof. Seppo Torvinen<p>

Lectures 14 h. Exercises 56 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE:  To give the student the skills to define and realise the control system of a Flexible
Manufacturing Unit (FMU).<p>

CONTENTS: Determining of the needed information flows and functions. Design of the application's database. Realising the control software as a project exercise. Special attentions is paid on
collecting feedback information from the manufacturing unit and utilising especially in the fields of
production planning, maintenance and occupational safety.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

REMARKS: Recommended supporting course 27210 Introduction to Production Automation.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27260 Industrial Robot Applications, Laboratory Course</b>  <b>	4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

			<p>

Assoc. prof. Seppo Torvinen, Lic. Tech. Jorma Vihinen, Prof. Reijo Tuokko<p>

Lectures 14 h. Exercises 56 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE:  To give the student the required skills in applying industrial robots in different end
applications.<p>

CONTENTS: Design of industrial robot applications including integration and selection of
peripheral devices. Through exercises students get acquainted with off-line programming, operation of robot groups, robot welding, finishing, grinding, deburring, loading/unloading, palletising
and assembly. Several robots representing different types and structures are used. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercise projects and examination on the contents of lectures,
exercises and literature stated at the beginning of the course.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

ACKNOWLEDGEMENT: The course is realised in collaboration with the Institute of Hydraulics
and Automation (IHA).<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27313 Calibration Systems        			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Heikki Tikka<p>

Seminars 14 h. Case Teaching 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Fundamentals of calibration systems and metrology which rise up from ISO 9000,
EN 45001 and EAL (European Co-operation for Accreditation of Laboratories).<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed exercises and course 27314 Quality Assurance.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27314 Quality Assurance          			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Paul H. Andersson<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To familiar the students with the technical methods in quality assurance.<p>

CONTENTS: Measuring methods and instruments commonly used in production metrology.
Error sources in dimensional measurements. Inspection of production machinery. Co-ordinate
measuring and SPC.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A passed examination on contents of lectures and literature.<p>

LITERATURE: Andersson: Laadunvarmistus- textbook and other literature announced at the
beginning of the course.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27315 Laboratory Course in Quality Assurance    	4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

Assoc. prof. Paul H. Andersson<p>

Lectures 14 h. Exercises 56 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To use essential measuring methods in practice.<p>

CONTENTS: Laboratory exercises in most commonly used measuring methods and instruments
in production metrology. Measuring reports, evaluations an uncertainty calculations.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: Andersson &amp; Oksanen: Laadunvarmistus harjoitusty&ouml;t-booklet.<p>

REMARKS: Recommended supporting course 27314 Quality Assurance.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27316 Systematic Resolution of Production Problems	4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Seppo Torvinen, assoc. prof. Paul H. Andersson<p>

Lectures 14 h. Exercises 56 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: To familiarise students with most common and typical problems within
production and with their resolution methods with the help of production games, simulations and
exercises.<p>

CONTENTS: Systematic data collection. Restriction of problems. Systematic problem resolution
tools. Improvement of process robustness with the help of industrial design of experiments
(DOE). Utilisation of simulation and production games in problem resolution.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed exercises and examination on the contents of lectures, literature and
exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27414 Laboratory Course in Machining Techniques	4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Paul H. Andersson<p>

Lectures 10 h. Exercises 90 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: To be acquainted with the normal machining and research methods.<p>

CONTENTS: Exercises and laboratory studies in machining. Theoretical measurements of the
cutting forces, temperature, vibrations and wear of the tool.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed exercises.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27415 Manufacturing Methods			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Paul H. Andersson<p>

Lectures 56 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To be familiar with the most important production methods in metal industry.<p>

CONTENTS: Basic theory of cutting and shearing process, utilised technologies, machinery and
parameters. Excursion to factories.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed exercises and examination on the contents of lectures.<p>

LITERATURE: Andersson: Lastuamisteoria and Andersson: Valmistusmenetelm&auml;t II -textbook
and other literature to be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

<p>

<b>27416 Tool Design				4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Paul H. Andersson<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 84 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To realise the role of tool design in the production.<p>

CONTENTS: Fundamentals of the tooling techniques, tool systems. Fixtures in machining and
welding. Design exercises.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed exercises and examination on the contents of lectures.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

REMARKS: Recommended supporting course 27415 Manufacturing Methods.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>27511 Special Student Work in Industry		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Ilkka Lapinleimu, assoc. prof Paul H. Andersson,<p>

assoc. prof. Heikki Tikka and assoc. prof Seppo Torvinen<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To give the student a practical contact with companies in a real life industrial
problem.<p>

CONTENTS: In the student work an industrial problem or a development assignment concerning
production activities is solved. The work shall be completed in 1-3 person teams. Projects are
carried out according to schedules desired by the companies. The obtained results are presented
to other groups in an end seminar taking place in the spring term.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed exercise.<p>

REMARKS: The course starts on the 2nd period of the fall term.<p>

<p>

<b>

27512 Advanced Project in Production Engineering	4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Ilkka Lapinleimu, assoc. prof Paul H. Andersson<p>

assoc. prof. Heikki Tikka and assoc. prof Seppo Torvinen<p>

<p>

GOALS AND CONTENTS: To increase students' knowledge of production engineering by a
demanding exercise. The field of the topic may be production metrology, production automation
or overall production engineering.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed exercise.<p>

<p>

<b>27777 Concurrent Engineering -project 		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Ilkka Lapinleimu, assoc. prof Paul H. Andersson<p>

assoc. prof. Heikki Tikka and assoc. prof Seppo Torvinen<p>

<p>

