<a name="etcs">
<h2>The ECTS Departmental Coordinator</h2>

<b>Professor Reino Kurki-Suonio</b><br>
Tampere University of Technology<br>
Kanslerinkatu 12 C<br>
P.O. BOX 553 <br>
SF-33101 Tampere, FINLAND<br>
Tel: 358-31-365 2699<br>
Fax: 358-31-365 2913<br>

<a name="institutes">
<h2>Institutes of Department of Information Technology</h2>

<p>

<b>General information</b><p>

<p>

Data processing -the combination of compouter and information technology - has made information technology into a discrete whole, which is required both as a separate area  of expertise in
technology and as a provider of indispensible basic skills for other areas in technology. This
development is reflected by the differentiation in 1993 of the Faculty of Information Technology
from the Faculty of Electrical Engineering.<p>

<p>

<b>Mathematics</b><p>

<p>

In addition to teaching, the Institute of Mathematics is actively engaged in research on coding
theory, hypermedia, mathematical control theory, fuzzy mathematics, optimization, computability
theory, and other areas of mathematics.<p>

<p>

Computer-aided hypermedia based teaching methods are being developed at the institute. This
hypermedia teaching material can be reached at a variety of levels and facilitates studying significantly.<p>

<p>

<b>Signal Processing</b><p>

<p>

The Institute is the leading recearch unit in Finland in the field of signal and image processing,
offering teaching of the highest order in many subareas of information technology.<p>

<p>

The most central research areas are signal processing algorithms and applications, digital image-processing methods, speech coding and processing, digital audio, digital processing circuit design,
and VLSI implementation. The Institute is participating on the EU research projects RACE,
COST, EUREKA, and ESPRIT.<p>

<p>

<b>Software Systems</b><p>

<p>

The importanceof software systems is based onthe central role of software engineering in the
applications of information technology and in product development. Central areas of strength in
teaching  and research are modern software methods  and tools, design of embedded and
distributed systems, forkmal methods, and compute networks. Activities, which have veen
developed to serve domestic industry, have achieved international recognition.<p>

<p>

<b>Telecommunications </b><p>

<p>

Activities focus on the central areas in telecommunications of the 1990's broadband telecommunication networks, digital transmission techniques, and the new digital mobile communication
systems. Together with several other institutes of the University, on extensive resesearch project
on broaddband network technology has been set up. This FASTER project includes the
construction on an ATM text network, research, and industrial projects in the field of ATM
engineering.<p>

<p>

<p>

<a name="information">
<h2>Courses Available in the Department of Information technology</h2>

<p>

<p>

Usually all the lectures, seminars and exercises are given in Finnish,
but there are many courses particalarly in Digital Signal Processing
given in English. <p>

<A NAME="mathematics"></a>
<h2>Courses Offered by the Institute of Mathematics</h2>

<p>

<p>

<b>73118 Formal Languages 			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Topi Urponen <p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS:Basic properties of formal languages. Classification of grammars. Automata for the
recognition of languages. Lindenmayer systems.<p>

REQUEST:Written exam.<p>

LITERATURE:Salomaa: Formal Languages, Academic 1973.<p>

NOTE: Lectured every third year. Will not be lectured in 1996-1997.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>73119 Graph Theory 				4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

Acting prof. Keijo Ruohonen <p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS:Basic properties of graphs, directed graphs, matrix representation of graphs, graph
theory algorithms.<p>

REQUESTS:Written exam.<p>

LITERATURE:Ruohonen:Graafiteoria, TUT Lecture Notes. Swamy &amp; Thulasimaran: Graphs,
Networks and Algorithms, Wiley 1981. Gibbons: Algorithmic Graph Theory, Cambridge Univ.
Press 1987.<p>

NOTE: Lectured every second year. Will be lectured in 1996-1997.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>73120 Coding Theory 				4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Acting prof. Keijo Ruohonen <p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Linear codes,Cyclic code,BCH codes,Burst-error-correcting codes.Convolution
codes<p>

REQUESTS: Written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Ruohonen: Koodaus- ja informaatioteoria, TUT Lecture Notes. Sweeney: Error
Control Coding, Prentice-Hall 1991. Heise &amp; Quattrocchi: Informations- und Codierungstheorie,
spronger 1989.<p>

NOTE: Lectured every third year. Will not be lectured in 1996-1997.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>73121 Information Theory 			3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

Acting prof. Topi Ruohonen<p>

Lectures 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The concept of information, entropy, properties on information sources, channels
and receivers.<p>

REQUESTS: Written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Ruohonen: Koodaus- ja informaatioteoria, TUT Lecture Notes. Yaglom &amp;
Yaglom: Probability and Information, Reidel 1983. Heise &amp; Quattrocchi: Informations- und
Codierungstheorie, spronger 1989.<p>

NOTE: Lectured eevery third year. Will not be lectured in 1995-1996.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>73122 Advanced Course on Integral Tranforms 		3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Contact person: Acting prof. Keijo Ruohonen <p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Algorithms for Fourier transforms and convolutions.<p>

REQUESTS: Written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Blahut: Fast Algorithms for Digital Signal Processing, Addison - Wesley 1985.<p>

NOTE: Not lectured; an exam may be arranged upon request.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>73123 Calculus of Variations 			3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

Assoc. Prof. Armo Pohjavirta<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: A modern treatment of the classical theory of calculus of variations. Direct
methods.<p>

REQUESTS: To be announced.<p>

LITERATURE: To be annonced.<p>

NOTE: Lectured at most every second year. Will be lectured in 1996-1997.<p>

<p>

<b>71124 Operations  Research 			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lecturer Martti Lehto<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Operations researchis the application of mathematical methods such as optimisation, propability theory, queuing theory, etc. to management  decision- making problems such as
resource allocation, work scheduling, equipment rerewal, etc.<p>

REQUESTS: Course work and/or written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>73125 Optimation Theory 2 			3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lecturer Risto Silvennoinen<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Theory and applications of discrete optimisation. Dynamic programming, discrete
programming.<p>

REQUESTS: Written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Nemhauser &amp; Wolsey: Integer and Combinatiorial Optimisation, Wiley 1988.<p>

NOTE: Lectured every second year. Will not be lectured in 1996-1997.<p>

