<p>

<A NAME="software"></a>
<h2>Courses Offered in the Software Systems</h2>

<p>

GENERAL INFORMATION:<p>

<p>

Currently, the Department of Information Technology has four laboratories in Tampere:<p>

-	Mathematics,<p>

-	Signal Processing (contains currently also Digital Systems and Digital Media)<p>

-	Telecommunications, and<p>

-	Software Systems.<p>

<p>

The laboratories cooperate closely in both education and research.  This<p>

cooperation involves also Electronics Laboratory in the Department of<p>

Electrical Engineering.<p>

<p>

Software Systems Laboratory has currently two professors and three associate<p>

professors, and the other laboratories of the Department are roughly of the<p>

same size.  The basic degree offered by the Department is that of Diploma<p>

Engineer (MSc), the postgraduate degrees being Lic.Tech. and Dr. Tech.  The<p>

annual educational output of the laboratory is some 50 Diploma Engineers, 2<p>

Lic. Tech., and 1 Dr. Tech.<p>

<p>

The main language of teaching is Finnish.  Signal Processing has an<p>

international programme, where all courses are given in English.  In<p>

Software Systems, seminars are held in English, when needed, and this has<p>

also been the case with advanced courses.<p>

<p>

The basic structure of Diploma Engineer&AElig;s degree in the department,<p>

comprising 180 credit units, is the following:<p>

<p>

-	Basic Studies in mathematics, physics, languages, etc., common to all engineering students, 45 cu;<p>

-	Introductory Studies in electronics, digital techniques, telecommunications, and software systems,
common to all students at the Department of Information Techonology, 40 cu;<p>

-	Four study modules, 15 cu each, with at least two modules from the major subject, and at least one
module from another subject (possibly also from another department);<p>

-	Elective Studies, 15 cu;<p>

-	MSc Thesis, 20 cu.<p>

<p>

Of the courses in Software Systems, the following are included in the basic and introductory studies
common to all students at the department:<p>

<p>

81000 Computer Literacy (3 cu),<p>

81010 Programming I (2 cu),<p>

81020 Programming II (3 cu),<p>

81210 Introduction to Software Engineering (2 cu).<p>

<p>

When only one module (15 cu) is taken in Software Systems, the following<p>

courses are obligatory in it:<p>

<p>

73116 Mathematics for Algorithms (3 cu),<p>

81120 Data Structures and Algoritms (4 cu).<p>

<p>

When two modules (30 cu) are taken, the following additional courses are<p>

obligatory:<p>

<p>

81130 Software Engineering Methodology (4 cu),<p>

81141 Principles of Programming Languages (3 cu),<p>

81180 Operating Systems (4 cu),<p>

81950 Software Laboratory (3 cu), and<p>

81151 Embedded Systems (3 cu) or 81530 Distributed Systems Software (3 cu).<p>

<p>

COURSE DESCRIPTIONS  (TUT/SOFTWARE SYSTEMS)<p>

<p>

<b>81000 Computer Literacy 			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lecturer Matti Rintala<p>

Lectures 38 h, exercises 10 h<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Computer systems of TUT, basic knowledge of computers and computer science in
general. Using UNIX, electronic mail, TUT's computer network, usenet news, ethical instruction of
FUNET, using student register and library databases. Structure and basic operation of computers and
processors, algorithms, applications software, operating systems, programming languages, compiling
and interpreting, representation of data in<p>

a computer, data communication.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam and attending the exercise sessions<p>

LITERATURE: Lokki, Haikala, Linnainmaa, Mattila, Susiluoto: Tietotekniikka (Tietotekniikan liitto
ry, 1989) Brookshear: Computer Science - An Overview (Addison-Wesley 1994) Davis: Concepts
3rd edition (Addison-Wesley 1991)<p>

<p>

<b>81010 Programming I 				3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assistent Rauno M&auml;kinen<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 14 h, laboratory work 14 h<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Basic ideas of software engineering and programming. Work phases in software
engineering.  Running a program.  Algorithms. Basic problem solving methods.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Final examination after laboratory work is accepted.<p>

TEXT: Pertti Kellom&auml;ki, Rauno M&auml;kinen: Ohjelmoinnin alkemia ja Scheme-kieli, or Springer,
Friedman: Scheme and the Art of Programming.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81020 Programming II				4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lecturer Pertti Lehtonen<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Basic programming skills that are needed in computer science. Problem solving with
structural language. Data types, flow of control, modularity, data abstraction, libraries. Input and
output.<p>

LITERATURE: To be annouced in the beginning of lectures.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and final exam.<p>

NOTES: Course have to be completed during one academic year.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 81010 Programming I<p>

<p>

<b>81120 Data Structures and Algorithms		6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Antti Valmari<p>

Lectures 56 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Design principles of data structures and algorithms, informal justification of correctness
of algorithms, estimation of efficiency of algorithms and problem complexity, and the most important
fundamental algorithms.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Final examination and 4 programming exercises.<p>

TEXT: Lecture notes and Cormen, Leiserson, Rivest: Introduction to Algorithms.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 81020 Programming II and 73116 Mathematics for Algorithms.<p>

NOTES: Exercises and final examination have to be passed in the same year.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81130 Software Engineering Methody		6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Ilkka Haikala<p>

Lectures 56 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Overview of SE, the software life cycle, quality system, documentation project
management, configuration management, quality assurance testing, specification, design,
object-oriented methods (OMT++).<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Weekly teamwork exercises, requirements specification and design assignment,
final examination.<p>

NOTES: Course have to be completed during one academic year.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81141 Principles of Programming Languages		4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Reino Kurki-Suonio<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

GOAL: To know the general principles and the basic concepts of high-level programming languages,
and to understand how these affect their implementation and use.<p>

CONTENTS: Syntax formalisms. Expressions and the principles of functional programming.
Structural programming: variables and the assignment operation, data types and strong typing,
parameter passing mechanisms, exception handling, memory allocation in stack and heap, pointers.
Modular programming: packages, encapsulation, abstract data types. Object-oriented programming:
calsses, inheritance, dynamic binding. Separate compilation of<p>

modules. Concurrent programming: shared memory (semaphores, monitors), synchronous
communication (rendezvous).<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Active participation on lectures and problem sessions, writing of short weekly
essays, and the final examination.<p>

TEXT: Sethi: Programming Languages, Concepts and Constructs, Addison-Wesley, 1989.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 81020 Programming II.  811220 Data Structures and Algoritms<p>

is also recommended.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81151 Embedded Systems			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Senior Assist. Hannu-Matti J&auml;rvinen<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: A low-level programmers view of the computer architecture, and specification and
structure of embedded systems. Representation of data. Parameter passing. Problems generated from
parallelism and their basic solutions.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Final examination and an assignment.<p>

TEXT: Lecture notes.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 81180 Operating Systems.<p>

NOTES: Assignment and examination shall be done in the same year.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81161 Computer Graphics			3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lecturer Matti Rintala<p>

Lectures 21 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: To give basic knowledge on computer graphics from a programmer's viewpoint. Input
andoutput devices. Data structures and algorithms. Graphics languages, packages, and standards.
Graphics processors and hardware, windowing systems, user interfaces, and applications.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam and a programming exercise<p>

LITERATURE: J.D. Foley and A. Van Dam: Introduction to Computer Graphics (Addison-Wesley
1994)<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81171 Compiler Construction			7,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Senior Assist. Kari Kyst&auml;<p>

Lectures 56 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

GOALS AND CONTENT: To give basic knowledge of programming language compilation and
run-time implementation, and to give basic skills in application of this knowledge. An additional goal
is to give experience in developing a fairly big program in a tight schedule. A simple compiler is
constructed during the cource.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: An extensive exercise implemented synchronously with the lectures.<p>

LITERATURE: Aho, Sethi, Ullman: Compilers: Principles, Tools and Techniques, Addison-Wesley
1985. or Fisher, LeBlanc: Crafting a Compiler with C. Benjamin Cummings Publishing Co, Inc., 1991<p>

PREREQUISITES: 81120, 81141, 81180.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81180 Operating Systems			6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Senior Assist. Hannu-Matti J&auml;rvinen<p>

Lectures 56 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The structure of an operating system, concurrent programming, memory management,
file systems, real time systems, distributed systems, performance evaluation.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: programming assignment, final examination.<p>

LITERATURE: Ilkka Haikala, Hannu-Matti J&auml;rvinen: K&auml;ytt&ouml;j&auml;rjestelm&auml;t (Operating Systems).
Modeemi Ry:n teos C3, 1994, or Silberschatz, Galvin: Operating Systems Concepts, 4th edition.
Addison-Wesley, 1993.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81201 Reactive Systems				6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Reino Kurki-Suonio<p>

Lectures 56 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

GOALS: To learn a formal basis for the specification and design of embedded, distributed, and
real-time systems. To understand how to formalize dynamic behavioral properties.  To know a formal
logic for expressing and proving such properties, and an associated object-oriented specification and
design methodology.<p>

CONTENTS: Action-based execution model, describing a system and its environment as a closed
system, behaviors as nonterminating sequences of states, safety and liveness properties, temporal
logic of actions and its relationship to the action-based execution model, object-oriented specification
with joint actions, superposition and an incremental specification and design method that is based on
it.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Final examination<p>

LITERATURE: R Kurki-Suonio, Lecture Notes<p>

NOTES: Intended mainly as a postgraduate course.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 81180 Operating Systems, 81240 Formal Methods. Also 81141. Principles of
Programming Languages is recommended.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81210 Introduction to Software Engineering		3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Ilkka Haikala, senior assist. Tero Ahtee<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Overview of software engineering, software engineering process, ERD, DFD, STD,
and related notations, requirements specification using SA/RT, basics of OOA.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Weekly team work exercises, requirements specification assignment, final
examination.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81220 Performance Analysis			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc.Prof. Leo Sintonen<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

<p>

GOAL: The purpose of the course is to give introduction to the methods used in computer and
software system performance modelling.<p>

CONTENTS: Queueing models, queueing networks,  Markov modelling, stochastic Petri-nets,
simulation modelling. Performability. Examples. Use of modelling tools.<p>

TEXT:  Leo Sintonen, Lecture Notes. Recommended additional reading: L.Kleinrock:Queueing
Systems, R.Jain: The Art of Computer System Performance Analysis, Wiley 1991, C.U.Smith:
Performance Engineering of Software Systems, AddisonWesley 1990, A.M. Law: Simulation
Modelling and Analysis, McGraw 1993.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Examination.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81234 Introduction to Databases			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lecturer Pertti Lehtinen<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Basics of data base systems. relational data bases, normalization, SQL, data base
managent systems, design and implementation.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: programming assignment and final examination.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81240 Formal Methods				4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Antti Valmari<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The goal of the course is to provide the student with the ability to understand and start
using formal methods. Specification and verification of small programs using logic and set theory.
Theoretical and practical limitations of formal methods.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Final examination.<p>

TEXT: Lecture notes. Backhouse, R.: Program Construction and Verification is also useful.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 73116 Mathematics for Algorithms and 81120 Data Structures and Algorithms.<p>

NOTES: Suitable also for MSc and PhD students. "Program verification" would have been a more
appropriate name for the course.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81301 Object-Oriented Programming		3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Antti Valmari<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Encapsulation of data and computation into classes, objects, inheritance, and dynamic
binding. The programming language C++.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Programming exercise.<p>

TEXT: Lecture notes. Some C++ text book is recommended, such as Stroustrup, B.: The C++
Programming Language.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 81020 Programming II.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81310 Graphical User Interfaces			1,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Senior assist. Kari Syst&auml;<p>

Lectures 14 h. Seminars 7 h. Exercises 7 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

GOALS AND CONTENT: To become familiar with graphical user interface from a user view point.
Simple exercises are done during the course and the second period contains a seminar which is used
for discussing the results of the exercise.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: An accepted exercise.<p>

LITERATURE: announced at the beginning of the lectures.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 81020.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81530 Distributed Systems Software			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Leo Sintonen<p>

Lectures 42 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

<p>

GOAL: Course on the design issues of dependable fault tolerant distributed software.<p>

CONTENTS: Time, real time, virtual time. Agreement, consensus. Process groups and related
problems. Reliable broadcast.  Global state, snapshot algorithm. Practical examples.<p>

TEXTS: Leo Sintonen, Lecture Notes. Recommended Reading: Colouris,<p>

Dollimore, Kindberg: Distributed Systems, 2.ed. AddisonWesley  1994.<p>

Sloman-Kramer, Distributed Systems.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Examination.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81820 User Interface				6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

To be held at Tampere University<p>

Lectures 39 h. Team work sessions 36 h<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Usability. Design principles based on human behaviour. Design and evaluation of
textual and graphical interfaces. Online help and documentation. New interaction techniques.<p>

LITERATURE: D. A. Norman, The Psychology of Everyday Things. Basic Books, 1988. J. Nielsen,
Usability Engineering. Academic Press, 1993. J. Preece et al, Human-Computer Interaction.
Addison-Wesley, 1994.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81830 Programming of Graphical User Interface	6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lectures 56 h. Team work sessions 24 h<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Basic components of a graphical user interface. Memory management and resources.
Graphics. Event handling. Windows and widgets. The X Window and Microsoft Windows
environments.<p>

LITERATURE: D. A. Young, The X Window System: Programming and Applications with Xt.
Prentice Hall, 1990. C. Petzold, Programming Windows 3.1. Microsoft Press, 1992. S. Rimmer,
Graphical User Interface Programming. McGraw-Hill, 1992.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81840 Advanced Computer Graphics		6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lectures 39 h. Exercises 24 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Raster algorithms. 2D and 3D viewing. 2D and 3D object transformations. Basic
animation. Segmented picture files. Hidden line and =20 edge removal. Representation of 3D shapes.
Intensity and color.<p>

LITERATURE: D. Hearn, M. P. Baker, Computer Graphics. Prentice Hall, 1986. E. Berger,
Computer Graphics. Benjamin/Cummings, 1986. J. D. Foley, A. van Dam, S. Feiner, J. Hughes,
Computer Graphics: Principles and Practice. Addison-Wesley, 1990.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81910 Postgraduate Seminar			1,5 - 7,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Reino Kurki-Suonio, Prof. Ilkka Haikala, <p>

Assoc. prof. Leo Sintonen, Assoc. prof. Antti Valmari<p>

Seminars 42 h. <p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

Seminars on varing topics.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81930 Special Topics in Software Systems		3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lecturer Pertti Lehtonen<p>

Seminars 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The topics covered change yearly. Each student gives a seminar<p>

presentation. The subject during spring 1995 was "The maintenance of a Unix<p>

based computing environment".<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81940 Software Systems Seminar			3,0-6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Antti Valmari<p>

Seminars 42 h. <p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Annually changing topic. In 1995 the seminar concentrates on the<p>

writing of rigorous specifications (or parts of specifications) using<p>

mathematical notations such as BNF, logic, set theory, and algebraic structures.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Active participation in the seminar and some homework and / or<p>

final examination.<p>

NOTES: Suitable also for MSc and PhD students.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81950 Software Laboratory			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assist. Tero Ahtee<p>

Laboratory exercises 84 h<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

GOAL: To teach independent problem solving and information search.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>81960 Software Engineering Project			4,5-7,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assist. Tero Ahtee<p>

Seminars 28 h.<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

GOAL AND CONTENTS: To teach project management and project work in practice. A project is
made in groups of four or more students. The duration of a project is approximately six months (i.e.,
both fall and spring terms). Students can also suggest a project subject themselves.<p>

<p>


<A NAME="telecommunications"></a>
<h2>Courses Offered by the Telecommunications Laboratory</h2>

<p>

<p>

<b>83000 Telecommunication Theory 			6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Markku Renfors<p>

Lectures 42 h. <p>

Exercises 42 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

GOALS:  Give basic understanding of the signals appearing in communication systems, the
distortions caused by different transmission channels, as well as the used signal processingtechniques
and their significance for the information transmission task.<p>

CONTENTS: Deterministic and random signals and the filtering of these signals. Correlationfunctions, Fourier transform and spectrum. Noise and distortions in informationtransmission.Analog
modulation methods. Sampling and pulse modulation. Introduction to digital transmission. Principles
of information theory. Computer simulation of some studied techniques as a project work.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project and exam.<p>

LITERATURE: A.B. Carlson: Communication Systems, 3rd Edition, McGraw-Hill, 1986.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in Finnish. Selfstudy program with project and exam can be arranged in English
on request.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83050 Digital Transmission 			6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Markku Renfors<p>

Lectures 42 h. <p>

Exercises 42 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

GOALS: Give basic knowledge of the signal processing techniques used in digital transmission
systems.<p>

CONTENTS: Elements of digital transmission chain: source coding, channel coding, modulation,
equalization, and synchronization. Some detection theory, Viterbi-algorithm.Adaptive methods in
equalization. Examples from practical systems. Computer simulation of some studied techniques as
a project work.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project and exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes (in Finnish). Other literature announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in Finnish. Selfstudy program with project and exam can be arranged in English
on request.<p>

<b><p>

<p>

83070 Multicarrier Techniques			3,0 ECTS credits<p>

         Accepted as a post-graduate course.<p>

</b>Lic. Tech. Jukka Rinne<p>

Seminars/Lectures 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Special course on multicarrier techniques (OFDM, DMT) and their applications to
terrestrial radio and TV transmission, mobile communication systems, and digital subscriber line
moderns.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project work and final examination.<p>

TEXT: Lecture notes, recent journal articles.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 83050 Digital Trtansmission.<p>

NOTES: Lectured every second year. Lectured during spring 1997.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83080 Synchronization in Digital Communications </b>	<b>3,0 ECTS credits<p>

          Accepted as a post-graduate course.<p>

         <p>

</b>Prof. Markku Renfors<p>

Seminars/Lectures 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Special course on synchronization issues in digital receivers (carrier and timing
recovery with special emphasis on digital techniques) and telecommunication networks (SDH, ATM).<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project work and final examination.<p>

TEXT: Lecture notes, recent journal articles.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 83050 Digital Transmission, 83505 Basic Digital Signal Processing.<p>

NOTES: Lectured every second year. Lectured in fall 1996.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83090 Advanced Course in Digital Transmission		4,5-7,5 ECTS credits<p>

          Accepted as a post-graduate course.<p>

<p>

</b>Prof. Markku Renfors<p>

Seminars/Lectures 42 h. <p>

Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

GOAL: The goal is to develop deeper theoretical understanding of digital transmission techniques
including modulation, channel equalization, detection, and error control coding.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project work and final examination.<p>

TEXT: J. G. Proakis: Digital Communications, 3ed. McGraw-Hill, 1995<p>

PREREQUISITES: 83050 Digital Transmission, 83505 Basic Digital Signal Processing.<p>

NOTES: Lectured every second year. Not lectured during 1996-97.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83101 Radio Systems				4,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Petri Jarske<p>

Lectures 42 h.<p>

Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.	<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: A course on radio systems and wireless transmission systems. Radio wave propagation,
multipath propagation, fading. Cellular networks. Satellite communications, mobilecommunication
systems, microwave links, radio and TV transmission techniques.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project and exam.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in Finnish. Selfstudy program with project and exam can be arranged in English
on request.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83150 Digital Mobile Communication Systems		4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Petri Jarske<p>

Lectures 42 h. <p>

Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS:Mobile communication systems and  mobile communication environment. GSM system
in more details.<p>

REQUIREMENTS:Exam.<p>

LITERATURE:To be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in Finnish. Selfstudy program with project and exam can be arranged in English
on request.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83170 Spread Spectrum Techniques			3,0-6,0 ECTS credits<p>

         Accepted as a post-graduate course.</b><p>

<p>

Lic. Tech. Jukka Rinne<p>

Seminars/Lectures 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Special course on spread spectrum techniques with emphasis on CDMA.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project work and final examination.<p>

TEXT: To be given at the beginning of the course.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 83050 Digital Transmission.<p>

NOTES: Lectured every second year. Not lectured during 1996-97.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83180 Wireless LANs				3,0 ECTS credits<p>

         Accepted as a post-graduate course.<p>

<p>

</b>Prof. Petri Jarske<p>

Seminars/Lectures 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Special course on wireless LAN technologies, such as DECT and HIPERLAN.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project work and final examination.<p>

TEXT: To be given at the beginning of the course.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 83050 Digital Transmission, 83150 Digital Mobile Communication Systems.<p>

NOTES: Lectured every second year. Lectured during spring 1997.<b><p>

</b><p>

<p>

<b>83200 Telecommunication Networks			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

DI Pekka Uotila<p>

Lectures 42 h. <p>

Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The structure of the fixed telecommunication network, switching and transmission
techniques. Telephone, modem and other terminal devices. Digital networks and ISDN. Packet-switched networks. Principles and applications of broadband communication. Telecommunication
service and telecom. operators.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project and exam.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in Finnish.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83311 Broadband Networks 			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

DI Mika Grundstr&ouml;m<p>

Guest lectures<p>

Lectures 42 h.<p>

Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.	<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: B-ISDN-concept. ATM-technology. Adaptation of services to ATM-network.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project and exam.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in Finnish. Selfstudy program with project and exam can be arranged in English
on request.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83350 Network Management 			3,0 ECTS credits<p>

<p>

</b>Prof. Markku Renfors <p>

Guest lectures<p>

Lectures 28 h. <p>

Exercises 7 h.<p>

Takes place during spring terms.	<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Network management for telecommunication networks and computer communication
networks. TMN and SNMP network management concepts, principles, and key elements.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project and exam.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in Finnish.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83380 Intelligent Networks			3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Markku Renfors<p>

Guest lectures<p>

Lectures 28 h.<p>

Exercises 7 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.	<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: What is an Intelligent Network (IN)? Central IN-services. The basic architecture of
IN, open IN architecture.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project and exam.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in Finnish. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83400 Introduction to Telecommunications 		4,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

DI Pekka Uotila<p>

Lectures 42 h.<p>

Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.	<p>

<p>

GOAL: To give general view of telecommunication technology, telesevices and developments in the
field.<p>

CONTENTS: Information, signal, noise, and channel. Modulation and  coding. Telephone, telephone
network andswitching. Radio and TV. Computer communication networks.<p>

REQUIREMENTS:  Project  and exam.<p>

LITERATURE: D. Petersen: Audio, Video and Data Telecommunications, McGraw-Hill, 1992.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in Finnish.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83500 Communications Protocols			6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Jarmo Harju<p>

Lectures 56 h. <p>

Exercises and seminars 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.	<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The layered model of communicatios, TCP/IP and OSIarchitectures.The concept and
modelling of protocols.The basic  functions  of layer 2 - 4 protocols. The  applicationlayrer protocols
and ASN.1 specification language. Examples from TCP/IP, OSI, SS7, and GSM protocols.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project and exam.<p>

LITERATURE: To be  announced at the beginning of the cours.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in Finnish. Selfstudy program with project and exam can be arranged in English
on request.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83550 Protocol Engineering			6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof.Jarmo Harju<p>

Lectures 28 h. <p>

Exercises and seminars 7 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.	<p>

                                     <p>

GOAL AND CONTENTS:The goal is that the student gets the practical knowledge and skills  to 
implement protocol software and distributed applications. At the course, an own protocol  is designed
and implemented using an object-oriented software tool.<p>

REQUIREMENTS:Project.<p>

LITERATURE:To be announced at the beginning of the course. Programming is recommended.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in Finnish. Selfstudy program with project and exam can be arranged in English
on request.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83700 Communication Circuits			6,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Dr. Nikolay Tchamov<p>

Lectures 42 h. <p>

Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall terms.	<p>

<p>

GOALS: Obtaining main knowledge on the communication circuits.<p>

CONTENTS: Theory, models, CAD-analysis and measurements of communication:  components:
transmission lines, BJT, MOS and MESFET, HEMT, HBT etc. - Circuits: RF amplifiers and
generators, current-mode RF circuits, multipliers, active and S-CFilters, VCO, PLL, mixers,
detectors, RF A/D &amp; D/A circuits for mixed and all-digital radio and TV transmitters and receivers;
- Technologies: Bipolar, CMOS, BiCMOS, GaAs.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Active participation in the exercises. Examination.<p>

PREREQUISITE: Working knowledge on electrical and electronic components and circuits.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in English.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83710 High-Frequency Filters,			4,5 ECTS credits<p>

      Accepted as a Postgraduate Course</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Nikolay Tchamov<p>

Lectures 28 h. <p>

Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

GOALS: Intermediate-to-Advanced level knowledge on High-Frequency Filters.<p>

CONTENTS: Detailed review and further development of Filter Synthesis Methods at Very-High
Frequencies, and specially using: Cascaded Biquads, Signal Flow Graphs, Gyrators, Coupled
Resonatoers etc. Transconductors Design. Tuning Methods. Realisations. Monolithic Filters.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Succesful completion of the exercise tasks, passing the design test on using the
software tools and passing the written examination.<p>

PREREQUISITE COURSES: 79143 Analog Filters, recommended also 83700 Communication
Circuits.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in English.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83720 PLL Communication Circuits			3,0 ECTS credits<p>

<p>

</b>Assoc. Prof. Nikolay Tchamov<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

GOALS: Intermediate level knowledge on PLL circuits and their applications in communications.<p>

CONTENTS: Operation principles and applications, analysis, parameters and models of: linear PLL,
classical digital PLL, all-digital PLL. Building blocks, locked/unlocked performance, noise, design
&amp; applications. IC implementations. Software support. Measurements principles of the: Center
Frequency, VCO-gain, Phase-Detector-Gain, Hold &amp; Pull-in range, Natural Frequency &amp; Damping
Factor, Phase-Transfer Function and Bandwidth.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Succesful completion of the exercise tasks, passing the design test on using the
software tools, and passing the written examination.<p>

PREREQUISITE COURSES: 74001 Basic Circuits of Electronics, 74052 Applications of
Semiconductor Components, 74510 Digital Technique.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in English.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83730 Mixed-Mode Communication Circuits		4,5 ECTS credits<p>

      Accepted as a Postgraduate Course</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Nikolay Tchamov<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

GOALS:Intermediate-to-Advanced level knowledge on high-frequency ADC/DAC and their
applications in communications.<p>

CONTENTS: Signal Conditioning. RF V-I Converters. RF Sample/Hold &amp; Track/<p>

Hold. Current-Scaling &amp; Differential-Current-Switch Digital-to-Analog Converters. Applications in
the All-Digital Receivers &amp; Transmitters. Pipelined &amp; Flash ADC. Oversampling ADC: First &amp;
Second Order, Interpolative &amp; Cascaded Modulators, Sinc, FIR &amp; IIR Decimation Filters. High-Performance ADCs.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Succesfull completion of the exercise tasks, passing the design test on using the
software tools, and passing the written examination.<p>

PREREQUISITE COURSES: 74001 Basic Circuits of Electronics, 74042 Electronic Circuits and
Devices, 74510 Digital Technique, recommended also 83700 Communication Circuits.<p>

NOTES: Lectured in English<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83750 Methods/Algorithms for High-Frequency Design	4,5 ECTS credit<p>

      Accepted as a Postgraduate Course</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Nikolay Tchamov<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

GOALS: Intermediate-to-Advanced level knowledge on CAD Methods and Algorithms for high-frequencies in communications.<p>

CONTENTS: Detailed review and further development of the knowledge on circuit modelling
methods and the ways to use them: Node Voltages and State-Space; Numerical, Semi-Symbolic &amp;
Symbolic, DC, AC, Transient, Spectral, Activity &amp; Stability Analysis, Voltera Series. Methods &amp;
Algorithms for Sensitivity, Noise &amp; Tolerance Analysis. Behavioural Modelling &amp; Analog-VHL.
Software in Focus: P- and H-Spice (review), Aplac, EEsof-Libra, MDS.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Successful completion of the exercise tasks, passing the design test on using the
software tools, and passing the written examination. <p>

PREREQUISITE COURSES: 74001 Basic Circuits of Electronics, 79142 Electronic Circuit
Modelling and Analysis. <p>

NOTES: Lectured in English<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83902 Telecommunications Thesis Seminar A		1,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Petri Jarske <p>

Prof. Markku Renfors<p>

Seminars 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.	<p>

<p>

GOALS: To get a general view of different types of Diploma Theses and the extent of the thesis
project for making it easier to select the topic for own thesis.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Listening the seminars during one term.The course is mandatory for everybody
who wants to make the thesis in Telecommunications.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83903 Telecommunications Thesis Seminar B	</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Petri Jarske <p>

Prof. Markku Renfors<p>

Seminars 1 h.<p>

Takes place during fall and spring terms.	<p>

<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Seminar presentation concerning the topic of the thesis.The course is mandatory
for everybody who wants to make the thesis in Telecommunications.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83933 Advanced Topics in Telecommunications 		3,0-6,0 ECTS credits<p>

         Accepted as a post-graduate course.</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Markku Renfors<p>

Seminars 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring terms.	<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Topics in telecommunications changing yearly.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Active participation, seminar presentation, and exam.<p>

LITERATURE:To be announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

NOTES: Lectured usually in English.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>83937 Telecommunications Seminar 		3,0-6,0 ECTS credits<p>

          Accepted as a post-graduate course.<p>

<p>

</b>Prof. Markku Renfors<p>

Seminars 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.	<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Topics in telecommunications changing yearly.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Active participation, seminar presentation, and exam.<p>

