<a name="etcs">
<h2>The ECTS Departmental Coordinator </h2>
<b>Professor Gunnar Graeffe</b><br>
Tampere University of Technology<br>
Korkeakoulunkatu 1<br>
P.O. BOX 692, SF-33101 Tampere, FINLAND<br>
Tel: 358-31-365 2544, Fax:358-31-365 3350<p>

<a name="#institutes">
<h2>Description of the Institutes and Laboratories and Their Activities in the Department of Electrical Engineering</h2>

<p>

<b><i>Physics</i></b><p>

<p>

The central areas of teaching and research in Physics are experimental
physics and semiconductor engineering. The Institute has five research
laboratories, namely the Laboratories of Semiconductor Engineering,
Surface Physics, Physics of Aerosols (Environmental Physics), Plasma
Engineering, and Fur and Leather Technology.<p>

<p>

In the vast majority of cases, research is conducted jointly with, and
financed by, some outside party. Central research projects are in
optical electronics directed by Professor Markus Pessa and several
others connected with combustion mechanisms, emissions, and the
quantification and clean-up of the latter.<p>

<p>

<b><i>Semiconductor and Surface Science Laboratories</i></b><p>

<p>

The laboratories directed by Professor Markus Pessa focus on the
development of compound-semiconductor and optoelectronic components,
research on reactions between catalytically active surfaces and gases,
and theoretical and experimental research on surface atomic
structure. The unit is active e.g. in three EU technology programs
(RACE WELCOME 2006, ESPRIT SUPERDEV 7227, ESPRIT SMILES 8447). <p>

<p>

The semiconductor group manufactures, anomgst other things,
client-specific epitaxial semiconductor discs, lasers ussed in fiber
reinforcers in optical telecommunication, lasers transmitting
brightred light, photo, X-ray, and particle detectors, optical power
transformers, and solar cells.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b><i>Electronics</i></b><p>

<p>

The microelectronics and Industrial Electronics Laboratories of the
Institute of Electronics together cover quite a wide spectrum of
pompetence within electronics. The Institute's computer equipment and
design tools are of top class. There is total command of design from
microcircuits right up to the final completed circuit
card. Information technology at the Institute has attained top
international standards in neural and fuzzy research.<p>

Other emphasis areas are advanced user interfaces and control of
embedded device structures ranging from sensors to
activators. Contacts with industry preserve wideness in the range of
activities, closeness to practice, and vital connections with
students' future workplaces.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b><i>Biomedical Engineering</i></b><p>

<p>

The most central research area at the Ragnar Granit Institute is
research on the bioelectric and biomagnetic phenomena occurring in
biological tissue. The aim is to apply these phenomena in practice
over broad areas in clinical diagnosis and medical therapy. The
outcome of theoretical and experimental research has been the
development of diagnostic instrumentation and methods for the
diagnosis of diseases of the heart and the nervous system. <p>

The Institute has wide international contacts and <u>all its tuition
is in English</u>. The knowledge gained can be widely utilizsed in the
fields of electronics and computer science.<p>

<p>

<p>

<i><b>Power Engineering</i></b><p>

<p>

The Institute is one of the leading electrixcal power research units
in Finland. Currently several research projects are underway, the aims
of which have been defined in line with the needs of electric
utilities, power companies, and the manufacturing industry. Wider
research projects relate to the prevention of disturbances in an
electricity transmission network, distribution network design and
fault diagnosis of its components, and the evaluation and attenuation
of the environmental impact of 50 Hz electrical and magnetic
fields.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b><i>Power Electronics</b></i>   <p>

 <p>

The Institute of Power Electonics concentrates on teaching and
research in power electronics, electric drives, and illumination
technology. The novel technical solutions for motor drives made
available by new power semiconductors have been central topics for
dissertations. <p>

<p>

In addition to questions relating to converter command and control
implemented by new power semiconductors, the Institute has special
competence e.g. in optics design for lamps and in power electronics
applications in lighting control. Results of research in these fields
are to be seen in industrial plants and at many airports round the
world. <p>

<p>

<b><i>Electricity and Magnetism</b></i><p>

<p>

For a decade now the Institute has conducted research on exploiting
the phenomenon of superconductibity in electromagnets, particularly
for energy engineering applications. The Institute is participating in
a joint project of the Northern Countries to develop high-temperature
superconductors for industrisal applications. The practical commercial
breakthrough of superconductivity may be only some years
away. Electric motors will increase in power thanks to enhanced
efficiency and decreased size. <p>

<p>

The cryogenic measuring station must be further developed along lines
enabling it to fulfill the wishes of industry.<p>

<p>

