<h2>Biomedical Engineering</h2>

<p>

<b>71100 Human Anatomy and Physiology		6,0 ECTS credits</b>	<p>

<p>

Prof. Arto Uusitalo		<p>

Lectures 56 h. Demonstrations 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term. <p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Basics of the human anatomy and physiology. Anatomy and
physiology of circulatory, respiratory and gastro-intestinal
system. Nervous and hormonal regulation.  Thermoregulation. Excertion
functions. Neurophysiology. Physiological and neurophysiological
measurements.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Final examination.<p>

LITERATURE: A. Vander, J. Sherman and D. Lucia
no: Human Physiology, International
Edition, Mc-Graw-Hill, New York, 1990.<p>

NOTES: Lectures are given in Finnish. Text book in English is
available. Final exam may be given in English.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>71111 Biomedical Engineering and Physiological 	4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

	<b>Measurements</b><p>

<p>

Assist. Prof.  Juha Nousiainen<p>

Lectures 35 h, Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Basics of methods and devices used in medical diagnosis and therapy. Diagnostic
methods and devices of human circulatory, nervous and respiratory systems. Patient monitoring
devices. Devices used to support central vital functions. Patient safety.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Final examination.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes. John G. Webster (ed): Medical Instrumentation, Application and
Design. Hougton Mifflin Company, Boston, 1992 (partly).<p>

NOTES: Lectures are given in Finnish during the fall term and, if required, in English during the
spring term.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>71201 Basics of Small-Signal Instrumentation</b>		3,0 ECTS credits <p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Hannu Eskola<p>

Lectures 21 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Connecting electrodes and sensors to a recording system. Electromagnetic
interference and its elimination: grounding, shielding, isolation. Signal conditioning by means of
electronic methods and circuits: impedance matching, bridge circuits, special amplifiers. Examples
of instrumentation systems.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Final examination.<p>

LITERATURE: R. Pall&aacute;s-Areny, John G. Webster: Sensors and Signal Conditioning. John Wiley
&amp; Sons, Inc. New York, 1991.<p>

NOTES: Lectures are given in Finnish. Text book in English is avalable. Final exam may given in
English.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>71210  Bioelectromagnetism			7,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Jaakko Malmivuo<p>

Lectures 56 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS:  Theory of bioelectric and biomagnetic phenomena of living tissue and their clinical
applications. Nervous, sensory and muscle cells as bioelectric and biomagnetic sources and their
modelling. Modelling of  living tissues as volume conductors. Theoretical analysis methods of
bioelectic recordings. Bioelectric and biomagnetic signals and their use in clinical diagnosis.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Final examination.<p>

LITERATURE: J.Malmivuo and R.Plonsey: Bioelectromagnetism,Principles and applications of
bioelectric and biomagnetic fields. Oxford University Press 1995.<p>

NOTE: Lectures are given in English. Approved for doctoral studies.<p>

