<p>

<b>72211 Thermal Physics				4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Docent Rolf Hernberg<p>

Lectures 28h, exercises 28h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Introduction to the thermal aspects of different areas of physics and to their
understanding on the basis of molecular interaction. The elements of classical thermodynamics,
introduction to kinetic theory, elements of heat transfer. The approach is based on experimental
knowledge and phenomenology rather than on formal deduction.  <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Written exams on problem sessions and the whole course. <p>

LITERATURE: Sprackling, M.: Thermal Physics, Macmillan, 1991.<p>

<p>

<b>72310 Mathematical Methods of Classical and Quantum 	4,5 ECTS credits

	Physics 

</b><p>

Dr. Jouko Nieminen <p>

Lectures 42 h, exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To learn essential mathematical toos of physics and to acquire capability to utilize
them to relevant problems in physics.<p>

CONTENTS: Coordinate systems and transformations, vectors and tensors, the elements of
group theory, compex analysis, elements of differential equations, Sturm-Liouville theory, Green
functions.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved examination or exercises and a case study.<p>

LITERATURE: G. Arfken: Mathematical methods for physiscists, 3rd ed., Academic Press,
London 1985.<p>

<p>

<b>72401 Ultrasonics				4,5 ECTS credits

</b><p>

Assoc. Prof. Esa M&auml;ntysalo<p>

Lectures 28h, Seminars 14 h.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Course in modern ultrasonics. US waves in single crystals, quasi-isotropic,
polycrystalline and amorphous materials, liquids and gases. Attenuation and phase velocity and
their measurements. US transducers. Applications.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved examination and seminar presentation.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes and Truell, Elbaum and Chick: Ultrasonic Methods in Solid State
Physics, Academic Press, New York.<p>

NOTE: Lectured every second year, no lectures academic year 1995-1996.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>72420 Aerosol Physics			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

PhD Jorma Keskinen<p>

Lectures 28h, exercises 14h<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Basic concepts of aerosol physics, mechanical, optical and electrical properties of
aerosol particles, nucleation, condensation, measurement techniques, health effects, atmospheric
effects, industrial applications. <p>

LITERATURE: Hinds, W.C. Aerosol Technology, Wiley, 1982.<p>

<p>

<p>

