<a name="electronics">
<h2>Electronics</h2>

<p>

<p>

<b>74001 Basic Circuits of Electronics 	 		7,5 ECTS credits

</b><p>

Lecturer Matti Ilmonen       <p>

Lectures 39h (fall), Exercises 36h (fall )<p>

Laboratory exercises 6h (spring), Laboratory works 9h (spring )<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The course consists of two main topics: Analog and Digital techniques, including
laboratory measurements. Analog part: Properties and circuit characteristics of junction diodes,
field-effect transistors (FETs), and bipolar junction transistors (BJTs). Use and analysis in most
common circuit lay-outs. Signal models for diodes and transistors: Use and validity.The
operational amplifier (Op-Amp) as a basic building block is also covered. Digital part: Basic logic-gate building blocks used in digital systems. Combinatorial logic (binary adders, decoders, read-only memories, programmable arrays) and sequential circuits and systems (one-bit memory, J-K
flip-flop, synchronous counters). Boolean algebra and Karnaugh-minimization method. The
course gives also a short survey on most common applications: regulated power supplies, A/D
and D/A converters, A- and B-class amplifiers. The laboratory works consist of measurements of
some common electrical equipment and CAD application using SPICE-programme. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Written examinations based on lectures, exercises, and laboratory works.<p>

TEXT:Neil Storey: Electronics - a System Approach, Addison-Wesley, 1992. The lectures are
based on this book.The course covers some 60% of the book. Millman &amp; Grabel:
Microelectronics,McGraw Hill,II edition,1987.This course covers only some 20% of the book.<p>

NOTES: Recommended basic knowledge: 79101 Introduction to Electrical Science.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>74031 Electronics Laboratory I 			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lecturers Riku M&auml;kinen<p>

Laboratory works 84h            <p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

SYLLABUS: Laboratory exercises related to courses 74052 Semiconductor Components, 74501
Analog Technique and 74521 Electronic Components and Citcuits. The assignments introduce
students to the basic electronic components.<p>

OBJECTIVE: The laboratory exercises will enable the student to verify and apply in practice
some of the theorical knowledge gained on other courses.<p>

<i>REQUIREMENTS</i>: Passed laboratory assignments and passed final examination.<p>

PREREQUISITE: 74001 Basic Circuits of Electronics<p>

NOTE: All laboratory assignments must be carried out in the same academic year i.e. passed
assignments from previous years can not be included. There will be three examinations, one in
spring and two in autumn. The student must pass one of these examinations in order to be
credited for the course. Also an intensive laboratory work course with a tight schedule is available
in the summer term.<p>

INFORMATION: Information on the course will be available on the notice board in front of the
laboratory (Room SL 309), and the newsgroup: tut.ele.eltk1 is associated with the course. The
information will be mainly in Finnish, version in English will be available if requested.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>74035 Electronics Laboratory II			7,5 ECTS credits

</b><p>

Senior Assistant Marko Antila<p>

Laboratory exercises 112 h<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

AIMS: To improve students capabilities of practical electronics design and support especially
teaching in industrial electronics.<p>

CONTENTS: Design and prototyping with commercially available components. Contemporary
design and testing environments. Data acquisition and processing. Usual families of
microcontroller.<p>

PREREQUISITE: Courses of basic module 74052, 74031, 74501 and 74510.<p>

Literature: Files for each exercise and other essential material<p>

NOTES: The whole course must be passed within a year. The course is recommended to take
same time or after as 74550 CAE in electronics. The course must be passed in one of three
following examination within a year.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Passed laboratory exercises and passed examination.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>74042 Electronic Circuits and Devices 		4,5 ECTS credits

</b><p>

Prof. Kimmo Kaski<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h. Lab 14 h.<p>

Takes place during ? term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Semiconductor materials. Transport of charge carriers in semiconductors. pn-junctions, diodes and equivalent circuits. Bipolar devices, especially BJT and its equivalent
circuits. Unipolar devices, especially JFET and MOSFET, and their equivalent circuits. Photonic
devices, especially LEDs and lasers. Microwave diodes. Examples of seting the operation and
biasing condition for single-element circuits.<p>

The aim is to learn how circuits of electronic semiconductor devices function and analyse them.To
learn about the physical phenomena and functions of semiconductor devices, their electrical
equivalent circuits and their usage. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Written exam covers the topics of lectures and exercises. Exam can be taken
only if laboratory assignement is passed. Acceptable exam grade can be increased by one grade-unit by completing 75 percent of the exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: *  S. M. Sze: Semiconductor Devices, Physics and Technology, Wiley 1985.
Chapters 1-7. Lectures are mainly based on this book. <p>

*  E. S. Yang: Microelectronic Devices, McGraw-Hill, 1988. Chapters 1-5, 7-9 and 14-15. This
book has the same structure as the first one but is more explanatory, thus being more suitable for
self-studying. Therefore, it is recommended to be purchased as a cheaper student-edition book
and as being useful hand-book in the future. <p>

*  D.A. Fraser: The Pysics of Semiconductor Devices, 4th Edition, Oxford University Press,
1986. Chapters 1-5. Suitable for self-studying.  <p>

*  B. G. Streetman: Solid State Electronic Devices, Prentice Hall, 1990.     Suitable for those who
want to learn more about semiconductor physics and its processing technologies.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>74052 Applications of Semiconductor Components 	4,5 ECTS credits          </b><p>

<p>

Prof. Markku Kivikoski, M.Sc. Tuomo Konnunaho<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

GOALS: Design and analysis know-how of common electronic circuits and systems based on
transistor stages.<p>

CONTENTS: Design and analysis of transistor circuits and systems. Characteristics and
applications of some commercial components and circuits. Basic amplifier stages at low
frequencies. Frequence response of amplifiers. Differential amplifiers. Active current and voltage
sources for biasing. Output stages. Multistage amplifier configurations. Basic concepts of
feedback. Stability and frequence response of feedback amplifiers. Operational amplifier
architectures. Noise. Regulators, amplifier classification and power circuits.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Written examination based on lectures and exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: A.R.Hambley: Electronics, A Top Down Approach to Computer-Aided Circuit
Design, MacMillan, 1994. Supplementary text book: J.Millman &amp; A.Grabel: Microelectronics,
McGraw-Hill, 2nd ed., 1987. Chapters 10-14 ja 17; Ahola, Heusala, Myllyl&auml;:
Analogiaelektroniikan perusteet, Hantro Products Oy 1993. Various databooks<p>

<p>

