<b>74501 Analog Technique			4,5 ECTS credits 

</b><p>

Ilpo Reitmaa<p>

Lectures 28h. Exercises 14h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

AIMS: Familiarigation to the possibilities and design of op. amp. based analog circuits.<p>

CONTENTS: The operational amplifier and its terminology. Unidealities feedback. Operational
amplifier circuits and solutions. Amplification, pulse generators, signal conditioning. Modulation
and demodulation. Detectors, sample and hold circuits, converters. Comparators. Phase-locked
loops.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Millman &amp; Grabel: Microelectronics, II ed. McGraw Hill 1987. Supporting text
D.J.Dailey, Operational Amplifiers and Linear Integrated Circuits: Theory and Applications,
McGraw-Hill, 1990<p>

NOTES: Pre-requisite 74001 and 74052.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>74510  Digital Electronics 			4,5 ECTS credits

</b><p>

Senior Ass. Marko Antila<p>

Lectures 28h. Exercises 14h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

AIMS: Get a student widely familiar with modern digital electronics at transistor and logic gate
level.<p>

CONTENTS: Practical considerations of digital electronics. BJT and CMOS transistors and their
characteristics, inverters, CMOS and TTL logic families and their characteristics, buffers,
interface circuits, regenerative circuits, semiconductor memories, programmable logic devices,
noise in digital circuits.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project work and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Theodore F. Bogart: Introduction to Digital Circuits, McGraw-Hill, 1992.<p>

NOTES: Pre-requisite 74042 and 74052.<p>

<p>

<b>74521 Electronic Components and Circuits 		4,5 ECTS credits

</b><p>

Lecturer Matti Ilmonen<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 20 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

GOALS: The course gives to the student a survey about typical electronic and electrical
components, their characteristics and most common area of use. Applications are analog or digital
oriented.<p>

CONTENTS: Main topics in the course are ( the yearly emphasis may change ):Passive
Components: Electrical ( resistors, capacitors, ...) and electromechanical components ( switches,
microphones ...).Active components: Diodes, transistors in signal processing and power
applications. Linear and switching power regulators. Analog and digital converters. Digital
integrated circuits, fuzzy logic. Optoelectronics-, ASIC-; CCD-; IR-, ultrasonic- components.
Semiconductor materials: New materials - their characteristics and use in applications. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved final report before the examination and passed written examination
based on lectures and material, collected during the course. A complete accomplishment consists
of a report and an examination.<p>

LITERATURE: The course material consists of a final report, made by the students and the
lecturer. This material is renewed every year.<p>

PREREQUISITES: 74031 Electronics Laboratory I.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>74541 Electronics Design 			3,0-6,0  ECTS credits

</b><p>

Prof. Markku Kivikoski<p>

Lectures 14 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

GOALS: The course gives to the students own practical experiences in a design project which will
be carried out as team work.<p>

CONTENTS: Practical topics of R&amp;D projects in electronics industry. Electrical and mechanical
design of electronics circuits and systems considering the requirements of manufacturing and
reliability. Furthermore essential topics are: needs of customer, marketing, validity for production,
and documentation. The projected team work is the most important part of this course.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Active participation in lectures and exercises. Completion of agreed project
and written final report.<p>

<p>

<b>

74550 CAE in Electronics 			3,0 ECTS credits

</b><p>

Lecturer Tuomo Konnunaho<p>

Lectures 14h, guided computer sessions 8h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

AIMS: Make a student familiar with computer-aided design and simulation of electronics.<p>

CONTENTS: New design and simulation technologies of electronics. Simulation of components
and real circuits of electronics. Practical topics in electronic desing procedure. Important
documentation things are practised in exercises. Basic tings of designing of printed circuit boards.
Overview of the programs such as Powerview, Pads and Spice.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Well reported and documented exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes and parts of the book: Lamitt and Lloyd, Drafting for electronics.<p>

NOTES: Pre-requisite 74001, 74031 and 74052. The course is recommended to pass before or
simultaneous with 74035. The course is optional only for extension and special modules, not for
basic module. The course have to be passed within a year.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>74560   High-Speed Electronics 			4,5 ECTS credits

</b><p>

Olli-Pekka Lunden<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h. Laboratory exercises 10 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

The Lectures and Exercises are meant to provide advanced knowledge in the field, using
simulations mainly with SPICE, HP-Libra and HP-MDS for MS-Windows and UNIX Platforms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Circuits, Interconnections, Transmission Lines: Characteristic Impedance,
Reflection Coefficients, VSWR, Smith Chart, Micro Strip Lines. Transfer Functions. Two-Port-Circuits and [s] Parameters. Impedance Matching. Stability Criteria. High-Speed Semiconductor
Components. Gain, Stability, Noise. Models. Diodes: Shotky, Tunnel, Gunn, IMPATT, PIN.
Transistors: BJT, FET, MOSFET, MESFET, HEMT, HBT. High-Speed Analog Circuits: Gain-Bandwidth Product. Noise. Input &amp; Output Conditions. Stability Criteria. Cascodes and
Differential Amplifiers. High-Speed Operational Amplifiers. Fast Comparators. Tuned and
Distributed Amplifiers. Oscillators. RF Circuits: Gain-Bandwidth Product. Power Gain. Stability.
Noise. Transistor Amplifiers. Impedance Matching. Low-Noise Design. Power Amplifiers.
Biasing. Oscillators; Two-port oscillators. Detectors and Mixers. Switches, Attenuators and
Phase Shifters. High-Speed Digital Circuits: Noise Margins; Propagation Delay. Bipolar, MOS
and BiCMOS Circuits. Emitter-Coupled Logic. MESFET and HEMT Logic Circuits. Loading
Restrictions. Distributed and Cascaded Drivers. Clocking Strategies. Clock Distribution. High-Speed A/D and D/A Converters. Delays and Errors. Fast Analog Switches and Track/Hold
Circuits. Digital to Analog Converters: Current, Voltage and Charge Scaling.Analog to Digital
Converters: Parallel; Interleaved; Pipeline. Parameters. Speed Limits.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved course works/homeworks and written examination on the theory
which includes also solving a design task in the computer classroom using SPICE or HP-Libra or
HP-MDS.<p>

REFERENCES:<p>

[1]   Geiger R., Allen P. and Strader N., VLSI Design Techniques, McGraw-Hill, 1990.<p>

[2]   Tomazou C., Lidgey F., Haigh D., Analog IC Design, IEE, 1990.<p>

[3]   Laker K., Sansen W.,  Analog Integrated Circuits and Systems, McGraw-Hill, 1994.<p>

[4]   Ismail M., Fiez T.,Analog VLSI: Signal and Information Processing, McGraw-Hll, 1994.<p>

[5]   Haznedar H.,  Digital Microelectronics, The Benjamin / Cummings, 1991.<p>

[6]   Weste N. and Eshraghian K., CMOS VLSI Design, Addison-Wesley, 1993, 2nd Edition.<p>

[7]   Long S., Butner S., GaAs Digital Integrated Circuit Design, McGraw-Hill, 1990. <p>

[8]   Ali F., Gupta A., HEMTs  &amp;  HBTs, Artech House, 1991.<p>

[9]   Elliot R., An Introduction to Guided Waves and Microwaves, Prentice-Hall, 1993.<p>

NOTES: Recommended pre-requisite is the basic knowledge from the courses:<p>

  74001 Basic Circuits of Electronics<p>

  74031 and 74035 Electronics Laboratory<p>

  74042 Electronic Circuits and Devices<p>

  74111 Integrated Analog Circuits<p>

  74251 IC Technique <p>

  74501 Analog Technique<p>

  74510 Digital Technique<p>

  74521 Electronic Components and Circuits<p>

