<b>79132	Superconducting Magnets		4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lecturer Risto Mikkonen<p>

Lectures 35 h, exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Physical background of supercondcutivity. Different coil geometries. Disturbance
spectrum and training phenomena. Cryogenics. Stability. Transition to the normal state.
Applications.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Written exam of the lectures and literature, approved case-exercise.<p>

LITERATURE: M. Wilson, Superconducting magnets. Clarendom Press 1983. <p>

Y. Iwasa, Case studies in superconducting magnets. Plenum Press 1994.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>79133	Electromagnetics and Telecommunication	4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Lauri Kettunen<p>

Lectures 42 h<p>

Takes place during ecery second spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The course deals with the foundations of modern wireless telecommunication.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Written exam of the lectures and literature. Literature remains to be
announced.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>79135	Research and Development Techniques in 	4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

		<b>Electrotechnical Engineering 	</b><p>

<p>

Lecturer Risto Mikkonen<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 21 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Introduction to working methods in projects. Start-up of a development project,
sketching and lead-through. Searching, evaluation and screening of ideas. Economic planning.
Supervision and time-schedules (PERT diagram). Reliability aspects.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Attendance at the seminars. Approved written exam and seminar work.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<p>

<b>79136	Seminar in Chaos Theory		4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Jarl-Thure Eriksson<p>

Lectures 28 h.<p>

Takes place during summer term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Student seminar of modelling of complex systems.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Attendance at the seminars. Approved seminar work.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>79137	Magnetism and Magnetic Materials		4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Ass. Jaakko Paasi<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Physical background of ferro-, dia- and paramagnetism. Hysteresis curve.
Magnetostriction and its applications to Hi-Tech products. Ferromagnetic metal glasses and their
usage in high-frequency tranformers. Permanent magnets. Technical superconductors.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Written exam of the lectures, approved case-exercise.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>79139	Methodics of Modelling			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Jarl-Thure Eriksson<p>

Lectures 30 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Development of modelling in physical science. Introduction and comparison of
different methods of modelling. System dynamics and growth models. Application examples.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Written exam of the lectures and literature.<p>

LITERATURE: P. Doucet, P. Sloep, Mathematical modelling in the life sciences. Ellis Harwood,
1993.<p>

<p>

<b><p>

79141	Special Task Work in Electrodynamic	3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. J.-T. Eriksson, Lecturer Risto Mikkonen, Assoc. prof. Lauri Kettunen<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The content of the work is specified individually.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved report.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>79143	Analog Filters			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Docent Pekka Valtonen<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS:  On the realisability of network functions. Matrix representations of  two-ports; the
connections between matrix parameters and network functions. Filter characteristics; frequency
band transformations. Ideal-filter characteristics and their approximation. On the synthesis
methods of passive one- and two-ports. Ideal active circuit elements. Selected active synthesis
methods. Sensitivity.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Written exam of the lectures and literature. Literature remains to be
announced.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>79150	Energy Storage and New Energy Sources	4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lecturer Risto Mikkonen<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Energy economy at local and global levels. Fossil fuels. Nuclear energy. Methods
of energy storage, technical and economical comparison. Renewable energy sources. Technical
options and future prospects of fusion. Effective usage of electricity. Climate changes, greenhouse
effect.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Active attendance at lectures and seminars. Written exam of the lectures,
approved seminar work.<p>

LITERATURE: J. Kraushaar, R. Ristinen, Energy and problems of technical society. John Wiley
&amp; Sons, 1988.  L. Burnham (ed.), Renewable energy, sources of fuels and electricity. Island Press,
1993.<p>


