<a name="#institutes">
<h2>Description of the Institutes and Laboratories and Their Activities in the Department of Automation Engineering</h2>

<p>

<b><i>Automation and Control Engineering</i></b><p>

<p>

Work at the Institute of Control Engineering is concerned with modeling, measurements,
simulation, control design, and the creation of control systems. Control Engineering's systems-oriented way of thinking is currently applied also outside actual engineering areas, e.g. in
bionedical engineering, environment protection, and economics. Some of the central teaching
areas at the Institute are systems engineering, process control, and robot automation. The
Institute has been paricularly active in commissioned research for over 15 years. <p>

<p>

Amongst the most important current application areas are wood processing, mechatronics, and
energy production. New areas in basic research are neural networks and automation applications
of fuzzy logic systems.<p>

<p>

<b><i>Measurement and Information Technology</b></i><p>

<p>

Activities at the Institute of Measurement Technology deal with automation and electrical
measurement. Also the Institute is developing measurement methods related to quality control
(TQM) and environmental engineering. Research is concerned with sensor technology and the
analysis and processing of measurement signals.<p>

<p>

Multivariate signal analysis has been applied, e.g. to the thermo-mecanical pulping process
(HIMA project), and the interaction model developed has made it possible to decrease process
disturbances. Research in sensor technology combines process models and sensor moderls in such
a way as to permit also questions of sensor location to be handled. Research in flow measurement
is tops in the world.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b><i>Hydraulics and Automation</b></i><p>

<p>

The Institute of Hydraulics and Automation (IHA) is the second-largest institute in the field in
Europe. The activities of the Institute include, e.g. Hydraulics, pneumatics, machine automation
and robotics. In addition to teaching, IHA is engaged in several research and product-development projects serving both large and small mechanical engineering enterprises and
requiring the expertise of the Institute. Importantly also, basic research activities at IHA ensure
the long-term development of technologies.<p>

<p>

Water Hydraulics replaces oil, the conventional medium with pure water or HFA liquid. This is a
significant advantage, e.g. from the vantage point of environment friendliness. In a water
hydraulics development project conducted jointly with industry, water hydraulics components on
the market were investigated and new commercial components were developed.<p>

<p>

<p>
<a name="study">
<h2>Study Options available in the Department of Automation Engineering</h2>
<p>

<b>Automation and Control Engineering</b><p>

<p>

- control engineering<p>

- Automation engineering<p>

- Systems engineering<p>

- Process and energy automation<p>

- Robotics<p>

<p>

<b>Measurement and Information Technology</b><p>

<p>

- Sensors<p>

- Signal analysis<p>

- Measurements and industrial automation<p>

- Electrical measurements<p>

<p>

<b>Hydraulics and Automation</b><p>

<p>

- Use of mechatronics in machines and equipment<p>

- Robotics<p>

- Automatic materials handling<p>

<a name="automation">
<h2>Courses Available in the Department of Automation Engineering</h2>
<a name="measurement">
<h2>Measurement and Information Technology</h2>

<p>

<b>75100  Thesis Seminar in Measurement Information <p>

          Technology</b>	<b>			1,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

	<p>

Prof. Olli Aumala, Assoc. prof. Jouko Halttunen<p>

Seminars 28 h. <p>

Takes place both fall and spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Aspects of preparing the Diploma thesis. Preparation of a paper and an oral
presentation. Seminars on ongoing thesis topics.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Accepted participation. Compulsory for those working on thesis in
Measurement Technology.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>75116 Measurement Technology			3,0  ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Olli Aumala<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 14 h, laboratory Exercises 14 h<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Design, execution and assessment of measurements. Methods of measurement and
measuring instruments. Digital measurements. Sensors. Analysis of measurement results.
Calibration and measurement service.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Laboratory exercises and final exam. The course 75116 (3 cu) is more
concise and intended to be taken by students in the program of Information Engineering.<p>

LITERATURE: Aumala: Mittaustekniikan perusteet. 3. painos. Otatieto 1994.<p>

<b><p>

<p>

75301  Processing</b> <b>of Measurement Information 		4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lic. Tech. Heikki Jokinen	<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 28 h. <p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Modelling of measurement systems. Performance criteria. Description of
measurement information. Origins of measurement errors and methods for correcting errors.
Introduction to systems for measurement signal processing.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE:  Aumala (et al.): Mittaussignaalien k&auml;sittely. Pressus 1995.<p>

NOTES: Preliminaries: 75310 Signal Analysis. The course may be supplemented with: 75802
Laboratory Course in Signal Analysis.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>75302 Parametric Signal Processing			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

M.Sc. Heli Sorsa<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 28 h<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Model-based methods and their application for signal analysis and processing, AR,
ARMA and adaptive models, neural and fuzzy models. Identification of models , spectral analysis,
prediction, simulation, and digital filtering. Theory and practical methods of computing.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Clarkson, P.M.: Optimal and Adaptive Signal Processing. CRC Press 1993.
Other text will be announced during lectures.<p>

NOTES: Preliminaries: 75310 Signal Analysis, 75301 Processing of Measurement Information,
73109 Matrix Calculus I, 80502 Basic Digital Signal Processing. The course may be
supplemented with 75802 Laboratory Course in Signal Analysis.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>75310 Signal Analysis				6,0 ECTS credits</b>  <p>

<p>

M.Sc. Juha Kortelainen<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h. Computing exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Fundamentals in signal processing: convolution, transforms, digital filtering.
Analysis of stochastic signals: distributions, correlation functions, spectra. Practical analysis of
measurements signals.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Aumala (et al.): Mittaussignaalien k&auml;sittely. Pressus 1995. <p>

Oppenheim &amp; Schafer: Discrete - Time Signal Processing, 1989. Bendat &amp; Piersol: Random Data:
Analysis and Measurement Procedures (second edition) Wiley 1986.<p>

NOTES: Preliminaries: 79120 Linear Systems. The course may be supplemented with: 73126
Stochastic Processes, 80502 Digital Filtering, 75301 Processing of Measurement Information.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>75400 Measurement of Industrial Processes		4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Olli Aumala<p>

Lectures and seminars 56 h.<p>

Takes place both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Application of measurement methods and sensors in industrial automation,
particularly in process automation. Applicability, installation matters, instrument construction.
Measurements for quality control. Writing a scientific paper, oral presentation, seminar.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Accepted seminar or final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Aumala O.: Teollisuusprosessien mittaukset. TTKK Opintomoniste 139, 1992.
Papers of the most recent seminar.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>75401 Sensors and Transducers			6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Jouko Halttunene<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 14 h, laboratory exercises 42 h<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Basic skills for the selection and application of sensors. Fundamentals of sensors.
Working principles and characteristics of the most common sensors and transducers.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes. Usher, M.J, Sensors and transducers, MacMillan Publishers Ltd.,
1985.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>75411 Advanced Topics in Sensor Technology		4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Jouko Halttunen<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 28 h<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Sensor fabrication technologies. Sensor materials. Semiconductor, thin and thick
film sensors. Interface between sensors and systems. Ultrasonics and optics in sensor technology.
Advanced topics in flow measurements.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes,Gardner, J.W.: Microsensors, John Wiley &amp; Sons, 1994.
Middelhoek, S., Audet, S.A.: Silicon Sensors, Academic Press,1989.<p>

NOTES: Recommended preliminaries: 72120 Microchip Fabrication, and 75401 Sensors and
Transducers.<p>

<p>

<b><p>

75500 Electrical Measurement Methods		6,0  ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Jouko Halttunen<p>

Lectures 28h, exercises 14h, laboratory Exercises 42 h<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Properties and use of electrical measurement methods and equipment in electrical
and non-electrical measurements. Measurement standards and calibration. Basic measurements.
Analog and digital methods and equipment. Measurement of low-level signals. Oscilloscope
measurements. Compensation and bridge measurements. Electrical interference and its reduction
methods. Recording instruments. Measurement systems and buses.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes.<p>

<b><p>

<p>

75600</b> <b>Project Engineering for Automation		4,5 ECTS credits </b><p>

<p>

Eng. Pekka Saloranta <p>

Design exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Basic methods in engineering of automation projects and their documentation.
Design and assembly of instrumentation applying modern automation systems. Preliminary design,
organised specification of the project, project management, basic design, purchasing, realisation of
the system, installation, start-up, training, guarantees. Design exercise.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes.<p>

NOTES: A closely related course: 76231 Industrial Control Components. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>75700 Advanced Topics in Measurement and Information Technology</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Olli Aumala, Assoc. Prof. Jouko Halttunen<p>

Lectures and seminars 56 h, exercises 28 h<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The course is intended for postgraduate studies with varying advanced topics.
Method of study and value in credit units will be specified individually for each topic.<p>

<p>

<b><p>

75710 Statistical Quality Design and Control</b> 		<b>6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

	<p>

Prof. Olli Aumala<p>

Lectures 5 h, computing exercises<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS:  A course intended for self-study. There is an introduction period of lectures at the
beginning of the fall term. Basic methods. Quality control of the manufacturing process. Design
and development of a robust product and a robust process. Case exercises.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: DeVor R. E., Chang T-h., Sutherland J.W.: Statistical Quality Design and
Control. New York 1992,Macmillan, 809 s.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>75801 Laboratory Course in Sensor Technology		3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Jouko Halttunen<p>

Laboratory Exercises 70 h<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Laboratory exercises in the use of measurement sensors. Transmitters, computer
buses, flow sensors and optical fibres.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Laboratory exercises and exam.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>75802 Laboratory Course in Signal Analysis		4,5 ECTS credits</b> <p>

<p>

Lic. Tech. Heikki Jokinen<p>

Laboratory Exercises 112 h<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Laboratory exercises for signal analysis and processing of measurement
information. Different tasks of digital signal processing.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Laboratory exercises and exam.<p>

NOTES: Preliminaries: 75301 Processing of Measurement Information, 75302 Parametric Signal
Processing, 75310 Signal Analysis.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>75803 Project Study in Measurement and Information <p>

         Technology 				3,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Lic. Tech. Esa Luntta<p>

Laboratory Exercises 56 h. <p>

Takes place during fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Individual project work on some topic of measurement and information technology.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Reported project work.  <p>

<p>

<p>

<a name="control">
<h2>Automation and Control Engineering</h2>

<p>

<b>76140 M.Sc. Thesis Seminar in Control 		1,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Prof Pentti Lautala, Prof. N. N<p>

Seminars 28 h. <p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The seminar is intended for M.Sc. thesis workers (obligatory to them) in order to
develop their oral and written presentation and to enhance their understanding of research
approaches and methods. The thesis workers give presentations to each other about their own
completed research. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Each worker must participate the sessions of the seminar during a semester.
Personal guidance is given. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76182 Laboratory Course in Control 		4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Ass. Pekka Pietil&auml;	<p>

Laboratory exercises 63 h.<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Laboratory exercises covering different areas of automatic control. The exercises
are done in groups of four persons.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Active participation together with carefully written pre-lab or post-lab
reports. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76183 Special Assignment in Control Engineering	1,5 ECTS credits<p>

<p>

</b>Ass. Pekka Pietil&auml;<p>

Laboratory exercises 21 h.<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: A personal wide enough and relevant task from any subarea of control engineering.
The participant is encouraged to make a proposal. Both hardware and software problems come
into question. The software problems may be associated with numerical algorithms for computer
aided design, practical implementation of advanced algorithms, or user interfaces.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The engineering work selected with a good written documentation. In
software problems the documentation also includes the commented source codes. The laboratory
is entitled to use the material and the codes in its courses.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76231 Automation Components			3,0 ECTS credits 	</b><p>

<p>

Ass. Pekka Pietil&auml;<p>

Lectures 28 h. Laboratory and tutorial hours 7 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Structure, operation, and characteristics of the most important industrial controllers
and control stations. Realization of controllers. Sensors, transducers, actuators, control valves,
pumps etc.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination. Laboratory works with good reports.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76240 Graduate Seminar in Control Theory  (*)<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Pentti Lautala<p>

Lectures 56 h, tutorials 28 h.<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The seminar is intended for graduate students pursuing their Lic. Tech. or Dr.Tech.
degrees, and belong to their Lic. or Dr. studies. Topics change yearly and consist of newest books
in control theory.<p>

REQUIREMENTS:Varies from time to time.Will be announced shortly before the the seminar.<p>

(*) The credit points depend on the literature.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76260 Digital Control 				4,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Pentti Lautala<p>

Lectures 28 h, tutorials including PC-exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Digital controller design. Sampling theory. DDC-algorithms. Applications.<p>

LITERATURE: K. J &Aring;str&ouml;m and B. Wittenmark : "Computer Controlles Systems", Prentice-Hall
1990, Chapters 1-9<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination. NOTE: Prior knowledge 76400<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76270 Robots Mathematics and Control		4,5 ECTS credits			</b><p>

<p>

M.Sc. Jarmo Sorvari<p>

Lectures 28 h, laboratory exercises and tutorials 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Principles, mathematical models, control and simulation of industrial robots.<p>

Analysis and compensation of non-linear dynamics. Basics of pattern recognition. Programming of
robots. The computer exercises are very important!<p>

LITERATURE: J. Craig : "Introduction to Robotics", 2nd edition. Scientific papers. Another
material will be possible and will be announced before the course.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination<p>

NOTE: prior knowledge 26271 Robotics and Teleperation, 73109 Matrix Calculus 1 and
MATLAB/SIMULINK -program<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76290 Graduate Seminar in Automation Technology (*)<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Pentti Lautala, senior assistants<p>

Lectures 56 h, tutorials 28 h.<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The seminar is intended for graduate students pursuing their Lic. Tech. or Dr. 	Tech. degrees, and belong to their Lic. or Dr. studies. Topics change yearly and consist of newest
books in control and automation theory.<p>

REQUIREMENTS:Varies from time to time.Will be announced before the the seminar.<p>

(*) The credit points depend on the book.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76331 Automation and</b> <b>Control and Technology 		6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Senior assistant Terho Jussila<p>

Lectures 28 h, laboratory exercises and tutorials 42 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The purpose is to lay foundation for understanding basic control ideas and analysis
as well as design methods. Importance of control in dynamical systems. Basics of linear control
systems. Examples of technical and other control systems. Basics of computer control. <p>

LITERATURE: R. Dorf : "Modern Control Systems", 7th edition, 1995.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination, a laboratory work and 3 PC exercises.<p>

NOTE: prior knowledge Basic courses of Mathematics, 76110.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76370 System Identification			4,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Lecturer Jukka Lieslehto <p>

Lectures 28 h, computer exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Identification principles. Prediction error methods. Nonparametric time- and 	frequency-domain methods. Recursive identification. Model structure selection and 	model validation. System identification in practice.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A Computer Examination with Matlab and System Identification Toolbox.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76380 Adaptive Control 			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Senior Ass. Terho Jussila <p>

Lectures 28 h, tutorials including PC-exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Principles of recursive identification and adaptive control, especially self-tuning
control, including multivariable systems. Numerical methods for reliable implementations.<p>

LITERATURE: &Aring;str&ouml;m and Wittenmark : "Adaptive Control", Addison-Wesley 1995.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination<p>

PRIOR KNOWLEDGE: 76260, 76470, (76370)<p>

NOTE: Will be lectured every second year, next time 1997.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76400 Controller Design			6,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Pentti Lautala<p>

28 lecture hours, 56 laboratory and tutorial hours<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Classical design methods for linear and nonlinear systems.  Introduction to
state-space techniques, especially for linear systems. Internal model control.<p>

LITERATURE: R. Dorf : "Modern Control Systems", 7th edition, 1995.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination, laboratory works.<p>

NOTE: Prior knowledge: 76331<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76410 Multivariable Control 			4,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Senior Ass. Terho Jussila <p>

28 lecture hours, 21 tutorial and PC-based exercise hours.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Optimal control theory. Basics of deterministic estimation and identification theory.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination, personal exercises.<p>

NOTE: Prior knowledge: 76331, 76400, 76260<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76420 Stochastic Control	 		4,5 ECTS credits			<p>

</b><p>

Senior Ass. Terho Jussila <p>

28 lecture hours, 21 tutorial and PC-based exercise hours.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Basics of stochastic estimation and identification theory.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76430 Advanced Multivariable control 		7,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Senior Ass. Terho Jussila <p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Predictive multivariable control. Output feedback. Frequency domain analyzing and
design methods.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination, personal exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: Maciejowski: Multivariable Feedback Design. 1981.<p>

PRIOR KNOWLEDGE: 76410, 76420, 73112<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76450 Modelling and Simulation  			4,5 ECTS credits <p>

</b><p>

Senior Ass. Jukka Lieslehto<p>

28 lecture hours, 28 computer exercise hours.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Modeling principles. Physical models. Identification principles. Simultation of
dynamical systems.<p>

LITERATURE: Ljung: Modeling of dynamical systems. 1994<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination or a computer examination<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76470 Advanced Digital Control 			4,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Senior Ass. Terho Jussila<p>

28 lecture hours, 28 tutorial and computer exercise hours.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Design of discrete time controllers using both state space and transfer function
methods, including numerical optimization of the controller tuning. Introduction to system
identification. Introduction to multivariable control. Numerical methods for estimation and
control.<p>

LITERATURE:K.J &Aring;str&ouml;m and B.Wittenmark:"Computer Controlles Systems", Prentice-Hall
1990, Chapters 10-15.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination or computer examination<p>

PRIOR KNOWLEDGE: 76260<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76490 Automation Systems	 		4,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Contact person: Senior Ass. Terho Jussila <p>

28 lecture hours, 28 seminar, laboratory and tutorial hours.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS:Structure, programming, and interfacing of real time computer-systems.  Operating
systems. Industrial applications of computer systems for process control.  Distributed
microprocessor based automation systems.<p>

LITERATURE: Bennett:"Real-time computer control introduction", Prentice-Hall 1988.
Pimentel:"Communication networks for manufacturing", Prentice-Hall 1990<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination and labworks.<p>

PRIOR KNOWLEDGE : 76331, 76260<b><p>

<p>

<p>

76500 Learning and Intelligent Control 		4,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Senior Ass. Jukka Lieslehto<p>

28 lecture hours, 28 computer exercise hours.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Experts systems. Fuzzy control. Neural networks. Fault diagnosis. Real-time expert
systems. Automatic tuning of controllers. Expert systems for control system design.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture material<p>

REQUIREMENTS:Passing: Personal exercises<p>

PRIOR KNOWLEDGE:76331, 76260<p>

NOTE: Will be lectured every second year, next time 1996.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76505 Fundamentals of Neural Nets and Fuzzy Computing 	4,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Contact person: Ass. Hannu Koivisto<p>

28 lecture hours, 28 tutorial hours.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS:Basics of neural computing and fuzzy logigs. Perceptron- and radial base networks,
the self-organizing map and associative memories. Applications of neural computing. Fuzzy logic,
fuzzy control and decision. The computer exercises are very important!<p>

LITERATURE:Freeman and Skapura:"Neural Networks-Algorithms, Applications and
Programming Techniques", Addison-Wesley, 1991. Lecture material<p>

REQUIREMENTS:A written examination and personal exercises.<p>

PRIOR KNOWLEDGE:Basic Courses of Mathematics and 73112. Optimization Theory 1, 73112
is not necessary but is strongly recommended<p>

<p>

<b>76540 Process Dynamics 			4,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Pentti Lautala<p>

28 lecture hours, 56 laboratory hours.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS:Modelling and analysis of basic unit processes found in process industry. Basic
control principles used in industry.Goals and problems. Simulation programs.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination and labworks.<p>

PRIOR KNOWLEDGE: 76331, 76400<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>76550 Industrial Applications of Control 		6,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Pentti Lautala<p>

28 lecture hours, 56 seminar, laboratory and tutorial hours.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS:The overall design of instrumentation and control system in industry.Advanced
methods in process control.Examples from process industry, especially from pulp and paper
industry and power plants.<p>

LITERATURE:Kehittyneiden s&auml;&auml;t&ouml;menetelmien k&auml;ytt&ouml; prosessiteollisuudessa, SAS 1992.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written examination, labworks and an oral seminar presentation.<p>

PRIOR KNOWLEDGE:76331, 76400, 76540<p>

<p>
<a name="hydraulics">
<h2>Hydraulics and Automation</h2>

<p>

<p>

<b>26111  Pumping Engineering			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Jari Rinkinen	<p>

Lectures 28 h,  Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE:  Understanding basics and the use of positive displacement pumps and centrifugal
pumps.<p>

CONTENTS: The basic theory of pump types in oil and water hydraulics. Theory and construction of pumps. Selection and applying pumps to different type of use. <p>

REQUIREMENTS:  Approved exercises and examination of the lecture material and exercises.<p>

REQUIRED READING:  Copies of lecture material, and selected parts of book: Allan Wirzenius,
Keskipakopumput.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>26121  Oil Hydraulic Engineering I			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Jari Rinkinen	<p>

Lectures 28 h,  Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The most essential knowledge of computation methods in hydraulics and control
theory. Computation method applying in oil hydraulic component and system design. <p>

CONTENTS: Theory and construction of oil hydraulic components for example: valves and
actuators. Design of hydraulic systems. Basics to design hydraulic servo systems. Cases in
industry and mobile hydraulics.  <p>

REQUIREMENTS:  Approved exercises and examination of the lecture material and exercises.<p>

REQUIRED READING:  Copies of lecture material.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>26131  Oil Hydraulic Engineering II			6.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Jari Rinkinen<p>

Lectures and seminars 42 h. Exercises 70 h.<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Understanding the static and dynamic behaviour of hydraulic components. Understanding the design of components and systems of massive and high power hydraulic systems.<p>

CONTENTS: CAE in the design of hydraulic components and systems. Components of high
power hydraulics. Hydraulic generator drives. Secondary control of hydraulic systems. Noise
problems in hydraulic systems. Applications from offshore, ship and press systems etc.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and examination on the material.<p>

REQUIRED READING: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>26141  Mobile Hydraulics			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Matti Vilenius	<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Understanding the construction and usage of mobile hydraulic components. Readiness to design mobile hydraulic systems. <p>

CONTENTS: The special features of mobile hydraulics. The hydraulic realization of working
movements, vehicle steering, wheel drives etc. Applications from transport, roadservice and forest
machines etc.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and examination on the material.<p>

REQUIRED READING: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>26151  Electrohydraulic Servo Systems         		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Matti Vilenius<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Readiness to apply control theory to electrohydraulic servo systems. Understanding
the behaviour of servo hydraulic components. Readiness to design, use and examine electrohydraulic servo systems.<p>

CONTENTS: Electrohydraulic servo valves. Transducers, amplifiers etc. electronic components.
The design of analog and digital systems. The static and dynamic behaviour of servo systems.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and examination on the material.<p>

REQUIRED READING: Walters R.B., Hydraulic and electrohydraulic control systems.<p>

<p>

<b>26161  Special Topics in Oil Hydraulic Engineering	4.5 ECTS credits</b>	<p>

<p>

Prof. Matti Vilenius<p>

Lectures and seminars 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE:  To give more hydraulic theory and give ability to apply knowledge in practical
cases.<p>

CONTENTS:  Special topics of hydraulic components. Basics of component modelling and
simulation. CAE in oil hydraulic engineering. Exercises with the simulation program SIMU.<p>

REQUIREMENTS:  Approved exercises and examination of the lecture material and seminar
material.<p>

REQUIRED READING:  Copies of lecture material.<p>

<p>

<b>26171  Licentiate Course in Oil Hydraulic Engineering 	4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Matti Vilenius<p>

Seminars 28 h. Exercises 28 h<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE and CONTENTS: This course is mainly meant for Post Graduate students.<p>

CONTENTS: Contents change yearly.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Requirements shall be told in the beginning of the course.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>26182  Environmentally Friendly Hydraulics		3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

	<p>

Lic.tech. Kari Koskinen<p>

Lectures 14 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To give an overall picture of applying environmental friendly concepts in fluid
power technology.<p>

CONTENTS: Use of environmentally friendly hydraulic fluids. Water-based hydraulic fluids.
Energy saving concepts in fluid power. Consideration of environmental load in design of fluid
power systems. Applications.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Project works and final examination of the lectures and exercises.<p>

REQUIRED READING: Lecture notes and other literature specified during the lectures.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>26186  Water Hydraulics       			3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

	<p>

Lic.tech. Kari Koskinen<p>

Lectures 14 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To give basic information of theory of water hydraulics, water hydraulic
components and systems, and application of water hydraulic technology on design of hydraulic
machines.<p>

CONTENTS: Basic theory of water hydraulics. Water hydraulic components. Design of water
hydraulic systems. Proportional and servo systems in water hydraulics. Applications.<p>

REQUIREMENTS:Project works and final examination of the lectures and exercises<p>

REQUIRED READING: Lecture notes and other literature specified during the lectures.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>26191  Hydraulics, Special Assignment         		6.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Matti Vilenius	<p>

Assoc. prof. Jari Rinkinen	<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Learn to solve problems in the field of research and design.<p>

CONTENTS: A research or product development assignment from the professional subject area.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercise.<p>

<p>

<b>26212  Control of Drives				4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Tapio Virvalo	<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Give the skill to select control systems for hydraulic, pneumatic and electric drives.<p>

CONTENTS: Dimensioning and selection of hydraulic, pneumatic and electro mechanical
actuators. Selection of mechanical transmission system, in control systems used sensors and
electric driver and controller.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and examination on the material.<p>

REQUIRED READING: To be informed during the course.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>26231  Pneumatics     		         		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Senior ass. Esa M&auml;kinen<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Understanding the design and selection principles for pneumatic drive and control
systems. Readiness to apply pneumatics to machine automation.<p>

CONTENTS: Pneumatic components. Designing pneumatic systems. Electric and pneumatic
control of pneumatic drives.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and examination on the material.<p>

REQUIRED READING: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>26242  Servo Drives				4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Tapio Virvalo	<p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Give the skill to design and dimension hydraulic, pneumatic and electro mechanical
servo drives.<p>

CONTENTS: Dimensioning and selection of hydraulic, pneumatic and electro mechanical
actuators in scope of control engineering. Analog and digital servo control. Profile generation of
movement. Interpolation. Realization of control algorithms. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and examination on the material.<p>

REQUIRED READING: To be informed during the course.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>26262  Special Topics in Mechatronics         		6.0 - 9.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Tapio Virvalo and prof. Markku Kivikoski<p>

Lectures, seminars, teamwork and exercises total 112 h<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Adoption of mechatronic way of thinking and realization in embedded systems and
applications in machine automation.<p>

CONTENTS: Different mechatronic design and realization tasks in areas of embedded systems
and machine automation. There is an emphasis in exercises in which the knowing range of
students will be extended over boundaries of departments.  An unit will be composed of a courses
of two terms which will be carried out in co-operation with the Institute of Electronics and the
Institute of Hydraulics and Automation.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Participating in lectures, approved examination, seminars, teamwork and
exercises<p>

RECOMMENDED PRELIMINARY KNOWLEDGE: At least one module given by institute of
Electronics and/or Hydraulics and Automation<p>

NOTES: An approvable unit includes courses 74462 Special Topics in Mechatronics (fall term)
and 26262 Special Topics in Mechatronics (spring term) both together. Amount of credits will be
determinated by the extent of the teamwork. The course can also be part of post-graduate studies.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>26281  Licentiate Course in Machine Automation   		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Reijo Tuokko<p>

Seminars 28 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: This course is intended for post-graduate students in hydraulics
and automation. Topics are selected annually.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: To be informed when the course starts.<p>

REQUIRED READING: To be informed when the course starts.<p>

<p>

