<a name="etcs">
<h2>The ECTS Departmental Coordinator</h2>
<b>Pirjo Kuhanen</b><br>

Tampere University of Technology, <br>
The Department of Materials Engineering<br>
Korkeakoulunkatu 2<br>
P.O.Box 589, SF-33101 Tampere, Finland<br>
Tel: 358-31-3162325, Fax: 358-31-3162330<br>

<a name="desc">
<H2>Description of the Department of Materials Engineering</H2>

The Department of Materials Science is founded on the 1st of August,
1993 and it consists of five institutes: Materials Science, Chemistry,
Electron Microscopy, Plastic Technology and Fibre, Textile and
Clothing Science. At present the amount of teaching staff is 19 (8
professors and associate professors, 7 assistants and 4 lecturers) and
the amount of students 370.

<a name="description">
<H2>Description of the Institutes and Laboratories and Their Activities</H2>

<H4>Materials Science</H4>

The development of new materials and applications of modern materials
engineering, in cooperation with industry, underpins activities in the
Institute of Materials Science. The Institute has many active research
fields such as mechanical alloying, ceramic materials, coatings and
coating techniques, high temperature superconductors, ceramic filters
and membranes etc. Generally the four main fileds are represented in
the Institute: physical metallurgy, process metallurgy, ceramic
materials and new materials. The research is mainly based on the
cooperation with the industry and from the beginning the Institute has
been the largest unit in TUT engaging in contract research. The
Institute is presently involved also in several international research
projects belonging to the COST- and BRITE/EURAM-programme.<p>

The student exchange is increased since 1990 and at the present the
Institute offers almost all the courses also in English. The students
have different possibilities to study in the Institute: participate in
projects, take courses or do the Master of Science-degree after B.Sc.
The most popular is the one year visiting status in which the student
participate in courses or in a project.

<H4>Chemistry</H4>

The Institute of Materials Chemistry is responsible for basic teaching
in chemistry on all degree programs of the University and conducts
commissioned research both inside and outside the University. Research
in the immediate future will focus on investigations of the molecular
properties of materials with a view to elucidating the cooperative
functions of naturally occurring and synthetic molecules, which will
be modified to desired form. A particular subject of research will be
the organized molecular films of organic and bioorganic compounds
which form sensor system, transmit energy or a charge and which could
be utilized e.g. for information storage or processing. Since the
central focus of research here is on phenomena caused by light, the
research could be termed supramolecular photochemistry which is
closely coupled to electronics.

<H4>Electron Microscopy</H4>

The Centre for Electron Microscopy is a institute specializing in
cross-disciplinary materials characterization and failure analysis; it
is responsible for professional , post-graduate studies, and
continuing education in these areas. The Centre has at its disposal
versaitile electron-optical equipment which makes possible e.g., the
chemical analysis of very small areas and characterization of
materials even at atomic level. The Centre is in close research
cooperation not only with the different Institutes at TUT but also
with other research institutes in Finland and abroad as well as with
industry.<p>

<H4>Plastics Technology</H4>

Teaching centres round the structure and techniques of manufacturing
polymer materials (plastics, rubbers, and plastic composites). The
Institute boasts the greatest number of publications and patents at
the University. The four words best describing the materials research
which ranges from the molecular level to applications are: structure,
processing, properities, and utilization.<p>

The Institute's internationally best known area is biodegradable
surgical products. The polymers which dissolve in the living body
developed by proferssor T&ouml;rm&auml;l&auml;'s research group are
already bywords under the name of Biofix amongst both surgeons and
patients.<p>

The ceramic core material used in the manufacture of hollow products
is an example of composite and multilayer structures which are
expanding the application areas of materials.<p>

<H4>Fiber, Textile, and Clothing Science</H4>

The Institute of Fiber, Textile, and Clothing Science has expertise in
fiber raw materials from polymers to fibers as well as in the
manufacture of finished textile products and controlling process.
Research plays an important role in the function on the Institute,
subjects of research are e.g. biotechnology in fiber and textile
treatment and surface chemistry phenomena. The Institute has carried
out research on the laundering of fabrics for jeans. Stone washing can
be replaced by cellulase enzyme treatment, which does not harm washing
machines.<p>

Dyeing and other chemical treatments and the control of static
electricity are textile and surface-chemistry phenomena that the
Institute has studied. The Institute has also worked on the recycling
and practical applications of textile waste. Recycled materials made
from textile waste are used e.g. as base mats under parquet and as
cleaning cloths.<p>

<a name="study">
<H2>Study Options Available in the Department of Materials Engineering</H2>

<H4>Fiber, Textile and Clothing Science</H4>

- Mechanical textile engineering <p>

- Fiber and chemical textile engineering<p>

- Garment and shoe technology<p>

- Fur and leather technology<p>

<H4>Materials Science</H4>

- Physical Metallurgy<p>

- Process Metallurgy<p>

- Ceramic Materials <p>

- New Materials<p>

<H4>Chemistry</H4>

- Basic studies in chemistry<p>

<H4>Plastic Technology</H4>

- polymers, plastics and rubbers and fabrication of plastics and composites

<H4>Electron Microscopy</H4>

- electron microscopy, x-ray techniques, NDT-techniques<p>

- characterization of materials<p>

- failure analysis<p>

<a name="course">
<H2>Courses Available in English in the Department of Materials Engineering</H2>

Usually all the lectures, seminars and exercises are given in Finnish,
but there are some courses given in English. <p>

All the credit units are given in the ECTS credit system.<p>

<a name="materials">
<H2>Courses on Materials Science</H2>

Most of the courses on Materials Science are given in English and in
Finnish. English and Finnish courses have different code number, but
they are actually the same courses. <p>

Following courses are given in English:<p>

<B>28124 Physical Metallurgy I    3,5 ECTS credits </B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tuomo Tiainen<p>
Lectures 21 h. Exercises  7 h.<p>
Given during fall term<p>
Lectures in Finnish, but literature in English.<p>
Examinations in English will be arranged<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to the background of the properties and
property of evolution of ferrous and non-ferrous metals.<p>

CONTENTS: Thermodynamics of phase transformations in metal alloys.
Equilibrium diagrams. Diffusional and diffusionless phase
transformations. Precipitation and precipitation hardening.
Fundamentals of heat treatments.<p>

<B>28126 Engineering Alloys I  3,5 credits</B><p>
Assoc. prof. Tuomo Tiainen<p>
Lectures 21 h, exercises 7 h. <p>
Given during fall term<p>
Lectures in Finnish, but literature in English.<p>
Examinations in English will be arranged<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to the properties, behaviour and
applications of ferrous and some non-ferrous metals and alloys.<p>

CONTENTS: Steel types, cast irons, other engineering alloys viewed. <p>

<B>28128 Laboratory Exercises on Metallography 1,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tuomo Tiainen<p>
Seminars 4 h, laboratory exercises 20 h. <p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to metallographic procedures and mechanical
testing.<p>

CONTENTS: Metallographic specimen preparation, light microscopy, photography, photograph interpretation, fundamentals of mechanical testing. <p>

<B>28132 Physical Metallurgy II 6,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tuomo Tiainen<p>
Lectures 42 h. Exercises 14 h<p>
Given during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to the crystal structure of metals and its
behaviour under external stress.<p>

CONTENTS: Sturucture and mechanical behavior of metals. Recovery and
recrystallization of mechanically worked structure. Fatigue, creep,
facture phenomena, wear. Tecting methods. <p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes.<p>

<B>28174 Physical Metallurgy III  4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pentti Kettunen<p>
Lectures 28 h, exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed insight in the background of the strength of metals<p>

CONTENTS: Elastic and plastic deformation. Dislocations in plastic
deformation. The thermal and athermal processes limiting plastic
deformation. Dislocation velocity and its measurement. Influence of
deformation rate on mechanical properties. <p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes available.<p>

<B>28204 Physical Metallurgy IV	3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lecturer Erkki It&auml;vuori<p>
Lectures 14 h, exercises  7 h.<p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed insight in the mechanisms of structural and
strength evolution in hardening and strain ageing.<p>

CONTENTS: Strengthening of metals. Martensite transformation, strain
ageing, rapid solidification techniques. <p>

<B>28206 Engineering Alloys II 	 3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lecturer Erkki It&auml;vuori<p>
Lectures 14 h, seminar exercises 7 h. <p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to speciality steel application and development.<p>

CONTENTS: High strength and extra high strength steels, special
treatments. History of steels, steel development and future prospects.
<p>

<B>28212 Physical Metallurgy V 4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pentti Kettunen<p>
Lectures 28 h, seminar exercises 14 h. <p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed insight in the mechanisms and processes
controlling the strength of metals.<p>

CONTENTS: Monotonic and cyclic strain hardening. Fatigue. Creep and
high temperature mechanical properties. Fracture physics. Modern
materials testing methods. <p>

LITERATURE: Lecture notes available.<p>

<B>28232 Corrosion Phenomena 	3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lic.Tech. Pekka Siitonen<p>
Lectures 21 h. Exercises 7 h <p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to the background, mechanisms and
identification of corrosion processes.<p>

CONTENTS:Electrochemical corrosion: reasons, mechanisms and
influencing factors. Oxidation and oxidation resistance. <p>

LITERATURE: M.G. Fontana: Corrosion Engineering, McGraw-Hill 1986.
J.M. West: Basic Corrosion and Oxidation, John Wiley &amp; Sons,
1986.<p>

<B>28236 Prevention of Corrosion  3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lic. Tech. Pekka Siitonen<p>
Lectures 21 h, seminar exercises 7 h.<p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to corrosion and corrosion resistance of
metals and alloys, and to the background and methods of corrosion
protection.<p>

CONTENTS: prerequisitates for corrosion protection, corrosion
resistance of engineering materials, methods for corrosion protection,
corrosion protection in design. <p>

LITERATURE: M.G. Fontana: Corrosion Engineering, McGraw-Hill 1986. <p>

<B>28273 Annual Course on a Current Theme 3,0 ECTS credits</B><br>
Finnish and foreign lecturers: invited<p>

Lectures 20 h. Seminars 20 h. <p>
Given during spring term<p>

CONTENTS: Topics selected form current research and development
activities in the field of Materials Science. <p>

<B>28472 Introduction to Composites  3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pentti Kettunen<p>
Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during spring term <p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to composite constructions and mechanics of
composites.<p>

CONTENTS: Fibre reinforcing. Factors influencing on mechanical
properties of composites. Evaluation of the stregth of composite
structures. <p>

<B>28494 Polymeric Materials I  3,0 ECTS credits</B><br>
(only in English)<p>

Prof. Pentti Kettunen<p>
Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during fall term <p>

OBJECTIVE: A survey on the chemistry and physics of polymers.<p>

CONTENTS: Polymerization reactions, microstructure of polymers,
mechanical properties, deformation, long-term strength properties,
fatigue of polymers. <p>

<B>28574 Polymeric Materials II   3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pentti Kettunen<p>
Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during spring term <p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed introduction to the polymer properties, their
background and utilization in advanced polymers.<p>

CONTENTS: Polymer blends, Specialty polymers, Degradation and reuse of
polymers. <p>

<B>28654 Ceramics and Glasses  3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tapio M&auml;ntyl&auml;<p>
Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during fall term<p>

CONTENTS: Structures of ceramics and glasses, polymorphism, glass
ceramics, structural imperfections, surfaces and surface properties,
ceramic phase-equilibrium diagrams, one component phase diagrams,
multi-component phase diagrams, metastable phases, development of
microstructure.<p>

<B>28656 Ceramic materials  3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tapio M&auml;ntyl&auml;<p>
Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during spring term<p>

CONTENTS: Mechanical properties of ceramics; elastic constants,
strength, measurements of strength, fracture toughness, fatinque,
creep, and stress corrosion. Electrical, magnetic, thermal and optical
properties of ceramics.<p>

<B>28662 Processing of Ceramics  4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tapio M&auml;ntyl&auml;<p>
Lectures 28 h, exercises 14 h.	<p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed insight in the practical properties, processing
and testing of ceramics.<p>

CONTENTS: Fabrication techniques for ceramics. Influence of
fabrication control on properties of ceramics. Mechanical, thermal and
chemical testing.<p>

LITERATURE: Richerson: Modern Ceramic Engineering, Marcel Dekker Inc.
1992.<p>

<B>28682 Engineering Ceramics  4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tapio M&auml;ntyl&auml;<p>
Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during fall term <p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to the properties and applications of
ceramics.<p>

CONTENTS: Engineering ceramic materials. Design with ceramics.
Machining and joining. Quality assurance and NDT. Examples of
applications. <p>

LITERATURE: Richerson: Modern Ceramic Engineering, Marcel Dekker Inc.
1992.<p>

<B>28692 Coatings  4,5 ECTS credits </B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tapio M&auml;ntyl&auml;<p>
Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during fall term. Examinations during both terms.<p>
Lectures in Finnish, but literature in English.<p>
Examinations in English will be arranged<p>

OBJECTIVE: A survey on conventional and modern metal and non-metal
coatings and coating processes.<p>

CONTENTS: Applications of coatings. Coating and film preparation
methods. Properties of coatings. Testing.<p>

<B>28873 Special Treatise on Materials Science 4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pentti Kettunen, Assoc. prof. Tuomo <p>
Tiainen and Assoc. prof. Tapio M&auml;ntyl&auml;<p>
Exercises 56 h.<p>
Given during both fall and spring terms<p>

CONTENTS: Personal treatise on a restricted subject on materials
science.<p>

<B>28874 Special Treatise II 4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

CONTENTS: Personal treatise on a restricted subject on material
sciense or related studies. <p>

<a name="microscopy">
<H2>Courses on Electron Microscopy</H2>

<B>20110 Crystallography  1,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 10 h, exercises 10 h.<p>
Given during fall term <p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to fundamentals and practical applications
of crystallography.<p>

CONTENTS: Crystal structures, determination of crystallographic planes
and directions, symmetries, methods for crystal structure
determination, stereographic projection, practical applications. <p>

LITERATURE: C. Hammond: Introduction to Crystallography, Royal
Microscopical Society, Oxford Sci. Publ. 1992.<p>

<B>20210 Electron Microscopy I  3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 21 h, exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed introduction to the theory and practice of
scanning electron microscopy and microanalysis.<p>

CONTENTS: Scanning electron microscopy, operation, image and contrast
formation, specimen preparation. Microanalyzing with EDS and WDS,
correction calculations, computer programs, image analysis, practical
applications.<p>

LITERATURE: Murr: Electron Optical Applications in Materials Science,
McGraw-Hill 1970. Goldstein et al: Scanning Electron Microscopy and
X-ray Microanalysis, Plenum Press 1981. Reimer: Scanning Electron
Microscopy, Springer-Verlag 1985.<p>

<B>20230 Electron Microscopy II  3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 21 h, exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed introduction to the theoryand practice of
transmission electron microscopy.<p>

CONTENTS: Transmission electron microscopy, operation, contrast
formation, electron diffraction, elemental analysis (EDS), detection
of light elements (PEELS) and examples of practical applications.
Specimen preparation techniques. Other electron optical
instruments.<p>

LITERATURE: Edington: Monographs and Practical Electron Microscopy in
Materials Science, the Macmillan Press ltd. 1975.<p>

<B>20310 X-ray Techniques  3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 24 h, seminar and laboratory ecercises 20 h. <p>
Given during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed introduction to the theory and practice of X-ray
techniques in materials science.<p>

CONTENTS: X-ray radiation, interactions with materials,
diffractometry, determination of orientation, fluorescense,
transmission photography, small-angle scattering and other
applications. <p>

LITERATURE: Cullity: Elements of X-ray Diffraction, Addison- Wesley
1978.<p>

<B>20330 Introduction to NDT Techniques 1,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 10 h. Exercises 10 h. <p>
Given during fall term<p>

CONTENTS: Radiography, ultrasonic testing, acoustic emission, Eddy
current testing, liquid penetrant inspection, magnetic inspection,
thermal inspection. Practical examples of industrials applications of
NDT techniques.<p>

<B>20350 Research Methods in Materials Science  3,0 ECTS credits </B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 18 h, exercises 12 h.<p>
Given during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A survey of the physical research methods applied in
materials science.<p>

CONTENTS: Mossbauer spectroscopy, positron annihilation, neutron
diffraction, mass spectroscopy.<p>

<B>20510 Powder Metallurgy  3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A survey on the techniques and applications of powder
metallurgy. <p>

CONTENTS: Production of metal powders, characterization and testing,
consolidation of powders, powder alloy systems, properties and
applications. <p>

LITERATURE: R.M. German: Powder Metallurgy Science, Metal Powder
Industries Federation, Princeton, New Jersey 1984.<p>

<a name="coursefin">
<H2>Courses Available in Finnish in the Department of Materials Engineering</h2>

<a name="materialsfin">
<H2>Materials Science</H2>

<B>28123 Physical Metallurgy I 	3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tuomo Tiainen<p>
Lectures 21 h. Exercises 7 h.<p>
Given during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to the background of the properties and
property of evolution of ferrous and non-ferrous metals.<p>

CONTENTS: Thermodynamics of phase transformations in metal alloys.
Equilibrium diagrams. Diffusional and diffusionless phase
transformations. Precipitation and precipitation hardening.
Fundamentals of heat treatments.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written examination of the contents of the
course. <p>

LITERATURE: Lindroos, Sulonen, Veistinen: Uudistettu Miekkojan
metallioppi, Otava 1986 (when applicable). Copies of lecture material.
P. Kettunen: Metallioppi 3, Lecture material of TUT nro 78, Tampere
1982.<p>

<B>28125 Engineering Alloys I 3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tuomo Tiainen<p>
Lectures 21 h, seminar Exercises 7 h. <p>
Given during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to the properties, behaviour and
applications of ferrous and some non-ferrous metals and alloys.<p>

CONTENTS: Steel types, cast irons, other engineering alloys viewed.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written examination of the contents of the
course. <p>

LITERATURE: Lindroos, Sulonen, Veistinen: Uudistettu Miekkojan
metallioppi, Otava 1986 (when applicable). <p>

<B>28127 Laboratory Exercises on Metallography	1,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tuomo Tiainen<p>
Seminars 4 h, laboratory exercises 20 h. <p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to metallographic procedures and mechanical
testing.<p>

CONTENTS: Metallographic specimen preparation, light microscopy,
photography, photograph interpretation, fundamentals of mechanical
testing. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises. Participation in lectures.<p>

<B>28130 Physical Metallurgy II 6,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof. Tuomo Tiainen<p>
Lectures 42 h. Seminar Exercises 14 h.<p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to the crystal structure of metals and its
behaviour under external stress.<p>

CONTENTS: Structure and mechanical behavior of metals. Recovery and
recrystallization of mechanically worked structure. Fatigue, creep,
fracture phenomena, wear. Testing methods. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written examination of the contents of the
course. <p>

LITERATURE: P. Kettunen ja T. Tiainen: Metallioppi 1, Metallien
plastinen muodonmuutos ja lujuusominaisuudet, TTKK:n opintomoniste nro
9, Tampere 1981. Pentti Kettunen ja Reijo Ahlroth: <p>

Metallioppi 1, Metalliopin perusteet, TTKK:n opintomoniste nro 73,
Tampere 1981 (when applicable). M.F. Ashby and D.R.H. Jones:
Engineering Materials, An Introduction to their Properties and
Applications, Pergamon Press, Oxford, 1980 (when applicable).<p>

<B>28173 Physical Metallurgy III  4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pentti Kettunen<p>
Lectures 28 h. Seminar Exercises 14 h.  <p>
Given during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed insight in the background of the strength of
metals<p>

CONTENTS: Elastic and plastic deformation. Dislocations in plastic
deformation. The thermal and athermal processes limiting plastic
deformation. Dislocation velocity and its measurement. Influence of
deformation rate on mechanical properties. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written examination of the contents of the
course and approved seminar exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: P. Kettunen: Metallioppi III.<p>

<B>28203 Physical Metallurgy IV 3,0 ECTS credits </B><p>

Lecturer Erkki It&auml;vuori<p>
Lectures 14 h. Seminar Exercises 7 h.<p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed insight in the mechanisms of structural and
strength evolution in hardening and strain ageing.<p>

CONTENTS: Strengthening of metals. Martensite transformation, strain
ageing, rapid solidification techniques. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written exercises and exam of the contents of
lectures and exercises. Approved exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: P. Kettunen, T. Tiainen: Metallioppi IV, TTKK:n
opintomoniste, Tampere 1987. Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>28205 Engineering Alloys II  3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lecturer Erkki It&auml;vuori<p>
Lectures 14 h, seminar Exercises 7 h. <p>
Given during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to speciality steel application and
