<a name="microscopyfin">
<H2>Electron Microscopy</H2>

<B>20100 Crystallography 1,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 10 h. Exercises 10 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: An introduction to fundamentals and practical applications
of crystallography.<p>

CONTENTS: Crystal structures, determination of crystallographic planes
and directions, symmetries, methods for crystal structure
determination, stereographic projection, practical applications.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written examination of the contents of the
course. Approved exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: C. Hammond: Introduction to Crystallography, Royal
Microscopical Society, Oxford Sci. Publ. 1992. Copies of lecture
material.<p>

<B>20200 Electron Microscopy I	3,0 credits</B> <p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 21 h. Seminar and laboratory Exercises 14 h.<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed introduction to the theoretical and practical
command of scanning electron microscope and microanalysis.<p>

CONTENTS: Scanning electron microscopy, operation, image and contrast
formation, special preparation. Microanalyzing with EDS nad WDS,
correction calculations, computer programs, image analysis, practical
applications.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written examination of contents of lectures and
exercises. Approved seminar and laboratory exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: Pentti Kettunen: Elektronimikroskopia I, Laitteisto ja
kontrastinmuodostus, Otakustantamo 1983. Pentti Kettunen ja Toivo
Lepist&ouml;: Elektronimikroskopia II, Otakustantamo 1983. (when
applicable). Murr: Electron Optical Applications in Materials Science,
McGraw-Hill, USA 1970. J.I. Goldstein ym.: Scanning Electron
Microscopy and X-ray Microanalysis, Plenum Press, New York 1981. L.
Reimer: Scanning Electron Microscopy, Springer-Verlag, SLT 1985.<p>

<B>20220 Electron Microscopy II 3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 21 h. Seminar and laboratory Exercises 14 h.<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed introduction to the theoretical and practical
command of transmission electron microscopy.<p>

CONTENTS: Transmission electron microscopy, operation, contrast
formation, electron diffraction, elemental analysis (EDS), detection
of light elements (PEELS) and examples of practical applications.
Specimen preparation techniques. Other electron optical
instruments.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written examination of contents of lectures and
exercises. Approved seminar and laboratory exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: P. Kettunen: Elektronimikroskopia I, Laitteisto ja
kontrastinmuodostus, Otakustantamo 1983, P. Kettunen ja T.K.
Lepist&ouml;: Elektronimikroskopia II, Otakustantamo 1983 (when
applicable). J.W. Edington: Monographs and Practical Electron
Microscopy in Materials Science, The Macmillan Press Ltd, 1975.<p>

<B>20300 X-ray Techniques 3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 24 h, seminar and laboratory exercises 20 h. <p>
Takes place during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A detailed introduction to the theoretical and practical
command of X-ray techniques in materials science.<p>

CONTENTS: X-ray radiation, interactions with materials,
diffractometry, determination of orientation, fluorescense,
transmission photography, small-angle scattering and other
applications. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written examination of the contents of the
course. Approved exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material. Cullity: Elements of X-ray
Diffraction, Addison-Wesley, USA 1978. <p>

<B>20320 Introduction to NDT Techniques	1,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 10 h. Exercises 10 h. <p>
Takes place during fall term<p>

CONTENTS: Radiography, ultrasonic testing, acoustic emission, Eddy
current testing, liquid penetrant inspection, magnetic inspection,
thermal inspection. Practical examples about the industrials
applicants of NDT techniques.<p>

<B>20340 Research Methods in Materials Science  3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Toivo Lepist&ouml;<p>
Lectures 18 h. Seminars, labs and exercises 12 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: A survey of the physical research methods applied in
materials science.<p>

CONTENTS: Optical microscopy, Mossbauer spectroscopy, positron
annihilation, neutron diffraction.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written examination of the contents of the
course. Approved laboratory exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>20500 Powder Metallurgy  3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

