<a name="fibre">
<H2>Fibre, Textile and Clothing Science</H2>

<b>30100 Textile Raw materials 	9,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pertti Nousiainen<p>
Lectures 70 h. Exercises 63 h.<p>
Lectures take place during fall term and<p>
exercises during spring term.<p>

OBJECTIVE: The objective of the course is to give knowledge of the
fibers used in textile manufacturing as well as the production and
properties of the fibers.<p>

CONTENTS: Production of natural and man-made fibers, their properties
and utilisation, texturing of fibers and threads and research methods
of fibrous polymers.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature. Seminar work.<p>

LITERATURE: Sundquist, J., Tekstiiliraaka-aineet 1-Luonnonkuidut,
TTKK. Lecture material 31, Tampere 1981, Sundquist, J.,
Tekstiiliraaka-aineet 2-Tekokuitujen valmistus, TTKK, Lecture material
72, Tampere 1981.<p>

ADDITIONAL LITERATURE: Moncrieff, R.W. Man-made Fibres, 6 Ed.,
Newnes-Butterworths, London 1975, 1904 s., Haudek, H.W., Viti, E.,
Textilfasern, Verlag Johann L. Bnodi &amp; Sohn, Wien-Perchtoldsdorf,
Melliand Tectilberichte KG, Heidelberg Wien 1980, 361 s. <p>

<B>30120 Man-Made Fibres  4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pertti Nousiainen<p>
Lectures 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Lectures take place during fall term and<p>
exercises during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: The objective of the course is to give
knowledge of man-made fibers used in textile manufacturing, the
production and properties of the fibers.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exam of contents of literature.<p>

LITERATURE: Announced at the beginning of the course.<p>

NOTES: This course is for students who don\xab t have textile
technology as the major subject.<p>

<B>30150 Textile Technology (Basic Course)	1,5 credit unit</B><p>

Prof. Pertti Nousiainen<p>
Lectures and demonstrations 10 h.<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: The objective of the course is to give basic
knowledge of textile fibers, yarns and textile constructions and the
chains of most important textile manufacturing processes.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Participation in demonstrations and approved
examination.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material<p>

<B>30201 Dyeing and Finishing 6,75 ECTS credits</B><p>

(Basic Course)<p>
Prof. Pertti Nousiainen<p>
Lectures 50 h. Exercises 84 h.<p>
Lectures take place during spring term and<p>
exercises during fall term<p>

OBJECTIVE: The objective of the course is to give a basic knowledge of
pretreatment, dyeing and finishing processes of textile products.<p>

CONTENTS: Scouring, bleaching, mercerising etc. Colour theories,
structure of colours, different types of colours and dyeing
techniques. Water-repellent, soil release and other chemical
additives. Mechanical finishes. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: Nousiainen P. and Puolakka, A., Tekstiilien viimeistys,
pinnoitus ja laminointi (in print) and Trotman, E.R., Dyeing and
Chemical Technology of Textile Fibres, 6. Ed., Griffin Co, London
1984, 587 s. Giles, C.H., A Laboratory Course in Dyeing. 4. Ed. The
Society of Dyers and Colourists, Bradford 1989. Miles, L.W.C., Textile
Printing, Dyers Company Publications Trust, Bradford 1981, 293 s.
Peter, M., Grundlagen der Textilveredlung, Deutscher Fachverlag 1989,
927. H Zollinger, Color Chemistry, VCH Verlagsgesellschaft nhH,
Weinheim 1987, 367 s.<p>

<B>30203 Surface and Colloid Chemistry 3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pertti Nousiainen<p>
Lectures 20 h.<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE: The objective of the course is to give a basic knowledge of
surface and colloid chemistry in textile technology<p>

CONTENTS: Surface phenomena in fiber manufacturing tai fiber-forming
process. The interaction between fibers. Washing and washing theories.
Colour-fiber interaction. Electric phenomena. Modification and
treating of fiber surfaces. Most commonly used surfactants.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material, Chwala A., Handbuch der
Textilhilfsmittel.<p>

<B>30210 Textile Chemitry I 7,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pertti Nousiainen<p>
Lectures 56 h. Exercises 56 h.<p>
Takes place during the both terms.<p>
