<B>30230 Industrial Laundry Technology 3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lecturer Pekka Paturi<p>
Lectures 14 h. Exercises 7 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term<p>
Every other year, will be lectured in 1995-96.<p>

OBJECTIVE: Basics of laundry technology.<p>

CONTENTS: Different fibers and textile structures as they are seen by
industrial laundry. The basics of laundry chemistry. The devices and
methods of industrial laundry.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam of contents of course.<p>

LITERATURE: Puchta-Grunev&auml;lder, Testilpflete-Waschen und
Chemischreinigen. L&ouml;cher, W., Kurz, J., Die W&auml;scherei,
Verlag Neuer Merkus GmbH. 220 s. Hauptmann, H., Grundlagen der
w&auml;schereichemie, Lorch-Verlag GmbH, Frankfurt 1977, 451 s.<p>

<B>30250  Fur and Leather   	  	6,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lectures 28 h. Exercises 70 h.<p>
Takes place during the both terms<p>
Every other year, not in 1995-96<p>

OBJECTIVE: The objective of this course is to give basic knowledge of
scouring, dyeing and finishing of leathers and furs and also testing
and quality control of leathers.<p>

CONTENTS: The structure of leather and fur. The processes of fur and
leather technology. Dyeing and finishing. Testing of fur and
leather.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: Esa M&auml;ntysalo &amp; Liisa Pakkala,
Turkismuokkaustekniikka I ja II.<p>

<B>30300 Textile testing  4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lectures 32 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>
Every other year, will be lectured in 1995-96.<p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: The purpose of this course is to learn the
methods of textile testing; physical and chemical test methods and the
systems of quality control.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved laboratory exercises and exam of contents of
course<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<B>30400 Textile Constructions	10,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Ahti Reijonen<p>
Lectures 80 h. Exercises 140 h.<p>
Takes place during the both terms<p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: The objective of the course is to give a
general knowledge of different yarn and fabric structures and their
physical and application related properties including product
development and clothing physiology.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: A. Reijonen, Tuotekehitys ja innovaatiot
tuotantotaloudellisine taustoineen, TTKK 1994. Opintomoniste, A.
Reijonen, Tuoteselostetoiminta ja tavoitelaatutaso, TTKK/ Tekstiili-
ja vaatetustekniikan laitos 1994, Raportti 43. Edholm: Man-Hot and
Cold.<p>

<B>30410 Textile Constructions 4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>
	(Basic course)<p>

Prof. Ahti Reijonen + group<p>
Lectures 35 h. Exercises 40 h.<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: The objective of the course is to give a basic
knowledge of woven textile constructions and the most important
methods of manufacturing and product development. Structure
analysis.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture material and A. Reijonen, Tuotekehitys ja
innovaatiot tuotantotaloudellisine taustoineen, TTKK 1994.
Opintomoniste.<p>

NOTES: The course is for students who don\xab t have textile
technology as the major subject.<p>

<B>30420 Spinning and Nonwovens  7,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

M.Sc. Allan Lindroos<p>
Lectures 56 h. Exercises 56 h.<p>
Lectures take place during spring term and<p>
exercises during fall term<p>
Every other year, will be lectured in 1995-96.<p>

OBJECTIVE: The objective of the course is to give a basic knowledge of
different structures of yarns, various spinning systems of fibers and
the most important spinning machines. <p>

CONTENTS: Different kinds of yarn structures in textile industry,
different kinds of opening, cleaning and blending systems, spinning
systems of different fiber materials and the most important machinery.
Theory of fiber mixtures and pretreatment of fibers in non-wovev when
manufacturing. New spinning methods.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material. E. H&auml;yrinen:
Kehruuteknologia (TTKK:n moniste nro 222), Oeser: Mechanische
Spinnerei.<p>

<B>30440 Weaving Technology	      	9,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Ahti Reijonen<p>
Lectures 60 h. Exercises 84 h.<p>
Lectures take place during spring term and<p>
exercises during fall term<p>
Every other year, will be lectured in 1995-96.<p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: The objective of the course is to give a basic
knowledge of weaving with machines. The course includes the weaving
process, weaving machines and the economical aspects.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: Recommended reading: Ishida: Modern Weaving-theory and
practice, P.R. Lord - M.H. Mohamed: Weaving - Conversion of Yarn to
fabric, J.J. Vinvent: Shuttleless Looms.<p>

<B>30460 Knitting Technology	      	9,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Ahti Reijonen<p>
Lectures 60 h. Exercises 84 h.<p>
Lectures take place during spring term and<p>
exercises during fall term<p>
Every other year, not in 1995-96<p>

OBJECTIVE: The objective of the course is to give a general view of
the knitting process and the knitting machine constructions in the
production of various knitted structures.<p>

CONTENTS: The knitting process, knitting machines and the quality
control in a knitting mill.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: Recommended reading. Karl Jansson - Riitta Salonen:
Neuleteknologia. Weber: Wirkerei und Strickerei, Wignall: Knitting,
Offerman - Tausch - Marton: Grundlagen der Maschenwarentechnologie.
Spencer: Knitting Technology.<p>

<B>30470 Textile and Make up Industry Economics 6,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Ahti Reijonen<p>
Lectures 50 h. Exercises 70 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term <p>
Every other year, not in 1995-96<p>

CONTENTS: Special course in economics and economical control in
textile and clothing industry considering international competition
and the problems of saturated field.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<B>30485 Textile Design	4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Spicial instructor, designer Tuulia Kuusinen and group<p>
Lectures 42 h. Exercises 15 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term <p>
Every other year, will be lectured in 1995-96.<p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: The purpose of this course is to learn the
principles of textile and clothing design including collection
development and colour theory. Product development in industry. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam, textile composition exercise and its criticism.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<B>30600 Clothing Manufacture I	 4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Senior lecturer Juha Heinola<p>
Lectures 24 h. Exercises 66 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term<p>
Every other year, will be lectured in 1995-96.<p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: Basics of the clothing industry. The main area
is product development concerning industrial series production. Visits
to different clothing factories.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<B>30610 Clothing Manufacture II	6,75 ECTS credits</B><p>
          (Machines and Processing)<p>

Senior lecturer Juha Heinola<p>
Lectures 56 h. Exercises 80 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term <p>
Every other year, not in 1995-96<p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: The course gives you an overall view of the
clothing manufacturing technique including lay and pattern layout
planning, cutting, sewing and finishing.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<B>30700 Shoe Technology	6,75 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Ahti Reijonen<p>
Lectures 56 h. Exercises 84 h.<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>
Every other year, not in 1995-96<p>

OBJECTIVE: The course gives you the basic knowledge of shoe design and
manufacture.<p>

CONTENTS: Manufacturing process and raw materials. Exercises include
making shoes with industrial machines, materials testing and visits to
shoe factories.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and exam of contents of lectures and
literature.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<a name="chemistry">
<H2>Chemistry</H2> 

<B>35100 General and Inorganic Chemistry 4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lecturer Marja Asp-Lehtinen<p>
Lectures 56 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>
Takes place during fall and spring terms<p>

CONTENTS: Atomic and molecular theories, chemical bonds, stochiometry,
phases, principles of thermodynamics, chemical equilibrium, base-acid
equilibrium, reaction kinetics, electrochemistry, corrosion, chemistry
of most important elemnts and compounds.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written exam of the lecture materials and
exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: R. Laitinen, J. Toivinen: Yleinen ja ep&auml;orgaaninen
kemia, 5. painos, Otapaino 1990, TKY 477 or Atkins: General
Chemistry.<p>

<B>35110 Laboratory Safety and Methods of Work 1,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lecturer Raija Mikkonen <p>
Lectures 12 h. Exercises 28 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term<p>

CONTENTS: The working methods in laboratory and the necessary safety.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written exam of the lecture materials.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>35120 Inorganic Analytical Chemistry, Laboratory 4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lecturers Raija Mikkonen and Marja Asp-Lehtinen and assitant Tapio Jussila<p>
Lectures 6 h. Exercises 64 h.<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>

CONTENTS: The working methods in inorganic and analytical laboratory,
reactions of inorganic ions, most important analytical methods in
qualitative and quantitave analysis. REQUIREMENTS: Approved group
exercises and written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>35130 Organic Chemistry 3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof.  Helge Lemmetyinen<p>
Lectures 42 h. <p>
Takes place during spring term<p>

CONTENTS: Structures and typical reactions of the important functional
groups, structure and function of the key classes of biomolecules.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written exam of the lecture materials and
exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material, or W.H. Brown: Introduction to
Organic Chemistry, 4th ed., Brooks/Cole Publishing Company,
California, USA, 1988.<p>

<B>35140 Organic Chemistry, Laboratory 3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lecturers Raija Mikkonen and Marja Asp-Lehtinen and assitant Tapio Jussila<p>
Lectures 6 h. Exercises 40 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term<p>

CONTENTS: The working methods in inorganic laboratory, reactions of
functional groups, most important analytical methods in organic
chemistry. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved group exercises and written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>35150 Physical Chemistry 4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assos. prof. Helge Lemmetyinen<p>
Lectures 56 h.  Exercises 14 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term<p>

CONTENTS. Thermodynamic laws and quantities, Gibbs function and
chemical potential, phase equilibrium, mixtures, chemical equilibrium,
kinetics, diffusion, electrochemistry, surface chemistry.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written exam of lecture the material.<p>

LITERATURE: K.Kalliorinne, A. Kankaanper&auml;, A, Kivinen ja S.
Liukkonen: Fysikaalinen kemia, parts 2 and 3, Kirjayhtym&auml;,
Helsinki, 1988 or P.W. Atkins:<p>

Physical  Chemistry, Oxford Univ. Press,1993<p>

<B>35151 Physical Chemistry, Laboratory 6,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc. prof. Helge Lemmetyinen<p>
Lectures 8 h. Exercises 72 h.<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>

CONTENTS: The working methods in physical chemisty laboratory,
exercises on thermodynamics, phase equilibriums, reaction
equilibriums, electrochemistry, surface chemistry, reaction kinetics,
photochemistry and spectroscopy.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved group exercises and written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>35160 Polymer Chemistry 			4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lecturer Raija Mikkonen<p>
Lectures 42 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term<p>

CONTENTS: Types of polymers and polymerisations, molar mass and molar
mass distribution, step polymerisation, chain polymerisation,
industrial processes for synthesis of polymers, thermoanalytical and
IR-spectroscopic methods in analysis of polymers, analytical methods
for determination of molar mass.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written exam of the lecture material and
exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>35170 Polymer Chemistry, Laboratory 		3 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lecturer Raija Mikkonen and lecturer Marja Asp-Lehtinen<p>
Lectures 8 h. Exercises 40 h.<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>

CONTENTS: Synthesis of polymers by step and chain polymerisations,
depolymerisation, characterization of structure and properties of
polymers by spectroscopy, thermal analysis and chromatography.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved lab exercises and written exam of
the contents of the course. <p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>35195 Surface and Catalytic Chemistry 3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Assoc.prof. Helge Lemmetyinen<p>
Lectures 24 h<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>

CONTENTS: Thermodynamics of solutions, surface and colloid theory,
sedimantation and diffusion, adsorption between solutions and phases,
viscosity, surfase tension, surface active substances and contact
angles, structure of colloids, electrophoresis,heterogenous and
homogeneous catalysis, enzyme catalysis.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written exam of the lecture materials.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material<p>

<a name="plastic">
<H2>Plastic Technology</H2>

<B>32300 Introduction to Plastics Technology 1,5 credit unit</B> <p>

Lectures 14 h. Prof. Pertti T&ouml;rm&auml;l&auml;<p>
Exercises 14 h. Ass. Tomi Tehomaa<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>

CONTENTS: Introduction to the terminology and polymer science.
Polymeric structure and the background of the structure. Presentation
of the properties and the use of the important engineering plastics.
The most important processing methods. Development and trends of the
use of plastics.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written exam and exercises.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>32310 Plastic Materials 4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pertti T&ouml;rm&auml;l&auml;<p>
Lectures 56 h. <p>
Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

CONTENTS: Molecular structure of polymers, bonding forces, phase
transformations, amorphous and crystalline structure. Rheology and
failure of polymers, viscous and elastic deformation, crazing and
cracking, viscoelasticity and relaxations. Technology of plastics:
composition and additives, mechanical, thermal and electrical
properties. Rubbers and thermoplastic elastomers.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exam of the contents of the course.<p>

LITERATURE: P. T&ouml;rm&auml;l&auml;, P. J&auml;rvel&auml; ja J.J.
Lindberg, Polymeeritiede ja muoviteknologia II, copies of lecture
material.<p>

<B>32320 Plastic Materials, Laboratory	3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Ass. Tomi Tehomaa<p>
Seminars and laboratory works 56 h. <p>
Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

CONTENTS: Identification of plastics. Tensile and impact testing.
Properties and use of different plastics types.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises.<p>

<B>32330 Plastic Composites 6,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lectures 56 h. Prof. Pertti T&ouml;rm&auml;l&auml;<p>
Exercises 28 h. Ass. Esko P&auml;&auml;kk&ouml;nen<p>
Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

CONTENTS: Types of polymer composites. Production and pretreatment of
filling and reinforcing agents. Fabricating and processing of filled
and reinforced composites. Fibre and particle reinforced plastics,
polymer blends. Principle of reinforcing. Advanced thermoplastic
composites.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exam. Approved seminar or project.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>32340 Technical Applications of Plastics 6,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lectures 56 h. Ass. Esko P&auml;&auml;kk&ouml;nen<p>
Exercises 28 h. Ass. Tomi Tehomaa<p>
Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

CONTENTS: Properties and use of engineering plastics and rubbers.
Special plastics. Selection and construction of plastics and rubbers
for technical applications. Design of plastic products according to
the manufacturing method.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written exam and seminars.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>32350 Processing of Plastics	6,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Doc. Pentti J&auml;rvel&auml;<p>
Lectures 56 h. <p>
Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

CONTENTS: Mechanical mixing of raw materials. Melt processing methods:
melt mixing and kneading, granulating, injection moulding, extrusion,
blow moulding. Other converting methods, coating, printing and
decorating. Fabricating of thermosets and reinforced plastics.
Machining and joining of plastics.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written examination.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture material.<p>

<B>32355 Melt Processing Technology of Plastics 3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Doc. Pentti J&auml;rvel&auml;<p>
Lectures 28 h. <p>
Takes place during fall term<p>
NOTE: Lectured every second year, not in 1994-95<p>

CONTENTS: Rheology of thermoplastics in the melt state. Flowing of
plastic melts in moulds and dies. Melt processing machinery and
process control.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written examination.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>32360 Processing of Plastics, Laboratory	3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Ass. Esko P&auml;&auml;kk&ouml;nen and ass. Tomi Tehomaa<p>
Laboratory works and seminars 56 h. <p>
Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

CONTENTS: Injection moulding, extrusion, pressing and laminating.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved case-exercises.<p>

<B>32371 Thermal Analysis 1,5 credit unit</B><p>

Doc. Pentti J&auml;rvel&auml;<p>
Lectures 14 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Takes place during fall term<p>

CONTENTS: Theory and instruments of thermal analyzing methods as DSC,
DTA, TOA, TGA and DMA. Operating, sample preparation and practical
demostrations. Other thermal methods as dilatometry.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written exam of content of lectures and
exercises. <p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>32372 Characterization of Plastics	3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Doc. Pentti J&auml;rvel&auml;<p>
Lectures 14 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>
NOTE: Lectured every second year, will be lectured in 1994-95<p>

CONTENTS: Characterization of polymeric properties by physical test
methods: Mechanical testing, instrumented impack testing and dynamic
mechanical methods. Standardization of plastics and plastics test
methods. Spectrocopic methods. Identification of plastics. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written exam of content of lectures and
exercises. <p>

LITERATURE: Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>32375 Special Treatise on Plastics	4,5-7,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Prof. Pertti T&ouml;rm&auml;l&auml;<p>

CONTENTS: Introduction to polymer research. Solving a specific problem
of moderate extent on plastic technology. Supervised by professor or a
person nominated. The extent in credit units will be determined in the
beginning.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved written report of work. The courses 32310,
32330 and 32350 have to be passed.<p>

<B>32380 Moulds and Dies for Plastics	4,5 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lectures 28 h. Ass. Esko P&auml;&auml;kk&ouml;nen<p>
Demonstration and Construction exercises 14 h. <p>
Takes place during spring term<p>
NOTE: Lectured every second year, not in 1994-95<p>

CONTENTS: Types of tools in plastics industry. Tool materials and
manufacturing methods. Prototype, short-run and production moulds.
Dies for continous processing. Use of CAE in design and
manufacturing.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises and examination on the material.<p>

LITERATURE: Lecture material and K. Stoeckhert: Mold Making Handbook,
Carl Hanser Verlag 1983.<p>

<B>32381 Long-Term Behaviour of Plastics	1,5 credit unit</B><p>

Doc. Pentti J&auml;rvel&auml;<p>

CONTENTS: Theorical introduction to long-term durabilyti of polymers
and affecting factors. Aging mechanism in plastics and composites.
Stabilization of polymers and control of aging and fatigue in
constructions.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: No lectures, only approved written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Copies of given literature.<p>

<B>32385 Biomaterials		3,0 ECTS credits</B><p>

Lectures 28 h. Prof. Pertti T&ouml;rm&auml;l&auml;<p>
Takes place during spring term<p>
NOTE: Lectured every second year, not in 1994-95<p>

CONTENTS: Basic types of biomaterials: metals, polymers, ceramics,
composites and bioactive materials. Biocompatibility and
biodegration.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exam of the lecture material.<p>

LITERATURE: F. Silver and C. Doillon: Biocompatibility, VCH
Publishers, Cambridge, UK. Copies of lecture material.<p>

<B>32390 Thesis Seminar in Plastics Technology</B>	<p>

Periodically. Prof. Pertti T&ouml;rm&auml;l&auml;<p>
Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

CONTENTS: Periodical seminars (about 4 times a year) where the thesis
works of the institute are presented and discussed. Obligatory for
those who will do their Master thesis in Plastics Technology.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved participation to the seminar and approved
Master of Science Thesis.<p>

