<a name="#institutes">
<h2>Description of the Institutes and Laboratories and Their
Activities in the Department of Industrial Management and
Engineering</h2>

<p>

<p>

<b>Industrial Management and Engineering</b><p>

<p>

Internationalization and disappearing restrictions on trade make demands on the ability of
enterprises to react quickly. Increasing complexity of the operating environment requires that
engineers have ever broader knowledge and skills and the ability to visualize in matters of business
economics.<p>

<p>

The Institute of Industrial Management and Engineering develops abilities needed in entrepreneurial life. Central teaching areas are business economics and accounting, production
management, quality management, international marketing, and speech communication and
negotiation skills. The institute operates in close connection with industry and is participating e.g.
in the 1994 national research project "Into Future with Productivity".<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>Safety Engineering</b><p>

<p>

The Institute of Safety Engineering is responsible for teaching and research in the areas of safety
science, risk management, and ergonomics. In safety engineering notable research includes work
on e.g. the safety of FM systems as well as improvements in workplace design from the viewpoint
of a good work environment.<p>

<p>

Amongst other subjects, the Institute has researched emissions to the environment from
machinery. It was found that diesel-powered machines are a risk to the environment of such
significance as was not appreciated before. Further research showed how adaptation of the load
on machine motors can reduce emission and fuel consumption.
<p>

<a name="study">
<h2>Study Options Available in These Departments</h2>


<b>Industrial Management and Engineering</b><p>

<p>

- Entrepreneurship<p>

- Entrepreneurial leadership<p>

- Accountancy<p>

- Theory of organizations<p>

- Production economics<p>

- International marketing and finance and communication<p>

<p>

<b>Safety Engineering</b><p>

<p>

- Safety engineering<p>

- Job content and analysis<p>

- Work environment engineering<p>

- Ergonomics<p>

<p>

<a name="industrial">
<h2>Industrial Management and Engineering</h2>

<p>

<b>29100  Basics of Business Administration     		4.5 ECTS credits</b>  <p>

<p>

Senior ass. Ilkka Kouri<p>

Lectures 56 h, Exercises 30 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Understanding basics of business administration.<p>

CONTENTS: The basic operation of an industrial enterprise. Economic process. Production
planning, planning of individual processes, quality issues, material requirement planning, work force, wages and salaries, industrial site planning. Markets and marketing. Products, research and
development. Basics of accounting.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam from the lectures and the contents of literature.<p>

LITERATURE: Uusi-Rauva, Haverila, Kouri: Teollisuustalous. 1 p. Infacs Johtamistekniikka Oy,
Tampere, latest edition. Copies of lecture material.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>29101  Production Management                 		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Markku Pirjet&auml;<p>

Lectures 42 h.             <p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES AND CONTENTS: Plant planning, building and production start-up. Economic
use of automation. Principles of production management in different types of production. Cooperation between production and marketing. Materials management. Purchasing. Utilization of
automatic data processing in production and management.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam from the lectures and the contents of literature. Approved exercises. <p>

LITERATURE: E.S.Buffa &amp; R.Sarin: Modern Production/Operations Management, latest edition
Wiley, New York. Copies of lecture <p>

material.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Preliminary requirements: course 29100 or equivalent knowledge.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>29102 Production Strategies                  		3.0 ECTS credits </b><p>

<p>

Assoc.prof. Markku Pirjet&auml;<p>

Lectures 28 h.            <p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES AND CONTENTS: Interaction between production management and business
management. The objectives and key figures of production. Improvement of productivity. Investment management. Production accounting. Assesment of the need to chenge production principles. Production strategies. The international operations of production. Management of R&amp;D.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam from the lectures and the contents of literature.<p>

LITERATURE: E.S.BUFFA: Meeting the Competitive Challenge. Dow Jones-Irvin Inc., Homewood latest edition. Copies of lecture material.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Courses 29100 and 29101 or equivalent knowledge.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>29105 Cases of Production Management         		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Markku Pirjet&auml;, Ass. Ilkka <p>

Kouri and Ass. Jukka Annala<p>

Exercises 64 h.<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: Understanding the production system and the production start-up of new products. Understanding production management, simulation and statistical quality
control of industrial firm. Practical approach to the methods used in industry with the help of
exercises and company visits.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved exercises. Preliminary requirements: courses 29101 and 29110 or
equivalent knowledge.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>29109 Cases of Marketing Management          		6.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor Ulla Korsman<p>

Lectures 20 h, Exercises 72 h.<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: Making the student acquainted with the specialities of marketing.<p>

CONTENTS: Marketing strategies, customer oriented marketing, purchasing behaviour, corporate image, image building, marketing campaigns, information systems of marketing.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Attending lectures, approved case exercises,approved summary of the literature. Preliminary requirements: courses 29101, 29110, 2953, 29120 and 29885 or equivalent
knowledge.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>29110  Business Economics                    		3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Erkki Uusi-Rauva and Ass. Jarno Ala-Sorvari<p>

Lectures 28 h, Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Getting to know the most essential concepts of business economics and the theories and methods of business accounting and financial administration.<p>

CONTENTS: Introduction to business economics, basics of business accounting, balancing of the
accounts, company analysis, taxable income, corts, calculation of profit margin, cost accounting,
budgeting, investments.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam of the lecture material, exercises and literature. Preliminary
requirements: courses 29100 or equivalent knowledge.<p>

LITERATURE: Leppiniemi, Koskela: Uudistuva kirjanpito, W&amp;G, latest edition. Riistama,
Jyrkki&ouml;: Operatiivinen laskentatoimi, W&amp;G, latest edition.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>29113 International Marketing II             		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Klaus Kerppola<p>

Visiting lecturers         <p>

Lectures 28 h. <p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

 <p>

OBJECTIVE AND CONTENTS: Providing the students with a knowledge of marketing of
industrial goods, marketing of consumer goods, demand, market research, use of competitive
strategies, internationalization, global market zones, international co-operation agreements between companies.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam of the lecture material (visiting lecturer) and literature.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>29115 Management Simulation Game             		1.5 ECTS credits </b><p>

<p>

Assoc. prof. Klaus Kerppola and Ass. Jarno Ala-Sorvari<p>

Exercises 24 h <p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Using simulation in order to help the student to understand the functions of a
company in a competitive situation. Getting to know management policies and decision making in
an enterprise. Starting a new company and the paperwork connected with the starting of it.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam, Management Simulation Game, approved case exercise. Preliminary
requirements: course 29101 or equivalent knowledge.<p>

