<b>

56502 Road, Railway, Waterway, and Air Transport</b>    	<b>6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Associate Prof. Jorma M&auml;ntynen<p>

M.Sc. Matti Maijala, M.Sc. Hannu Asumalahti<p>

Lectures 56 h. Exercises. <p>

Takes place during fall and spring terms.<p>

<p>

GOAL: To provide understanding of the special features of road, railway, waterway, and air
transport from different points of view (i.e. producer, customer, society) <p>

CONTENTS:  Passenger and goods transportation by road, railway, waterway and air. The
infrastructure, operation and economy of different transport modes. Domestic and international
development of the modes of transport. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and a written examination.<p>

LITERATURE: Tie-, raide, vesi ja ilmaliikenne. TTKK, liikenne- ja kuljetustekniikka.<p>

NOTES: Road and railway transportation during fall term, waterway and air transportation during
spring. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>56503 Transport Policy </b>     		<b>	3,0 ECTS credits

</b><p>

Associate professor Jorma M&auml;ntynen, Guest speakers. <p>

Lectures 20 h. Group work.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

GOAL: To provide knowledge of current situation in the rapidly changing field of transport policy. <p>

CONTENTS:  An overview of the factors that regulate transportation sector both in domestic and
international markets. Current topics of transport, land use and environmental policies.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Participation in group work, approved report <p>

LITERATURE: Material given during lectures.<p>

<p>

<b>

56504 Advanced Course of Logistics </b>   	<b>	4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Associate Prof. Jorma M&auml;ntynen<p>

Guest speakers <p>

Lectures 28 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

GOAL: To provide knowledge of the logistical systems in the fields of trade and industry in
Finland and abroad. <p>

CONTENTS:  Logistics of the major companies in the fields of trade and industry, third party
logistics, international development. Logistical systems in different lines of business. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exercises and a written examination.<p>

LITERATURE: Kaupan ja teollisuuden logistiikka. TTKK, liikenne ja kuljetustekniikka.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>56551 Planning Work in Logistics </b>   	<b>	4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Associate Prof. Jorma M&auml;ntynen<p>

<p>

GOAL: To provide experience of practical work in the field of logistics.<p>

CONTENTS: Planning or analysis of logistics in a chosen company.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>56571 Special Research Work in Transportation </b>   	<b>4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

	 <b>and Logistics</b> <p>

<p>

Associate Prof. Jorma M&auml;ntynen<p>

Senior Ass. Harri Rauham&auml;ki<p>

<p>

GOAL: To provide profound knowledge in a chosen subject from the field of transportation or
logistics.<p>

CONTENTS: Preparing a research paper or analysis on the chosen subject. <p>

<p>

<b>

56581 Seminar in Transportation and Logistics    	4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Associate Prof. Jorma M&auml;ntynen<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

GOAL: To provide comprehensive knowledge of transportation or logistics as well as prepare
students for research work and critical evaluation of data.<p>

CONTENTS:  Preparing and presenting a research paper mainly based on written information.
Critical evaluation of other research papers.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Approved research paper, attendance in the seminar and participation as a
speaker and an opponent.<p>

<p>

<p>

<a name="safety">
<h2>Occupational Safety Engineering</h2>

<b>

31110 Introduction to Safety Engineering</b> <b>		3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

(for Students in Mechanical Engineering, Automation Technology, Textile &amp; Garment Technology and Industrial Economics, Environmental Engineering)<p>

<p>

Instructor: assistant professor<p>

Lectures: 14 h and labs: 28 h<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: The students should be able to define the main principles of Occupational Safety
and understand their relationships to industry. The students should be able to identify hazards in
the workplace and know how to avoid them.<p>

CONTENT: Definition of terms, identification of hazards, safety principles, current safety practices in industry, the definition of a good work environment, motivation, safety standards, and safety legislation in Finland.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students are expected to complete all lab exercises and homework
before taking the exams.  The exams will cover material presented in the lectures and lab exercises.  <p>

LITERATURE: Will be assigned in class<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31111 Introduction to Safety Engineering</b> <b>		3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

(for Students in Electrical Engineering and Computer Science, Environmental Engineering, Architecture and Civil Engineering)<p>

<p>

Instructor assistant professor <p>

Lectures: 14 h and labs: 28 h<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: The students should be able to define the main principles of Occupational Safety
and understand their relationships to industry. The students should be able to identify hazards in
the workplace and know how to avoid them.<p>

CONTENTS: Definition of terms, identification of hazards, safety principles, current safety practices in industry, good work environment, motivation, safety standards, and safety legislation in
Finland. This course will also cover the electrical standards.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students are expected to complete all lab exercises and homework
before taking the exams. The exams will cover the material presented in the lectures and lab
exercises.  <p>

LITERATURE: Will be assigned in class.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31121 Occupational Safety Management 		4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Markku Mattila<p>

Lectures: 56 h and Labs: 28 h<p>

Lectured during fall term.<p>

Lab exercises continue in fall term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: The students should be able to manage safety activities in industry.<p>

CONTENTS: Identification of hazards, occupational safety measures, how to select safety
measures, analysis and estimation of danger, organization of safety in industry and safety management.<p>

REQUIREMENTS:  The students are expected to complete all lab exercises and pass an exam. 
NOTE: some labs will be conducted in industry.<p>

LITERATURE: Will be assigned in class.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31126 Machine and System Safety</b> <b>Engineering 		3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Markku Mattila<p>

Lectures: 28 h and Labs: 14 h<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: To learn the principles of designing safe machines and systems. To learn Macinery
Safety directive and to know how to use it.<p>

CONTENTS: Hazard analysis of machines and technical systems, reliability analysis, assessment
of damage, safety planning, control mechanisms in automated processes, safety apparatus, safety
in machine design, and how to monitor safety programs.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students are expected to complete all lab exercises and pass an exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Keskeiset turvallisuusstandardit. MET. Integraatiotiedote 24: Koneturvallisuusdirektiivin soveltaminen. MET. Integraatiotiedote 22: K&auml;ytt&ouml;ohjeet. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31128 Safety of Automation 			3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Visiting Lecturer<p>

Lectures: 28 h and Labs: 14 h<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: The students should understand the meaning of safety in automation, and become
familiar with how to design safe automation systems and how to improve existing ones.<p>

CONTENTS: Relationship between automation and safety, safety and reliability, failure situations, reliability of computer softwares, man-computer systems, safety and robots.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students are expected to complete all lab exercises and pass an exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Will be assigned in class<p>

<p>

<b>

31133 Safety and Productivity 			3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Markku Mattila<p>

Lectures: 28 h and Labs: 14 h<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: How to save money through safety measures, the total costs of accidents, comparing different measures and their effects, productivity and improvement of working environment, safety innovations, and programs with feedback.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students are expected to complete all lab exercises and pass an exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Will be assigned in class<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31143 Industrial Hygiene 			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Rauno P&auml;&auml;kk&ouml;nen, Salme Rantanen<p>

Lectures: 28 h and Labs: 42 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

Lab exercises continue in spring term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: The students should learn the effects of the physical and chemical exposures and
how to prevent harmful exposure to the worker.<p>

CONTENTS: Physiological damage from noise, vibration, radiation, thermal stress, and chemical
hazards, technical protective measures, and occupational diseases.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students are expected to complete all lab exercises and pass an exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Will be assigned in class.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31145 Human Computer Interface (HCI) Design 	3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Invited lecturer Enda Fallon<p>

Lectures: 28 h. Exercises 14 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: To introduce students to the basics of human computer Interface and user-centered design.<p>

CONTENTS: The role of human factors in computing. Principles and methods of user-centered
design. Task analysis. User interface. Software usability evaluation.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Lectures, accepted exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Will be spesified during first lectures.<p>

NOTES: <b>Lectures will be held in English.</b> Approved for post-graduate studies.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31147 Industrial ergonomics 			4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Veikko Louhevaara<p>

Lectures: 32 h and Labs: 28 h<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: The students should know the principles of planning interactions between computers and workers, and be able to design machines and systems which consider human factors.
Physical work load, and mental stress.<p>

CONTENTS: Definitions and concepts of ergonomics, designing machines to match the abilities
of the worker, control mechanisms, and video display terminals. Physical work load and
measurements, mental stress and work organization.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students are expected to complete all lab exercises and pass an exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Saari J.: Teollisuusergonomia, K&auml;sikirja suunnitteluun. Ty&ouml;terveyslaitos, Helsinki
1992.<p>

NOTE: Course can also placed to post-graduate studies.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31149 Biomechanics 				4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Hannu St&aring;lhammar<p>

Lectures: 42 h and Labs: 28 h<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: To become familiar with the biomechanical principles of work load, and how to
apply  biomechanical knowledge to designing the contents of work. <p>

CONTENTS: Construction of the human body, biomechanical modeling, the stresses involved in
manual material handling, and Computer Aided Biomechanical analysis and design.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students are expected to complete all lab exercises and pass an exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Chaffin, D. &amp; Andersson, G. 1990. Occupational Biomechanics. 2nd edit. Wiley
&amp; Sons. Inc. 518 p.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31151 Safety Analysis and Reliability Engineering   	4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Veikko Rouhiainen<p>

Lectures: 28 h and Labs: 42 h<p>

Takes place during fall term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: The student should become familiar with the most common safety and reliability
analyses so that he/she may conduct such an analysis if required.<p>

CONTENTS: Definitions and concepts of reliability, failure mechanisms in mechanical systems,
and how to identify failing mechanisms.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students are expected to complete all lab exercises and pass an exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Will be assigned in class<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31157 Risk Management 			3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Markku Mattila<p>

Lectures: 28 h and Labs: 14 h<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: The student should become familiar with the different type of accidents in
industry, and be able to organize and manage a loss control program.<p>

CONTENTS: Losses that may occur in factories, organization and administration of a loss control
system, the economic feasibility of occupational safety and health programs, assesment of
damage, planning for loss control, teaching methods in a factory, and loss control of environmental resources.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students are expected to complete all homework and pass an exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Will be assigned in class.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31158 Assessment of the Environmental Risks		3.0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Visiting Lecturer<p>

Lectures: 28 h and Labs: 14 h<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: To recognize the risk of accidental hazardous emissions, to know the most
common risk analysis methods and their usability.<p>

CONTENTS:  Terms used in risk management, how to choose a suitable risk analysis method,
description of hazardous emissions, how to evoluate the effects of emissions. Environmental
legislation.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students are expected to complete all homework and pass an exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Ymp&auml;rist&ouml;riskit - Satunnaisp&auml;&auml;st&ouml;jen analysointi. 1995. Julkaisija Opetushallitus.
toimittajat H&auml;m&auml;l&auml;inen. Mattila ja  Molarius.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31159 Environmental Management		 	ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Invited lecturers<p>

Lectures: 28 h. Exercises 14 h<p>

Takes place during spring term<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES: To learn the principles of recognizing environmental problems in industry and to
manage environmental issues.<p>

CONTENTS: Environmental management within the overall management system of an
organisation, contents, targets and methods of environmental managing, environmental standards
and management systems, effects of the activities and products of the organization upon the
environment.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Lectures, accepted exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Will be specified during first lectures.<p>

<b>

31160 Post Graduate Seminar in Occupational Safety </b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Markku Mattila<p>

Seminars: 56 h<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

<p>

Course description: This seminar is for students who have received a Master of Science degree
and who are pursuing a Licentiate or a Doctorate degree. The students present their research
projeck to other post graduate students.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students should attend all lectures and prepare a report.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>31165 MSc Thesis Seminar in Occupational Safety</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Markku Mattila <p>

Seminars: 28 h<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

 <p>

Course description: This seminar is for students who are pursuing a Master of Science degree.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: The students should attend all lectures and prepare a report.<p>

<p>

<b>

31175 Special Project in Occupational Safety	  	4.5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Instructor: Markku Mattila<p>

Labs: 28 h<p>

Takes place during both fall and spring terms<p>

 <p>

COURSE DESCRIPTION: This course is for the student's independent study. The study may be
used as an introduction to the student's diploma work. The student chooses a subject in which he
wants to specialize. Usually the study deals with analysis and synthesis of accidents in industry.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Written report<p>

<p>

