<a name="institutes">
<h2>Description of the Institutes and Laboratories and
Their Activities in the Department of Architecture</h2>
<p>

The Department of Architecture at TUT is participating in the multidisciplinary research program
" Urban and Regional Development in the Future" along with many other Universities and
research centers in Finland.<p>

<p>

<b>History and Theory of Architecture</b> <p>

<p>

History of architecture, conservation of buildings, theory of design of new buildings and artistic
expression.<p>

<p>

<b>Architectural Design</b><p>

<p>

Teaching at the Institute of Architectural Design aims to impart competence in the design skills
needed in the profession of architecture. In line with teaching in the field, research is oriented
towards professional practice. Competition is part fo the methology. <p>

<p>

<b>Urban Planning and Design</b><p>

<p>

Design of towns and other communities and regions and teaching in municipal architecture with
associated research.<p>

<p>

<p>

<a name="course">
<h2>Courses Available in the Department of Architecture</h2>
<p>

Most of the courses in the Department of Architecture are taught in
Finnish. Foreign students are encouraged to study the subject
concerned, for instance from books written in English.  Examinations
can also be arranged individually, preferably in English.<p>

<p>

! All the credit units are given in ECTS credits.<p>

<p>

<a name="histo">
<h2>Institute of Architectural History and Theory</h2>
<p>

<b>12046 History of Architecture in Finland and Scandinavia	7,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Assoc Prof. Ville Lukkarinen<p>

Lectures 56 h, exercises 112 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The course aims at giving a picture of the Finnish architectural development from
the Middle ages to the beginning of the 20th century. The lectures will also deal with the history
of architecture in the countries surrounding the Baltic Sea. Basic methods of research on the
history of architecture will be discussed.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written exam and a minor exercise on reseach.<p>

LITERATURE: Anounced later. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>12100 Environmental Psychology 			4,5 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Senior Lecturer Seppo Aura<p>

Lectures 30 h, exercises 15 h.<p>

Takes place during autumn term.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: A short history and basic concepts of environmental psychology. Psychological
principles as a basis for urban planning and architexctural design; examples and empirical results.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>12103 Visualizing Architecture 1			3,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Lecturers Petri Siitonen, Ilkka Alavalkama<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 56 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To give skills to understand and use picture media as a tool in architecture. Basic
skills in the use of urban simulator (model videography system), video cameras, video editing
systems and computer-aided video processing. Principles of using videography as a tool in
architectural design and as a form of art. <p>

LITERATURE: Videokuvaus, TTKK/AHA 1995 or basic books in English.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>12202 Visualizing Architecture 2			3,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Lecturers Petri Siitonen, Ilkka Alavalkama<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 56 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To give skills in three-dimensional architectural thinking and in design methods.
Visual methods in planning process. Urban simulator as a planning tool. Virtual reality. Video and
computer-aided design in combination, tools and possibilities.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>12302 Still Media 1				3,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Lecturer Ilkka Alavalkama<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 28 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To give basic skills in architectural photography, photographic laboratory
processes, computer-aided picture processing and photographic light systems. Principles of using
photography as a tool in architectural design and as a form of art. Basics of the theory of
photography.<p>

LITERATURE: Arkkitehtuurin valokuvauksesta, TTKK/AHA 1994 or basic books in English.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>12403 History of Art				3,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Assoc. Prof. Ville Lukkarinen <p>

Lectures 42 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The course is designed to complement the studies in architectural history and
artistic expression by giving the student a basic konowledge in art history. The course will cover
major periods in art history and deal with their social and economical backgrounds.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Lectures and a written exam.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>12404 Still Media 2				3,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Lecturers Petri Siitonen, Arto Kiviniemi, Hannu Penttil&auml;, Ilkka Alavalkama<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: No lectures, a special program of photography, computer visualization or picture
processing. Project guidance by one of the lecturers.<p>

Working with progessional photographic equipment, urban simulator, video editing system or
computer system. A personal work using technical methods as a part of architectural project.<p>

LITERATURE: Special literature.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>12408 History of Modern Architecture 		6,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Lectures 56 h. <p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The course will give an ovcerall view on the history of modern architecture. Main
focus will be on the development in Europe and in the Scandinavian countries from the beginning
ogf the 19th century to the 1960's. An important aim is to develop the students' critical eye by
studying the quality and contents of modern architectural tradition from different angles.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written study on a given subject and a written exam on the contents of the
lectures and given literature. <p>

LITERATURE: A list of required reading will be given in the beginning of the course.  <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>12501 Protection of Buildings 			15,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Tore Tallqvist <p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 140 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

GOAL: The course aims at giving the student basic skills connected with the architects tasks in
the conservation of buildings. The lectures will deal with theoretical as well as practical questions
arising in the architectural conservation. <p>

CONTENTS: The student project begins with a documentation work in teams. For this there will
be a ten days' "camp" in the beginning of the first period at a chosen site, usually a group of
dwellings in a historical environment. Next part of the project consists of defining repair
guidelines and producing a minor adaption of the documented building(s).  <p>

REQUIREMENTS: An approved student project, a written exam.<p>

LITERATURE: A selection on required reading will be given in the geginning of the course.<p>

<p>

<b>12503 History and Theory of Architecture,		7,5 ECTS credits <p>

	 Special Course	<p>

</b><p>

Invited Lecturers<p>

Lectures and seminars 12 h, exercises 30 h.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: To offer basic information about Finnish Architecture and prepare the student for
architectural design projects. <p>

CONTENTS: Development of the Finnish architecture. Current issues. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: Presence, and accepted exercise project (group work or individual work).<p>

LITERATURE: To be specified at commencement <p>

<u><i>NOTE: LECTURED IN ENGLISH</u></i><p>

<p>

<b>12504 Traditional Structures and Their Restoration	6,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Senior Ass. Panu Kaila<p>

Lectures 42 h, exercises 84 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

GOAL: Traditional building materials and techniques - history, fabrication, qualities, damage,
conservation, repair methods. Laboratory studies on different materials. Field trips to factories,
laboratories and construction sites. A voluntary work camp will be organized, during which there
will be an opportunity to practise with the production of traditional building materials or repair
work at a historical building. The student project will consist of an "anatomical" study of a
building or a part of it.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: A written exam based on the lectures or a corresponding written research
paper and an approved student project.<p>

LITERATURE: A selection on required reading will be given in the beginning of the course. <p>

<p>

<b>12601 Protection of Building, Advanced Course</b> 		<b>15,0 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Tore Tallqvist, Ass. Sari Schulman<p>

Lectures 56 h, exercises 168 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

GOAL: The course consists of an extensive student project on architectural conservation and
adaptation. Along the architectural aspects, also technical and historical questions will be dealt
with. The course aims at giving a professional background for the diploma work.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: An approved student project and a written exam.<p>

NOTE: The course can either be a part of the basic studies included in the architectural diploma
or it can be a part of post-graduate studies.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>12602 History of Architecture, Advanced Course 	15,0 ECTS credits	<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Tore Tallqvist<p>

Lectures 56 h, exercises 168 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

GOAL: The course will concentrate on a special theme within the history of architecture. The
course aims at offering methodological tools and developing the students' skills in the field of
architectural and historical research.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: An approved written study and participation to an extensive study trip.<p>

NOTE: The course can either be a part of the basic studies included in the architectural diploma
or it can be a part of post-graduate studies. <p>

<p>

<p>

<a name="desi">
<h2>Institute of Architectural Design</h2>
<p>

<b>13052 Housing Design 2				6,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Assoc. Prof. Matti Sepp&auml;nen<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 112 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The course advances the student's professional abilities in housing design and
public services. The course provides the basic knowledge in housing for the elderly, for students
and youth, children's day-care, renovation of apartment blocks, ekological housing.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13201 Architectural Construction,			12,0 ECTS credits<p>

	 Professional course<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Unto Siikanen<p>

Lectures 70 h, exercises 140 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Improvement of preparenessies of the architectural design and the design for built
environment concerning building methods, building systems and the use of materials. Modul
system and the building with prefabricated units. Materials used in building: wood, natural stone,
ceramic products, concrete, light concrete, plastic, metals etc. Basic things of the design of the
structures. Structures complementing the skeleton of the building: balconies, roof, staircase,
windows, doors, partitions. Covering works, suface coatin and the finishing of the building.
Building project, deeds of building and specification.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13301 Architectural Design, Professional Course 2:	12,0 ECTS credits<p>

	 Public and Service Buildings</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Juhani Katainen <p>

Lectures 42 h, exercises 112 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The aim of the course is to provide the ability to design public buildings.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13302 Building Acoustics			3, 0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Special Lecturer Eija Halme-Salo <p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 14 h. Takes place during autumn term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The course provides basic knowledge in building acoustics.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13401 Housing Design				6,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Assoc. Prof. Matti Sepp&auml;nen<p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 84 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The course provides basic knowledge in housing design related specifically to
apartment blocks and communal spaces in residential areas.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13402 Interior Design				6,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Special Lecturer Eero Keto<p>

Lectures 56, exercises 56.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The course provides a general view of interior design, materials, lighting, and
furniture design.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13502 Productional Buildings Design		6,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Snior. Ass. Kari Salonen<p>

Lectures 35 h, exercises 168 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The course provides basic knowledge of productional building design, factory lay-out, and working environment.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13503 Architectural Design, Special Course		7,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Architects Christopher Bearman and Meri M&auml;kipentti<p>

Lectures and seminars 12 h, exercises 30 h.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: A study of the cultural diosyncrasies of architectural design, practise and education
in Britain. Through a small-scale project set in a tight urban context the aim is to explore the
forms of architecture that match the significant tendencies of contemporary culture and to
investigate the city as a complex area systems and effects.<p>

<i><u>NOTE: LECTURED IN ENGLISH.</i></u><p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13601 Architectural Design, Advanced Course 1		15,0 ECTS credits<p>

	 (Public, Office and Administrational Buildings)<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Juhani Katainen <p>

Lectures 56 h, exercises 168 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The aim of the course is to advance professional abilities in design of public
buildings.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13602 Architectural Design, Advanced Course 2		15,0 ECTS credits<p>

	 (Special Houring Problems)</b><p>

<p>

Assoc. Prof. Matti Sepp&auml;nen <p>

Lectures 56 h, exercises 224 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The aim of the course is to provide the ability to design special requirement
housing, hotels, commercial buildings and service centres.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13606 Architectural Design, Varying Topics Course 4	6,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

a) Steel Construction Course for Architectural Students.<p>

b) Concrete Construction Course for Architectural Students.<p>

<p>

Courses a)  and b) are lectured in turns between every two or three years.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13607 Architectural Design, Special Course 5		7,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Juhani Katainen and Assoc. Prof. Matti Sepp&auml;nen <p>

Lectures and seminars 48 h, exercises 30 h.<p>

Takes place during both autumn and spring terms.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: Solving special architectural problems in order to support diploma projects.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13608 Construction Management 			6,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Senior Ass. Kari Salonen <p>

Lectures 28 h, exercises 30 h.<p>

The beginning of the lectures informed in the beginning of academic year 1995-96.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: The aim of the course is to provide an insight into construction management,
contract planning, negotiation procedures etc.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13615 The Basics of Computing in Architecture		4,5 ECTS credits </b><p>

<p>

Hannu Penttil&auml; <p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Gives a  general overview of information technology (IT), data processing and
computers from an architectural viewpoint. What are architects' possibilities to use computers in
their work? <p>

CONTENTS: Mainly a lecture course, basic word processing exercises for those who have not
used a microcomputer before. Both PC and Macintosh-computers are used. This course is a basis
to department's other IT courses, suggested for 1 st. or 2 nd. year students, no previous
knowledge required. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13616 Data Management for Architects		3 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Hannu Penttil&auml; <p>

Takes place during autumn term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Gives an understanding and training in integrated data management, in architect's
various working environments and construction field reality. <p>

CONTENTS: Course emphasis is in alphanumeric data management (calculation, databases), and
training consists of small individual computer-aided exercises (PC or Mac) included in students'
design couses. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: the basic course or qual knnowledge required. <p>

<p>

 <p>

<b>13617 Computer Aided Design 1 			4,5 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Arto Kiviniemi<p>

Takes place during autumn term.<p>

  <p>

OBJECTIVE: Gets acquanted with a computer-aided architectural design, and CAD in 2-D
drawing (AutoCAD). Computer as a design and modelling tool. <p>

CONTENTS: Lecture and exercise course, emphasis in graphical and geometrical data management. <p>

REQUIREMENTS: The basic course (13615) or equal knowledge required. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>13618 Computer Aided Design 2 / AutoCAD-Visualization 	3,0 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Arto Kiviniemi<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVE: Using and developing a CAD-system as a sopbisticated design tool. Architectural
application software development in AutoCAD environment. <p>

basic skills: CAD I or equal knowledge required.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<a name="urban">
<h2>Institute of Urban Planning</h2>
<p>

<b>14201 Urban Planning Professional Course 1		12 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Professor Jere Maula<p>

Lectures 56 h. Exercises 140 h.<p>

<p>

OBJECTIVES AND CONTENTS: The knowledge and the control of the basic elements<p>

on the basic elements of the local environment, the internal land use, and the <p>

townscape. The readiness for the detail planning. The position end the inportance<p>

of the plans affecting the physical environment. The requirements laid on the <p>

detail plans. The components and the structure of the community. The planning of <p>

the different kind of areas. The town architecture. The exercise: A detail plan<p>

of a new housing area or a supplement to an existing area: landscape, technical<p>

networks, building volume, and townscape.<p>

<p>

<b>14301 Urban Planning Professional Course 2		15 ECTS credits<p>

</b><p>

Prof. Jorma M&auml;nty<p>

Lectures 56 h, exercises 140 h.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The aim of the course is to provide the ability to general level urban planning and
design. The exercises consist of different analytical and design approaches to general level
planning of the urban environment. The course is intended to provide, for example, the basic
concepts of general planning on the theoretical and concrete level. Exercises consist of two
phases. The first one is intended to develope the students ability to analyse the structure and
possible futures of community in order to make it possible to create master plans for the chosen
enviroment. The second phase consist of creating a master plan for the analysed environment. <p>

<p>

<p>

<b>14401 Urban Planning Advanced Course		15 ECTS credits</b><p>

<p>

Prof. Jorma M&auml;nty<p>

Lectures 56 h, exercises 140 h.<p>

<p>

CONTENTS: The aim of the course is to advance the student's
professional abilities in urban planning and design especially on
theoretical issues. One essential way to improve the student's
analytical abilities in urban planning and design is the dicussion and
consideration of certain acute and current issues in the field. This
consideration is taken into concrete level by the student's in
exercises, which are mostly literal but could also consist of visual
analysis of the environment. The basis in the course is in the field
of theoretical approaches and applications to urban problems.

