<a name="econo">
<h2>Institution of Construction Economics and Management</h2>
<b><p>

57100 Basic Methods of Construction Economics </b>	<b>3,0 ECTS credits </b><p>

<p>

Prof. Raimo Salokangas, Ass. Seppo Aalto<p>

Lectures 30 h. Case exercises 60 h, excursion.<p>

Takes place during fall and spring term. 2nd year students.<p>

<p>

GOAL: To introduce the most important concepts and methods of construction economics and
management, and to familiarize the students with theories of economic choice.<p>

CONTENTS: Concept and objective of construction economics. Economic units and their
economic choices. Choice alternatives, their quality and properties. Time value of money.
Investment appraisal. The concepts of cost and cost estimation. Concepts of revenue, benefit and
value, and the corresponding analyses. Profitability analysis. Risk assessment and management.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam covering the essentials of the literature in the beginning of the course,
exercises, exam on exercise topics, and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced later.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>57110 Economics of Construction Sector </b>	<b>	3,0 ECTS credits</b> <p>

<p>

Senior Ass. Erkki Anttila <p>

Lectures 29 h. Case exercises 55 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term. <p>

<p>

GOAL: To review the main economic characteristics of construction industry and introduce its
role in the economy and society.<p>

CONTENTS: The importance of construction industry in the economy. Construction project as a
process, parties to it, and legal foundations of construction. Contractor's activities in a construction project. Basics of Business Management.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam on the essential literature in the beginning of the course. Case
exercises and report. Paper on current project management topic. Final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: 1) Perttil&auml; H. &amp; S&auml;til&auml; H. 1992. Rakennuttaminen. Rakentamistalous 2. Helsinki:
Rakentajain Kustannus Oy. 2) Koski, Hannu. 1989. Handbook of Production Planning and
Management in a Construction Project. Tampere University of Technology, Institute of
Construction Economics and Management 1989/6. 3) Luentomoniste.<p>

<p>

<b><p>

57121 Building Production Techniques </b>	<b>	3,0 ECTS credits</b> <p>

<p>

Lecturer Hannu Koski<p>

Lectures 35 h. Case exercises 15 h. Exercises 25 h. Excursion 6 h.<p>

Takes place during fall and spring term.<p>

<p>

GOAL: To describe the main site types, to introduce how the activities are breaked down for time
planning, and to familiarize the students with the most important production techniques and
production planning databases and files.<p>

CONTENTS: During the course, the general managerial activities at the site, the main activities in
the earth moving, building frame construction and indoor installation phases, and the main types
of production plans are reviewed.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Case exercises, excursions and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Koski, Hannu. 1992. Talonrakentamisen ty&ouml;maatekniikka. Tampere: Tampereen
teknillinen korkeakoulu, rakentamistalouden laitos, julkaisuja 1992/4. 2) a set of videos and slides
on production techniques. 3) Ratu-databases.<p>

<p>

<b>57213 Building Project Management </b>	<b>	3,0 ECTS credits</b> <p>

<p>

Prof. Raimo Salokangas<p>

Senior Ass. Mauno Siev&auml;nen<p>

Visiting lecturers<p>

Lectures 24 h. Case exercises 24 h. Exercises 40 h.<p>

Takes place during spring term.<p>

<p>

GOAL: To familiarize the students with the employers' and designers' main tasks, choices,
decision support systems and information sources in a building construction project.<p>

Contents:  Cost, value and profitability analyses with applications. Property systems for building
construction. Cost, value and profitability databases in building construction. Employer's,
designer's and contractor's building project processes. Energy management in buildings. Student
groups prepare implementation plans for a construction project as their case exercise.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam covering the essential literature in the beginning of the course. Case
exercises and report. Paper on current topic in Project Management. Final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: To be announced later.<p>

<p>

