<b><p>

57240 Facilities and Real Estate Management</b> 	<b>	4,0 ECTS credits</b> <p>

<p>

M.Sc.(Eng) Petri Murtomaa <p>

Visiting lecturers<p>

Lectures 30 h. Case exercises 24 h. Exercises 80 h. Excursions.<p>

Takes place during fall term.<p>

<p>

GOAL: To introduce the field of facilities and real estate management and its relations to building
design and construction.<p>

CONTENTS: The economic principles of facilities and real estate management. Acquisition
alternatives of built space. Administration, costs and documents in different types of facilities.
Technical solutions in buildings. Operation and maintenance activities and their planning.
Economic appraisal of open lines of actions in facilities and real estate management.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Pre-exam, seminar, presented seminar paper and final exam. <p>

LITERATURE: 1) Murtomaa P. (toim., edit.): Kiinteist&ouml;npidon tekniikka, Talous ja hallinto,
Rakennuskirja 1996. 2) Myyryl&auml;inen, L. 1990. Kiinteist&ouml;nhoidon k&auml;sikirja. Jyv&auml;skyl&auml;. 3) Anon.
1994. KIMI-Uudistuva kiinteist&ouml;ty&ouml;kirjasarja. Helsinki. 4) KH-databases.<p>

<p>

<b><p>

57310 Production Management</b> 		<b>	4,0 ECTS credits</b> <p>

<p>

Prof. Raimo Salokangas<p>

Lecturer Timo Saros <p>

Lectures 30 h. Case exercises 30 h. Exercises 80 h.<p>

Takes place during fall term. <p>

<p>

GOAL: To familiarize the student with the methods, tasks and means of production planning and
management, especially from a contractors' viewpoint.<p>

CONTENTS: Production planning process in a construction firm and a construction project. The
levels and types of schedules. Procurement planning and management in a construction company
and a construction project. Machinery and equipment plans. Scheduling methods; Gantt
schedules, arrow and precedence networks, and line of balance schedules. Project planning
software and their selection. Application of a project planning software to a real construction
project.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Exam covering the essential literature in the beginning of the course, case
exercises, report including production plans for a given real construction project, and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Koski, Hannu. Handbook of Production Planning and Management in a
Construction Project. Tampere University of Technology, Institute of Construction Economics
and Management.<p>

<p>

<b><p>

57320 Renovation Techniques and Management</b> 	<b>	4,0 ECTS credits</b> <p>

<p>

Lic. in Tech. Matti Pentti, M.Sc. (Eng) Juha Kaivonen, visiting lecterers <p>

Lectures 46 h, case exercises 30 h, exercises 50 h. <p>

Takes place during fall and spring term. Every second year, next time 97/98.<p>

<p>

GOAL: To familiarize the student with the technical and managerial aspects in the implementation
of a renovation project, and to illuminate the importance of renovation for the construction
industry and facilities and real estate management.<p>

CONTENTS: Building stock and renovation in Finland. Employer's management, planning and
design, costs and implementation alternatives in renovation. Contractor's production planning and
quality management. Historical development of technical and functional solutions in differerent
building types, and the renovation techniques of structural building components. Methods of
assessing the technical performance of structural components.<p>

REQUIREMENTS: Accepted individual exercises, case exercises and final exam.<p>

LITERATURE: Kaivonen, J. (toim.). Korjaustekniikka ja -talous, Rakennuskirja 1994. <p>

<p>

