<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Story of Ron Arad (Page 1)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#CC00CC" VLINK="#000066">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-read.gif" ALT="Read Ron's Story">
</CENTER>
<P><IMG WIDTH=164 HEIGHT=276 HSPACE=4 SRC="/Images/wedding.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT>Since October 1986, Captain Ron Arad, a navigator in the Israeli Air Force, has been held prisoner of war in Lebanon.

<P>Although Ron was known to be in good physical condition when he was taken prisoner, there has been no news of him since October 1987. Until the present day, he has not been accorded the fundamental right of any prisoner - visits by a representative of the International Red Cross.

<P>Since there has been no word from Ron Arad himself or any reliable information about his condition or whereabouts, his family is appealing to anyone who can assist in obtaining information about him or establishing contact with him, so that he may return to his home and family as soon as possible.
<BR><BR>
<HR NOSHADE WIDTH=70% SIZE=3>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>The Capture</H2>
<P><IMG WIDTH=216 HEIGHT=202 SRC="/Images/bday.jpg" ALIGN=RIGHT>
On October 16, 1986, an Israeli Air Force Phantom aircraft flying over Sidon in Southern Lebanon blew up due to mechanical problems. The pilot and the navigator, Rod Arad, bailed out and landed safely. After the two had landed, the area was surrounded by members of Palestinian and Shi'ite organizations operating in the area. The pilot of the aircraft was rescued by an l.D.F. Cobra helicopter in a daring operation. The navigator, Captain Ron Arad, however, was taken prisoner by the Lebanese Shi'ite organization Arnal.

<P>Ron Arad was transferred by Amal to Beirut, where the organization's leader, Nabi Berri, announced that he was holding Ron and later even proposed an exchange for Shi'ite Lebanese detainees.

<P>The man responsible for Ron Arad's welfare and safety during his detention by Amal was Mustafa D'orani, the head of the organization's security service, a Shi'ite religious fanatic with links to Iran. At the beginning of 1988, he left Amal because of ideological differences, taking the navigator with him.

<CENTER>
