</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Friday, December 20, 1991



Illustration: Photo

Caption: UN Secretary-General Perez de Cuellar welcomes families of
Israeli soldiers held in Lebanon at UN headquarters in New York
yesterday.  From left, Tamy Arad and daughter Yuval, and Avraham
Feldman and wife Pnina.
Credit: Reuter

Source: JONATHAN SCHACHTER

          Cuellar.  Lebanon.  Visit.  Tamy Arad.

        UN CHIEF VOWS TO 'DO HIS UTMOST' FOR MISSING ISRAELIS


UNITED NATIONS - UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
last night gave his commitment to the families of Israeli missing
soldiers that he would "do his utmost" to bring about the release of
their captured relatives, and would continue his involvement beyond
the end of his term of office, if necessary.

"I received massive support from the Secretary-General that Ron
is alive," said Tami Arad, the wife of missing airman Captain Ron
Arad, following the meeting.

While Perez de Cuellar could provide her with no proof of her
husband's whereabouts or condition, "the secretary-general told me
that he believes Ron is alive," Arad said.

Perez de Cuellar told her that he had "received a specific
promise" from Iranian president Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani "that he
will help him to search for Ron and help him to find him," she told
the Jerusalem Post.  "He talked with Mr. Rafsanjani about Ron
specifically."

Earlier this week, Perez de Cuellar sent his envoy Giandomenico
Picco back to the region in an effort to bring about the release of
the missing Israelis.

Arad said the UN chief gave the families no new information as a
result of the Picco mission, but that he would share with them any
details as soon as they became available.  "I expect something in a
matter of days from Mr. Picco," she added.

Arad said she had received no information to substantiate news
reports earlier in the day that her husband, who was shot down in
October 1986, was in Syrian hands.

There has been no word about airman Arad for the past two years.
He was originally held by the Shi'ite Amal militia, but later
transferred to Iranian Revolutionary Guards, although Iran has never
officially admitted to holding him.

The other three Israelis, First Sgt.  Zvi Feldman, Sgt.  Zachary
Baumel and Cpl.  Yehuda Katz disappeared after a 1982 tank battle in
Sultan Yakoub, in eastern Lebanon.

Despite his own previous statements that he had information that
the three tank crew members were dead, Perez de Cuellar told their
relatives not to give up hope.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
