</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Thursday, December 12, 1991



Source: YIGAL KOTZER

          Peace.  Israel.  Egypt.  Arab States.  IDF.  Missing Person.
          Perception.

        BASSIOUNY SURE BOUTROS GHALI WILL ACHIEVE ARAD'S RELEASE


HAIFA - The Egyptian ambassador, Mohammed Bassiouny, said
yesterday he was convinced newly elected UN Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros Ghali will be more successful in his efforts to gain the
release of Israeli MiAs, including airman Ron Arad, than the outgoing
secretary-general, Javier Perez de Cuellar.

Bassiouny said he expected Boutros Ghali to succeed where Perez
de Cuellar had failed so far because "he is aware of the problems of
the region.  As a result, I am full of hope that the problem will be
solved quickly."

Bassiouny, who was visiting Nesher, near Haifa, said the venue
for peace talks between Israel and the Arabs was unimportant, and that
efforts should be made to focus on substance in the talks.

"The Middle East will be a paradise and other countries will sign
a peace agreement with Israel" if talks succeed, he said, adding:
"Future generations will not forgive us if we miss this golden
opportunity for peace.  The peace between Israel and Egypt will also
grow 'warm up' when the talks become fruitful."



</PRE>
