<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Wednesday, December 11, 1991



Source: JONATHAN SCHACHTER

          Iran.  Visit.  IDF.

        CLAIMS NO KNOWLEDGE THAT CAPTURED AIRMAN IS ALIVE.
UN CHIEF 'HAS PLAN' FOR ARAD'S RELEASE.


UNITED NATIONS - UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
"has a plan" for the release of captured Israeli airman Ron Arad, "and
he is moving on it," Israel's chief hostage negotiator, Uri Lubrani,
told reporters Monday night.  Perez de Cuellar told The Jerusalem Post
he "was not in a position to know" if Arad was indeed alive, but said
it was his "very sincere hope" he was.

The disclosure followed a 45-minute meeting with the
secretary-general, in which Lubrani appealed to him to continue his
efforts to locate and free the Israeli navigator and arrange for the
return of the bodies of other missing Israeli servicemen.

"The secretary-general has been extremely clear about his
commitment to do whatever he can in order to exhaust all possibilities
by the time he leaves his office" at the end of this month, Lubrani
said.  "He will see to it that Mr. Arad is included in the completion
of his initiative."

Israel is still trying to ascertain the fate of four Israeli
soldiers, three of whom disappeared after a 1982 tank battle in
eastern Lebanon.  The fourth, airman Arad shot down in 1986, is still
thought to be alive, although Israel has not received any reliable
information about his condition.

Despite having no new information on Arad, Perez de Cuellar
confirmed that the other three soldiers were dead, and their bodies
were being held by "groups, but I don't know which groups.

"I have information that they have the bodies and they will be
eventually prepared to release them to the families," Perez de Cuellar
told the Post.

Lubrani said he had no additional knowledge of the fate and
whereabouts of Arad, and that while Israel has "no concrete, hard
intelligence" that he is still alive, "we have reason to believe that
he is."

The secretary-general said the two had discussed "ways and means
of accelerating the information we need about Mr. Arad and the other
missing Israelis," adding, "I feel personally committed to their
freedom.  I intend to end up this very sad experience before the end
of my mandate; that means I have still 22 days for completing my
work."

Perez de Cuellar provided no details about any plan or specific
course of action, however.

Speculation has centered over a possible upcoming trip to Iran or
elsewhere in the region by Perez de Cuellar's envoy, Giandomenico
Picco, to try to win Arad's release.  Asked specifically if he were
sending Picco to Teheran, the secretary-general responded, "It is not
yet decided, but if it is needed he will certainly go.  I am fully
committed to the government and people of Israel in helping in this
particular case."



</PRE>
