<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Tuesday, December 10, 1991



Source: ALON PINKAS; Jonathan Schachter adds

          Arad.  IDF.  Uri Lubrani.  Interview.  Kidnapping.

        HIZBULLAH SAYS IT NEVER HELD RON ARAD


Israeli officials expressed "surprise" at a Hizbullah leader's
statement that IAF navigator Ron Arad is not now in its hands, nor was
he ever.

Naim Kassem said yesterday that the Hizbullah organization "never
arrested or held Ron Arad."

But he did say say Hizbullah is holding two missing IDF soldiers.
It is believed he was referring to the bodies of Yossi Fink and
Rahamim Alsheikh, whose death was confirmed over a month ago.

His remarks apparently dispersed any optimism still maintained by
Israeli negotiators, who had been led to believe that the Shi'ite
group was holding Arad, or knows his whereabouts.

Last night, a Defense Ministry official said the optimism
exhibited by chief hostage negotiator Uri Lubrani had been unfounded.
"He gave the impression we had new information, but today I'm less
sure we had anything at all," the official said.

In a possible attempt to reignite MiA negotiations, the ministry
released an interview with abducted Shi'ite cleric Sheik Abed Karim
Obeid, held since July 1989, videotaped two weeks ago.

Obeid said his situation and that of Arad should not be separated
from the broader Western hostage issue.  Obeid said that he did not
create the link between his fate and that of Arad, but that the link
was natural and made sense.  He said he knew of "the brothers holding
the pilot," thus contradicting Kassem's statement.

Obeid explicitly criticized "brothers who pledged not to release
Western hostages before my situation is resolved, but did not live up
to their commitment and let my situation be disconnected from the
hostage issue."

He acknowledged that from what he understood, "my situation is
frozen and nothing is being done to resolve it."

Jonathan Schachter adds:

Lubrani flew from Washington to New York for a meeting late last
night with UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar at UN
headquarters.  Sources said they were to discuss the the four MiAs
thought to still be alive.

"This is not a courtesy call, it is about the hostage story," an
Israeli official stressed.

The meeting followed contacts over the weekend between Lubrani
and UN hostage negotiator Giandomenico Picco, and earlier meetings in
Germany with other UN officials, a UN spokesman said.



</PRE>
