<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Monday, December 9, 1991



Source: ALON PINKAS

          Syria.  Lebanon.

        ARENS: NO NEW INFORMATION ON RON ARAD


Israel has no new information on the whereabouts or fate of
missing air force navigator Ron Arad, Defense Minister Moshe Arens
said yesterday.

Arens was answering reporters' questions at a ceremony at the
Irgun Zvai Leumi (IZL) museum in Tel Aviv.  He refuted persistent
rumors, the last coming from the British "Sky" television network,
according to which Arad was held by Syria.

Arad was reportedly originally captured by the Shi'ite militia
Amal, then sold to Hizbullah, which transferred him to the Iranian
Revolutionary Guards in Lebanon.  However, there have been conflicting
reports on his whereabouts ever since his plane was shot down over
Lebanon in July 1986.  According to some reports, he was transferred
to Ahmed Jibril's Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command and eventually to Syria.

Israel has consistently contended that Arad is alive.

Following a week of cautious optimism - Arad's wife Tami
reportedly flew to Europe last Tuesday - the first signs of renewed
Israeli frustration surfaced yesterday.  "At this point, it is
essential to say out loud to the UN secretary-general and to all those
holding [the missing] and to those who have already welcomed their
captive sons back home that Israel must see an end to this episode as
well," hostage negotiator Ori Slonim said.

He was expressing anxiety concerning Israel's hopes that its MiAs
be returned or new information be provided before the term of UN
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar expires at the end of
December.

Meanwhile, a Lebanese Shi'ite leader said that Arad is being held
by Syria, which "puts him out of any exchange deal.  The Israelis said
they wanted information on Arad, and the problem now is only how to
tell them he is with the Syrians."

That argument was rejected by UN assistant secretary-general
Giandomenico Picco, who said that "we do not know where the Israeli
navigator is, who holds him.  This is something which has yet to be
discovered."



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
