</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Tuesday, November 19, 1991



Source: DAVID MAKOVSKY

          Israel.  Prison.  Perez de Cuellar.

        OFFICIALS SAY RELEASE PART OF A WIDER DEAL


Israeli officials said yesterday's release of hostages Terry
Waite and Thomas Sutherland were part of a wider deal being brokered
for months by UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.  One
senior official voiced hope that the complex negotiations, involving
Iran, Lebanon, Syria, Hizbullah, and Israel and would conclude by the
end of next month.

Yohanan Bein, a senior Foreign Ministry official dealing with the
hostage issue, said last night that the release of Waite and
Sutherland showed that the overall deal was "on track."

"We knew it was coming," he said.  "Today's step can be described
as one wheel in the machine.

"We welcome the releases and are happy for the families.  Perez
de Cuellar has kept up his efforts and has overcome obstacles put in
his way.  I hope the entire deal is completed by the end of December,
when he completes his tenure at the UN."

Bein said the next step was up to Hizbullah, but refused to
detail what it would be.  "They know exactly what we are waiting for."

He denied reports that Israel would release the approximately 300
Shi'ite prisoners being held by the South Lebanon Army, as well as
Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid, being held in Israel, if Hizbullah or its
Iranian patrons releases IAF navigator Ron Arad and the bodies of
Yossi Fink and Rahamim Alsheikh, irrespective of Syrian accounting for
the other three IDF soldiers missing in Lebanon.

Bein admitted that the fate of the three is "separate" from the
PoWs, such as Arad, believed held by Hizbullah.  "It is true the fate
of those three taken by Syria is a separate affair from those taken by
the Hizbullah, but at the same time, we seem them as somehow being
tied together." He refused to elaborate.



</PRE>
