</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Tuesday, November 19, 1991



Source: ALON PINKAS

          Thomas Sutherland.  Terry Waite.

        INFORMATION OF MIAS, RETURN OF BODIES NOT PART OF THE DEAL


Information on the fate of the four Israeli MiAs and the return
of the bodies of Yossef Fink and Rahamim Alshiekh are at this stage
not part of the hostage deal which took place yesterday, according to
sources involved in the negotiations.

The sources expressed their frustration, stressing that the issue
of the Western hostages vis-a-vis the Shi'ite organizations is moving
at a far greater pace than that of the Israeli MiAs.

Ori Slonim, a lawyer working with Uri Lubrani on the negotiations
concerning the Israeli MiAs, was quoted last night by the BBC World
Service as saying that Israel would return all Lebanese Shi'ites it is
holding in exchange for the bodies of Fink and Alsheikh and the return
of IAF navigator Ron Arad.

Israel welcomed the release of Thomas Sutherland and Terry Waite
in Lebanon yesterday saying that it hopes that the efforts of the UN
Secretary General will result in obtaining information on the
whereabouts of its own MiAs.

The short statement, attributed to "security sources," made no
reference to any release of Lebanese prisoners held by Israel or its
Lebanese allies in south Lebanon.

Israel is now concentrating its efforts in three directions:
obtaining information on Arad's whereabouts, believed to be held by
Iranian proxies or by Iran itself, although the possibilty of Syrian
custody is not discounted; retrieving the bodies of Fink and Alsheikh;
and ascertaining the fate of Armor Corps soldiers Yehuda Katz,
Zecharia Baumel and Zvi Feldman, missing since the battle of Sultan
Yaacub in June 1982.

Sources close to the hostage issues said last night Israel hopes
that the information it is seeking will become available before Javier
Perez de-Cuellar's term as UN Secretary General expires.



</PRE>
