<HEAD>
	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Tuesday, October 22, 1991



Source: DAVID RUDGE and news agencies

          Lebanon.

        ISRAEL, SLA FREE 15 LEBANESE.
REPORTS OF HOSTAGE RELEASE SQUASHED.


Reports here that an American hostage had been released were
squashed yesterday in the Syrian capital of Damascus, where a senior
Syrian official said no release was imminent.

"I assure you that you can go home to sleep tonight.  Come back
for tea tomorrow," said Nasser Kaddour, minister of state for foreign
affairs, addressing the mob of reporters outside the Foreign Ministry
in Damascus.

"I hope that a hostage will be released soon," he said.

The Beirut bureau of Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency earlier
reported that American professor Jesse Turner had been released.

An editor in the Beirut office of the Islamic Republic News
Agency said Turner was set free at 8 p.m. The editor, who refused to
be named, said he had no further details.

But the report appeared false immediately because it did not
follow the usual pattern--there was no statement from the kidnap group
announcing the specific time and location of the release and Syrian
security forces were not given custody.

Kaddour, who appeared assured that the process was continuing,
did not comment on why a 24-hour deadline set by the kidnappers
themselves at midnight Sunday would pass.

But numerous events in Lebanon could have delayed the
process--including fierce fighting around Hizbullah headquarters in
the Bekaa valley capital of Baalbek, where many of the hostages are
believed held.  Eight people were killed and 15 wounded in the
fighting.

The Organization of Islamic Jihad also warned that renewed IAF
raids on south Lebanon could hamper U.N. efforts to win freedom for
the Western hostages.

Earlier yesterday, 15 Lebanese detainees were released by Israel
and the South Lebanon Army.

Fourteen Lebanese, including two women, were released from the
el-Khiyam jail inside the security zone in south Lebanon.  They had
all been detained for periods of between one to four years terrorist
activities or belonging to terrorist organizations.

Nine of them, including the women, decided to return to their
home villages inside the security zone.  The other five were handed
over to Red Cross officials and transferred north of the zone.

The single detainee who had been held inside Israel was brought
to the Rosh Hanikra border crossing in car with army plates.  When
photographers tried to snap a picture of him, the bearded Hizbullah
activist ducked between the seats in a vain attempt to keep out of
sight.

The man was later named as Ali Abbas Fawaz, who was captured by
IDF troops after being wounded trying to plant an explosive device in
the eastern sector of the security zone about five years ago.

Fawaz told Lebanese reporters afterwards that following his
recuperation he had been kept in Ramle jail, where regional Hizbullah
chief Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid is also being held.

He was handed over to Red Cross officials who escorted him out of
the zone towards Beirut.  When they reached Tyre, however, Fawaz's
brother, now serving in the Lebanese army tried to prevent them going
on to Beirut.

According to reports from Lebanon, the brother said he wanted to
take Fawaz back to his family who live in a village in south Lebanon,
rather than let him go on to Beirut and be used for propaganda
purposes.

The release of the 15 followed the Saturday night receipt of
irrefutable evidence that missing Givati Brigade soldier Yossi Fink,
like his comrade-in-arms Rahamim Alsheikh, was dead.

The UN-brokered negotiations to conclude an exchange deal that
would secure the release of all foreign hostages and the return of
missing IDF servicemen and PoWs, including IAF navigator Ron Arad, for
the freeing of Lebanese prisoners held by Israel and the SLA had
become stalled recently.  Israel had accused Iran and Hizbullah of
reneging on its promises to supply conclusive information about the
fate of Fink and Arad.

The information on Fink and the release of the 15 Lebanese
detainees appeared to have broken the deadlock.

Israel, however, tried to play down the release because of
Hizbullah's roadside bomb attack against an IDF patrol inside the
security zone on Sunday in which three IDF soldiers were killed and
two others wounded.

Dr. Yossi Olmert, director of the government press office, said
the release of the detainees was part of the "continuing support for
the initiative of UN Secretary-General [Javier] Perez de Cuellar."

"It is hoped that the process of resolving this humanitarian
problem will continue and will soon come to a successful conclusion,"
said Dr. Olmert.



</PRE>
