<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Thursday, October 10, 1991



Source: DAVID RUDGE and news agencies


        DISINFORMATION CONTINUES ON ARAD'S FATE, SAYS OFFICIAL


Israeli officials yesterday decried the latest statement by an
unnamed Lebanese Moslem fundamentalist that the fate of missing IAF
navigator Ron Arad was unknown.

The officials said the announcement was "yet another piece of
disinformation in the Hizbullah's war of nerves" over the hostages and
MiA's affair.

"From Israel's point of view nothing has changed.  We have many
reasons to believe that Ron Arad was transferred to the hands of the
Iranians, alive and well, and we would like to have information
concerning him as soon as possible," said a well-informed government
source.

A pro-Iranian Moslem fundamentalist said in Beirut that the fate
of Arad was the main stumbling block to a settlement of the hostages
affair.

"The fate and whereabouts of Ron Arad are still shrouded in
mystery.  Apparently he is not in the hands of pro-Iranian Moslem
activists.  We don't know where he is," the fundamentalist leader was
quoted as saying.

Arad ejected from his plane over Lebanon in October 1986.  He was
reported to have been captured by the then security chief of the Amal
Shi'ite organization Mustafa Dirani, who later allegedly sold Arad to
Iranian Revolutionary Guards stationed in Lebanon.

The pro-Iranian leader, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
that despite the apparent hiatus in negotiations, progress was being
made in efforts to secure the release of foreign hostages held by
Hizbullah extremists in Lebanon.

"Breakthroughs can be expected, but closing this file totally
will depend on how much Israel is willing to bypass the issue of its
pilot," the fundamentalist was quoted as saying.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
</CENTER>
