<HTML>
<HEAD>
	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif" >
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Sunday, May 22, 1994



Source: DAVID MAKOVSKY

          Lebanon.  Hizbullah.  Analysis.  Ron Arad.  Israel.  Missing Person.
          Information.

        DIRANI ABDUCTION TO GET DATA ON ARAD - RABIN


IDF commandos kidnapped Mustafa Dirani in the Bekaa Valley early
yesterday morning, not as a bargaining chip to trade for the release
of missing Israeli navigator Ron Arad, but to extract information
about the soldier's whereabouts, Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin said
last night.

The prime minister told a Tel Aviv press conference Israel is
willing to take further actions to free Israeli soldiers missing in
action, but at the same time he admitted he had no definitive proof
that Arad was either alive or dead.

It remains unclear what information Dirani could provide Israel
about Arad's whereabouts, since officials say Dirani, head of the
"Believers Resistance," an organization linked to Hizbullah, has
probably not held the airman since 1988.

Other senior officials said last night that Dirani would
constitute decisive proof that a "pro-Iranian group" has held Arad,
and thereby aid Jerusalem in eliciting international pressure on
Teheran.  Israeli sources said the IDF commandos searched Dirani's
home for a videotape showing his group turning Arad over to Iran.

Rabin said he hoped Dirani "would provide information definitely
on the period Ron Arad was in his hands, and possibly also on his
situation in the future."

Rabin added: "We have no definitive proof that he is alive and no
definitive proof that he is dead.  Until proven otherwise, missing
soldiers are assumed to be alive."

The inner cabinet unanimously approved the IDF commando operation
on Thursday.  Sources say the operation was approved after Rabin
pledged that "it would be clean," i.e., without civilian casualties.
Ministers wanted these assurances since family members were killed
when IDF helicopters used rockets to kill Hizbullah leader Sheikh
Abbas Musawi in February 1992.  Shortly thereafter, a pro-Iranian
group claimed responsibility for bombing the Israeli Embassy in Buenos
Aires.

Speaking to reporters last night, Rabin candidly admitted he
personally learned a lesson when, as defense minister, he ordered the
kidnapping of Shi'ite Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid in 1989, saying at the
time he mistakenly thought the Lebanese cleric could be traded for
Israeli MiAs.

"I hoped the kidnapping of Sheikh Obeid could be a bargaining
chip in negotiations.  I have no more delusions thinking that anyone
could be a bargaining chip in those negotiations, certainly not
Mustafa Dirani.  The goal is to find out what has happened and what is
happening to Ron Arad, as well as to deal with Lebanese terror against
southern Lebanon," he said.

Rabin declared more operations will take place if they will help
find Israel's missing soldiers.  "I can promise that we will also
conduct operations like this in the future if there is a need for them
...  we are responsible for all the missing and captured whose fate
has not yet been determined."

When asked privately if the kidnapping was timed to improve the
government and the IDF's standing among the public at the time of IDF
withdrawal from Gaza and Jericho, he answered: "This is negligible."

Rabin said the operation to kidnap Dirani was actually supposed
to take place a few months ago, but was canceled for unspecified
"intelligence reasons." The prime minister said the operation was
resumed when another chance to obtain information about Arad was
scotched.

Efforts to elicit information about the missing soldiers from
Syria, which controls the Bekaa Valley where Israeli soldiers were at
least once held, had failed, Rabin indicated.

The premier said that he did not think the operation would hurt
the peace process, noting that while it took place in a
Syrian-controlled area, it did not happen on Syrian soil.



</PRE>
