</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Sunday, October 6, 1991



Source: ALON PINKAS

          Information.

        ISRAELI OFFICIAL: NO PRISONER SWAP IN THE WORKS


Israel will not make any more goodwill gestures to Hizbullah
until credible information is received on the whereabouts of Israeli
MIA's, a high level Defense Ministry official said last night.

Iran's official news agency reported yesterday that Israel will
soon release a group of Arab detainees in exchange for a Western
hostage, possibly an American.

It quoted sources in the southern port city of Sidon as saying
Israel will also return the bodies of Lebanese fighters who had been
killed in battles with Israeli troops and what the report termed their
militia allies.

"Both the Iranian information agency's reports and [Hizbullah
leader] Abbas Mussawi's statements regarding a further Israeli gesture
in the form of freeing Lebanese prisoners are unsubstantiated.  In
short, there is nothing going on today that is new," said the
official, who is close to the negotiations on freeing Israeli MiAs
held in Lebanon last night.

The official, who preferred to remain anonymous, said that Uri
Lubrani, Israel's top negotiator and coordinator of activities in
Lebanon, made it clear in a weekend interview he gave in New York that
Hizbullah is not living up to its commitments to provide Israel with
information on the whereabouts of the five IDF MiAs still missing.

The information received so far, said the official, is clearly
inadequate.  "We are stil waiting for information on Yossi Fink and on
[IAF Navigator] Ron Arad.  Before we get reliable and confirmable
information on the two, Israel is not likely to free more detainees or
return more bodies of Shi'ite militiamen ", emphasized the official.

Israel freed 51 Shi'ite detainees and returned the bodies of 9
Hizbullah men last month.  In exchange Israel was to get information
on Fink, who disappeared with Rahamim Alsheik in 1986 and on Ron Arad.
Alsheik's death was confirmed last month, based on information
supplied by Hizbullah.



</PRE>
