<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Friday, September 27, 1991



Source: DAVID RUDGE; Allison Kaplan adds

          International Red Cross.  Iran.  Information.  Israel.  Yossi Fink.
          IDF.

        HIZBULLAH: RED CROSS MAY PROBE FINK CASE


Hizbullah council member Hussein Musawi yesterday hinted the Red
Cross could soon investigate the fate of missing IDF soldier Yossi
Fink, whom he said was probably dead, several Lebanese radio reports
said.

Israel has been pressing for irrefutable facts on the fate of
Fink who was captured in an Hizbullah ambush inside the security zone
in south Lebanon in February 1986, along with Rahamim Alsheikh,
another Givati Brigade soldier.

Earlier information relayed by Hizbullah via UN Secretary-General
Javier Perez de-Cuellar, who is leading efforts to solve the hostages,
MIA's and prisoners affair, provided conclusive proof that Alsheikh is
dead.

Partly in return for that information, 51 Lebanese prisoners were
freed from El-Khiyam jail in south Lebanon and the bodies of nine
Hizbullah men were returned.

Musawi said he expected International Red Cross officials to be
allowed to inspect Fink and pass the relevant information to the UN,
the radio reports said.

Musawi, echoing other Moslem sources, said he expected another
foreign hostage to be freed by Sunday.  He was apparently referring to
American Joseph Cicippio, the last hostage held by the Revolutionary
Justice Organization which on Tuesday freed the 77-year-old British
World War II fighter ace, Jack Mann.

In Iran, the English-language daily Teheran Times reported again
yesterday that an American hostage would be freed "by the end of the
western weekend."

Cicippio, the deputy comptroller at the American University of
Beirut was kidnapped in September 1986.

Several Moslem spokesmen said they expected Israel to release a
fresh batch of prisoners from El-Khiyam after the freeing of the
American.

But Jerusalem has accused Iran of failing to honour its
commitments to provide Perez de Cueller with conclusive evidence on
Fink.  Officials said the details relayed previously were
insufficient.

Musawi's comments yesterday, if reported accurately, mark the
first time a Hizbullah leader has hinted publicly that the Red Cross
would be allowed to inspect a missing IDF serviceman.

Allison Kaplan adds from Washington:

Iran's Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said this week his
government had no information about missing IAF navigator Ron Arad.

"We don't know anything" about Arad," Velayati told the
Washington Post.

He said that he could "categorically deny" reports that the
missing Israeli transferred to Iran or kept at the Iranian embassy in
Lebanon.

Velayati also pointed the finger at Israel as a source of
information on Iranians who vanished in Beirut in 1982.

He said that Lebanese sources alleged the men were being held in
Israel.

He told the newspaper these "hostages" - four employees of the
Iranian embassy in Beirut and an Iran News photographer - were
important to Iran.

Velayati strongly denied allegations surrounding the so-called
"October surprise" - charges that the Reagan-Bush presidential
campaign negotiated with Iran in 1980 to keep U.S. Embassy hostages
from being freed before the election.

It was the first public comment on the issue from a senior
Iranian official since former Carter administration official Gary Sick
made the allegations.



</PRE>
