<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Thursday, September 26, 1991



Source: DAVID RUDGE, and ALON PINKAS

          Kidnapping.  IDF.

        ISRAEL AWAITING WORD ON MIAS BEFORE ANY ADDITIONAL RELEASES


Israeli officials yesterday rejected reports of the pending
release of a fresh batch of Lebanese prisoners from the El-Khiyam jail
in the security zone in south Lebanon, following the freeing by
Lebanese Shi'ite extremists of British captive Jack Mann.

"We are waiting to receive information about Yossi Fink and
missing South Lebanese Army soldiers, and as long as we don't get this
information there won't be any move on our part," Uri Lubrani, the
government's coordinator on Lebanon, told The Jerusalem Post last
night.

"To the best of my knowledge there is no intention to release any
[Lebanese] prisoners [from El-Khiyam] at this point in time, unless
the conditions mentioned earlier are fulfilled," said Lubrani, who is
heading Israel's negotiating team on the hostages, prisoners and MIAs
issue.

He noted that Israel had been promised irrefutable information
regarding the fate of Givati Brigade soldier Yossi Fink, who was
captured along with Rahamim Alsheikh by Hizbullah gunmen in an ambush
inside the security zone over five years ago.

Previous information relayed by the Hizbullah via UN
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, who is leading the efforts
to solve the affair, provided conclusive proof that Alsheikh was dead.

In return for that information, 51 Lebanese prisoners were
released from the El-Khiyam jail, and the bodies of nine Hizbullah
gunmen were returned to Lebanon.

Danny Naveh, media adviser to Defense Minister Moshe Arens, in a
statement issued yesterday, said Iran had pledged to provide
conclusive proof to de Cuellar regarding the fate of both Fink and
Alsheikh.

Iran, however, had failed to honor its commitments and the
details regarding Fink were insufficient.  Israel had also expressed
to de Cuellar its willingness to release more prisoners, provided it
received, via the secreatry-general, conclusive evidence over the fate
of IAF navigator Ron Arad.  So far such information had not been
forthcoming.

Naveh said Israel utterly rejected recent allegations made by a
Hizbullah leader that the release of Jack Mann was delayed because of
Israel's refusal to release 80 prisoners from the El-Khiyam jail.

He said Israel hoped that the release of Mann would lead to the
freeing of Israel's missing servicemen, as well as the remaining
foreign hostages in Lebanon.

Naveh stressed that Israel fully supported the initiative taken
by de Cuellar and saw his efforts as the only channel through which a
solution to the overall problem could be achieved.

Lubrani expressed optimism that a solution would eventually be
reached, despite the allegations, which he described as "standard
procedure," that had been leveled at Israel by the hostage-holders.

He was highly skeptical of reports in a London newspaper that
Arad was being held by a Palestinian terrorist group and not as
believed by Iranian Revolutionary Guards.

Lubrani said he was confident that Arad was alive, adding that
Israel expected to receive information on him from de Cuellar.

The English language Iranian daily, the Tehran Times, reported
yesterday that another foreign hostage, probably American Joseph
Ciccipo, is expected to be released by the end of this week.

Similar comments have been made by Hizbullah leader Abbas Musawi,
giving credence to the report.  Israeli officials, however, said they
had no information on the matter.

"We would welcome the release of another foreign hostage very
much, should it transpire.  At the same time, we believe that hostage
holders should also make some gesture towards us," lawyer Ory Slonim,
another member of Israel's negotiating team told the Post.

"There is momentum and I believe that all the sides want to solve
the problem.  The other side, however, also wants to squeeze Israel at
every stage in the process," said Slonim, adviser to the Defense
Ministry on the missing servicemen.

The other three MIA's are First Sgt.  Zvi Feldman, Sgt.  Zacharia
Baumel and Cprl.  Yehuda Katz, who have been missing since the Sultan
Yacoub tank battle with a Syrian armored unit in June 1982, in the
early days of the Lebanon War.

Slonim noted that the "address" in the case of these three was
different to that of Fink and Arad.

Israel has always held Syria responsible for the safety and
well-being of the three.

Slonim revealed that de Cuellar was also working on this matter
and was in touch with the Syrian authorities.



</PRE>
