<HEAD>
	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Friday, September 13, 1991

Memo: Analysis

Source: David Rudge

          Zvi Feldman.  Yehuda Katz.  Zacharia Baumel.  Yossi Fink.  Analysis.
          Ron Arad.  IDF.  Prison.

        HOPES RAISED FOR END TO HOSTAGE SAGA


The release of 51 Lebanese prisoners from El-Khiyam jail inside
south Lebanon's security zone and the return of the bodies of nine
Hizbullah gunmen on Wednesday may seem a high price to pay for
reliable information on the sad fate of one missing Israeli
serviceman.

Nevertheless, the very fact that the Hizbullah released such
conclusive evidence about the death of Givati Brigade soldier Rahamim
Alsheikh is a major breakthrough after five-and-a-half years of
silence.

For the Hizbullah to relay credible, corroborative details to
Israel, albeit via intermediaries, is seen by veteran Lebanon watchers
as a crucial step in overcoming the first and most difficult of the
obstacles towards resolving the hostage, prisoners, and MIAs affair
once and for all.

The apparently imminent return to Israel of the body of another
slain IDF serviceman, Druse Sgt.  Samir Assad, in exchange for
allowing a leading Palestinian who was deported from the territories
to return, is likely to further boost hopes for an early end to the
whole issue.

Government sources noted that, although Assad's case was not
directly linked to the hostage/prisoners issue, it was another
positive link in the chain.

Meanwhile, the crux of the hostages and MIA's problem continues
to focus on the Iranians and their Islamic surrogates in Lebanon.

It may well be that at least one of the remaining foreign
hostages will be released in the near future in response to Israel's
gesture on Wednesday.

More tough bargaining, however, confronts the negotiators, led by
UN Secretary-General Perez de Cuellar, before a package deal that
would result in the release of all the foreign hostages and the return
of Israel's MIAs is likely to be consummated.

Israel has outlined its general terms for such a deal in
behind-the-scenes meetings with de Cuellar and his chief aide on the
hostage issue, Giandomenico Picco.  The latter reportedly visited
Israel before joining de Cuellar in Teheran, where the
secretary-general is holding talks on the hostage issue with Iranian
leaders.

It is also uncertain whether the three Israeli servicemen missing
since the June 1982 Sultan Yacub battle with Syrian armoured forces -
Yehuda Katz, Zacharia Baumel, and Zvi Feldman - would be included in
any package deal involving the Hizbullah.

The three were reported to have been captured and later handed
over to the pro-Syrian E-Saika Palestinian terrorist organization.
Nothing officially has been heard of them since, while the Syrians
have consistently denied any knowledge of their wherabouts, despite
repeated requests from international bodies.

Israeli officials stressed that, despite the difficulties,
strenuous efforts are continuing to ascertain the fate of the three
soldiers.

In the meantime, Israel's efforts are concentrating on clarifying
the fate of IDF soldier Yossi Fink, who was captured with Alsheikh in
a Hizbullah ambush in the Beit Yahoun region of the security zone in
February 1986, as well as the whereabouts and wellbeing of Israel Air
Force navigator Ron Arad.

Arad was reportedly handed over to Iranian Revolutionary Guards
stationed in Lebanon by Amal renegade Mustafa Dirani, whose Believers
Resistance group captured him after he ejected from his plane over
Lebanon in October 1986.

Officially, nothing has been heard about Arad's fate since the
first few months after he was taken prisoner.

Despite the complexities and prospects of further tough
negotiations, Israeli officials are optimistic that a deal will be
achieved in the not-too-distant future.

"There's a lot more to be done, but two things have happened
which, hopefully, will help speed-up the process," said a government
source.  "On the one hand, a framework for a solution has been
established, while on the other it has become clear, without a shadow
of doubt, that the Iranians and their proxies in Lebanon, as well as
the Syrians and ourselves, are very keen to solve this problem once
and for all.

"In this context, we could expect to see one or more of the
western hostages released in the near future, perhaps even in the next
few days.  Overall there are real signs of an end to the whole affair,
provided the Iranians don't suddenly change the rules," the source
added.



</PRE>
