<HTML>
<HEAD>
	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Thursday, September 12, 1991

Memo: Lead Story.  Related articles on pages 1 and 2.

Source: ALON PINKAS, DAVID RUDGE and news agencies

          Rahamim Alsheikh.  Yosef Fink.  Kidnapping.  Prison.  IDF.  Iran.
          Lebanon.  Israel.

        'ALL WE WANT TO DO IS BRING BACK OUR POWS'.
LUBRANI CONFIRMS ALSHEIKH DEAD;  SLA FREES 51 IN GOODWILL GESTURE.


UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said he would
redouble his efforts to arrange an exchange of Western hostages in
Lebanon and other captives after Israel freed 51 Arab prisoners
yesterday.

The prisoners, and the bodies of nine Hizbullah terrorists killed
in clashes with the IDF, were released after the Defense Ministry
received information that soldier Rahamim Alsheikh, missing in action
since 1986, was dead.

"The release of the 51 prisoners held by [South Lebanese Army]
Col.  Antoine Lahad in El-Khiam Prison is a gesture of goodwill, the
kind we said would be made in exchange for hard and reliable
information," Uri Lubrani, government coordinator of activities in
Lebanon, said at a Tel Aviv press conference yesterday.

Sources in the Defense Ministry indicated yesterday that they
hoped that the remains of IDF fallen Rachamim Alsheikh would be handed
to Israel in a few days, if not hours.

Information about the fate of Yosef Fink, the second soldier
believed taken prisoner with Alsheikh, was not conclusive, Lubrani
said.

"We do not know that he is not alive," said Lubrani.  "The
information on Alsheikh was conclusive enough to determine that he is
unfortunately dead, but that is not the case in regard to Fink."

He added that he hoped the fate of Samir Assad would be clarified
in a matter of days.

Lubrani also said he had no firm news concerning missing IAF
navigator Ron Arad.

"In this game we have no rules and no regulations," said Lubrani.
"All we want to do is bring back our POWs and MIAs."

The new information received regarding the fate of IDF MIA
Rachamim Alsheikh, and Israel's reciprocal release of 51 Shiites held
by the South Lebanese Army and repatriation of niine bodies of
Hizbullah men killed is a step in the right direction, said Lubrani.

"It is a first step and a result of laborious efforts on our and
UN Secretary General de-Cuellar's part," said Lubrani.

Nevertheless, he added, his public announcement was not a new way
of conducting business.  "We will continue using quiet and cautious
diplomacy in our efforts to reveal the whereabouts of the other six
MIAs," Lubrani emphasized.

Asked whether Israel would allow the International Red Cross to
visit Sheikh Karim Obeid, snatched and held by Israel since 1989,
Lubrani said that "Yes.  But only when the Red Cross will be allowed
to visit our remaining POW's".

Meanwhile in Tehran, the UN chief's spokesman, Francois Giuliani,
said in a statement: "The secretary-general is very happy with this
news and very encouraged by this further step."

Sources close to the negotiations for the release of the
Westerners voiced optimism over a possible end to the hostage affair
after Israel broke a stalemate by freeing the 51 Lebanese and handing
over the bodies of nine guerrillas.

"There is movement," said one non-Iranian source just before
Israel completed the handover in what it said was a goodwill gesture
to help UN efforts to end the hostage saga.  The SLA still holds more
than 300 Arabs captured in Lebanon.

"We are not speaking about six weeks or six months," he added,
apparently referring to a solution to the entire hostage affair.  The
source was speaking on condition he was not named.

UN officials said the hostages were one of the issues discussed
with Iranian leaders yesterday by Perez de Cuellar on the first full
day of a visit to Tehran.

There was no immediate comment on the Israeli move from Iran,
which has been seen as a key player because it commands the allegiance
of Shi'ite Moslem Lebanese guerrillas holding up to 10 Westerners.

Iran and Shi'ite Lebanese leaders had demanded that Israel make a
move since kidnappers released a British and an American hostage last
month and asked Perez de Cuellar to arrange an overall swap.

One signal that something was in the air was the fact that Perez
de Cuellar's hostage trouble-shooter, Giandomenico Picco, arrived in
Tehran yesterday, a day after the UN chief.  He would not say where he
had been.

The secretary-general held more than four hours of talks with
Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani and Foreign Minister Ali
Akbar Velayati on hostages, Afghanistan, Gulf security and the
aftermath of the Iran-Iraq war.

Leading members of the radical pro-Iranian Hizbullah indicated
yesterday that some foreign hostages may be released in the near
future in the wake of the release.

Sheikh Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, spiritual leader of the
fundamentalist Shi'ite organization, told news agency reporters that
the release created "an atmosphere conducive to positive results."

Moslem cleric Hussein Musawi, a member of the Hizbullah ruling
council, went a step further, saying he expected some of the Western
hostages to be freed soon.

The Amal renegade said, however, he did not know when such a
release was likely to take place, saying it could be "next week, next
month or more."

Twenty nine of those released yesterday were taken to a crossing
point on the northern border of the security zone, near Tibnin village
and released.  Several returned to the market town of Nabatiya.



</PRE>
