<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Thursday, September 12, 1991

Memo: Related articles on pages 1 and 2

Illustration: 4 Photos

Caption: IDF servicemen still missing include Zacharia Baumel, Yehuda
Katz, Zvi Feldman and Samir Assad.

Source: DAVID RUDGE

          Baumel.  Yehuda Katz.  Zvi Feldman.  Samir Assad.

        INFORMATION SCARCE ON THOSE STILL MISSING


The five other IDF servicemen missing or believed held as
prisoners in Lebanon include Zacharia Baumel, Yehuda Katz and Zvi
Feldman.

The three have been missing since the June 1982 confrontation
with Syrian armored units in what came to be known as the Sultan Yacub
battle.

They were reported to have been seen in a "victory" parade in
Damascus a short time later aboard a captured IDF tank.  They were
then believed to have been handed over to the Syrian-backed A-Saiqa
Palestinian terrorist organization.  Since then nothing has been heard
or seen of them.

A year later, in April 1983, Druse soldier Sgt.  Samir Assad was
captured by members of Naif Hawatmeh's Democratic Front for the
Liberation of Palestine (DFLP) in the Sidon area of Lebanon.

The DFLP claimed that Assad was subsequently killed in an Israel
Air Force raid on Rabbit Island near Tripoli in northern Lebanon.
Israeli officials, however, maintained that the story was concocted to
cover up his murder by the terrorists.

Assad's family, from the Druse village of Beit Jann, on Mount
Meiron, still hope against hope that he is alive, although local
residents said yesterday that the chances of him returning home alive
are very slim.

There have been reports lately that a separate deal might soon be
worked out concerning Assad.  This was confirmed by Uri Lubrani, the
government's corodinator on Lebanon who is handling the issue of
Israel's MIA's.  Lubrani said yesterday that some progress had been
made in the case of the missing Druse soldier.

The seventh missing Israeli, IAF navigator Ron Arad, was captured
by the Amal Shi'ite organization after ejecting from his plane over
Lebanon in October 1986.

He was later reportedly handed over to a contingent of the
Iranian Revolutionary Guard in Lebanon by Amal's former security chief
Mustafa Dirani who defected from the organization.  Dirani reportedly
received a large sum of money for handing over Arad.

Apart from letters and photographs sent to Arad's family, nothing
had been heard about the fate of the other MIA's until yesterday.

There has been a plethora of reports from Amal and Arab sources
recently over the whereabouts and fate of Arad.  None of the reports,
however, has been officially confirmed.



</PRE>
