<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Friday, August 30, 1991



Source: Compiled from news agencies

          Person.  IDF.

        EX-AMAL OFFICIAL CLAIMS NO KNOWLEDGE OF ARAD


Former Amal security head, Mustafa Deirani, said in a statement
broadcast by several Beirut radio station that he has no information
about Ron Arad, one of seven missing Israeli servicemen whose fate is
linked to the release of Western hostages in Lebanon.

Deirani was fired as Amal security chief in 1988.

The leadership of Amal claims Deirani took Arad with him to
Baalbek and later sold him for $500,000 to the Revolutionary Guards
who smuggled him to Iran via Syria.

"This claim is untrue and irresponsible," Deirani said in his
statement.  "I am not responsible for any misdeeds that occurred after
my dismissal."

UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said yesterday he is
awaiting developments in the hostage situation and hopes for a
prisoner exchange "in the next few weeks."

"I am waiting," he said, "I am in the role of broker, going from
one side to another."

In Teheran yesterday, a radical Lebanese Shi'ite Moslem leader
renewed demands for U.S. pressure on Israel to free Arab prisoners as
a step to gain release of Western hostages, Iran's Islamic Republic
News Agency reported.

The agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Sheik Abbas Musavi as
saying in Teheran Wednesday that the U.S. is delaying the release of
hostages in Lebanon for political gain.

Hizbullah has said it is holding two of the Israelis, but has
refused to provide further information until some of the Arab
prisoners are freed.

In Jerusalem yesterday, Defense Ministry spokesman Dan Naveh
urged the media to tone down their coverage of the hostage issue,
claiming they were becoming a channel for wrong information and
propaganda.

Naveh's comments followed statements this week by Amal that it
holds two of the seven Israeli servicemen missing in Lebanon, and that
missing Israeli navigator Ron Arad was sold to the Iranian
Revolutionary Guards for $500,000.

Naveh said Israel has no news on Arad other than the Amal
announcement published in the press, and called on Teheran to admit
the Israeli is in Iran.



</PRE>
