<HEAD>
	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif" >
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Sunday, May 22, 1994

Memo: Lead Story

Illustration: Two Photos

Caption: 1. Shi'ite Muslim leader Mustafa Dirani in 1992 file photo. 2.
The house where Shi'ite leader Mustafa Dirani was seized by Israeli
commandos in east Lebanon's Bekaa Valley early Saturday morning.
Credit: AP

Source: ALON PINKAS

          Lebanon.  Hizbullah.  Ron Arad.  Israel.  Missing Person.
Leadership.

        IDF KIDNAPS SHI'ITE LEADER DIRANI IN LEBANON.
'BELIEVERS RESISTANCE' HEAD HELD RON ARAD FROM 1986 TO 1988.


MUSTAFA Dirani, the head of a Hizbullah-affiliated group which
held missing air force navigator Ron Arad from 1986 to 1988, was
snatched by helicopter-borne IDF commandos from his home in Lebanon's
Bek'a Valley early yesterday morning.

Dirani heads the "Believers' Resistance," an organization linked
to Hizbullah.  He is being interrogated in an undisclosed location.
According to OC Military Intelligence Maj.  -Gen.  Uri Saguy, Dirani
has "already provided some answers to questions we asked for a long
time."

Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin indicated the operation grew out of
frustration that Syrian President Hafez Assad had spurned US President
Bill Clinton's appeal earlier this year to help determine the fate of
the missing Israeli solders.

Hizbullah vowed yesterday to step up actions against Israel in
response to Dirani's kidnapping.

"The enemy has resorted to the option of expanding the scope of
confrontation," the head of Hizbullah's politburo, Hussein Khalil,
told news agencies.  "This will put it [Israel] in a huge predicament
in the future because the resistance in return will respond  ...  in a
way that adopts expanding the scope of fighting."

Chief of General Staff Lt.  -Gen.  Ehud Barak told military
correspondents the operation was "meticulously planned, making full
and effective use of the element of surprise, and was executed
impeccably, with the highest professional standards conceivable."

Barak revealed that one soldier was slightly wounded in the hip
by shrapnel, when shots were fired from the adjacent home, belonging
to Dirani's brother.

At approximately 2 a.m., an IDF force entered the village of
Kasarnaba in the Syrian-controlled Bek'a Valley.  "The terrain is
hilly, tough, and the village itself is at the bottom of a very steep
hillside.  That made both the landing and advance extremely
difficult," Barak said.

The IDF unit was transported to the Bek'a in two CH-53
helicopters, which flew north along the Lebanese coast, then veered
east north of Beirut, and followed the Beirut-Damascus highway, along
the backbone of the central ridge of the Lebanese mountains.

The helicopters landed and discharged the ground force, which
advanced down the slope to the relatively large village of 5,000
residents.  Unconfirmed reports from Lebanon claim that the force used
4x4 vehicles.

"The force was in the area for several hours, but the actual
operation in the village lasted a few minutes," said Barak.  "We
ordered the force not to harm Dirani's family or any other civilians,
even when shot at."

The force then stormed the first-floor apartment and tied up
Dirani, his wife, and his brother.  Dirani's children, three boys and
two girls ages 2 to 11, were kept in another room.  One of Dirani's
sons told news agencies that the soldiers were in thhe house "for seven
minutes." Army sources confirmed that estimate.

Barak and Saguy both stressed that the force was ordered to
refrain from any contact with Syrian units deployed in the area.  The
village, which lies north of the old Riak airfield, is surrounded by
Syrian anti-aircraft batteries.  The two helicopters carried the force
and Dirani back to Israel, and were apparently shot at by Lebanese
anti-aircraft guns north of Beirut.

Barak said the operation serves as both "a contribution to
Israel's deterrent power and a moral debt we owe Ron Arad, about whose
whereabouts we may now learn some more."

Asked about the operation's timing, Barak revealed that in fact,
it was planned several months ago, but put off "because some
components necessary to insure success were missing."

Until 1988, Dirani, 46, headed the pro-Syrian Amal militia's
military arm, responsible for numerous operations against Israel and
the South Lebanese Army.  Dirani is believed to have held Arad since
he parachuted from his Phantom jet in October 1986.

In 1988, Dirani is believed to have "sold" Arad to the
Iranian-backed revolutionary guards for $300,000.  Since then, Arad's
whereabouts remain unknown, although Israel has indications that he
was alive well after 1988.

Saguy said that between 1986 and 1988, Dirani negotiated the
release of Arad, but when he broke with Amal's head, Nabih Berri, and
formed his own group, affiliated with Hizbullah, negotiations broke
down, and Arad was eventually handed over to the revolutionary guards.

The kidnapping of Dirani was almost a carbon copy of the
abduction of Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid in south Lebanon in July 1989,
though Obeid was taken to be used as a bargaining chip in the return
of the MIAs, and Barak denied that Dirani was taken for this purpose.
Obeid is still being held.

In February 1992, Israel also assassinated Hizbullah operations
leader Sheikh Abbas Musawi, when helicopter gunships ambushed his
motorcade in south Lebanon.  "This is a continuous and unrelenting war
against terrorism.  Any vacillation will result in paralysysis said
Barak.

"One of the lessons of Obeid's kidnapping is that we still lacked
vital intelligence data.  The primary purpose of getting Dirani was to
enhance our intelligence-gathering capability.  In this sense, we
already achieved partial success, although it will take time to
interrogate him and study the documents we found in his home," Saguy
said.  .

But the two previous operations also precipitated a violent
response from Hizbullah, which included Katyusha rocket barrages on
northern Israel.

"I expect Dirani's organization to respond, but I don't think
this will trigger a response from Hizbullah," said Barak.

On Friday, IDF helicopter gunships strafed Arab gunmen who had
attacked the security zone, Lebanese security sources told news
agencies.

The sources said unidentified gunmen raked four positions manned
by the South Lebanese Army with rocket-propelled grenade and automatic
rifle fire.

The attacks on the security zone provoked a four-hour clash with
SLA militiamen and Israeli soldiers.

The sources said the Israeli helicopters fired at least 10
rockets at the attackers.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
