<HEAD>
	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Sunday, August 18, 1991



Source: MICHEL ZLOTOWSKI

          Hizbullah.  Roger Auque.

        LUBRANI MET HIZBULLAH IN 1989, FRENCH NEWSPAPER CONFIRMS


PARIS - A French newspaper today confirms an earlier report that
Israel's government coordinator for activities in Lebanon Uri Lubrani
met a high official of Hizbullah in France in 1989.

The French weekly, Le Journal du Dimanche, writes about the first
encounter between the two, confirming report in The Jerusalem Post
last week.

According to the French weekly, French journalist and former
hostage in Lebanon Roger Auque was vacationing in Saint-Tropez, a
resort on the French Riviera, in the summer of 1989.

Auque was sitting on the terrace of a cafe with two friends - a
Lebanese businessman and a Palestinian - when he was approached by an
Israeli who introduced himself as a member of Israel's Defense
Ministry.  After chatting over drinks, the four went for a short ride
on a speed boat, laughing at the uncommon situation.

Auque met again with his new Israeli friend, this time in
September 1989 in Israel.  The Israeli officer told him then that Uri
Lubrani wanted to see him.

Lubrani already knew that Auque's friend, the Lebanese
businessman, had good connections with the Hizbullah, according to the
report.  Lubrani asked Auque to arrange a meeting for him with the
businessman.

In December 1989, Lubrani flew to Paris and met Auque's Lebanese
friend at a dinner organized by Auque.  Lubrani told the Lebanese
businessman that he was ready to meet with representatives of
Hizbullah, provided the Iran-supported group sent proof that it was
holding Israeli hostages.

A few weeks later, a photo of Israel Air Force navigator Ron
Arad, captured in Lebanon in 1986, reached Israel.  Obviously, the
connection was the right one.  But the negotiations dragged on before
the meetings, held last May and June in France, between Israelis and
the Hizbullah, under the auspices of former French ambassador to
Beirut Rene Ala.

Apparently, the negotiations stopped, because Hizbullah did not
come up with tangible proof that the Israelis missing in action were
still alive and detained by groups which Hizbullah could influence.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
</CENTER>
