<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Sunday, August 18, 1991



Source: JONATHAN FREEDLAND


        ARAD BEING HELD BY IRANIAN RADICAL GROUP - 'SUNDAY TIMES'


LONDON - Hostage release negotiations are stuck over the case of
IAF navigator Ron Arad, according to the Sunday Times.

The paper reported that Arad, shot down over Lebanon in 1986, is
being held in the Bekaa Valley by Iranian Revolutionary Guards, and
not by the Beirut kidnapers thought to be holding the remaining six
Israeli PoWs and MiAs and other Western hostages.

The Sunday Times said Israeli intelligence fears Iran will not
want to admit it holds a hostage directly and that, as a result, no
deal involving Arad will be possible.  It is thought Arad was handed
to the Iranians during a split in the pro-Syrian faction that
originally captured him.

Israel is reportedly hoping that the Revolutionary Guards - who
were sent to Lebanon to fight against Israel in the 1982 war - will
turn Arad over to Hizbullah, the pro-Iranian group wihich is holding
most of the hostages.  That way he could become part of the exchange
deal that Uri Lubrani is thought to have been negotiating in Geneva
last week with UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.

Any more hostage releases are unlikely for at least another few
weeks, as the "real business" of dealing has only just begun,
according to the paper.



</PRE>
