<HEAD>
	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Sunday, August 11, 1991



Illustration: Photo

Caption: The Baumels, whose son, Sgt.  Zacharia Baumel was reported
missing in action in the early stages of the war in Lebanon, expects a
long and painful process.
Credit: Debbi Cooper

Source: GREER FAY CASHMAN

          Perception.  Government.

        ISRAELI HOSTAGES' FAMILIES KEEPING HOPE IN CHECK


The families of seven Israeli servicemen captured or missing in
Lebanon have a fresh sliver of hope for their release, but that
optimism is guarded.

British journalist John McCarthy was freed by the pro-Iranian
Islamic Jihad on Thursday after five years of captivity in Lebanon,
and an American hostage is reportedly to be released this week.

"We have had enough disappointments.  We have to be realistic,"
Uri Lubrani, government coordinator for Lebanese affairs, said on
Israel Television on Friday night.  I want to see our soldiers freed,
and as long as this does not happen we will have to be tense and
expectant."

"We don't allow ourselves to be carried away by newspaper
headlines," said Merton Fink, the father of captured soldier Yosef
Fink.  Nothing has been heard from the younger Fink or fellow Givati
Brigade member Rahamim Alsheikh since their capture in February 1986.

"We believe that our boy is alive, but until we have something
concrete, until we have proof, we won't allow ourselves to be carried
away," Fink said in a telephone interview.  "If we did, we'd end up in
an asylum."

Fink was not sure what to make of the events surrounding
McCarthy's release.  "We hope that it will be the beginning of a
process which will include the Israelis," he said.  "We're just taking
it day by day."

"There's always hope," said Pnina Feldman, the mother of Staff
Sgt.  Zvi Feldman who, with Sgt.  Zacharia Baumel and Cpl.  Yehuda
Katz, was reported missing in action in the early stages of the war in
Lebanon.  The three Israelis had been engaged in a tank battle with a
Syrian armoured unit in the Beka'a Valley.

Feldman is encouraged by the fact that nothing was heard of
McCarthy for some time before it became known that he had been taken
hostage.  "As a mother, I wish that maybe this time the Hizbullah will
keep its word  ...  but I won't be jumping for joy until I see [Zvi]
on Israeli soil.  Perhaps, at last, things will turn out well."

Whenever a hostage is allowed to leave Lebanon, the families of
remaining hostages are put under intense emotional and psychological
stress.  They are subjected to a barrage of phone calls day and night
from all over the world, mostly from the news media, pressuring them
with the same old questions, seeking to add another dimension to a
story with an endlessly elusive final chapter.

"It's bothersome, but we're used to it," said Baumel's father,
Yona.  Like the other parents, he is not on the verge of euphoria.
"The ball is still in the Arab court." Even if the the message carried
by McCarthy to UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar does
advance negotiations for the release of all the hostages, Baumel
predicted that it would be a long and painful process.

The Hizbullah, he noted, was playing true to form, by indicating
that someone else would soon be released.  "It's part of their
psychological warfare program."

Baumel and his wife have not always agreed with government policy
on measures to secure the freedom of the missing Israeli servicemen.
"They've made some terrible mistakes," he said, "but today we see eye
to eye with the government.  Our contention is that they're doing more
than any other country would."

If Baumel and the other parents have from time to time, been
angry and impatient with the government, they have been more upset by
new reporting about their situation.

Fink said he was annoyed by some things he had read in Friday's
Hebrew newspapers.

Baumel cited a Sky Channel report Thursday saying the only
missing Israeli thought to be alive was Israel Air Force navigator Ron
Arad, who ejected over southern Lebanon in October 1986.

"I think I can say that the report is patently false," said
Baumel, who has never faltered in his faith that his son is alive.  He
has eyewitness evidence to make that belief more than just wishful
thinking.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
