<HTML>
<HEAD>
	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Sunday, August 11, 1991

Memo: Lead Story.

Source: ALON PINKAS and news agencies

          Perception.  US.  UN.  Jerome Leyrand.  Kidnapping.

        THREAT TO KILL KIDNAPED FRENCHMAN COULD BLOCK RELEASE OF U.S.
HOSTAGE


United Nations and U.S. officials were hopeful yesterday that
pro-Iranian Lebanese kidnapers holding two U.S. hostages would release
one in the next two or three days.

UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said his envoy in
the region had confirmed a statement released to a news agency
yesterday that a group holding Joseph Cicippio and Edward Austin Tracy
since 1986 would release one within 72 hours.

President George Bush said yesterday "there is an expectation"
that Lebanese kidnapers could free a second Western hostage soon and
the White House urged governments with influence on the captors to
work to free the hostages.

But the kidnapers of French aid worker Jerome Leyrand again
threatened to kill him to try to block the reported release.

Meanwhile Uri Lubrani, the government's coordinator of activities
in Lebanon, said last night negotiations to release the hostages are
stalled because of the kidnaped Frenchman.

Perez de Cuellar said he had spoken to UN envoy Giandomenico
Picco, who is in Lebanon, and that Picco had confirmed news reports of
an imminent release.

"I had confirmation that they have exactly the same information
that we have - that at least one will be released within three days,"
the UN chief said.  "After what I have heard, I am rather hopeful."

Perez de Cuellar was speaking to reporters in New York just
before leaving for Britain, where today he is to meet former hostage
John McCarthy.

McCarthy, who was freed by his Islamic Jihad captors on Thursday,
will deliver a sealed letter from them to the secretary-general.

The counter-claims appeared to escalate a growing fight among
Iranian-backed kidnap factions on whether to participate in a deal.

Senior military sources also said last night Israel would not bow
to British government pressure to release the Lebanese prisoners it
holds in order to facilitate the freeing of the western hostages in
Lebanon.

The sources reiterated Israel's position that it is only willing
to release the prisoners in a deal which would include the seven IDF
soldiers believed to be held as prisoners or missing in Lebanon.

Dr. Ahmed Tibi, an Israeli Arab from Taibe, came back from
meetings with PLO officials in Geneva yesterday, saying he had
information concerning two of the missing soldiers.  He said that the
PLO is holding the body of First Sgt.  Samir Assad and has indications
that IAF navigator Ron Arad is alive and well.  There was no
independent confirmation of Tibi's claims.

The pro-Iranian Revolutionary Justice Organisation (RJO), which
holds two 60-year-old American hostages, said in a statement sent to
an international news agency yesterday it would release one within 72
hours.

"Generally speaking, we think there is an expectation" a hostage
could be freed, Bush said, speaking from his holiday home at
Kennebunkport, Maine, adding that the United States wants to "run down
every lead we can, but not raise the hopes of the hostage families".

A White House statement, issued earlier by presidential spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater, stressed that the administration had no direct
information from the captors on any pending release.

"We reiterate that now is the time for all hostages and others
held outside of the legal system in the region to be released
immediately, unconditionally and safely for humanitarian reasons,"
Fitzwater's statement said.  "We call on all governments with
influence to make this happen," said the statement.

Fitzwater said a U.S. medical team remained on standby at a U.S.
base in Wiesbaden, Germany, in case any Americans were released.
Previous freed U.S. hostages have been taken there.

Hours after McCarthy was freed, a rival Lebanese group that is
opposed to freeing the hostages seized Frenchman Jerome Leyraud.

The group, calling itself the Organisation for Defending
Prisoners' and Hostages' Rights, said it would kill Leyraud if any
other captives were released.

With Leyraud, Lebanese extremist groups are now holding 12
Western hostages as part of their attempts to put pressure on
governments to persuade Israel to free hundreds of Arab prisoners.

The remaining Western hostages in Lebanon include six Americans,
two Britons, two Germans, and an Italian.  One of them, U.S.
journalist Terry Anderson, has been held for more than six years.

Britain on Friday publicly urged Israel to release some of the
more than 300 mostly Shi'ite prisoners held by Israel and its allies
in south Lebanon.

British Foreign Office Minister Douglas Hogg on Friday summoned
Israeli Ambassador Yoav Biran to press Israel to secure the release of
Arabs prisoners and a kidnaped sheik held by Israeli allies in south
Lebanon, officials said.

The RJO stressed that a final settlement to the ordeal of Western
hostages hinged on the release of prisoners held by Israel and its
allies, notably Sheik Abdel-Karim Obeid, a Shi'ite Muslim activist
kidnaped by Israel in 1989.

Statements released last month demanded their freedom, but no
deal has ever been mentioned.

The stance taken repeatedly by Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah,
Hezbollah's main cleric in Lebanon, as well as the governments of Iran
and Syria who helped spring hostages in the past, is that they want
the hostage file closed.

Fadlallah met with Iran's hardline interior minister, Abdollah
Nouri, in Damascus on Saturday.  Nouri is a key figure in the Iranian
Revolutionary Guards who maintain camps in Lebanon and are the main
link between Iran and the hostage takers.

The abduction of Leyraud, a 26-year-old relief worker with the
Paris-based Medecins du Monde or Doctors of the World, has angered and
embarrassed Syria, which is largely responsible for security in the
city.

Lebanese riot policemen backed by Syrian troops started a series
of quiet house raids in Beirut to locate Leyraud.

"We've raided at least a dozen suspected hideouts.  The outcome
is encouraging," the operation's commander, Lebanese police Maj.
Mohammed Qassem, told The Associated Press.  He would give no details.

The state-run national news agency said security forces were
"expected to secure Leyraud's release in 48 hours." It did not
elaborate.

Longest held is American journalist Terry Anderson, 43, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press.  He was kidnaped
March 16, 1985.

Anderson's sister said yesterday that Israeli willingness to free
Obeid could trigger the release of all the captured Westerners.

"Right now if Israel took that leap of faith and released perhaps
Sheikh Obeid, that would be the catalyst that would allow everything
else to fall into place," Anderson's sister, Peggy Say, told
reporters.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
