	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Friday, August 9, 1991

Memo: Box at end of text.

Source: DAVID RUDGE; Post Defense Correspondent adds

          IDF.  Kidnapping.  Ron Arad.

        ISRAEL WELCOMES RELEASE, HOPES FOR FURTHER EXCHANGE


Israel yesterday welcomed the release of British hostage John
McCarthy and expressed its willingness to participate in a prisoner
exchange provided Israelis believed held in Lebanon were included.

Danny Naveh, media adviser to Defense Minister Moshe Arens,
issued a statement saying that Israel welcomed McCarthy's release and
extended warm wishes to him and his family.

The government wanted to see, it said, the release of more
hostages and the beginning of a process that would speedily lead to
the release of all prisoners and hostages held by various factions in
Lebanon.

The statement said the government would continue to make every
effort to bring about the release of all the hostages, including
Israeli servicemen believed to be held as prisoners or missing in
Lebanon.

Naveh reiterated previous calls to the organizations believed to
be holding the IDF soldiers to allow the Red Cross to visit them, or
to provide proof they are alive.

In such circumstances, Israel would be willing to conduct
negotiations for the release of Lebanese detained by Israel in
exchange for the hostages, prisoners and those missing in Lebanon.

There were unconfirmed reports yesterday that the note given to
McCarthy by his kidnappers, the Islamic Jihad, to pass to UN
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, contained a message
relating to IAF navigator Ron Arad.

Arad was captured by the Shi'ite organization Amal after ejecting
from his plane over south Lebanon in October 1986, but was later
handed over to the Iranian Revolutionary Guard in Lebanon.  Apart from
documents and photographs sent to Arad's family at the time he was in
Amal's hands, nothing has been heard of him.

A few months earlier, in February 1986, the pro-Iranian Hizbullah
fundamentalists kidnapped Givati Brigade soldiers Yosef Fink and
Rahamim Alsheikh inside the security zone in south Lebanon.  Nothing
has been heard of their fate since.

The four other IDF soldiers missing in Lebanon are First Sgt.
Zvi Feldman, Sgt.  Zacharia Baumel and Cpl.  Yehuda Katz.  They went
missing after a tank battle with a Syrian armored unit in Lebanon's
Beka'a Valley in the early days of the Lebanon War.

They were subsequently reported to have been taken by the
pro-Syrian Saika Palestinian organization.  Israel has said it holds
Syria responsible for the safety and well being of the three.

The seventh missing soldier, Druse Sgt.  Samir Assad, was
kidnapped by Naif Hawatmeh's Democratic Front for the Liberation of
Palestine in the Sidon area in April 1983.  The organization reported
that Assad had been killed in an IAF raid on Rabbit Island near
Tripoli the following year.  Officials here, however, maintained they
had information that Assad was not killed in the raid.

Baumel's father Yona told Israel Radio yesterday that he believed
his son was still alive and well after nine years in captivity.

Yona Baumel, who also holds an American passport, revealed that
he had traveled extensively in Arab countries and had received
information about his son, including from somebody who had seen and
spoken with him.

Baumel said he had implicit faith in the government and its
handling of the prisoner situation.

He maintained that families who, in previous prisoner exchange
deals, had pressed the government to pay any price to secure the
release of their sons had damaged Israel's interests.  "We have tried
to be responsible and will continue to act responsibly, and we won't
put pressure on the government publicly do do anything unacceptable,"
Baumel said.

Government coordinator on Lebanon Uri Lubrani expressed cautious
optimism yesterday, while warning against building up too much hope.
"I have learned to see what I see and not raise my level of
expectation too much," he told The Jerusalem Post.

Lubrani, who was also interviewed on Israel and Army radio, said
that "unfortunately" there was no indication at this stage that the
Hizbullah was ready to release Israeli servicemen.

Nevertheless, he expressed the hope that the release of McCarthy
heralded the start of a process that would terminate in the release of
all the hostages and prisoners held and missing in Lebanon.

Lubrani stressed that Israel would want to contribute to any such
release, but only if it included the freeing of the missing Israeli
servicemen.

Lubrani said the release of McCarthy seemed to indicate that
Hizbullah and its Iranian mentors had come to the realization that the
holding of hostages and prisoners of war was no longer and asset but a
liability.

(Box) Wife renews hope

The wife of IAF navigator Ron Arad, captured by Lebanese
militiamen four years ago, said moves on Western hostages gave her "a
good feeling, hope for a prisoner exchange."

"I hope our story will finish soon," Tami Arad said yesterday on
the Mabat TV news.  She has heard nothing from him except for one
letter and photo, but she is sure he is alive.

She appealed to Arad's captors to "allow the Red Cross to meet
you and take a letter and photo from him, so his daughter, who doesn't
know him at all, can see what he looks like."



</PRE>
