<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Friday, July 19, 1991



Source: DAVID RUDGE and news agencies

          Jihad.  Islam.  Israel.  Missing Person.

        OFFICIALS DUBIOUS OVER PRISONER EXCHANGE BID


A militant Palestinian group of Moslem fundamentalists yesterday
offered to help arrange an exchange of Israeli prisoners for
Palestinians and Lebanese, but the Defense Ministry in Jerusalem said
the offer was vague and dubious.

"The Islamic Jihad Movement in Palestine expresses its
willingness to facilitate the process of exchanging Israeli prisoners
held by the Islamic resistance in return for the release of
Palestinian and Lebanese mujahideen held in Israeli jails," the
organisation said.

The group, in a statement handed to an international news agency
in Amman, said it could also help arrange for the International
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) to visit Israeli prisoners in
Lebanon.

But Israel must first set free four Moslem leaders and give a
public commitment that it would release all the other Arab detainees,
it said in the one-page statement signed by spokesman Fathi
al-Shuqaqi.

The Defense Ministry spokesman here said in a statement: "The
announcement made by the body called Islamic Jihad is vague.

"[It] does not clarify the identity of the Israeli captives in
question and we have no proof which lends truth to the claim of the
organization that it holds, or that an element called the Islamic
Opposition holds, Israeli captives."

"This is an attempt to try and extract some questionable benefit
by taking advantage of this painful humanitarian problem," the
statement said.

But it added that Israel would consider "any proposal or demand
for the release of prisoners" if it was given proof that its captives
were alive and "in the hands of those elements raising proposals."

The four "Moslem leaders" cited in Islamic Jihad's statement are
Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, leader of the Moslem fundamentalist movement
Hamas; Nidal Zaloum, sentenced for stabbing dead two elderly Israelis
in Jerusalem; Abdel-Hadi Ghneim, who killed 14 people in 1989 by
forcing Bus 405 off the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem road; and Eitaf Uleyyan.

The group said it was making its offer "after coordination and
consultation with our brothers in the Lebanese Islamic resistance
movement".

But it did not spell out what it could do to help secure the
release of the Israelis or say how many Arab prisoners it wanted the
Israeli authorities to set free.

The Hizbullah, and its affiliated groups, is believed to be
holding Yosef Fink and Rahamim Alsheikh, who were both kidnapped by
Islamic fundamentalists near Beit Yahoun in February 1986.

Navigator Ron Arad was captured originally by the Shi'ite Amal
organization after ejecting form his plane over Lebanon in October
1986.  He was later reported to have been handed over to Iranian
Revolutionary Guard by Mustafa Durani, who defected from Amal.

Apart from documents and photographs sent to Arad's family,
nothing has been heard of him.

The four other IDF men missing in Lebanon are First Sergeant Zvi
Feldman, Sergeant Zechariah Boumel, and Corporal Yehuda Katz who went
missing after the Sultan Yacoub tank battle with a Syrian armoured
unit in Lebanon's Beka valley in the early days of the Lebanese war.

They were subsdequently reported to have been captured by a
pro-Syrian Palestinian organization Esaika organization.  Israel has
said it holds Syria responsible for the safety and well-being of these
three missing soldiers.

The other missing soldier, Druse Sergeant Samir Assad, was
kidnapped by Naif Hawatmeh's Democratic Front for the Liberation of
Palestine in the Sidon area in April 1983.

The organiztion later reported he had been killed in an Israeli
air raid on Rabbit Island near Tripoli the following year.  But
officials here maintain they have official information that Assad was
not killed in that raid.

The Defense Ministry statement here, "using this opportunity,"
expressed satisfaction that "an SLA company commander held by Mustafa
Sa'ad, head of the Nasserist organization in Sidon, was freed released
in exchange for two terrorists who were detained in Al-Hiram prison.

"In this case," it added, "a humanitarian approach and common
sense were victorious.  "



</PRE>
