<HTML>
<HEAD>
	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Monday, June 10, 1991



Source: DAVID RUDGE, Jerusalem Post Reporter

          Visit.  Hizbullah.  Abdel Karim Obeid.  Lebanon.

        VISITS MUST BE RECIPROCAL - OBEID AND IDF SOLDIERS


Israel would allow Red Cross representatives to visit captured
regional Hizbullah leader Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid if, simultaneously,
reciprocal visits were made by members of the international
organization to Israeli servicemen believed to be held by the
Hizbullah and other groups in Lebanon, The Jerusalem Post has learned.

Government officials have made it clear - in response to recent
offers by the Hizbullah to swap the Israeli servicemen for Lebanese
and Palestinians held by Israel - that Israel wants proof and "signs
of life" from the Israeli prisoners.

Only then would Israel be willing to negotiate the release of
Lebanese detainees, including Obeid, who was snatched by IDF
paratroopers from his home in Jibshit village in South Lebanon in July
1989.

Israel has repeatedly called for Red Cross officials to be
allowed to visit the servicemen.

Of the seven Israelis missing in Lebanon, two, Yossi Fink and
Rahamim Alsheikh, who were kidnapped near Beit Yahoun in South Lebanon
in 1986, are believed to be held by the Hizbullah.

Navigator Ron Arad was captured by the Amal Shi'ite movement
later the same year after ejecting from his plane over Lebanon.  He
was taken by former Amal security chief Mustafa Dirani, who
subsequently defected from Amal and reportedly transferred Arad,
apparently in good health, to members of the Iranian Revolutionary
Guard, a group controlled by Iran, in Lebanon.

Three other soldiers, Zacharia Baumel, Yehuda Katz and Zvi
Feldman, have been missing since the June 1982 tank battle with Syrian
forces in the Sultan Ya'acub region of eastern Lebanon.  A year later,
Druse soldier Samir Assad was kidnapped in Lebanon by members of Naif
Hawatmeh's Palestinian terror group.

With the exception of letters and photographs sent to the family
of Arad, nothing has been heard, officially, about the fate of the
other soldiers since they were missing.

Government sources have announced in the past that visits by the
Red Cross to Israelis believed to be held as prisoners in Lebanon
would be reciprocated.  The policy, laid down by former defense
minister Yitzhak Rabin, has apparently not changed in this respect.

The Hizbullah, for its part, is demanding the release of around
400 Lebanese and Palestinians held by Israel in exchange for the
Israelis it is holding.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
</CENTER>
