	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Tuesday, May 28, 1991



Source: DAVID RUDGE / Jerusalem Post Reporter and news agencies

          Palestinian.  Yossi Fink.  Rahamim Alsheikh.  Lebanon.  Prison.

        HIZBULLAH ADMITS HOLDING IDF MEN, CLARIFIES SWAP TERMS


New Hizbullah leader Abbas Musawi confirmed yesterday for the
first time in three years that his group is holding two IDF servicemen
as prisoners.

In an interview broadcast on the leftist Voice of the People
radio station, Musawi said "We have two Israeli prisoners and a few
soldiers of [South Lebanese Army commander Gen. Antoine] Lahad's
force."

Musawi also clarified his terms for a possible prisoner exchange,
saying that the Hizbullah wanted to secure the release of all the
captives held by Israel and Lahad.

The Lebanese press said that Musawi was not satisfied with the
public response from Israel so far that it would be willing to
negotiate the release of Lebanese prisoners in exchange for the
freedom of Israelis held by the Hizbullah.

Musawi was quoted as saying that this response did not meet the
Hizbullah's conditions, which included the release of Palestinians as
well as Lebanese prisoners.

Musawi also intimated that foreign hostages believed held by
groups affiliated or directly allied to his pro-Iranian organization
would not necessarily be included in any deal with Israel.

Musawi did not give the names or ranks of the Israeli servicemen
held captive, but they were believed to be Yossi Fink and Rahamim
Alsheikh, who were captured on February 17, 1986, in a terrorist
ambush in the security zone.

A third missing serviceman, Air Force navigator Ron Arad, was
captured after his jet was shot down in Lebanon the same year, but he
is believed held by another Shi'ite faction.

The last time Hizbullah publicly mentioned two missing Israeli
servicemen was in a communique in February 1988.

There has been speculation that if a swap of Israeli prisoners
could be worked out with Lebanese Shi'ite groups, it would clear the
way for release of 13 Western hostages in Lebanon.

Musawi, in his radio interview, suggested that efforts to arrange
a deal with Israel were not going well and repeated the traditional
Hizbullah line that the group has no control over the Westerners.

The 13 Westerners include six Americans, four Britons, two
Germans and an Italian.  The longest held is American journalist Terry
Anderson, who was kidnapped in West Beirut on March 16, 1985.

Israeli officials have stated that Israel would only enter
negotiations once it received "signs of life" or other proofs about
the prisoners held by the Hizbullah.

Until last week, the fundamentalist organization had not even
admitted publicly that it was holding any Israelis.  It has not
allowed visits to them by any outside organizations, not even the Red
Cross.

Israel television quoted senior military sources last night as
denying an American newspaper report that Israel and the Hizbullah had
already started negotiations over a prisoner swop.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
