<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Sunday, March 31, 1991



Illustration: Photo

Caption: Scowcroft

Source: Jerusalem Post Correspondent and News Agencies

          Lebanon.  Terror.  IDF.  Missing Person.  Visit.

        TALK OF DEAL ON HOSTAGES AS BUSH AIDE ENDS SECRET VISIT TO ME


WASHINGTON - A quick secret visit to the Middle East by President
Bush's national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft, has led to
speculation that his mission concerned not only the post-war situation
in Iraq, but also a possible deal for the release of Western hostages
held by Moslem terrorists.

In announcing the trip on Friday, White House spokesman Bill
Harlow declined to say where Scowcroft had been, with whom he had
talked or what he had talked about, how long he had been gone or when
he returned.  He did confirm that Scowcroft was back.  The White House
comment came after CBS News broke the story early Friday.

"At the president's request, Scowcroft made a trip to the Middle
East for discussions on the situation," Harlow's statement said.  He
was accompanied by the National Security Council's top Middle East
specialist, Richard Haass.

Scowcroft arrived in the Middle East on Tuesday and returned to
Washington on Thursday night, according to one official.

The trip took place at a time of growing uncertainty over the
future of Iraq and U.S. policy toward that country.

But Iraq is not the only topic of concern.  The Iranians are
signalling that they want closer relations with the U.S., and they
know that a sine qua non for a thaw with Washington is release of the
remaining hostages held by the pro-Iranian Hizbullah in Lebanon.

There are 13 western hostages still believed held in Beirut, of
whom six are Americans.

CBS reported that a deal to free the hostages would be based on
the payment of cash ransom, not political concessions.  The network
said the terrorists understand there will be no political deals.

The possibility of a deal to free the hostages has implications
for Israel.  Six Israelis are believed held in Lebanon.  All were
captured while serving there with the IDF.

They are Zacharia Baumel and Yosef Katz, captured during the
early days of Operation Peace for Galilee; Samir Assad, taken in
April, 1983 and believed held by the Democratic Front for the
Liberation of Palestine; Rahamim Alsheikh and Yossi Fink, captured in
February, 1986 and believed held by by Hizbullah; and IAF navigator
Ron Arad, shot down in October, 1986.

One key bargaining chip in Israel's hands is Shi'ite Sheikh Abdel
Karim Obeid, kidnapped from his village in southern Lebanon by an IDF
commando unit in July 1989.  Obeid is considered a central Hizbullah
leader with ties to numerous terror operations.  He has been held in
Israel since the commando raid.

In London, meanwhile, a committee of Arab journalists on Friday
called for the release of Associated Press correspondent Terry
Anderson, the longest-held of all the Western hostages, and British
television reporter John McCarthy.

The International Committee for the Defense of Journalists and
Correspondents, set up by the Federation of Arab News Agencies, said
the kidnapping and detention "goes against all human values and divine
teachings."

In a statement, they said the kidnappings hamper the objective
reporting of Arab and Islamic news.

Anderson, AP's chief Middle East correspondent, began his seventh
year in captivity last Saturday.  McCarthy was kidnapped on his way to
Beirut airport on April 17, 1986.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
