<HEAD>
	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Tuesday, December 19, 1989



Source: By KENNETH KAPLAN, Post Defence Reporter; Menachem Shalev adds

          Israel.  Budget.  Statistics.  Diplomacy.

        RABIN: FAMILIES OF MISSING MET PLO


Defence Minister Yitzhak Rabin disclosed yesterday that he had
allowed the families of IDF soldiers listed as missing since the
Lebanon War to meet with PLO officials in an effort to learn of the
fate of the missing men.  In one instance, he said, family members
travelled to Tunis at government expense to meet with PLO officials.

Rabin, addressing students at Tel Aviv University, said there
were no "strictures" in the search for missing soldiers.

Israel, he said, has mobilized presidents, parliamentarians,
journalists and world public opinion in efforts to ascertain the fate
of its seven missing soldiers.  These efforts have been frustrated, he
said, because of the Arabs' policy of not allowing visits or providing
reliable information.

In the case of the three IDF soldiers missing since the June 1982
tank battle against the Syrians near Sultan Ya'acoub - Yehuda Katz,
Zacharia Baumel and Zvi Feldman - Rabin said he had given his
permission to the families to meet with PLO officials and anyone else
in order to obtain information on the men.

Israel television reported last night that it was the relatives
of Baumel who went twice to Tunis last January and met there with
Yasser Abed Rabbo and other PLO officials.

Rabin said it appeared that kidnapped soldier Samir Assad was
killed by his captors, as has been repeatedly claimed by sources in
Lebanon.  Defence officials disclosed yesterday that they believe IAF
navigator Ron Arad is being held by the Iranian Revolutionary Guards
inside Lebanon.

Asked to comment on the recent reopening of the annual debate
over the defence budget, Rabin warned that further budget cuts would
result in more firings from defence industries, and criticized those
who publicized figures "which had no bearing on reality."

He put the current defence budget at NIS 10.5 billion, of which
NIS 3.6 b. is supplied by the U.S.

Menachem Shalev adds: Defence Minister Yitzhak Rabin's statement
yesterday on contacts between the families of missing soldiers and the
PLO appeared to give the organization another bit of legitimacy, but
most officials were confident last night that the public would
differentiate between the humanitarian and political aspects of the
matter.

Rabin's statement, coming at this delicate diplomatic and
political juncture, is bound to be utilized by those advocating
negotiations with the PLO, the officials said.  But they did not
believe that it would have any immediate diplomatic or political
impact.

Sources close to Rabin pointed out that his mention of the PLO
came in the context of wide-ranging efforts to secure the release of
prisoners and learn the whereabouts of missing soldiers; immediately
following this reply, they noted, Rabin attacked the organization with
ferocity, reiterating that Israel would never negotiate with the PLO.

A Foreign Ministry source said that Rabin's statement was poorly
timed against the background of Jerusalem's stated diplomatic
offensive against talks with the PLO.  A supporter of negotiations
with the PLO said: "It's another brick in the building.  It's not the
arrival of the Messiah.  "



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
