</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Monday, December 18, 1989



Source: By KENNETH KAPLAN, Post Defence Reporter


        IRANIAN GUARDS HOLDING ARAD IN LEBANON


Air Force navigator Ron Arad, missing since his F-4 Phantom was
shot down over Lebanon three years ago, is being held by Iranian
Revolutionary Guards inside Lebanon, defence officials said last
night.

The officials' comment followed the statement in Paris on
Saturday by Arad's wife Tamar that she believed he was being held by
Iranians, a claim confirmed earlier yesterday by lawyer Uri Slonim,
who is a special adviser to Defence Minister Rabin on missing IDF
soldiers.

Tamar Arad said she was not sure whether the Iranians had taken
her husband to Syria or Iran, but the officials said last night it was
known he was being held inside Lebanon.  The officials would not say
where or for how long he had been held by the Revolutionary Guards, or
how long the ministry had known the identity of his captors.

The Iranian Revolutionary Guards were sent to Lebanon to help arm
and train members of the radical Shi'ite militia Hizbullah, which has
declared its intention to help liberate Jerusalem.  There is an
estimated minimum of several hundred Revolutionary Guards now in
Lebanon.

The Revolutionary Guards' Lebanese stronghold is in the vicinity
of Baalbek in the Bekaa Valley, an area controlled by the Syrian army.
A number of the Guards are also said to be stationed with Hizbullah
forces in the southern sections of Moslem West Beirut.

Arad was first held by a faction of the Shi'ite militia Amal
headed by Mustafa Dirani.  Dirani eventually broke with Amal leader
Nabih Berri and reportedly moved to the Baalbek region near the
Hizbullah headquarters.  Both Dirani and Berri have denied to Red
Cross officials they are holding Arad.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
