<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Sunday, December 17, 1989



Source: By MICHEL ZLOTOWSKI, Post Correspondent


        IRAN'S GOT MY HUSBAND, SAYS IAF AIRMAN'S WIFE


PARIS - Ron Arad, the Israeli Air Force navigator shot down in
Lebanon three years ago, is probably being held prisoner by the
Iranians, his wife Tamar told The Jerusalem Post yesterday.

Mrs. Arad said she has been assured by Israeli authorities that
her husband is alive.  "At first Ron was held by Mustafa Dirani, head
of a group attached to Amal headed by [Shiite leader] Nabih Berri.
Berri in fact held a press conference in Sidon the day after my
husband's plane was shot down, when he said Ron was his prisoner.  But
later, Dirani and Berri separated.  Dirani took my husband along with
him and after a while probably handed him over to the Iranians," she
said.

Tamar Arad stressed that "I do not know where he is now.  Maybe
the Iranians took him to Iran or to Syria.  We have no clue, but I
know that the Israeli government is doing whatever is possible to free
my husband," she added.

The International Committee of the Red Cross has been denied
access to Arad until now, she said.  "I know that the Red Cross has
not been allowed to meet Sheikh Abdel-Karim Obeid," the South Lebanese
Hizbullah leader captured by Israel in August, said Tamar Arad.  "I
have been told this situation will not change until the Red Cross is
allowed to meet my husband and all the other Israeli prisoners." Those
missing are Yehuda Katz, Zachary Baumel, Zvi Feldman, Yosef Fink,
Rahamim Alsheikh and Samir Assad.

She has received only one letter from her husband since his
capture on October 16, 1986, through an unnamed third party, in the
first year of his captivity.  Sometime during his second year of
captivity, the Red Cross asked Dirani to pass to Arad a picture of his
then two-year-old daughter.  Dirani then answered that Arad was held
by Berri, while Berri claimed the opposite.

Mrs Arad is in Paris trying to convey a message to her husband
through the participants to an international symposium on Human Rights
in Arab Countries currently being held here under the auspices of
President Francois Mitterrand.  "I just hope that Ron and the other
Israeli prisoners are treated as well as Sheikh Obeid is in Israel.
Ron's daughter is now four, and she really hopes that her daddy will
soon be back home," she said.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
