</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Thursday, August 31, 1989



Source: By DAVID HOROVITZ, Jerusalem Post Correspondent

          War.

        QUOTES SOURCES IN BEIRUT.
CAPTURED SOLDIER YOSEF FINK 'MAY BE ALIVE,' SAYS UK PAPER.


LONDON - Less than three weeks after a British newspaper claimed
Israel had reached the conclusion two of its missing servicemen in
Lebanon were dead, another newspaper yesterday asserted that one of
them might still be alive.

The latest claim appeared in the Independent, in an article by
the paper's award-winning Beirut correspondent Robert Fisk.  Quoting
unnamed sources in West Beirut, the paper said Yosef Fink, one of two
soldiers ambushed near Beit Yahoun in south Lebanon in February 1986,
"may be alive." However, Fink's comrade, Rahamim Alsheikh, was "badly
wounded" and later died, said the Independent.

On August 13, the Sunday Times claimed Israel believed both Fink
and Alsheikh were dead - a report since vehemently denied by Israeli
ministers.  A week later, the paper reported that Israel was now
negotiating for the return of their bodies.

Conceding that imprisoned Hizbullah leader Sheikh Abdul Karim
Obeid told his interrogators both soldiers died soon after the ambush,
Israeli ministers have nevertheless made it clear that Obeid's
information is far from reliable, and that the two soldiers will
continue to be regarded as alive unless conclusive proof is obtained
to the contrary.

While the Sunday Times report originated in Jerusalem and was
based on Israeli sources, Fisk's sources come from the Lebanese
capital and presumably receive up-to-date information concerning
hostages and captives being held in the city.  Yesterday's report
added that a third missing Israeli, Air Force navigator Ron Arad, was
no longer in the hands of Nabih Berri's Amal militia.

Fisk's report, a lengthy piece examining numerous aspects of the
hostage crisis, included another bombshell - the assertion that the
Soviet Union provided "expertise" for the suicide attacks on American
marines and French paratroopers in October 1983.

The attacks, according to Fisk's Shi'ite sources, were planned
jointly by Syrian intelligence and former Iranian interior minister
Ali Akbar Mohtashemi, with the Soviets providing "the information
necessary to pack the explosives in the suicide drivers' trucks in
such a way that they totally destroyed the two military bases."



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
</CENTER>
