<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Friday, August 25, 1989



Source: By DAVID HOROWITZ, Jerusalem Post Correspondent


        'IDF HOSTAGES MAY BE ALIVE'


LONDON - Minister Yitzhak Moda'i last night played down
suggestions that two of Israel's missing servicemen in Lebanon were
dead, insisting that "we don't know for sure how many of them are
alive."

Addressing an Israel Bonds gathering here, the Economic Affairs
Minister said that two months ago Israel "thought we had a sign of
life" concerning abducted IDF servicemen Yosef Fink and Rahamim
Alsheikh.

Defence sources in Israel said shortly after the abduction of
Hizbullah Sheikh Obeid last month that the action had been delayed -
after the cabinet had already approved it - precisely because of those
signs of life.

He added that the group holding air force navigator Ron Arad has
admitted that he is still alive.

Referring to British press reports claiming that Israel has
concluded that Fink and Alsheikh are dead, on the basis of information
obtained from Obeid, Moda'i said that Israel could not be sure that
Obeid was telling the truth.

He said Israel still hopes Obeid's capture will pay dividends.
He added that Obeid would not be released unless all Israeli captives
were freed in exchange, and that the process may take a very long
time.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
