</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Monday, August 21, 1989

Memo: Box at end of text

Source: By MENACHEM SHALEV, KENNETH KAPLAN and News Agencies

          Syria.

        'HIZBULLAH OFFERS PROPOSALS FOR FREEING HOSTAGES'


Hizbullah spiritual leader Sheikh Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah was
quoted yesterday as saying that his organization has indirectly
presented proposals to Washington for the release of Western hostages
in Lebanon.

A Hizbullah proxy, however, once again threatened the lives of
the American hostages it holds, warning that the presence off the
Lebanese coast of French warships could be "dangerous" for the
captives.

In a wide-ranging discussion on Lebanon at yesterday's weekly
cabinet meeting, security sources said that concerted international
lobbying had deterred Syria from pressing on with its offensive in
Lebanon.

The sources said that Damascus is seeking ways of renewing its
offensive in Beirut, which has been relatively tranquil since the end
of the week.  If the international community does not apply pressure
on Damascus, the sources said, Syria is likely to resume its attack at
once.

Relatively small forces have participated in the fighting in
Beirut, consisting of Syrian allies among the Druse, Sunnis and
Shi'ites, the sources said.  Damascus has been careful not to employ
its own ground troops or air force in attacks on the Christians, the
sources added.

They added that the Christians appear to have abandoned hope for
an alliance with any other Lebanese group, and have now resigned
themselves to taking on the Syrians by themselves.

Between 20,000 and 40,000 refugees have sought refuge in the
security zone in South Lebanon since the latest round of fighting
began, the sources added.

In Tel Aviv yesterday, the Defence Ministry issued a flat denial
of a Sunday Times report claiming that Israel was involved in
negotiations with Hizbullah for the return of navigator Ron Arad and
the bodies of kidnapped Givati soldiers Yossi Fink and Rahamim
Alsheikh in exchange for Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid and 450 Shi'ites.

The ministry also announced the extension of the appointyment of
Tel Aviv attorney Ori Slonim as special adviser to the defence
minister on the captive IDF soldiers.  Slonim, a confidant of Rabin
first appointed to the post last September, was recently in Europe and
is said to be closely involved with the latest intense efforts to
establish a dialogue with Hizbullah.

In an interview with the United Arab Emirates newspaper
al-Ittihad yesterday, Fadlallah said: "What has taken place so far is
that mediators have presented ideas to the U.S. according to proposals
put forward by the kidnappers," He gave no details of the proposals,
however.

The Revolutionary Justice Organization, which holds two American
hostages, said their lives would be at stake if the French navy
intervenes in Lebanon.  The RJO is widely viewed as a cover used by
Hizbullah.

France has dispatched the aircraft carrier Foch and the destroyer
Duquesne to the eastern Mediterranean, ostensibly to evacuate some
7,000 French nationals from Lebanon if the need arises.

(Box) Pope John Paul II is determined to visit Beirut, a
spokesman for the Vatican said yesterday during the pope's visit to
the northern Spanish city of Oviedo, where he celebrated mass.

"As soon as he returns to Rome, the Pope intends to discuss the
question of his visit to the Lebanese capital with his advisers,"
spokesman Joaquin Navarro said.

Earlier yesterday, the pope, addressing a gathering in Santiago
de Compostela, implored the Syrians, and Lebanese Christians and
Moslems, to stop fighting and to accept an immediate cease-fire.



</PRE>
