<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Sunday, August 13, 1989



Source: By DAVID HOROVITZ, Jerusalem Post Correspondent

          Abdel Karim Obeid.  Hizbullah.

        'OBEID TOLD OF SOLDIERS' DEATHS FROM WOUNDS.'
UK PAPER SAYS TWO IDF MEN DIED AFTER 1986 HIZBULLAH AMBUSH.


LONDON - The Israeli government has notified the families of two
soldiers captured by Hizbullah in February 1986 that the pair are
dead, senior Israeli officials are quoted as saying in a news report
published here today.

The Sunday Times, in a report from Jerusalem, said Israel has
"concluded" that the two - Joseph Fink and Rahamim Alshech - died from
wounds sustained during their capture by Hizbullah in an ambush near
Beit Yahoun in southern Lebanon.

In Jerusalem, official IDF sources said last night that the army
did not respond to questions concerning the prisoners.  "We regard
them as alive until proven otherwise," they said.

Prime Minister Shamir, according to the Sunday Times report, has
ordered ministers not to discuss the matter and has attempted to keep
the deaths secret from the Bush administration "for fear that
Washington will put heavy pressure on him to free [Sheikh Abdel Karim]
Obeid in exchange for western hostages in Beirut."

Prior to the abduction of Obeid, said The Sunday Times, Israeli
intelligence agents thought that at least one of the pair might still
be alive.  But Obeid has apparently confirmed to his interrogators
that both died from their wounds soon after capture.

The third missing Israeli serviceman, air force navigator Ron
Arad "is believed to be alive, but in the hands of a Lebanese militia
that has closer ties to Syria than to Iran," according to today's
report.

Israel's information as to the fate of the two soldiers, added
The Sunday Times, has been confirmed by Arab sources in West Beirut.

The Israeli government "now believes one of the missing men died
of wounds about 15 minutes after the ambush," according to the report,
while the second "died hours later."

Arab sources told the paper that the soldiers' captors "staged" a
photograph that appeared in a Beirut magazine showing the soldiers
lying in beds with intravenous drips three days after the ambush.  The
sources said "both were dead when the picture was taken." Israeli
sources, said The Sunday Times, have confirmed that Obeid told his
interrogators the same story.

Israel has sought to keep its information on the deaths secret
from the U.S. because it expects Bush to demand that Obeid be offered
as a bargaining chip in negotiations for western hostages, since
Israel no longer needs him.  The IDF abducted Obeid in the hope that
Hizbullah would release the Israelis to recover him.

While Israel is aware that a swap for Obeid would help ease the
strains in its relationship with the U.S., the government fears that
Obeid's release "would prompt criticism at home," said The Sunday
Times.  Israel would be seen by its electorate as having risked the
lives of its soldiers for an operation that solely benefited the U.S.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
