	<TITLE>
		Ron Arad - Artical
	</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Tuesday, August 1, 1989

Memo: See related Lead Story, page 1

Source: By KENNETH KAPLAN, Post Defence Reporter

          Karim Obeid.  South Lebanon.

        RABIN: WE'LL TRADE OBEID FOR IDF MEN, FOREIGN HOSTAGES


Defence Minister Yitzhak Rabin yesterday ended three days of
speculation when he stated that Israel is prepared to exchange
abducted Hizbullah leader Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid and all other
Shi'ites being held by the IDF in Israel or southern Lebanon, in
return for the release of all IDF soldiers and foreign nationals held
by the various Shi'ite organizations in Lebanon.

In Beirut, a senior Shi'ite security source said three IDF
prisoners captured in South Lebanon were still alive.

Rabin's dramatic announcement seemed timed to coincide with the
expiry of the 3 p.m. deadline for the execution of kidnapped U.S.
Marine Colonel William Higgins.

Observers said the timing of the announcement appeared to be part
of the war of nerves between Israel and Hizbullah, with Rabin
signalling that Israel would not give in to the Shi'ite demands.
Rabin emphasized that his announcement was made without knowledge of
Higgins's condition but expressed the hope he was still alive.

Within an hour the Oppressed of the Earth announced the alleged
execution of Higgins.

Rabin, speaking to reporters at an impromptu press conference at
the Dan Hotel in Tel Aviv, said the proposed prisoner exchange should
be carried out through the normal channels of the International
Committee of the Red Cross.

Rabin said the decision to include the Western hostages in the
proposed exchange stemmed from the danger Israel perceived was caused
to their lives by Israeli actions.  He emphasized the decision was
taken by Israel alone, without consulting other countries, "just as
the decision to bring Sheikh Obeid back to Israel was an Israeli
decision aimed to help gain the return of Israeli prisoners."

Rabin stressed that when a military option existed to obtain the
return of hostages, it was preferred, as had been the case in the 1976
Entebbe rescue operation.

But by the same token, he said, when Israeli soldiers sent into
war fall into captivity, Israel is also willing to conduct
negotiations for their return, including the release of enemy - in
this case Shi'ite - prisoners "held by Israel or captured by Israel."

The latter reference appeared to be aimed at the approximately
150 Shi'ites held in the el-Khiam prison in the security zone in
southern Lebanon.  Israel is believed to be holding several dozen
Shi'ites in security prisons in Israel.

Hizbullah is believed to be holding Rahamim Alsheikh and Yossi
Fink, two Nahal soldiers captured in February 1986 when their patrol
was ambushed in the security zone.  The navigator of an IAF Phantom
jet downed over Lebanon in October of that year, Ron Arad, was
originally held by Hizbullah's rivals Amal, but may now be under
Hizbullah's control after a split between Amal leader Nabih Berri and
the Amal officer responsible for holding Arad.

"The government of Israel," Rabin said, reading from notes,
"calls for the immediate release of all Israeli prisoners and missing
soldiers and all other hostages held by the Shi'ite organizations in
Lebanon.  Israel proposes an exchange of prisoners and hostages.
Included in this proposal are all the Israeli prisoners held by all
the Shi'ite organizations, and all the Shi'ites held by Israel, among
them Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid, Jawad Kasfi, and others.

"The exchange will be carried out under the auspices of the
International Red Cross according to the accepted practice for these
situations."



</PRE>
