<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Sunday, January 22, 1989



Source: By DAVID HOROVITZ / Jerusalem Post Correspondent.


        'MISSING ISRAELI SOLDIERS HELD IN PRO-IRANIAN HANDS IN LEBANON.'


LONDON - Six Israeli soldiers, who have been missing in Lebanon
for three years or more, are in the hands of pro-Iranian groups,
according to a document seized recently from the offices of Iran's
consulate in Geneva.

The document, dated September 30, 1988, was quoted by the
Independent newspaper here yesterday.  It was reportedly among a batch
of Iranian government papers stolen last month from the office of
consul Manuchehr Tale by left-wing opponents of Ayatollah Khomeini's
regime.

The soldiers are named as Sergeant Zacharia Baumel, Sergeant Zevi
Sergment, Corporal Yahuda Kat, Sergeant Samir Asad, Corporal Yussef
Sink and Corporal Rahamim Levy Alfriky.

The corporal named as Sink is thought to be Yosef Fink, while
Alfriky is believed to be Rahamim Levy Alsheikh.  The two were
captured together on February 17, 1986, in an ambush south of the Beit
Yahun junction in the South Lebanon security zone.

The document, signed by Tale, also mentions a certain "Moslem
Shaban," whom it describes as "a Mossad man living in Geneva."

It makes no mention, however, of air force navigator Ron Arad,
who was shot down in his Phantom jet over South Lebanon more than two
years ago.

Last October, the Observer quoted Lebanese sources as reporting
that Arad, Fink and Alsheikh were still alive.  Arad, it said, was
being held by former Amal militia security chief Mustapha Zirani.  And
Fink and Alsheikh were presumed to be alive since they had been
threatened with execution by Hizbullah extremists if Israel retaliated
for a car bomb attack on the northern border.

The Geneva documents were reportedly stolen by members of the
Mujahedin Khalq Iranian opposition group.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
