<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/Images/head-know.gif">
</CENTER>
<PRE>
                        (C) The Jerusalem Post 1992
                        Friday, December 30, 1988



Source: Jerusalem Post Reporter

Keywords:

        IAF HITS HOME OF AMAL MAN WHO AIDED TERRORISTS


METULLA - Air Force helicopters yesterday attacked a house in
South Lebanon that had been visited by three Palestinian terrorists on
their way to attack this Galilee Panhandle town.  Eight Amal security
members were wounded, and the house was severely damaged.  The
helicopters returned safely to base.

Israeli military sources say that the house, near Sultaniya, was
used by Amal supporters who volunteered their assistance to the
terrorists.

The gang belonged to the Organization for the Liberation of
Palestine, a splinter of the Ahmed Jibril group operating in Lebanon
under Syrian auspices.

The three terrorists were killed Tuesday night by a patrol of
paratroopers as they tried to cross the border fence near Kibbutz
Manara.

IDF sources stressed that Israel would maintain its policy of
refraining from hitting Amal targets in South Lebanon.  Nevertheless,
they added, any persons or groups involved in attacks against Israel
would have no immunity from IDF retaliation.

OC Northern Command Aluf Yossi Peled yesterday told The Jerusaelm
Post that he suspected that the three Palestinians had been led to the
border by Amal guides. "We will not tolerate a situation like this,"
he said, "and we will have to find a military response."

UN sources in South Lebanon reported that at 9:00 a.m. yesterday
two Israeli Cobra helicopters flew over the village of Sultaniya and
shot five missiles into a house used by Amal's security unit.  The
house was badly damaged and eight Amal security force members who were
in the building at the time were injured.

They were taken to hospital in Tyre for treatment.

The Amal commander in South Lebanon, Abdul Majid Salah, told
reporters in Tyre that the Israeli attack on his headquarters would
not go unavenged.  He expressed his fury over "the savage attack" and
said that the agreement signed last week between Amal and the Fatah
organization demonstrates Amal's hegemony over South Lebanese
territory.

Sultaniya has been known as the stronghold of the extreme
Believers' Resistance, which split from Amal last year and has since
operated under the zealous wings of the Hizbullah.

The head of the Believers', Mustafa Dirani, is holding the
Israeli Air Force navigator, Ron Arad, who was captured two years ago.

Yesterday, SLA Christian soldiers in Jezzine opened fire on two
terrorists who were preparing to attack a position near Falous, on the
outskirts of the town.  One of the terrorists was killed in the clash
and the other managed to escape.  No SLA soldiers were hurt.



</PRE>
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="http://www.macom.co.il"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/Images/macom.gif"></A>
</CENTER>
</BODY>
